<HEADLINE>
PADRES HAND EXTINGUISHER TO HEALTHY HITCHCOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ He didn't sneeze or wheeze and his throat wasn't
raspy.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy Sterling Hitchcock provided some relief to the San
Diego Padres' medical situation yesterday, arriving for the off-day
workout at Qualcomm Stadium without a handkerchief or clutching a
bottle of antihistamine.
</P>
<P>
   Sinus ailments hampered Padre pitchers Kevin Brown and Andy
Ashby in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I'm fine,'' Hitchcock said. ``I feel a little
congestion, but it's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's health is better than the Padres' predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The National League champions are in a two-games-to-none bind
against the New York Yankees in the best-of-seven World Series. The
American League champions are two wins away from stamping
themselves as perhaps the best team in major league history.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Yankees pound Padre pitching for 18 runs in
two games at Yankee Stadium and improve their overall record to
123-50 this season, Hitchcock reached an understandable conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can hit,'' he said. ``Bottom line, they can hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Hitchcock, a one-time Yankee and former Mariner, can
continue his remarkable October and solve the Yankee hitters the
way he did against the Houston Astros and Atlanta Braves, going 3-0
with a 1.13 ERA, the Padres will find themselves looking at a
potential Series debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has just been tremendous,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy
said. ``To go against the pitchers he had to (Randy Johnson, Tom
Glavine and Greg Maddux in the NL playoffs) and do what he did, it
shows the mental makeup of this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But can he do it one more time?
</P>
<P>
   Although Hitchcock understands the significance of Tuesday
night's Game 3 and the pressure that accompanies his first World
Series start, he downplayed the win-or-else scenario.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was more pressure just getting here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like going into any game saying it doesn't matter if
we win,'' he said. ``Obviously, I want to win every game I pitch,
and that's how I will approach this game. Basically, against
Houston and Atlanta I wanted to go out there and give us a chance
to be close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to have to be pretty good to get by
Johnson, Maddux and Glavine. The same holds true (Tuesday) with
(David) Cone out there. I've got to try to limit my mistakes and
have some fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Yankees are having the most fun. But manager Joe
Torre hasn't clicked into the giddy stage and is wary of Hitchcock,
who was 9-7 during the regular season that began with him in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have noticed in Sterling Hitchcock is his command seems
to be better than what I remember, although I didn't manage him,''
Torre said. ``We played against him when he was with Seattle, and
he just seems to have better command of his stuff. I have been very
impressed with what he did in (the playoffs). He was getting ahead
in the count, and that's important for any pitcher to be able to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said that is his game plan: ``I'll try to throw
strikes, get ahead in the count and be aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander said the fact his start is against the team that
drafted and developed him before trading him to the Mariners in
1996 isn't causing an adrenaline overflow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if we're playing the Bad New Bears right
now, it's the World Series. It's an opportunity to pitch in the
Series, and as a kid that's what you dream of.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees are making this a San Diego nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   After playing well in Game 1 and building a 5-2 lead going into
the seventh inning, the Padre relief corps collapsed during a
seven-run Yankee uprising that featured Tino Martinez's
game-winning grand slam. The Padres played miserably in Game 2,
falling seven runs behind by the third inning, and never
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has survived all year on our pitching staff and
defense,'' Hitchcock said, ``and we've got to get back to throwing
the ball the way we're capable.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Dave Stewart concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitching is better than it has shown,'' Stewart said. ``We
haven't pitched well at all, but it can turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Having almost 65,000 rabid backers at the park should help the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be home,'' Bochy said, ``and this team has been
very resilient all season. We weren't celebrating by any means
(during the flight from New York). But this club doesn't get down,
and I'm proud of them that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, losing the first two games of the World Series creates
a difficult task. Of the 44 previous occasions when a team won the
first two games, 33 have won the Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
