<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEAF-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING PAINS: NFL A RUDE AWAKENING FOR LEAF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The spiral begins behind the ear and zips through
the air like a laser-guided missile locked on its target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice throw Ryan,'' San Diego Chargers interim head coach June
Jones yells out, trying to coax his 22-year-old prodigy back from
the depths of despair.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Leaf drops back again and lets another pass fly. Again and
again. Forty yards into the end zone. Over the middle. Into the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   With his $11.25 million signing bonus, a five-year, $31 million
contract and a new home in San Diego, the No. 2 player taken in
last spring's NFL draft still shows the natural ability with which
he led Washington State to its first Rose Bowl in 67 years.
</P>
<P>
   But on and off the field, the youngest quarterback to start an
NFL game since fellow ex-Cougar Drew Bledsoe in 1992 _ the Colts'
Peyton Manning is two months older _ is not the exultant young man
who threw a record 59 touchdown passes in his WSU career and made a
serious Heisman Trophy run.
</P>
<P>
   Going into last Sunday's game, Leaf was the NFL's lowest-rated
quarterback (29.8), having thrown 12 interceptions (three in one
game against the Raiders). He hadn't thrown for a touchdown in
25-plus quarters. What's more, his head coach, Kevin Gilbride, was
fired last week largely because of an inept Chargers offense run by
Leaf that contributed to a 2-4 start.
</P>
<P>
   Things settled down a bit Sunday with a shaky 13-10 victory over
Philadelphia. Now he is preparing to face a Seahawks defense prone
to rattling a young quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, Leaf tries to shrug off his rude awakening to
NFL life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little strange, losing a head coach and all that,''
he said last week in an interview at Chargers headquarters. ``I
guess that's all in the business. I don't know much about it, but
I'm learning pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also learning that fans can turn on him for what he does on
and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``CRYIN' RYAN''
</P>
<P>
   Sparked largely by his nationally televised, profanity-laden
tirade against a San Diego sports reporter, in addition to his poor
play, fans have begun to show their displeasure with the rookie.
When his public service announcement for the Make a Wish Foundation
was shown on the stadium video screen, it drew a round of boos.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Union-Tribune's ``Voice of the Fan'' weekly column
has become a flogging post for Leaf: ``Cryin' Ryan! What a shame.
Your mouth is bigger than your game. We should have drafted Brian
Griese,'' wrote Daniel Gray of Bonita.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf's first response was to stop talking to the media. Then he
switched to only ``yes and no'' answers. Now, he's just trying to
move on.
</P>
<P>
   He pretends not to hear the boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bothered at all,'' he said. ``It comes with the
business and it doesn't matter anyway. The fans are fickle
everywhere in the country, and you just have to play well. That's
the way it is and you find it out quickly in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   But it has bothered him enough that he doesn't want his family
to come from Great Falls, Mont., to see him play, and he doesn't
plan to stack Qualcomm Stadium with friends for this Sunday's game
with the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a long career in this league, you know,'' he said.
``They don't need to see the games where the crowd is booing you or
where you're struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   So now it is up to Leaf's coaches and teammates to rally around
him, hoping he can take that precision spiral from the practice
field to the playing field, where he has been abysmal in recent
weeks. Against the Raiders, he was only 7-of-18 for 78 yards and
was in danger of losing his job to backup Craig Whelihan.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Gilbride was fired and Jones, the team's
quarterbacks coach, was installed in his place by general manager
Bobby Beathard. Jones' first act was to give Leaf a vote of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to play,'' said Jones, the former Atlanta Falcons
coach who has had plenty of experience tutoring another troubled
quarterback, Jeff George, and a young prodigy, Brett Favre, before
Favre went to Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be some games when he's probably going to
have to come out again. But at the same time, he understands that's
part of the growing process,'' Jones said. ``We've just got to
build him up and get him doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   After so much was invested to get Leaf, the Chargers made a
statement that he, not Gilbride, is where the future lies, for
better or for worse.
</P>
<P>
   PATIENCE AND PENITENCE
</P>
<P>
   Even players like Whelihan, a fourth-year backup who started
seven games for the Chargers last year, are sympathetic and patient
with Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially the last few weeks when he's been struggling, I've
been saying, `Slow it down a little bit. Don't aim the ball. Throw
the ball like you do during practice,''' Whelihan said on the
Chargers' pregame show on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just tell him he's going to be all right, because he's going
to be a good quarterback. He's just got to get through this rough
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That so many care about his well-being is hard for Leaf to
accept, given his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates are unbelievably supportive, which blows me away
because I'd probably be very upset with me,'' he said after the
loss to the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   He also is trying to make his peace with the media and Chargers
fans. After his eruption at the reporter, Leaf issued a statement
prompted by talks with his father that said he was being ``selfish
and I have let my personal shortcomings get in the way of my
professional behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Leaf said, ``It kind of feels like someone ripped my heart
out of me, I want to succeed so much.''
</P>
<P>
   To the fans, Leaf asks for understanding: ``I understand the
fans' reaction. They have a player coming in here that the team
gave so much up for. Everyone expects you to be a huge success, and
you go out and play so poorly. It's understandable. I'd be upset,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   With such mixed emotions, Leaf admits he is having a tough
education in the business of professional football. But he still
expects the world from his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about Jones' continuing to go with him as a
starter, Leaf still can muster his well-worn bravado: ``It's good
to have that, but that's what I expected. I expect to be the
starter. I was given the job and that's my role on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he passed for only 83 yards (9-19) against
Philadelphia, he played the whole game and didn't fumble the ball
or throw an interception despite being sacked six times.
</P>
<P>
   LETTING LEAF GROW
</P>
<P>
   WSU coach Mike Price talks frequently with Leaf and has
counseled him through his troubled first season. He notes that Leaf
was raw and unbridled in his first years with the Cougars, just
like his first year in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Ryan Leaf when he was young, he was not a
pretty-looking guy,'' Price said. ``I can remember going to the
Alamo Bowl (in 1994, Leaf's freshman year), and in practice he was
throwing the ball terrible. But he was saying, `Boy, I better get
my chance to start.' He was starting with the media then.''
</P>
<P>
   While Price doesn't make excuses for Leaf, he does dismiss the
blowup at the reporter as just one incident that happened to be
caught on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, he'll tell it like it is, and it explodes,'' Price
said. ``It's on tape, and they keep playing it again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Leaf can avoid similar problems in the future, Price
offers: ``I don't really know if there is anything other than not
blowing up at the media. Just relax and things will fall into place
eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Price has not seen Leaf play in a Chargers regular-season game,
but he did visit him in preseason camp. Leaf looked as capable and
confident as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was throwing such a tight spiral. He really improved his
mechanics and throwing since he was a freshman,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   But Leaf needs more than a tight spiral to spark new life in the
Chargers offense. It could take weeks, maybe years.
</P>
<P>
   ``His growth at quarterback will determine how fast we can go,''
Jones said. ``We're going to try to do the base things that we know
he can do. Obviously, we have to be able to throw the football, and
we haven't thrown the football very well as of late.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones is not sure exactly what Leaf can do, technically, to
bring him back to his collegiate confidence level and preseason
playing form. Leaf needs to learn how the pass routes run by
receivers adjust to NFL coverages, Jones suggests. He needs to know
when to take a sack and not force interceptions. He needs a
psychological boost as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing and experiencing successful games will start to breed
confidence,'' Jones said. ``That's what it's going to take at this
point. He's doing what most rookie quarterbacks do right now, and
that's not play very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Successful quarterbacks often don't have instant success, Jones
notes, listing veterans such as Steve Young, John Elway and Favre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarterbacks who have experience are the ones who are
successful,'' Jones said. ``You have to lose long enough to gain
that experience.''
</P>
<P>
   So in the absence of such experience, Price offers this
suggestion: ``I just think what he needs to do is have a little
more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   FOREVER A COUGAR
</P>
<P>
   Before the season began, Leaf posed for an ESPN Magazine photo
shoot in scuba gear throwing a football underwater. But he has yet
to become immersed in the Southern California lifestyle and claims
not to have much time to enjoy his newfound wealth or his house
near the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live here (at the Chargers practice facility) and I live in
my house. The weather is beautiful, and that's about it. I don't
have any time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also has abandoned Great Falls as the place he calls home.
Reminded that he once contemplated building a new football field in
Great Falls, Leaf claims, ``I never said that. No. I can't remember
ever saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Pullman and Eastern Washington are where he considers
himself at home, and he plans a brief return Oct. 31 during the
Chargers' bye week to donate an as-yet undisclosed amount of money
to WSU when the Cougars host Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   A true Cougar at heart, Leaf still has sharp-tongued disdain for
the University of Washington, and Seattle in general.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would be inviting a large group of friends and
family to watch him in the Kingdome when the Chargers return to
Seattle Dec. 13, Leaf was blunt: ``I really don't have any friends
or family in Seattle. That's the bad part of the state, where the
Huskies roam.''
</P>
<P>
   With the tense few weeks behind him, Leaf seems most relaxed
when conversation turns to the Cougars' future. According to Leaf,
that future soon will lie in the hands of his first cousin, Matt
Kegel of Havre, Mont., who has committed to play quarterback at WSU
next year. Kegel, rated the No. 12 quarterback prospect in the
country by SuperPrep magazine, also was recruited by the Huskies,
but Leaf had a subtle way of letting his cousin know what the
choice should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day he was wearing a Husky hat, and I tore it apart and
said a bunch of disgusting things to it,'' Leaf said with a devious
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Like his cocky cousin, the 6-foot-5, 205-pound Kegel already has
declared that he intends to take the Cougars to the Rose Bowl _
only he plans to win it. And Leaf wouldn't be surprised if he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's better than me coming out of high school,'' Leaf says.
``He's a lot more fundamentally sound than I was. He's the real
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his flaws and the rookie mistakes, the Chargers are
betting that Leaf and his fabulous spiral are the real deal, too.
They were even willing to change coaches in mid-season to give him
plenty of room to grow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
