<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BIG TO BIGGER FOR NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Before last weekend, it was a big game.
Scratch that now because Montana State and Cal State Northridge
both lost.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's meeting has become huge. Gargantuan. Perhaps the
biggest in CSUN's football existence. At the least, the biggest
since moving to NCAA Division I-AA in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way: One season will be nearly destroyed
Saturday. Another will be kept alive.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves no time for CSUN (4-2, 3-1 Big Sky) to reflect on a
dismal 35-21 loss to Sacramento State, while Montana State (4-2,
2-1) must rid itself of evil thoughts emanating from a 34-31 loss
to Portland State.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, if we both won we could have both made the
postseason,'' CSUN coach Ron Ponciano said. ``Right now, it's not
going to be both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, two teams from the Big Sky Conference reach the
playoffs, and that should still stand true.
</P>
<P>
   However, with nearly half the schedule remaining, and a pair of
difficult road trips awaiting each team, rebounding from a second
consecutive loss could be too much. Montana State still has games
at Eastern Washington and Montana while CSUN plays at Weber State
and Southwest Missouri State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the losses did anything to change the importance
of this game,'' Montana State coach Cliff Hysell said. ``We have
four huge games left, and so does Northridge. This is a big game
coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Still ranked, but barely: CSUN survived for another week in the
polls, but barely. The Matadors slid eight spots in the Sports
Network poll to 24th and nine slots to 25th in the USA Today
coaches' poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like we were content with being 16th,'' said
Ponciano, who gave his team Sunday and Monday off. ``We spent five
hours watching film of the Sac State game. I think it was important
as a staff that we looked at reality. We needed some time, and
those kids needed time away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana State, ranked 18th in both polls last week, is ranked
24th by the coaches but not ranked by the Sports Network.
</P>
<P>
   The never-ending story: Another day, another offensive line
crisis. Ponciano said center Julio Alcala, who left the team last
Sunday because of personal problems, is expected back Wednesday.
Meanwhile his replacement, Beau Cherry (ankle), and left tackle
Mike Barnes (shoulder) both could miss the Montana State game.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said he will shift tight end Ryan Schatz to left tackle
and use Joe Bergman as a backup. The Matadors haven't started the
same offensive line in back-to-back games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no more people. The bodies have run out,''
Ponciano said. ``It's to the point now where it's beyond
frustrating. We're trying to make a run at the league title and
it's something different every week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
