<HEADER>
A6098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-MEDAL-CHANGES-NYT     10-20 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MEDAL-CHANGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY SEEK TO CHALLENGE EAST GERMAN MEDALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee is preparing for a controversial
process that seeks to upgrade medals for American athletes who lost
to East Germans in cases where the use of performance-enhancing
drugs can be documented.
</P>
<P>
   The first request could be made within the next several weeks,
and involves seeking a gold medal for American women who finished
second to East Germany in the 400-meter medley relay at the 1976
Summer Games in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of the Berlin Wall, documents and testimony have
established what had been long suspected: a state-sponsored system
of performance-enhancing drug use that existed in the former East
Germany from 1968 to 1988 and that may have involved 10,000
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   After first saying that it could not rewrite history, the
International Olympic Committee said earlier this year that it
would consider adjusting results on a case by case basis.
</P>
<P>
   Urged on by athletes who felt they were cheated out of medals,
the U.S. Olympic Committee has begun preparations to challenge East
German results, particularly in swimming, where 50 possible cases
could come under scrutiny, Bill Hybl, president of the committee,
said.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC has got ammunition for its challenges from trials this
year in Germany in which a former East German doctor and a swimming
coach admitted giving performance-enhancing drugs to young female
swimmers, were convicted of causing bodily harm and were fined
about $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hybl said in an interview that challenges would be made only in
cases where there was an admittance of drug use or a conviction in
court.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC would not seek to take medals away from East Germans,
Hybl said, but would seek to give Americans ``appropriate
recognition'' for their achievements. This means seeking to give an
American a duplicate gold medal if he or she had won a silver or to
have an asterisk placed by the result of a particular race.
</P>
<P>
   The first case that may be challenged involved the 400-meter
medley relay in Montreal, where the East German team of Ulrike
Richter, Hannelore Anke, Andrea Pollack and Kornelia Ender defeated
an American team of Linda Jezek, Lauri Siering, Camille Wright and
Shirley Babashoff.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf Glaeser, a former East German coach, admitted in court last
summer that he had given Pollack and other swimmers
performance-enhancing drugs. The USOC is awaiting a German judge's
written decision in which Glaeser was convicted last summer of
causing bodily harm to swimmers. Once that decision is received,
perhaps within the next two or three weeks, Hybl said that the USOC
might use the medley relay as the first case in challenging the
East German swimming dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our gold medal,'' said Wendy Boglioli, an alternate on
the American relay team, who also won a bronze medal behind Ender
and Pollack in the 100-meter butterfly in Montreal. ``We deserve to
have that in the record books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LABOR-RULING-HNS &LR;      10-20 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-RULING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Labor negotiations are built on a foundation of give and take, and
it was NBA owners who did all the taking Monday afternoon.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what represents the biggest victory yet in a 112-day labor
battle between the league and the National Basketball Players
Association, arbitrator John Feerick sided with NBA owners in a
grievance filed by the union.
</P>
<P>
   And it's what the owners don't have to give _ money to 226
players with guaranteed contracts _ that represents what might be
the final blow to the Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the players' union were not happy with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's garbage,'' said Denver's Nick Van Exel. ``That's what
we're looking at. You put anybody in that position, with a
guaranteed contract, and the owner locks you out, you get paid. We
had a legitimate argument. There's no way that should go against
us.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrating what he termed a ``novel and difficult'' issue,
Feerick, dean of Fordham Law School, ruled that the ``salary
provisions of the player contracts are not effective or operative
during a lawful lockout.''
</P>
<P>
   With that decision, the biggest bargaining chip in the
increasingly acrimonious negotiations goes to the owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with the arbitrator's ruling,'' said Jeffrey
Mishkin, the NBA's chief legal officer. ``Unfortunately, it does
not get us any closer to a deal with the union's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only negotiations will end our current impasse and lead to a
settlement of our dispute. This is yet another defeat for the
union's strategy of litigation instead of negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   But little negotiation is expected in the coming days. The
players are heading to Las Vegas, where the union's next step will
be hammered out in a Thursday summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   League commissioner David Stern would have preferred the players
were heading to the bargaining table instead. The lockout already
has caused the NBA to lose the first two weeks of the regular
season, 99 games in all, and Stern and deputy commissioner Russ
Granik said the cancellation of more games was ``inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, for us, we're glad to have the ruling that we got
today,'' Granik said. ``It certainly eliminates a stumbling block
that we've had as we've tried to bargain, but the fact is it
doesn't get us any closer to an agreement if the players won't come
to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, as I said, it removes a stumbling block, but it's not like
we're gleeful here, because as each day goes by we're missing more
and more games.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a league that had never lost a game to a work stoppage
in its 51-year history could be inching closer to losing an entire
season.
</P>
<P>
   Union executive director Billy Hunter hinted that the two sides
appear to be headed toward disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find ourselves to be in the same position as we were in
(Sunday),'' Hunter said of the players. ``The players are not
inclined to back down. As soon as the owners realize this and end
the lockout, the better chance we have to avoid enormous damage to
the sport of professional basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel confirmed that the players aren't about to give an
inch, saying Monday's ruling probably won't speed up the bargaining
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it doesn't speed up our end, unless it's for a deal
everyone can agree on,'' Van Exel said. ``I hope we stand by each
other and battle it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle, of course, is over money. Lots of money.
</P>
<P>
   Owners, eyeing skyrocketing player salaries, imposed the lockout
effective July 1 and hope to address the Larry Bird exception to
the salary cap, which allows teams to spend any amount of money to
re-sign their own free agents, regardless of the cap. While the two
sides have been discussing a ``luxury tax'' on Bird-exception
salaries, they remain far apart in their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The union had argued that players should have been paid during
the lockout, saying owners should have included lockout-protection
language in individual player contracts.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to Olden Polynice's contract with the Sacramento
Kings, which contains a clause that says he won't be paid during a
lockout. The union contended that other owners should have done the
same.
</P>
<P>
   The union filed the grievance just hours before the lockout was
imposed July 1, and even though Feerick's jurisdiction expired
along with the collective-bargaining agreement, he ruled the union
had beaten the deadline and he was entitled to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
   What now?
</P>
<P>
   Players who were expecting a paycheck Nov. 15 will instead have
to wait until they set foot on the court to get paid. And even
though Hunter still insists players will receive their full
salaries should the season get under way, Stern and Granik said
that was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has already been decided, and unless they have some means
by which they think they can appeal it, which would surprise me,
that issue is over,'' Granik said. ``I don't ever see the owners
agreeing to pay for games where they lost the revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't even make any sense to me, and I don't understand
where that is coming from and on what basis he (Hunter) thinks that
would ever be attainable. These dollars have been lost. I think by
now the players have lost well over $100 million in salaries just
on the games that have been canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   With more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Before Feerick announced his decision, Stern sent a letter to
Hunter that he hoped would spur negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   It contained three proposals to address the salary structure:
</P>
<P>
   An NFL-style hard salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   An escrow account from which players would receive money if
their salaries fell below a certain percentage of the
basketball-related income, or from which owners would receive
payments from the players if salaries were above that percentage.
</P>
<P>
   And the luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
   Stern insisted the NBA was more interested in working with the
players rather than smashing the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this notion that's been let out there that the owners
are suddenly here with a strategy trying to make the players
cave,'' Stern said. ``This is not about getting the players to
cave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the owners reopened the agreement is that they
couldn't operate under the expired system. And they recognized the
risk that reopening posed, but they were prepared to take the
risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
