<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-McLAUGHLIN-LADN </SLUG>
 
SCOUTS MAKE CAL'S McLAUGHLIN NERVOUS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY _ Ssssshhh! An NFL scout is at practice, on the
sideline. Don't let John McLaughlin know. He hates when they come
to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Games in front of 60,000 or so hostile strangers who would love
nothing more than to see him get pancaked, or juked by a running
back, don't faze him.
</P>
<P>
   When an NFL scout stops by a Cal practice to check out a
late-blooming senior defensive end with linebacker speed, now
that's worrisome. McLaughlin, a Hart High graduate, is that player.
And the thought of being on display in practice makes him a little
queasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me nervous when they're here,'' said McLaughlin, a
former Daily News All-Area pick who lines up against No.2 UCLA at
Cal's Memorial Stadium on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why they're here,'' McLaughlin said. ``I
don't think I'm that good of a football player.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of others believe McLaughlin is that kind of player.
His position coach, Bill Dutton, loves to add to McLaughlin's
frenetic feeling. Any time a scout pops by, including last
Thursday, Dutton makes it a point to tell McLaughlin as he dresses
for practice. And, boy, does McLaughlin despise that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting because before a game he's really poised,''
Dutton said. ``I tell him (about scouts) and he gets really
nervous. I tell him because if I was in his position, it would
motivate me to play harder knowing a scout was there to see me.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's John. He's a strong, fast, active athlete. But
sometimes he can be his own worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get this relationship wrong. Dutton and McLaughlin get
along fine. It's just that Dutton is trying to boost McLaughlin's
self-esteem as a football player because success, and being a
high-profile player, is new.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago McLaughlin, moved from linebacker to the rush end
position for Cal, was trying to get used to the Golden Bears' way
of doing things after transferring from Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   And a year ago he weighed 220, at best. Now his 6-foot-4 frame
checks in at 242 pounds and his speed is better. He covers 40 yards
in 4.5 seconds, but more will be made of that during the NFL
combines this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scouts are very intrigued by his combination of speed and
size,'' said Cal head coach Tom Holmoe, himself a local product
(Crescenta Valley) and an NFL veteran. ``John is very disciplined,
great speed pass-rusher and does a great job on special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for McLaughlin's metamorphosis was the heavy stuff.
The weights. It seems that even at storied Notre Dame, the coaching
staff couldn't get McLaughlin within a Hail Mary of the weight
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always hated it, but as soon as you start lifting a
little bit, get a little size on you and some strength, it feels
good,'' McLaughlin said. ``It becomes kind of addicting. Once you
get stronger, you like that feeling. You keep working on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gained speed because I never had any muscle in my legs. I
didn't have any power in my legs.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem Cal had earlier this season was keeping McLaughlin
fresh. Not because he lacked endurance but because he didn't get
rest during a game. Not only does he start on the defensive line,
but he's on the kick-return team, the kick-coverage team and lines
up on the outside on punt coverage. Yes, a defensive lineman on the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be just like a Billy Bates kind of player,'' another
NFL scout said. ``He'd be perfect for a team like the Minnesota
Vikings where they let their defensive linemen move around.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin has 17 tackles, five of which are for a loss, and two
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Early projections have McLaughlin, a relative unknown until
spring ball in college circles, going in the later rounds of the
NFL draft. Obviously, that could change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything they want me to do to play in the NFL,''
McLaughlin said. ``I'll be the damn water boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But McLaughlin's got to go now. Between practice, slight anxiety
attacks and position meetings, he has to talk to a scout. It's a
guy from the New York Giants, which also happens to be McLaughlin's
favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, by the way. As it turns out, McLaughlin already knew a scout
was at practice....
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
