<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES READY FOR FAMILIAR SCENERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The forecast for San Diego today calls for blue
skies and sunshine, gentle breezes and 65,000 screaming fans at
Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After getting mugged in the Bronx, the San Diego Padres are
clinging to the belief that a change of coasts will do wonders for
their endangered World Series hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our morale is fine,'' outfielder Tony Gwynn said Monday as the
Padres worked out at their home park in preparation for Game 3
tonight against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still confident we can do some things that will give us
a chance to win,'' Gwynn said. ``Coming home is a lot easier. I
know I feel comfortable in my own home, in my own bed, driving my
own car. Especially as opposed to New York, where I don't know
where the hell I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates were just as lost, as the Padres went down in the
first two games against the Yankees who, after 114 regular-season
victories and nine more in 11 playoff games, appear invincible.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres blew a 5-2 seventh-inning lead in the first game and
lost, 9-6. Then, they were thoroughly outclassed, 9-3, in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' third baseman Ken Caminiti said. ``We can
be happy just being here, or we can go do something about it. I'm
not content to be here. I want to win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres know history is against them, just as it was against
the Braves when San Diego won the first three games of the National
League Championship Series. The Padres are the 45th team to lose
the first two games of a World Series. Of the previous 44, only 11
came back to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thinking about the (11) who came back,'' manager Bruce
Bochy said. ``That's all we can do. This club has done a good job
handling adversity all year, and that's what we have to do now.
We'll come out strong here in San Diego.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres took a red-eye charter from New York after Sunday's
loss, and when the team bus arrived at Qualcomm Stadium at 5:30
Monday morning, there were several hundred fans at the stadium to
greet them. Several thousand more were at Qualcomm Monday afternoon
for a Padres rally, giving them a chance to show their support or
get in one more tailgate party before the season comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
   But fan support alone won't slow down the Yankees juggernaut.
The Padres also know they have to play better, especially after
Sunday's disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know why we're here and why we got here,'' Gwynn said. ``So
far we haven't played like it. There are no excuses. They've done a
better job of doing what it takes to win than we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres do have the excuse that their first two starting
pitchers _ Kevin Brown and Andy Ashby _ were suffering from
flu-like symptoms in New York. But Bochy said Game 3 starter
Sterling Hitchcock is healthy, and so is the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The club is doing well,'' Bochy said. ``Kevin Brown feels a
lot better, and checking out the guys, they're fine. That's not
coming into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy said he'll decide today if Brown is ready to pitch Game 4
or if he'll go with Joey Hamilton instead and save his ace for Game
5. By using Brown in Game 4, Bochy could bring him back for Game 7
on three days.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy's decision depends on how quickly Brown overcomes the bug
that bit him in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's health is a priority as far as when he's pitching,''
Bochy said. ``It's a matter of if he's strong enough to pitch. If
he doesn't, we'll go with Joey.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Padres know there likely won't be a Game 7 if they don't
win tonight. Hitchcock has been terrific in the playoffs, winning
three consecutive starts against former Cy Young Award winners
Randy Johnson, Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine. He'll face a fourth
ex-Cy Young winner in David Cone tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has survived all year long on pitching and
defense,'' Hitchcock said. ``We have to get back to the way we were
throwing all year long: get ahead and continue to throw quality
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   They have 65,000 fans basking in the warm sunshine counting on
that. A couple of well-pitched games and the horror in the Bronx
will start to fade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0036EDT &QL; 
