<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SCRAMBLE AFTER GOALIES' INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Stephane Fiset is expected to be sidelined for at
least one game. Jamie Storr will miss at least a week.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the groin injuries suffered by their two goalies
10 minutes apart in the third period of Sunday's 5-5 tie with the
Colorado Avalanche, the Kings found themselves scrambling Monday as
they prepared for a five-game trip that begins Wednesday night
against the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset accompanied the Kings on their flight Monday to Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. Storr did not. He has been placed on injured
reserve, meaning he can't play for a week.
</P>
<P>
   To fill the void, the Kings (2-1-1) on Monday recalled Manny
Legace from the Long Beach Ice Dogs of the IHL and Alexey Volkov
from the Halifax Mooseheads of the Quebec Major Junior Hockey
League.
</P>
<P>
   Volkov, an 18-year-old from Russia, is expected to be the
backup. The 25-year-old Legace, who was recalled several times
earlier in his career while in the Hartford Whalers organization,
will make his NHL debut in Florida unless Fiset makes a miraculous
recovery between now and then.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, Legace was in Chicago with the Ice Dogs when their
coach, John Van Boxmeer, told him Fiset had been injured and that
he was going to be joining the Kings. But Legace didn't learn until
Monday afternoon, after flying to Florida, that both Kings goalies
had been hurt. He figured he'd been recalled to be Storr's backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably get really nervous and really emotional,''
Legace said, thinking ahead to the prospect of playing Wednesday.
``This is what I've been dreaming about since I was 4 years old,
ever since I laced up a pair of skates. But I feel kind of bad that
it's happening because guys have gotten injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Legace is 4-0 with a 1.75 goals-against average for the Ice
Dogs. Volkov, the Kings' third-round draft choice this year, is 8-0
for the Mooseheads, also with a 1.75 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a taste of the NHL, both of the Kings' new goalies
will notice a little more money in their upcoming paychecks. Both
are on two-way contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Legace's salary is $80,000 when he's in the minors, a prorated
portion of $400,000 for the time he's in the NHL. Volkov makes
$47,500 in junior hockey, $425,000 in the NHL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
