<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     10-20 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ The Padres keep telling themselves things will be
better at home, because that's all they have left in a World Series
that has abruptly left them in the gutter.
</P>
<P>
   It has happened before to other visitors to the Big Apple. The
bus pulls up, and the wide-eyed tourists step off like so many
innocent lambs being led to slaughter. Their pockets are picked
clean. They are victimized by the three-card monte dealers on 42nd
Street and the vendors selling ``Rolex'' watches for $20 at Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   So they come home and hope for a miracle or an earthquake or
anything at all that can shake loose the timely plays and the
clutch hits and the fierce confidence that had previously
victimized the Astros and Braves in the National League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In two games, the Yankees have come at them like a rolling
bundle of butcher knives, and the Padres have spent most of their
time in a defensive posture, trying unsuccessfully to avoid getting
cut.
</P>
<P>
   They gave up nine runs in Game 1 and nine runs in Game 2, and it
seems like all that's stopping the Yankees from running it up into
double figures is their more significant goal of getting this thing
over with and hurrying along into the history books.
</P>
<P>
   The way things are going, these Yankees _ the ones with no
individual stars in the tradition of Ruth, Gehrig, DiMaggio, Mantle
or Jackson _ will keep cruising to another pair of victories and
make their final season mark an incredible 125-50, which will rank
with the greatest of all time in any sport.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, the path the Yankees have been following
since they came blazing out of the starting gate in the spring. But
it's not the one that was entirely expected against the Padres, who
had previously shown a great penchant for shoving a wrench into the
gears of favored opponents and then making everything turn in their
direction.
</P>
<P>
   In beating the Astros in the NL Division Series, the Padres
settled quickly into Houston and stole away Game 1 behind Kevin
Brown. In dismissing the Braves in the NLCS, the Padres won all
three games played in Atlanta. They had become the road warriors of
these playoffs, the worst thing to hit towns this side of funnel
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   But that all stopped suddenly upon check-in at New York, where
their ace, Brown, first suffered from a case of the flu, then was
made to feel even more miserable by getting roughed up by the
Yankees' bats and the likes of a rookie left fielder in the opener.
When somebody named Ricky Ledee is ripping you for big hits at a
.667 clip, there is nothing at all fearsome about your reputation.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Andy Ashby stepped onto the mound to pitch Game 2
for the Padres, the Yankees were lining up to tee off, while the
Padres were meekly toting their bats back to the dugout
unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a certain attitude, an aggressive mindset, to survive
and to thrive in New York, and the Padres never demonstrated that
in the first two games. Their leader, Tony Gwynn, spoke politely
about making a pilgrimage to Monument Park in left field at Yankee
Stadium to see the plaques of the former greats. Greg Vaughn, who
had a trade to the Yankees nullified last year because he could not
pass a physical and then went out and clobbered 50 home runs this
season, never once took a verbal shot at New York management. Even
Jim Leyritz, the grizzled cowboy who had so many key hits against
Houston and Atlanta, returned to New York _ the scene of his 1996
World Series heroics _ and rode the subway to the ballpark and
chatted with the local fans.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Padres were a courteous bunch that was about as
interesting and ominous as the always-68-degree San Diego weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, of course, have helped themselves by showing great
patience at the plate, working the Padres' pitchers deep into the
count. Unlike the Astros, jumping like hungry gorillas on the first
banana, the Yankees forced Brown and Ashby into giving them strikes
to hit and then made the very most of those opportunities. Which
has quickly turned the expected into the seemingly inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The other night outside one gate at Yankee Stadium, the vendor
collected money for programs and said, ``See you next year.'' It
doesn't look like the Series is going back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   What the former NL terrors have left is a return to Qualcomm
Stadium, which is named after a cellular-phone company. Maybe
someone will call with the answer to the Yankees. Maybe there is no
answer.
</P>
<P>
   For the Padres, as Yogi Berra once said, ``It's getting late
early.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
