<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS &LR;      10-20 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SAN DIEGO _ ``Spank the Yanks'' is the phrase of choice here in
Mission Valley, where the San Diego Padres were glad to return
after some hostile treatment over the weekend at Yankee Stadium.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, their mission seems darned-near impossible. So
far, they've been on the wrong end of the corporal punishment, and
the New York Yankees are just two lashings shy of leaving a
permanent bruise.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time during their improbable jaunt through the
playoffs, the Padres have found themselves in a hole almost as big
as the valley they call home.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven World Series,
and they'll send 20-game winner David Cone to the mound tonight to
try to move one step closer to their second Series championship in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are hoping their fortunes will change before a
sold-out crowd at Qualcomm Stadium, but they know it will take more
than home cooking to nourish them back into title contention.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees outscored the Padres 18-9 in the first two games of
the Series and have pretty much had their way with the National
League champions. What is it going to take for the Padres to
finally win a game? Don't ask Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done it yet,'' Gwynn said. ``So I really don't know
what we're going to have to do to beat them. I have to admit, from
what I've seen of the Yankees, they're pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   While that may sound like a concession speech, the Padres are
hardly ready to throw in the towel. They appeared loose at Monday's
late-afternoon workout, during which several players had their
children on the field. If anything, the Padres appeared more
willing to get back on the field rather than spend the day off
answering questions about being down 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our morale is fine,'' said Gwynn, the only remaining Padre
from the 1984 World Series team. ``We're still confident that we
can win this thing, but we know we can't win it playing the way we
did in the first two games. I think we're just tired of talking
about it. I haven't been (to the World Series) in a while, so I
forgot how much you had to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 44 teams that have taken a 2-0 lead in the World Series,
33 have completed the job, including six in a row until the Yankees
overcame a 2-0 deficit to beat Atlanta in the 1996 World Series.
Twenty-two of the 29 teams that have won the first two games at
home have won the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Padres' odds will be worse if they don't win
tonight behind lefthander Sterling Hitchcock, who is 3-0 in the
postseason with victories over Randy Johnson, Greg Maddux and Tom
Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone asked me if we have to win (tonight's) game,'' Padres
third baseman Ken Caminiti said. ``I don't think we have to, but it
would be nice. I wouldn't say never with this team. I believe we
will win. I believe we can come back from anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some work cut out for us, but we'll have a change of
atmosphere (at Qualcomm Stadium). I thought some guys were finding
it hard to relax (in New York). I saw some guys taking deep
breaths. We're down a little. Everyone is a little ticked off. But
I think we'll be fine. I don't think being down two games to none
scares us. We're veterans. This team will loosen up (at home).''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres were 54-27 at Qualcomm Stadium this season, and they
were 10-1 when the crowd exceeded 50,000. They have won three of
their five games at home this postseason, and if they ever needed a
home-field advantage, now is the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home crowd could be huge for us,'' Gwynn said. ``But
that's only if we do the things we need to do to win. If we don't,
it will be quiet just like it was when (Andres) Galarraga hit that
grand slam (in the NL Championship Series).
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk about the home-field advantage all we want, but it
won't mean anything if we don't play better. That's the bottom
line; we have to play better, and it needs to start (tonight).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
