r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     10-20 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES DOWN BUT NOT OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ On the flight home, the San Diego Padres, down 2-0
in the series of their lives, were so quiet you could hear a peanut
drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were done, toast,'' Tony Gwynn said. ``Guys all had their
travel brochures out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Friars were fried.
</P>
<P>
   So how about some good news for Padres fans?
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn wasn't talking about (begin ital)these(end ital) Padres,
by all accounts a chipper group as they winged their way home from
New York early Monday morning after being bombed by the Yankees in
the first two games of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the 1984 Padres, who made their silent
flight home from Chicago after being outscored by the Cubs 17-2 in
the first two games of the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Padres fan, you know what happened next. As their
bus from the airport pulled up to the San Diego stadium late on
that Wednesday night 14 Octobers ago, their closed mouths dropped
open at the sight of hundreds of cheering fans in the parking lot,
an enormous welcoming committee. Gwynn remembers the crowd
numbering 5,000. Bruce Bochy, a Padres benchwarmer then and their
manager now, says it was more like 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, both say it revived the Padres, who took three
straight games from the Cubs in front of consecutive club-record
crowds, clinching the best-of-five series with the help of Gwynn's
bad-hop double and Leon Durham's fielding error.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans played a big role in helping us come back,'' Bochy
said Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that at least three Padres _ Gwynn, Bochy and
third-base coach Tim Flannery, another holdover from '84 _ have an
idea what it takes to overcome 0-2. Who could blame the rest if
they pulled out the cruise pamphlets?
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been awesome, the Padres have been miserable
beyond the need for second-guessing, and even the Padres' stabs at
the obligatory ``something positive'' sound far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take away the seventh inning of Game 1, and you've got a
pretty good series going,'' Gwynn said, referring to the Yankees'
(begin ital)seven-run(end ital) inning.
</P>
<P>
   What you've got is the Yankees scoring nine a game against the
Padres' 18- and 17-game winners, and nine-game winner Sterling
Hitchcock being counted on to stop the mayhem in Game 3 tonight at
Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   You've got a flu bug, or something, going through the Padres'
pitching staff, and possibility a shin bruise will keep Kevin Brown
from making his Game 4 start Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And lest anybody think the San Diego pitchers are the whole
problem here, there's also the matter of the Nos.3 through 6
hitters in their lineup going 1 for 12 with runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   Fans? Anybody? A little help!
</P>
<P>
   The Padres flew all night after Sunday's game and pulled into
the parking lot about 6 a.m. There were not 5,000 fans at that
hour. There were a few hundred, according to local television
reports.
</P>
<P>
   This is, generally, a city deflated after underdog wins over
Houston and Atlanta in the National League playoffs made it think
anything was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Soaking up local color at the bars and restaurants (and more
bars) of the Gaslamp Quarter Sunday evening, as Game 2 went from
3-0 to 6-0 to 7-0 in the early innings, one encountered a San Diego
sports publicist trudging up Fifth Street with a ``Yes on C''
placard under his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition C would approve the use of public money to build the
Padres a new park. The PR guy was shepherding around a video crew,
looking for outbreaks of baseball fever, fodder for a campaign
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not looking too good,'' he said outside a sports bar
where the game was being watched on a dozen TV screens by
long-faced Padres faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sun came up in a cloudless sky the next morning, and
all the ``Go Padres!'' signs remained in place in store windows and
on hotel marquees. A Padres T-shirt was still the uniform of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   San Diegans, once roused from their Garden of Eden slumber by a
winning team, tend to discover they like the feeling and don't want
to lose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rise to the occasion,'' Bochy said Monday, standing
behind the batting cage during an offday workout.
</P>
<P>
   What he was really saying was, the Padres need them to rise
again. Qualcomm is sold out the next three nights, and what the
fans lack in Yankee Stadium profanity, they'd better make up for in
sheer deafening noise.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the way the Yankees are going, picking up the Padres
might be too much to ask of only 65,000 people. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
