<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DISTRICT MAY BE MODEL FOR TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles educators learned Monday how a poor
Texas school district transformed itself into one of the best in
the Lone Star State by stressing test scores, involving parents and
holding employees accountable for student achievement _ even firing
a whole school staff.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Ysleta Independent School District in El
Paso described their successful reform efforts to more than 200
parents, teachers and administrators during a daylong conference
sponsored by the Los Angeles Annenberg Metropolitan Project and the
Annenberg Institute for School Reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas delegation is in town just as LAUSD Superintendent
Ruben Zacarias is receiving a series of reports on accountability
from a task force of parents, educators and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a very powerful model for our folks to
explore,'' said Maria Casillas, president of LAAMP. ``We're
beginning to explore how to build public understanding of school
reform ... and move forward to school accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Located near the U.S.-Mexico border, Ysleta was considered one
of the worst school districts in the state five years ago. Last
year, up to 90percent of its students passed the Texas Assessment
of Academic Skills _ a standardized exam of reading, writing and
math _ at higher rates than any other large-city district in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the lowest-scoring urban school district,'' said
Ysleta Superintendent Anthony Trujillo. ``Last year, we were the
first `recognized' urban school district in the state,'' &UR;  &LR; a special
commendation conferred by Texas education officials.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the accountability system, Trujillo fired the entire
staff of a high school, removed all but 19 of 58 principals
districtwide and forced out 2,000 teachers of 3,000 in the system.
He also gave schools control over their budgets and curriculum,
gave principals the authority to hire and fire teachers and urged
parents to participate in campus decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can do it with 50,000 students (in Ysleta), you can do
it with 600,000 (in the LAUSD),'' Trujillo told the Los Angeles
audience. ``The key is the 1.2million parents out in your
community.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Los Angeles Unified School District board members,
administrators and parents visited Texas to study the state's
accountability system and see how districts such as Ysleta
implemented reforms.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD parent activists said they were impressed by what they saw
in Ysleta, and want to replicate many of its reforms but fear they
face a contentious political battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can do it but we need a school board that will back
the superintendent and the school district,'' said Kathleen Dixon,
chairwoman of the LAUSD's parent collaborative and a member of the
superintendent's accountability task force. ``We need a school
board that is willing to make hard political decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
