<HEADER>
A6153 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-20 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS HAS BAT IN TUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ You could say Bernie Williams was classically
trained to be a featured attraction in the Bronx Zoo. As a
teen-ager he studied the guitar with the idea of becoming a
professional musician.
</P>
<P>
   The instrument he wields now is a very different kind of wood,
but the setting really hasn't changed all that much. As in his
recital days, he practices for months for that one shot, as he put
it, ``to get it right'' when everyone is looking.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday in the visiting clubhouse of Qualcomm Stadium, the
Yankees center fielder spoke of sitting alone in front of the whole
school in his native Puerto Rico, playing a piece of music he had
been memorizing for months and being graded on the performance. He
was 15 or 16 when he had an experience on that stage that would
help steel him for the day, years later, when he'd be standing in
the batter's box on baseball's grandest stage staring at an 0-2
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing a Brazilian piece. A beautiful piece, too,''
said Williams wistfully. ``I got about halfway through it and I
blanked out. So I started again and on the exact same chord, I
blanked out again. I went running off the stage crying.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment Williams let the memory carry him off like a
long-forgotten melody. Then he shook his head and chuckled. What
seemed so traumatic then sounds trivial now.
</P>
<P>
   No one at his school, after all, carried batteries and change in
their pockets to throw at the first sound of a discordant note. No
one from his school newspaper reported that he would be moving on
to another school next year. No one at his school made him feel
uncomfortable in his own skin.
</P>
<P>
   Williams wishes he could say he has enjoyed the Yankees'
remarkable run this season. Instead, he settles for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a grind,'' said the man who won his first batting
title and second Gold Glove in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is no small reason why the Yankees have won 123 games
and are on the edge of something ethereal. If they can put away a
San Diego team that they have outscored 18-9 in the first two games
of this World Series, Williams, 30, will go down as the all-around
best player on arguably the all-time greatest team.
</P>
<P>
   He's a huge part of the Yankees' present, but he doesn't know
how he figures in their future. Williams will be a free agent the
day after the curtain falls on the season and he isn't convinced
the Yankees will pay whatever it costs to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Some media reports already have his bags packed and tagged for
Arizona. In the American League Championship Series, the
speculation about his future reached a crescendo and Williams
started to feel trapped, like air in a singer's larynx.
</P>
<P>
   He had to escape, lest he let slip away the focus that enabled
him to play a sonata on stage or hit the sweet spot of the bat
precisely as he had practiced it over and over and over.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees' best-of-seven series against Cleveland found
Williams taking a commercial flight instead of the team charter and
evading reporters and champagne corks, ``simplifying things'' in
his words.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' uncharacteristic aloofness raised eyebrows among
outsiders, but inside the clubhouse, right fielder Paul O'Neill
said, everything was harmonious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier for him that way,'' O'Neill said. ``We understand
that you only have so much room in your head and sometimes all the
media and all the distractions take you away from your game.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' focus found its way back to Yankee Stadium Sunday,
making a grand entrance in Game 2 of the best-of-seven series that
continues tonight. In his second at-bat against Padres starter Andy
Ashby, Williams saw two quick strikes. He didn't panic, as someone
who had gone hitless in the previous game might have been wont to
do. Instead, he got really, really patient.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at two balls, fouled off the fifth pitch, looked at
another ball _ that made the count, 3-2 _ fouled off another pitch
and then sent Ashby's eighth offering into the bleachers for a
two-run home run that extended the Yankees' lead to 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to a musician to hold out for the perfect pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Williams called it ``one of the best at-bats I've had all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things I strive for as a hitter, to have the
odds so against you and then work your way through it and get the
best possible result,'' he said. ``Most of my home runs this year
have been on the first couple of pitches. I've gotten a hold of a
mistake and hit it out. The fact that I had to struggle so bad and
work so hard for that pitch made (the homer) remarkable in
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   That it broke wide open a World Series game made an impression
on a lot of other people.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson, one of the finalists for the Dodgers' managerial
position, was so moved by what he witnessed, he urged George
Steinbrenner to re-sign Williams, whom he referred to as ``the
heart and soul'' of the ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of chorus that has the Yankees' Melody Man
reaching for his guitar a lot these days. If you're Williams,
nothing cuts through the tension like a few chords. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
