<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6155 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-HNS &LR;      10-20 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SAN DIEGO _ They're a blue-clad, mask-wearing fraternity that every
manager, player and devout baseball fan loves to hate.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when umpires considered themselves a success if
no one noticed them or talked about them. Nowadays, umps are
constantly analyzed, scrutinized and second-guessed.
</P>
<P>
   Some are well-respected, others reviled. They are bumped and
occasionally spit at, and, oh, are they stirring up some dust.
</P>
<P>
   After one of the most memorable baseball seasons ever, the
postseason has turned into open season on the umps. Names such as
McGwire, Sosa and Ripken find themselves replaced by Hendry,
Brinkman and McKean.
</P>
<P>
   Who?
</P>
<P>
   Ask Toronto Blue Jays righthander Roger Clemens, a four-time Cy
Young Award winner, and he can tell you just about anything you
want to know about the threesome and many of the other 61 full-time
umps in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens regularly compiles files on how each umpire interprets
the strike zone. Scouting umpires, as well as scouting opponents,
is a major part of a pitcher's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing that is important for me to know about umpires
is where they call balls and strikes,'' Clemens said last week. ``I
try to keep track of which umpires call an east-west strike zone
and which call north-south.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein, some baseball insiders say, lies the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Umpires long ago stopped using the strike zone as specified in
the rule book, ignoring the area above the waist. Many are going to
a broader interpretation, sometimes calling strikes on pitches that
are several inches from either side of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Some umpires call low strikes; some call high strikes. Still
others call wide inside or outside pitches for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' New York Yankees outfielder Paul O'Neill
said. ``I don't know if they're intentionally doing it to speed
games up. But if the strike zone is here (gesturing with his
hands), they're going to throw it there. If it's here, they're
going to throw it there. As wide as they go, the pitchers are going
to continually throw wider and wider.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the plate umpire's definition of the strike
zone has become a hot topic during this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2 of the American League Division Series between
Cleveland and Boston, Joe Brinkman's ball-and-strike calls provoked
a dispute that led to his ejecting Indians manager Mike Hargrove _
three pitches into the game. Cleveland starting pitcher Dwight
Gooden was tossed after he had faced only four batters and thrown
22 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's World Series opener, home-plate umpire Richie
Garcia was criticized for his call on a 2-and-2 pitch from San
Diego reliever Mark Langston to Tino Martinez with two out in the
seventh inning. Garcia called the pitch, which appeared to be
straight down the middle, a ball, and Martinez smacked a
game-deciding grand slam on the next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Garcia was working Game 1 of the ALCS when a
young boy reached over the Yankee Stadium fence and caught Derek
Jeter's fly ball just as Baltimore's Tony Tarasco prepared to catch
it. Garcia ruled no interference, and the non-call helped the
Yankees set the tone for the series.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove said most players don't mind a different strike zone,
but it becomes a problem when few umpires stick to it. Some umpires
subscribe to the ``call 'em as you see 'em'' theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our job to adjust to that strike zone,'' Hargrove said.
``Nobody has a problem with that. What's a problem is one time this
is a ball, and the next time it's a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   National League umpire Eric Gregg came under fire during Game 5
of the NLCS in 1997 with his broad strike zone, routinely giving
Florida Marlins rookie Livan Hernandez the outside part of the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out 15 Atlanta Braves in the game, ending the
game by ringing up Fred McGriff on a called third strike _ a curve
that never ventured closer than a foot to what the rule book
defines as the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know me,'' Gregg said in a postgame interview, ``you
know my strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   NL director of umpires Paul Runge, however, said the strike zone
does not fall under the category of a judgment call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody interprets (the strike zone) the same, but I
don't think everybody handles it the same,'' Runge said. ``But I
don't think any umpire should have his strike zone. There is no
umpire with his strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he makes that statement, I think it's a mis-statement. I
don't think he really means that. The strike zone is the strike
zone. When he reads the book, he reads it the same as anybody else.
If he adjusts his strike zone to something different than what it
should be, he'll have to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy among umpires hasn't been contained to balls and
strikes. Ted Hendry, who worked the AL Championship Series,
triggered a national debate for not calling interference against
Cleveland's Travis Fryman in Game 2. Fryman, who bunted down the
first-base line, was hit by a throw from Yankees first baseman Tino
Martinez to second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who was covering first.
The Indians went on to score the go-ahead run as Knoblauch
protested while the ball was still in play, lying untouched on the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 6, Hendry called Bernie Williams safe at second, ruling
that Cleveland shortstop Omar Vizquel's foot came off the base
before he caught the ball _ a ruling even some of the Yankees
thought was the wrong call.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4, Jeter was attempting to steal second in the fifth
inning when an on-target throw from Sandy Alomar Jr. hit Jim
McKean, who tried to jump out of the way but kicked the ball into
right field.
</P>
<P>
   Hendry was also hit by a line drive by Vizquel in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   How can such mistakes happen at such a pivotal point of the
season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you do in your career is magnified (in the
postseason). Your name is synonymous with the play,'' AL director
of umpires Marty Springstead said. ``People don't forget. They seem
to remember one play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's so unfair. There are hundreds of plays, and probably 99
percent are all right. We're not superhumans, and we don't pretend
to be. We're trying to do our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the system that took effect in 1995, all umpires are
eligible for postseason play and the All-Star Game. However, an
umpire cannot work more than one ``special event'' _ All-Star Game,
League Championship Series or World Series _ in a year, although he
can work a Division Series and the World Series. No umpire can work
successive World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Under an earlier collective-bargaining agreement, umpires were
chosen strictly on a rotating basis. The leagues have long awaited
a merit system to determine who works the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The three AL umpires _ crew chief Garcia, Dale Scott and Tim
Tschida _ who are on the six-man World Series crew worked during
the first round of the playoffs. Jerry Crawford, Dana DeMuth and
Mark Hirschbeck represent the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speak for the NL, but these guys are right at the
top,'' Runge said of Crawford, DeMuth and Hirschbeck, who have a
combined 46 years' experience in the NL. ``They are the best-rated
guys from this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratings become irrelevant, however, when television puts every
call and play under a microscope. During one game in the ALCS, NBC
showed diagrams and charts of the strike zone after several
disputed calls.
</P>
<P>
   Even with certain camera angles, though, there isn't an accurate
gauge of determining who's right and who's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of eyes on you. There are all kinds of ways
for television to pinpoint every single thing,'' said ESPN analyst
Kevin Kennedy, a leading candidate to become the next manager of
the Los Angeles Dodgers. ``You have to realize everybody is human,
everybody different. Everybody sees things a different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there is a strike zone by definition, the umpires
aren't computers back there. That's what makes the human element of
the sport so great, because there are going to be replays that say,
`Oh, maybe that was a ball; maybe that guy was out.' Over the
course of the long haul, for the most part things work out pretty
even.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't stopped the media from scrutinizing the umpires.
Throughout the World Series, the Los Angeles Times is running a
guest column by Doug Harvey, who umpired in the NL for 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   What did he think of Garcia's calls in Game 1?
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the entire ballgame, I saw two pitches that I might
have possibly disagreed with _ one in the fourth inning that was
called a strike and the 2-2 pitch to Tino Martinez in the
seventh,'' wrote Harvey, who worked more than 4,000 consecutive
games from 1962 to 1988. ``Of course, that's the pitch that
everybody was griping about.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you went out there and you measured it with the finest
instruments in the world, you'd find out that pitch was in that
gray zone between a ball and a strike. It's in that zone, because
the difference in an umpire's eye between ball and strike is a fine
pencil-lead mark. And that son of a gun, that's where it was _ it's
in one of those gray zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for some reason _ it's the bane of the Irish, it's the
luck of the umpire _ you always seem to get a pitch like that with
bases stacked. I guarantee you, the next one's at least going off
the wall someplace. It always seems to happen. That same pitch, if
it's a tied ballgame and nobody's on base, everybody says, `Aw,
c'mon, get the ball up. Oh, hey, it's a little low.' And they move
on. But because of the situation, it suddenly becomes a big, big
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Springstead: ``Any mistake (in the playoffs) is magnified
a hundred-fold. I think the postseason has always been
pressure-packed. It used to be everybody watched the World Series.
Now, they watch the Division Series and there are more
opportunities to visualize umpires making mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
