<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL'S NEW RULES NEED WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ROGER PHILLIPS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When Wayne Gretzky's New York Rangers scored three goals on
Saturday night, it was a veritable offensive explosion for the
Broadway Blueshirts, which should tell you something about how
effective the NHL's new offense-friendly rules were in the first 10
days of the new season.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller, narrower crease, the extra two feet behind the net,
the size restrictions on goalies' equipment all were supposed to
lead to more scoring, which would lead to more fans, which would
lead to higher television ratings, which would lead to more
revenue, which would lead to hockey becoming the hot sport of the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some numbers: In 1981-82, the year Gretzky scored a
record 92 goals for Edmonton, teams combined to average eight goals
a game. Last season, the average was 5.28. Through Sunday this
season, with 52 games in the books played under the new rules, the
average was 4.75.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest impediment to more scoring is those darned coaches.
They like to keep their jobs, which requires winning, and in an era
of 27 teams and not enough offensive talent to go around, the
surest road to success is keeping the puck out of your own net. The
defenses have gotten so stingy, in fact, that even a team such as
Colorado _ one of a diminishing number of clubs with excellent
offensive depth _ struggles at times to score. The Avalanche was
shut out twice in its first three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 2-1 games because defense wins in hockey,'' said
Boston coach Pat Burns, whose team already has recorded three
shutouts this season. ``If you cut down on your goals-against
average, you have a chance. If you don't, you're not going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson agrees more credit needs to go to
those who are responsible for the low scores.
</P>
<P>
   Said Robinson, ``Do they ever think that maybe teams are
concentrating more on playing well at both ends of the rink and
goaltenders are doing a good job of keeping the puck out of the
net?''
</P>
<P>
   One man's proposal: Kings center Ray Ferraro says he thinks if
the NHL really wants to perk up offense, it should experiment
seriously with eliminating the center red line for two-line passes.
It would still be used for icing.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the two-line pass would allow for more wide-open
play. A defenseman could feed the puck ahead to a forward hanging
on the far side of the neutral zone, which presumably would lead to
more breakaways and outnumbered rushes.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro said he's not surprised this season's rules changes have
had such a minimal effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two feet behind the net is not going to open up the game,''
Ferraro said. ``That's not the magical answer. The only thing I've
seen to open up games is to take away the red line. But if they
want to do that, they have to try it in every exhibition game.''
</P>
<P>
   During this preseason, there were 109 games, with teams
combining for an average of six goals a game. In 12 of those games,
the red line was eliminated, with teams averaging 6.17 goals. In
the 97 games played with a red line, teams averaged 5.89.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are hardly compelling, and there is one major
reason why eliminating the red line might not be the solution: With
teams already so focused on defense, they probably would play even
more conservatively than they do now in order to avoid those
breakaways and outnumbered attacks. Still, eliminating the red line
might be worth more of a look than it so far has been given.
</P>
<P>
   Another embarrassment: The NHL just can't seem to get through a
season without at least one major embarrassment involving a
franchise owner.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't former Kings owner Bruce McNall ending up in prison
for fraud or former New York Islanders owner John Spano ending up
in prison for his own McNallian activities or the new Islanders
owners trying and failing to escape their county-owned arena by
claiming that it's falling down, then it's the Pittsburgh Penguins
sliding into bankruptcy six years after winning two consecutive
Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Pittsburgh has spent nearly $13 million in public
funds to prop up the franchise, yet new co-owner Roger Marino came
onto the scene, knowingly took on millions of dollars in debt to
former Penguins players (including about $30 million to the retired
Mario Lemieux), tried to avoid some of those commitments, then
rewarded the Steel City's taxpayers for propping up the team by
investigating relocation of the franchise to Kansas City or
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, commissioner Gary Bettman may get the NHL's house
completely tidy. But that day doesn't appear likely anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Snowed under: While the Penguins are flailing about off the ice,
the Avalanche is struggling on it. Just a little more than two
years ago the Avalanche captured the Stanley Cup, led by young
stars Joe Sakic and Peter Forsberg and a deep, talented squad. The
future appeared bright.
</P>
<P>
   But the Avalanche has not been back to the finals since winning
the Cup, and last season Colorado was bounced from the playoffs in
the first round. This season, following a 5-5 tie Sunday with the
Kings, Colorado is off to a disappointing 0-4-1 start.
</P>
<P>
   What's happened? Up front, Colorado is still to be envied, led
by franchise centers Sakic and Forsberg. But the Avalanche is thin
on defense, and the absence of unsigned power-play quarterback
Sandis Ozolinsh has Colorado off to a 2-for-27 start with the man
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all this, goalie Patrick Roy will be an unrestricted
free agent at season's end and looked extremely ordinary in
Sunday's tie with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the heck is wrong with me,'' said Roy, 33.
``I wish I knew. I've got to play with more intensity, there's no
doubt about it. I'm soft right now and I have to start playing
hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche has too much talent to remain in its early-season
rut. On the other hand, they have a long way to go to reclaim the
stature they enjoyed such a short time ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
