<HEADLINE>
WIN BORING, BUT BEAUTIFUL  
 KHABIBULIN FACES ONLY 14 SHOTS IN STUFFING BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a guy who only gave up one goal and just saw his team win
for the second straight time, Coyotes goalie Nikolai Khabibulin
didn't look too upbeat in the team's dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice game,'' someone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Khabibulin answered. ``It wasn't so good at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Coyotes just stuffed the Boston Bruins, 3-1?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, and it was the most boring game I've played in the
National Hockey League,'' Khabibulin said. ``It wasn't any fun.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. So Khabibulin only had to face 14 shots. Ask the 25-year-old
Russian, and he'd tell you he'd rather face 40 every night. But ask
his teammates, and they'll say Khabibulin should shut his trap and
be khabby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to kill him for saying something like
that,'' said captain Keith Tkachuk, who scored his first goal of
the season and whose line dominated the Bruins throughout most of
the game. ``We don't want to see him face 40-50 shots. We know he's
a good goalie. But we know we're doing our job when he only faces
14 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (2-1-0), coming off an equally impressive 5-2 rout
of Colorado on Thursday, now have scored eight goals in their past
two games and have gotten nine goals overall from nine different
players.
</P>
<P>
   Center Cliff Ronning and right wing Dallas Drake also scored
goals, and the Coyotes also got two assists from Jeremy Roenick.
Tkachuk's line, which includes Drake and Roenick, accounted for
five of a possible nine points on the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked real well together, I think,'' Roenick said. ``Our
line is very powerful, offensively, and we do the job, defensively.
A lot of you media people were talking about how we shouldn't be
playing together, but tonight was a perfect example of how we can
mesh and jell as long as we keep it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, the Coyotes controlled the tempo and took it
right to the Bruins, who were playing for the third time in four
nights and are in the middle of a seven-game trip, their longest of
the season. It showed.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for good things to happen, either. On
Tkachuk's second shift, he and Roenick took turns throwing a series
of big body checks on veteran defenseman Ray Bourque in the Phoenix
zone. The old man must have been drilled three or four times along
the boards.
</P>
<P>
   It created space for Roenick and Tkachuk to operate, and after
Drake gave Bourque a check of his own for good measure, he fed
Roenick, who in turn, fed Tkachuk right in front for an easy
one-timer.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes captain finally was cheered instead of jeered by the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew the fans in this town were behind me,'' he said,
referring to the criticism he took for his prolonged contract
holdout this summer.
</P>
<P>
   So much for another Boston shutout. Goalie Byron Dafoe, Monday's
starter, had two of them coming in. Backup Robbie Tallas had one
the night before in San Jose. The three shutouts in five games were
the most ever for a Bruins' team in the franchise's storied,
75-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Ronning made the score, 2-0, at the start of the second period,
wristing a shot high over Dafoe's right shoulder toward the end of
a five-minute man-advantage situation. Boston left wing Rob DiMaio
gave it to the Coyotes, drawing a major elbowing penalty _ and a
game misconduct _ for going at Drake's head at the 16:58 mark of
the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ferraro got a loose puck alone in front of Khabibulin and
made the score, 2-1, on what was just Boston's third shot of the
game 24 minutes and 31 seconds after the first drop of the puck.
The Coyotes got their two-goal cushion back, though, when Drake
sent a hard slap shot past Dafoe midway through the second on a
setup pass from Roenick for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin and the penalty-killing unit finished the job. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
