</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOT IN THE ARM  
 DEVILS HOPE FOR BOOST WITH QB SWITCH 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-QB-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what may prove to be the most important audible of the
season, Arizona State Coach Bruce Snyder named Chad Elliott as
starting quarterback for Thursday's game against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said he hopes the redshirt freshman can salvage the
season for a team off to a disappointing 2-4 start. It marks the
end, at least temporarily, of a mystifying effort by sophomore Ryan
Kealy, whose accuracy and decision-making has fallen far short of
his impressive 1997 debut.
</P>
<P>
   After benching Kealy for Elliott in a 28-9 loss to Notre Dame on
Oct. 10, Snyder did some soul-searching before meeting with all of
his quarterbacks individually Sunday and breaking the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically told me he thought about this a lot, and he
decided on me to be the starter right now,'' Elliott said. ``He
said he thought it would give us the best opportunity to win games
and get back on track. He said go out there and have a good time
and play like I have before.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to play it cool,'' he said. ``I hid my smile and then
called my dad the first thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy, understandably, was somber after Monday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine,'' he said. ``He's a great quarterback and hopefully
he'll lead these guys to a couple of wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it fair? Yeah, it's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy said he'll be ready if called to come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be prepared to play, but I probably won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott has played in five games, completing 26 of 48 pass
attempts for 249 yards, one touchdown and one interception. Kealy
was 78 of 143 with eight touchdowns and seven interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott played most of ASU's game against Southern California
after Kealy suffered a concussion and the entire fourth quarter
against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's strength may be his deep ball. Whether he proves as
accurate as Kealy, who was particularly effective with mid-range
passes during his peak last season, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws a real nice deep ball,'' wide receiver Lenzie
Jackson said. ``He just kind of hangs it up there, a real tight
spiral, and gives you a chance to run up under it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Elliott, ``I like throwing it to these guys because they'll
go up and get it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott came to ASU from Sacramento's Grant High School, an
inner-city school he transferred to after his junior year because
he liked its program. He threw for 3,150 yards, 47 touchdowns and
three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   He is confident, although Snyder suggested Monday that it has
been portrayed unfairly as arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real confident when he comes in there. You can tell he's
not nervous,'' Jackson said. ``You wouldn't be able to tell he's a
freshman. We're all confident that he's going to get us the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Elliott, ``You have to have confidence to perform at this
level, or you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence is something Kealy appears to have lacked recently.
How this decision will affect him is unknown. But surely he has
dwelled upon the ramifications if Elliott continues to play well.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's performance will be under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evaluation we've just gone through is probably ongoing,''
Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   On Kealy's psyche, Snyder said, ``My job as a head coach is to
care about each player. I know how Ryan is and how emotional he is.
I care about him as I would anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said, ``He's handling it real well out here in practice.
I feel for him, but he's a team player so I'm sure he'll take it in
stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott has longed for this opportunity. He has suggested in the
past that he would consider transferring if he felt a starting job
wasn't in his future.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is probably a good starting debut for him. The Cardinal
ranks last in the Pac-10 in pass, rush and scoring defense. &QL; 
Notes &QL; 
Other personnel changes for Thursday's game include Thomas Schmidt
replacing Troy Davis at right tackle. Snyder said it was a move
based on performance.
</P>
<P>
   Kickoff for ASU's Oct. 31 game against Washington State has been
set at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Stephen Trejo is expected to play against Stanford
but will return to the inside after spending much of the season
outside. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
