<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-CASSTEVENS-TYSON-     10-20 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-CASSTEVENS-TYSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON MAY BARK, BUT BITE IS GONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Mike Tyson stopped and smelled the flowers, would the flowers
be afraid?
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, the answer was yes. Every living thing feared
Tyson, the ghetto kid, the ex-delinquent from Brooklyn. Iron Mike
was the ``baddest man on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, Tyson knocked out Marvis Frazier in 30
seconds. Don King can't clear his throat in 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, 1986, Tyson met Trevor Berbick for the
heavyweight title. When the bell sounded, the 20-year-old
challenger launched himself from his corner like a missile from an
aircraft carrier. Berbick, whose name sounds like that of a
newscaster on the BBC, was doomed.
</P>
<P>
   The fight lasted two rounds. Tyson threw 106 punches. He set up
Berbick with a right behind the ear and then anesthetized him with
a left hook to the head.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest heavyweight champ in history described the punch as
``murder.''
</P>
<P>
   He exploded on the scene like no fighter since the young poet
Cassius Clay. But there was nothing lyrical about Tyson's
pugilistic style. He was as swift and efficient as a butcher.
</P>
<P>
   Black satin trunks. No socks. Tattooed biceps. During prefight
instructions, he fixed opponents with a malevolent glare. He sensed
their fear _ he could smell it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Naked aggression &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tyson knocked out Michael Spinks in 91 seconds. As if
anticipating his fate, Spinks wore kneepads into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was, and is, a psychological study. ``We fear that naked
aggression,'' Bill Hoffman, a psychiatrist, once said. ``Tyson has
that pure animal brutality in the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   A convicted rapist, Tyson's celebrity grew. So did his
box-office appeal. When he returned to the ring after serving three
years in prison, he became the most popular villain in boxing
history _ more fearsome and far better known than former
prizefighter Wilbert Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vampire'' Johnson didn't wear a robe, favoring a black satin
cape. He would enter the ring in a coffin and drink red-colored
water.
</P>
<P>
   Scary? Buster Mathis Jr. stood nose to nose with Tyson and
contemplated the violence that was about to pour out. Buster didn't
last long, although he did remain upright longer than Peter
McNeeley.
</P>
<P>
   In Tyson's first fight as a free man, he KO'd McNeeley in 89
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was bad, bad to the bone. He cultivated an aura of
invincibility. His fights ended so quickly that King _ his promoter
and boxing's carnival barker _ felt it necessary to point out to
the paying public, some of whom felt they weren't getting their
money's worth, ``A good fight does not involve longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Bruno nervously made the sign of the cross as he walked
reluctantly to the ring. Tyson knocked him out in three rounds and
won the World Boxing Council heavyweight title. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meeting his match &QL; 
 &QL; 
Then Tyson met a man who didn't fear him, who didn't cower, didn't
flinch. Evander Holyfield knocked Tyson down. The fight ended in
the 11th round.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield won again seven months later when Tyson, losing, bit
Holyfield's ears and was disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson got his boxing license back Monday. If he isn't convicted
on assault charges stemming from a car accident, he will return to
the ring, perhaps as early as December.
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't the same.
</P>
<P>
   He never will be.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield stripped away Iron Mike's mythical aura. He exposed
him as mere flesh and blood _ mortal, vulnerable, beatable.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson hadn't bitten Holyfield, his career might be over.
Strangely, because he did, Tyson remains a big attraction. A
celebrity, in a weird way. A curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he can reinvent himself. But he won't have the fear factor
in his corner like he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``His toughest fight will be the first opponent who is not
afraid of him,'' ex-champ Larry Holmes said. ``Tyson's hole card
has been tipped. Holyfield showed how to to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't run.
</P>
<P>
   Stand your ground.
</P>
<P>
   Box.
</P>
<P>
   David Casstevens can be reached at 444-8635 or
david.casstevens(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
