<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6178 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-J-ARRETT-A     10-20 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-J-ARRETT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT DRIVES ON SPEEDWAYS, NOT FAIRWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ned Jarrett did what any parent might do with a scratch golfer
in the family. He tried steering his son toward Pebble Beach, not
Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale was very, very good,'' the elder Jarrett said. ``He was a
zero handicap, and we thought he had the potential to be on the PGA
Tour. So did a lot of other local professional golfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I personally knew how tough it was in racing. I knew the
sacrifices he would have to make, and I just didn't want to see him
have to go through the long period of time it would take to into
NASCAR (Winston Cup) racing. It's a hard road.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, for stock-car fans, Dale Jarrett didn't listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could think about was working on race cars and then
driving them. I knew I'd never be happy without at least giving
racing a try,'' said Dale, who won the equivalent of Arizona's 4A
high school golf championship as a senior in 1974 at Newton-Conover
(N.C.) High School, where he also was the football team's starting
quarterback, the baseball team's starting first baseman and one of
two starting forwards on the basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Although the younger Jarrett turned down golf scholarships to
Alabama and South Carolina and football scholarships to two smaller
four-year colleges, he's never thought twice about the decision.
</P>
<P>
   And after twice winning the Daytona 500, last season's Dura
Lube/Kmart 500 at Phoenix International Raceway _ he will try for a
repeat on Sunday _ and 15 other races in a Winston Cup career that
began in earnest 11 years ago, it's not likely Jarrett will ever
look back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senior PGA Tour? I can't ever imagine me doing that,''
said Jarrett, 41. ``I don't play that much anymore. (Sponsor
commitments) and racing keep me so busy, I just don't have the
time. I probably play to about a 10 or 11 handicap now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing still comes first for me.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Jarrett's perseverance almost was rewarded with his
first Winston Cup championship. He won a career-high seven races
and finished a scant 14 points behind series champion Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett thought this season might be even glossier. But finishes
of 34th and 40th in two of the first three races put him in a hole
too steep to completely overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Although three wins, 12 top-three finishes and 17 top-five
finishes have rallied him to third in the driver's standings with
three remaining races, Jarrett knows its unlikely he'll climb any
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'd have to give us an eight (on a scale of 1 to
10),'' said Jarrett, who trails second place Mark Martin by 262
points and is mathematically eliminated from chasing down Gordon.
``It wasn't the year we were looking for. We thought we'd be
battling for the championship. But it's still been a good year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is Mark Martin's had a 9.5 season, and Jeff Gordon
has had a 10. It's hard to give someone a perfect score, but
(Gordon's team has) done all the right things.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett blamed the rough start and the introduction of the Ford
Taurus as two major reasons for the slight decline on the driver
pedestal. But the main enemy, Jarrett said, has been the engine
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some uncharacteristic engine problems,'' Jarrett
said. ``That's what's hurt us the most. It's kind of strange
because it's really our strong point.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we've definitely had our work cut out for us trying to get
the Taurus to run like we wanted it to. Then, at other times, we've
put ourselves in holes where we really had to play catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Indianapolis (in the Brickyard 400), we got four laps down.
We ended up making those laps up, but we still finished way down
(16th).''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Indianapolis also showcased Jarrett's unwavering mettle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't won as much this year and they're further down on
the points ladder, but I think Dale's done some of his best driving
this season,'' said the elder Jarrett, a two-time NASCAR driving
champion. ``He drove his heart out at Indianapolis and finished on
the lead lap. I thought that was a tremendous driving feat.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Patrick, who for 25 years has been Newton-Conover's football
coach, isn't surprised Jarrett refused to throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale was a natural athlete and a natural leader when he was
here,'' Patrick said. ``He led by example. He never gave up at
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really was a `Cool Hand Luke.' '' &QL;
</P>
