<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
JETS BEAT PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
 FBN-PATRIOTS-JETS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Nick Cafardo  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Curse of the Tuna continues.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells and Curtis Martin left their former home field
with ear-to-ear smiles last night, while Pete Carroll, who was on
the verge of receiving the respect he seems to deserve, walked away
sad.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and Jets defensive coordinator Bill Belichick put
together a tremendous game plan, holding the Patriots scoreless in
the second half as New York posted a 24-14 victory that
disappointed 60,062 fans at Foxboro Stadium and left a locker room
full of Patriots shell-shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what went wrong,'' lamented Patriots defensive
tackle Chad Eaton. ``I get sick and tired of hearing it was because
Bill Parcells was standing over at the other side. That wasn't it
at all. We haven't been able to win on Monday night. Maybe it's a
Monday night jinx or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we have too many young players who still don't
understand what it takes to win a big game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety Willie Clay said, ``Our goal was to win all of our home
games. But we still have another chance to beat them at their
place. It's disappointing because we were ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets trailed at halftime, 14-10, but scored twice in the
fourth quarter as quarterback Vinny Testaverde, who is now 3-0 as a
starter, completed 22 of 32 passes for 294 yards and three
touchdowns, two of them 1-yard throws to tight end Kyle Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde did everything Drew Bledsoe couldn't do. The Patriots
quarterback threw a costly interception into the end zone in the
third quarter that seemed to turn the momentum the Jets' way.
Bledsoe (18 of 30 for 206 yards) had taken the Patriots from their
4 to the Jets' 18 before Bledsoe, intending to hit Shawn Jefferson
in the left corner of the end zone, underthrew the pass and had it
picked off by Aaron Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They borrowed some stuff from the Broncos, where they rolled
over the safeties on the weak side,'' said Bledsoe. ``They didn't
use much else to surprise us beyond that. The fact is, I missed on
the play in the end zone and we committed too many penalties (11
for 71 yards) along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense again had problems on third down (the Jets
converted 62 percent), while New York played a containment game
(they allowed Robert Edwards 104 yards on 22 carries).
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless third quarter, the Jets took their first lead
since the first quarter when they drove 80 yards on 17 plays and
ate up 8:35 of the clock. Testaverde's 1-yard pass to Brady _ after
Martin was stuffed on first and goal _ put the Jets ahead, 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' hopes of a comeback went up in smoke on the Jets'
next possession when Testaverde threw a 43-yard bomb down the right
sideline to Dedric Ward, who beat Chris Canty and caught the ball
on the fly, making it 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was one in which both the new back and the old
back showed their talents. Edwards carried 16 times for 67 yards
and caught two passes for 15 yards, while his predecessor, Martin,
carried 11 times for 62 yards for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   But the game couldn't have started _ or ended _ any worse for
New England.
</P>
<P>
   On the first series, Bledsoe threw too low to Shawn Jefferson,
too long for Terry Glenn, and then got sacked by Anthony Pleasant.
Three and out.
</P>
<P>
   Then the reliable Tom Tupa, punting into a stiff wind, lined a
37-yarder, his shortest kick of the season, to the Jets' 44.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Testaverde made it look easy. He connected on passes
of 20, 14, and 11 yards, while Martin, on his first carry against
his former teammates, avoided a 5-yard loss on a missed tackle by
Lawyer Milloy and rambled 6 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The drive culminated with a 1-yard pass from Testaverde to Brady
for a touchdown on a questionable call. It appeared that linebacker
Ted Johnson had forced a fumble before the ball crossed the goal
line, and replays supported that, but the score stood.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were not demoralized by this. Any notion that
Parcells was getting into Bledsoe's head was dismissed when Bledsoe
orchestrated a well-balanced 76-yard drive that culminated in a
gutsy fourth-and-1 touchdown by Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards had been stopped cold on third and 1, but on fourth down
Bledsoe pitched it left and Edwards collided head on with
linebacker James Farrior before bouncing into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has scored touchdowns in each of his first six NFL
games, an unprecedented achievement in the league.
</P>
<P>
   During the drive, Bledsoe connected on an 18-yard pass to Troy
Brown over the middle, but the big play was a 29-yard gain by Ben
Coates. Bledsoe threw a bullet that went between the hands of
linebacker Pepper Johnson to Coates. The tight end hurdled a
defender to get to the 4-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets got going again from their 30, seemingly moving at
will. But the Patriots did make three superb defensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   First, Willie McGinest chased down Testaverde for a 9-yard sack
that moved the ball back from the Patriots' 18 to the 27.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the second quarter began, Milloy sneaked in on a
delayed blitz and pulverized Testaverde for an 8-yard loss, forcing
third and 27.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ran around right end for a 14-yard gain to set up a
38-yard field goal attempt by John Hall. But Eaton blocked the
attempt, creating a sense of deja vu. In a Monday night meeting
here last September, former Patriot Mike Jones blocked a 34-yard
attempt by Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots took over at their 23, and with another very
patient drive, went 77 yards in 5:33. A 6-yard touchdown reception
by backup tight end Lovett Purnell with 8:22 remaining gave them
their first lead, 14-7.
</P>
<P>
   On the last play of the half, Hall kicked a 23-yard field goal
to bring the Jets within 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
