<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BICKLEY_SERIES-MANAGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOCHY BALL A SERIES BUST FOR SAN DIEGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ In the wee hours after the Bronx massacre, a
television flickered in a New York tavern.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was a clip of Paul O'Neill destroying a water
cooler. Next, old footage of Paul O'Neill smashing his bat against
a dugout wall.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a shot of Paul O'Neill sitting on the edge of the
bench, next to the manager, staring forward with a pacified gaze.
Leaning back, Joe Torre was doing all the talking. While there was
no audio available, you could almost hear the wisdom. And you could
tell O'Neill was listening to every word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget the double switch,'' one fan said aloud. ``Now
``that's'' managing.''
</P>
<P>
   As the World Series threatens to end with a disgusted click of
the remote, a dull thud to cap off a season of fireworks, the
contrast in managers is striking.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost unheard of that a manager in New York _ the man who
must sit where Casey Stengel sat, who hears the jeers and the
terrible things they say about your mother, who is subjected to
scrutiny found nowhere else on the planet _ has created one of the
most serene environments in baseball. There is no controversy, no
clash of egos, just the steady hum of professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   In the other dugout . . .
</P>
<P>
   Well. Is there any other manager who has adversely affected his
team's chances in a World Series quite like Bruce Bochy?
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, he lifted Kevin Brown at the first whiff of trouble.
In Game 2, he went the other route, stringing along his pitcher
until the Padres were getting their Ashby kicked.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, after Donne Wall flamed out, he brought in Mark
Langston, a 38-year-old lefty against whom opposing lefties have
hit .360 this season. Langston loaded the bases before surrendering
a grand slam to Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Bochy's decision,'' Padres pitching coach Dave
Stewart said. ``I don't know why we left him in as long as we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Bochy claimed a sinus infection led to Brown's quick
hook. In Game 2, he said Andy Ashby had contracted a similar virus,
one he knew about before the game. Yet, he let Ashby linger for 66
pitches in 2 innings, yielding 10 hits and seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   A complete flip-flop in logic in the span of 24 hours. And both
times, the wrong baseball decision.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of two losses came a string of excuses. Brown had a
bruised shin to go along with his sinus problem. Ashby had a virus
and _ we're not kidding here _ mechanical problems caused by
tendinitis in his left buttock.
</P>
<P>
   The real diagnosis: The Padres and their manager are shriveling
in the moment.
</P>
<P>
   While Bochy's reputation has spiraled from unnoticed genius to
buffoon in the span of a week, Torre has gone the opposite
direction. Two years ago, he was the sentimental favorite, the guy
who finally won a World Series after 35 years while his brother
awaited a heart transplant. Now, at age 58, he has risen to the top
of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   He is in tune with the pulse of his players, knows every mood in
the clubhouse, has shown an uncanny knack when laying out his
cards. From the surprise start of Ricky Ledee to El Duque's start
in Game 2, the results speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the other dugout, the manager is being questioned by his own
pitching coach. And if the Padres fail to recover, they'll go down
as a team that twice ruined a marquee match-up. In 1984, it
should've been the Cubs and Tigers. This season, the Braves
would've surely provided better drama.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is an unpredictable game. The Reds somehow swept the
heavily favored A's in 1990. The Royals somehow rallied from a 3-1
deficit to clip the Cardinals in 1985. The Yankees dropped the
first two at home before snatching four straight from the Braves in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres know there is precedent. Problem is, the gap between
these two teams was enormous when the Series started. And thanks to
their manager, it's widening by the moment. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
