<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6195 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  FBN-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN-BO     10-20 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 FBN-SHAUGHNESSY COLUMN-BOS  
 TUNA LEAVES BAD TASTE FOR PATRIOTS FANS
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Dan Shaughnessy  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ We might as well admit it: He is never going away.
Bill Parcells might coach in New York, New Orleans, or New Delhi,
but he will never be far from the New England mind.
</P>
<P>
   He is like nasty traffic on the Expressway, northeasters in
February, and green flies at Crane Beach. He is like ... the New
York Yankees _ guaranteed to torture New England sports fans for
eternity.
</P>
<P>
   So why were we so surprised when the Tuna's downtrodden Jets
came to town last night and embarrassed the muscle-flexing
Patriots, 24-14, under the glare of ``Monday Night Football''?
</P>
<P>
   Nights like these assure that Parcells and Bob Kraft, a k a the
Bonfire and the Vanity, will keep their silent war going into the
next century. The Tuna tried not to be smug after winning, but
admitted, ``I'm very pleased to come in here and beat these guys,
obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Old ``Press Corner'' Kraft looked as if he'd spent four days
locked in a room with Massachusetts Speaker of the House Thomas
Finneran. Poor Bob. He runs his Super Bowl coach out of town and
Parcells takes a 1-15 team and beats the Patriots twice in three
meetings. If not for a low kick by John Hall last year, Tuna would
be 3-0 against the vastly superior Patriots. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   For Kraft, the price of being the star of his own team keeps
going up. Certainly it looked like everything was going his way
before Tuna III. The Patriots had ripped off four straight wins,
including a shredding of the estimable Kansas City Chiefs. Robert
Edwards and draft picks in exchange for Curtis Martin was looking
darn good and Kraft's courting of the media produced
round-the-clock infomercials disguised as news.
</P>
<P>
   But it all came apart under the watchful eye of Michaels,
Dierdorf, and Esiason. Everybody knows New England has more talent
than the Jets. So what is Patriot Nation to think? How to explain a
10-point whupping at home on national television?
</P>
<P>
   Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe said his team wanted this
badly because it was ``Monday Night Football,'' because the game
was at home, and because it was against a division rival. He didn't
say anything about the Tuna, but that's what made the game special
and that's what took New England players out of their game again.
</P>
<P>
   The Martin-Edwards matchup proved to be even. Martin had 107
yards on 28 carries, while the impressive rookie Edwards came
through with 104 yards on 22 carries. But it had to be infuriating
for Patriots coach Pete Carroll to lose again to Parcells,
especially after Pistol Pete had been quoted as saying that
everything the Tuna says is a crock.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells would not gloat. It's one of the maddening things about
the Tuna. He comes back here and sticks it to Kraft, then says all
sorts of nice things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to win anywhere, but to beat the division leaders on
the road is a good feeling,'' he said. ``But I have a warm feeling
for this place. And the fans. I mean that. When I first came here,
you could hold archery practice in the stadium during games. I'm
proud to see what's here for fan support in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe last week compared the Patriots-Jets rivalry to the Red
Sox-Yankees century-long Holy War. It has grown to all of that and
more. Patriots-Jets games have become a referendum on local sports
fans' way of life. Just as you are a Republican or Democrat, you
are a Bill Guy or a Bob Guy. And most of Patriot Nation is
populated by Bob Guys who hate Bill and bring their venom to the
stadium. That's why this loss hurt so much throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   The big pantload with the big teeth _ the man who allegedly
ruined Super Bowl week and then stole Martin _ did it to New
England again.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots may go on to beat Miami and Pittsburgh and San
Francisco. But New England fans are going to circle Dec. 27 on
their calendars. That's the final game of the season and it's at
the Meadowlands against the ... New ... York ... Jets. God help the
Patriots if they need that game for playoff positioning. The Tuna
will be standing on the sideline, pretending it's just another
game, dying to stick it to Kraft one more time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
