u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  FBN-McDONOUGHCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-20 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
JETS HAD COORDINATED EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
 FBN-McDONOUGH COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Will McDonough  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ On the last day of practice for last night's game,
Bill Parcells shut down the Jets' workout early and threw his team
off the field. They stunk that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you guys can't get ready to play a division opponent on
Monday night, then you better start looking for another job,''
Parcells lashed out.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no Jets in the unemployment line this morning. All
of them can walk up to the paymaster and get compensated in full
for the whipping they put on a stunned Patriots team last night.
</P>
<P>
   The game turned in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad second period,'' said Parcells. ``Penalties,
mistakes, missed opportunities. It was bad. But we played very well
in the second half. We stayed aggressive, and it really helped
us.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a wonderful chess match between the teams'
coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, New England offensive coordinator Ernie
Zampese had the edge on Jets defensive coordinator Bill Belichick.
It turned around in the second half when the Jets shut out the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very hard to stop,'' said Belichick. ``In the first
half, Ernie had a real nice mix going. They kept us off balance
with the way they were able to run the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is a guessing game. You can't focus on any one
guy on their offense. You have to move the strength of your
coverage around. Some plays we doubled (Ben) Coates. Some we
doubled (Terry) Glenn. Some we doubled the other wide receivers. I
have such great respect for all of those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big factor for us was getting some hits on Drew (Bledsoe).
If you let him sit back there the whole game and throw in rhythm,
he will pick you apart. At key points, we got some hits on him. We
had to blitz him to do it, but at times it worked for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots seemed to have control of the game with 2:30 left
in the third quarter. They were sitting on a 14-10 lead with third
and 11 at the Jets' 18, easy field goal range for Adam Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, out of a shotgun formation, went to throw. Mo Lewis,
the Jets' best linebacker, came on a blitz and jumped at Bledsoe,
forcing him to alter a pass intended for Shawn Jefferson in the
back corner of the end zone. Bledsoe had to put an arc on the pass,
which allowed Aaron Glenn to recover and make the interception.
Instead of being ahead, 21-10 or 17-10, the Patriots were still up,
14-10, and New York had the ball on its 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big sequence for us,'' said Parcells. ``Glenn's
play was big. Then we controlled the ball for 18 plays, ran all
that time off the clock (8:35) and got the go-ahead touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   New York went up, 17-14, six minutes into the fourth quarter
when tight end Kyle Brady caught his second 1-yard TD pass for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Patriots had plenty of time. But they stalled at
their 34 and had to punt.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Parcells and his staff had to make their most critical
decision of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom said to sit on the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were five minutes left,'' said Parcells, ``and I told
our guys we were going to stay aggressive. I wanted to put some
distance between them and us. I didn't want to give the ball back
to Bledsoe (with just a 3-point lead).''
</P>
<P>
   On first down, the Jets surprised the Patriots by again throwing
to Brady, a seldom-used receiver. The Patriots weren't paying any
attention to him, and the Jets took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, the Jets' staff made the call that put the game
out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our guy (Dedric) Ward can run a lot faster than most
of the guys they had covering him,'' said Parcells. ``We wanted to
get him singled up in coverage if we could. It just turned out that
they blitzed on the play and Ward ran by his guy (Chris Canty), and
Vinny (Testaverde) made a great throw. That was big. Very big.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the conversation, Dan Henning, the former
Boston College coach now with the Jets' offensive staff, walked
past and said, ``I'll say big. That takes a lot of guts to go for
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the staff was for it. Some wanted to sit on the ball
and hope the defense could hold on. But Parcells wanted all of it,
on this night that will go down as one of the sweetest victories he
has had in his long career. Forget that stuff about beating a
division opponent on the road. There was more to that in this one,
and every football fan in New England is smart enough to realize
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GOMEZ-WILLIAMS-AZ     10-20 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-WILLIAMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SHOULD STAY IN BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ No offense, Valley residents, but Bernie Williams
should not become a Diamondbacks outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   He can't. Not if he wants to maintain the status he has achieved
to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody who plays center field for the New York Yankees should
ever consider leaving the Bronx, where the most storied franchise
in sports plays its games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our Number 1 priority,'' Yankees General Manager Brian
Cashman said. ``We want to make him a Yankee for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a Yankee since he was drafted, will be given a choice,
and he should think twice if he believes he can match what he has
now by going elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Being a Yankees center fielder, at least a great one,
automatically links a player with Joe DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle.
It's simply the best position to play in baseball. It is cloaked
with unbridled elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but being the Diamondbacks center fielder next year only
connects you to Devon White. For Williams, it should be a
no-brainer. Staying in New York and wearing the pinstripes keeps
Williams in select company.
</P>
<P>
   Little kids dream of playing center field for the Yankees. It's
a position that elevates a player into a stratosphere that no other
organization can match.
</P>
<P>
   Staying with the Yankees means Williams will have a chance to
play in the World Series every year. Joining the Diamondbacks means
his social calendar will be fairly wide open every October.
</P>
<P>
   Being a Diamondbacks center fielder may one day hold a special
status. If so, it should be because the club brought along its own
player, not one from another organization. DiMaggio and Mantle were
Yankees before they reached the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   It appears Williams, who declined to speak about the subject,
will indeed become a free agent once the World Series ends. That's
all right if he's simply trying to leverage Yankees boss George
Steinbrenner for more money.
</P>
<P>
   But if Williams is serious about leaving, whether it be to play
in downtown Phoenix or elsewhere, he would be making the mistake of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite possible that some outside force is behind Williams
leaving the Bronx. If, say, his wife wants out of New York City,
for the sake of their family, well, that justifies his leaving.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams and his wife have lived in New York City for years.
As Puerto Ricans living in the city with a larger Puerto Rican
population than even San Juan, he enjoys a revered status that is
unmatched anywhere on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to sit here and tell Bernie what he should do,''
said Yankees shortstop and Williams' friend Derek Jeter. ``But none
of us are in Bernie's shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams _ at least his agent, Scott Boras _ wants megastar
money in his next contract. This is where the situation becomes a
bit messy. The Yankees last multiyear proposal to Williams was a
five-year $37 million offer made one week before the Diamondbacks
virtually gave the same deal (five years for $34 million) to
shortstop Jay Bell, whom Boras also represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbeknownst to us, Boras already knew the Bell contract was
coming down the pike,'' Cashman said. ``It definitely affected
where we stood.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a player whose skills are just a hair below the
superstar category. Make no mistake, he's a tremendous player, but
on the scale between above-average major leaguer and superstar,
Williams falls below the superstar line.
</P>
<P>
   Which still makes for a fabulous player. There is little he
cannot do on a field, but he is not quite on the same level as Ken
Griffey Jr., Barry Bonds and Alex Rodriguez. Herein lies the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   If you're the Yankees, do you bend your own rules, albeit skewed
when measuring them against most every other club, and give
Williams $10 million a year when you know he's not quite in that
category?
</P>
<P>
   The problem is someone out there _ quite possibly Jerry
Colangelo _ might be willing to twist the measuring stick
(Colangelo proved that with the Bell contract).
</P>
<P>
   Williams occupies the famed corner locker stall inside the
Yankee clubhouse, the one previously taken by Don Mattingly. It's
the locker that is basically passed down to the greatest of the
Yankees. It's inhabitants before Mattingly were Dave Righetti, Dave
Winfield and Ron Guidry.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has reached a certain exalted status with the Yankees.
If he leaves, he blows it.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but wearing purple pinstripes with a turquoise cap
doesn't quite measure up to donning blue pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   There IS something unparalleled in sports about that distinctive
``NY'' on a uniform. Walking away from it, especially by choice,
would be regrettable for Williams. Maybe not next year, but
regrettable nonetheless. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
