r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NOTEBOO     10-20 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER READY TO PUT BEST FEET FORWARD  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Snake has gone out of Jake Plummer, it's not by design.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, who's ability to improvise on the run made him a star
at Arizona State, suddenly seems reluctant to slither and slide as
the Cardinals' starting quarterback. And when Plummer has left the
pocket out of necessity, he has forced throws.
</P>
<P>
   The result, predictably, has been bad. Plummer threw two
interceptions, his 10th and 11th this season against six
touchdowns, Sunday in a 34-7 loss to the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer said teams are defensing him differently than last
season, when he was able to improvise for some big plays. Defensive
backs and linebackers aren't leaving coverage to go after him.
</P>
<P>
   And Plummer said Monday that he needs to stop trying to make
huge plays every time with his arm and take what his nimble feet
can get him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most times when I've gotten out of the pocket, I haven't seen
a lot of guys coming after me,'' Plummer said. ``They're chasing me
from behind, but you get those big plays out of the pocket when you
bust out of there and the (defensive back) or linebacker sees you
running and wants to come get a tackle or a sack. That leaves his
guy behind him wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not coming up, and hopefully, I can make the better
decision to tuck the ball and run. I'm a good runner. I can get
some yards. If I get five yards, even if a guy is open, the drive
is still alive. I don't make a bad decision.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be just fine with Coach Vince Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've ever told him not to do that (run),''
Tobin said Monday. ``Jake has got to where he is in his career by
being a certain kind of quarterback. Part of his success has come
from his ability to run the football and pick up vital first downs,
vital yardage. You also make big plays by being able to throw it on
the run. That's where it puts double pressure on the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where's the D? &QL; 
 &QL; 
While most of the focus after Sunday's debacle was on Plummer and
the club's offensive woes, the defense's performance might be more
alarming.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had the NFL's 30th-ranked offense going into the game
but gained 390 total offensive yards against an Arizona defense
that had been playing so impressively that fans and media have been
searching for an appropriate nickname.
</P>
<P>
   So much for that. The Giants razed the Cactus Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a defense has to be evaluated over the long haul,''
Tobin said. ``A lot of times we're too quick to put a good label or
a bad label on anything whether it's the defense or the offense or
the special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to evaluate them on how you do over the course of the
year. We had a couple of pretty good ballgames. We've got some good
players on defense, but it's still how you do consistently against
all the different variety of offenses you're going to see in the
National Football League. You've got to be able to come up strong
against all of them. We didn't come up very strong against the
Giants.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Getting Bye &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Cardinals (3-4) have until Nov. 1 to lick their wounds thanks
to a bye week. And it couldn't have come at a better time for their
health, both physical and mental.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said he hopes the Cardinals will have cornerback Tom
Knight (hamstring) and guard Chris Dishman (neck), running back
Adrian Murrell (leg) healthy by then. He also reported that
injuries to defensive end Simeon Rice (leg bruise) and Mark Smith
(ankle sprain) against the Giants are not serious.
</P>
<P>
   Returner/receiver Eric Metcalf (leg), defensive tackle Eric
Swann (arthritic knees) and receiver Rob Moore (foot) have been
playing, but also will benefit from the extra time off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
