<HEADER>
A6218 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMENTIA- &LR;      10-20 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMENTIA- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART SKILLS BLOSSOM AS MIND DECLINES DURING DEMENTIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A rare form of mental illness can bring out
``startling artistic talents'' in adults with no previous creative
interest, brain researchers report.
</P>
<P>
   Art history is replete with examples of strong talents torn
apart by depression and other forms of mental disquietude _
hallmarks of tortured geniuses who, in the words of Lord Byron,
``by the dint of glass and vapor, discover stars, and sail in the
wind's eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new study shows that some unusual cases may be explained
by a genetic mutation linked to a condition known as frontotemporal
dementia.
</P>
<P>
   The disease typically strikes when people are in their 50s,
affecting a region of the brain that influences social behavior. It
accounts for about 10 percent of all cases of dementia, and differs
both in symptoms and brain chemistry from the much more widespread
dementias that are among the hallmarks of Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Lead author Bruce Miller of the University of California at San
Francisco, joined by colleagues at UCLA and UC Irvine, illustrated
the study, which appears in Tuesday's issue of the journal
Neurology. Accompanying the report are paintings and photography
done by people with dementia.
</P>
<P>
   In the five cases chosen for close scrutiny, mental illness
seems to have unleashed talents that had lain dormant _ opening
what the researchers called ``an unexpected window into the
artistic process.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parallels emerged between the late-blooming obsession with
artistic efforts shown by the patients and the life stories of
Vincent Van Gogh and Francisco de Goya, two painters whose work
``blossomed in midlife, when they spurned conventional rules of
society,'' the researchers noted.
</P>
<P>
   Frontotemporal dementia has been traced to a mutation in a gene
called tau, which leads to the destruction of a part of the cortex
used for speech and social skills but which may spare regions for
visual perception.
</P>
<P>
   Patients stopped talking, withdrew socially, became irritable,
developed odd obsessions and failed at memory tests. But in each of
the five case studies, the most severe problems were preceded by a
period of exceptional creativity.
</P>
<P>
   One middle-aged advertising executive developed a sudden
interest in photography, leaving his family behind to take
dangerous trips into Central America to get what he described as
the ``perfect'' image.
</P>
<P>
   He later took to carving wax miniatures from candle drippings.
Worsening mental function led to his being placed in a nursing
facility at age 56.
</P>
<P>
   A woman without artistic training signed up for art classes at
age 51, about the time she became uncomfortable in social settings.
She completed her first paintings at age 55, depicting rural scenes
from childhood, and continued to paint while her condition worsened
until she reached age 66. She died two years later of advanced
dementia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A break with social conventions is common among artists and
can lead to a freer, more creative output,'' the study concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Some so-called ``outsider artists'' seem to couple a distinctive
artistic style with a set of clinical hallmarks, such as social
disinhibition, hallucinations and ``little interest in the
teachings of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows whether such people may have a distinct form of
mental illness. Researchers noted that the ``mechanism for enhanced
artistic skills in these patients and outsider artists reported
previously remains a mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, experts said, creativity may not be so much a
direct product of a mental illness but rather part of the person's
way of coping with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a vulnerability that's part and parcel of having a
mental disorder,'' said Michael Faenza, president of the National
Mental Health Association in Alexandria, Va. ``A lot of times that
finds an outlet in different forms of art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
