<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SYBASE _  &LR; When John Chen joined Sybase as president a little more
than a year ago, he had a mystery to solve: How could a company
with loyal customers and a billion dollars in sales fail to make a
profit?
</P>
<P>
   Chen, now chief executive of the ailing database software-maker,
found the answer in one of his chief passions: golf. Sybase was
like a player on a difficult course who used the same club no
matter what hole or hazard he faced. By Jamie Beckett
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOROX _  &LR; Oakland's Clorox Co. said yesterday it will boost its
sales by nearly half with its $2 billion acquisition of First
Brands Corp., the Danbury, Conn., maker of Glad bags, STP auto
products and Scoop Away cat litter. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POSTEL _  &LR; The sudden death of one of the Internet's founding
fathers has stunned the Web world, but is unlikely to disrupt its
privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Postel, who oversaw the intricate computer system for
routing all online traffic and maintaining a lexicon of popular
domain names, died Friday night in Los Angeles from complications
following heart surgery. The ``guardian of the Internet's
infrastructure'' was 55. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIGITAL _  &LR; No matter who wins, the Justice Department's
antitrust trial against Microsoft Corp. is likely to be the
beginning, not the end, of government efforts to ensure fair
competition in the technology arena. By columnist Tom Abate
</P>
