<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARBITER'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SALARY RULING A VICTORY FOR OWNERS
</HEADLINE>
 RULING-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBA owners seemed to have gained the upper hand in their labor
clash via the ruling Monday that they don't have to pay players
during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   But after arbitrator John Feerick ruled that owners are not
responsible for paying almost $800 million to players with
guaranteed contracts during the lockout, the players have circled
the wagons because they fear that the season could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it; the season's in jeopardy,'' Orlando guard
Penny Hardaway said. ``We're upset that we didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   For players, who have been locked out since July 1, when owners
suspended the NBA collective bargaining agreement, the next move is
to meet Thursday at Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas. Michael Jordan,
Patrick Ewing and Shaquille O'Neal are expected to be on hand when
decertification of the NBA Players Association and a new
counterproposal will be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners are kind of sitting pretty now,'' San Antonio guard
Avery Johnson said. ``They feel they have all the power in their
hands. We have to see how to keep the owners negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Feerick's ruling, which affects 226 players, means that players
will begin missing paychecks if a settlement isn't reached by Nov.
15. That could affect the solidarity of members, but the players'
union claims to be more committed than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought we were zealous before, you should see us now,
because we're even more rabid,'' union executive director Billy
Hunter said. ``We're worlds apart, and our membership is committed
to not accepting a bad deal under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts feel that a longer lockout favors owners, who will
receive a guaranteed $23 million per team from the television deal
signed a year ago. So how long will the players wait?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't hold out as long as the owners, and everybody knows
it,'' said a Dallas-based agent who represents several players.
``The players may be right in this, but they are backed in a corner
now because soon the money they're used to won't be rolling in.''
</P>
<P>
   With the lockout in its 112th day and two weeks of the regular
season canceled, the sides remain at odds over the growth of player
salaries vs. league revenues. A week ago, players proposed a luxury
tax on lucrative contracts, and the owners submitted a counterbid
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their latest proposal is nothing more than a wolf in sheep's
clothing,'' Hunter said. ``It's a hard salary cap disguised as a
tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have sufficient money to take us as far as we have
to go,'' Hunter said. ``We're convinced we'll be able to help the
minimum players who need us.''
</P>
<P>
   Exercising an early-out clause in the 1995 collective bargaining
agreement, owners began this lockout July 1 because player salaries
had begun eating up more than 52 percent of the league's total
revenue. At the heart of the struggle is a Larry Bird exception to
the cap, a loophole that allowed 24 of the league's 29 teams to
exceed the $31 million cap, Minnesota Timberwolves forward Kevin
Garnett to sign a six-year, $126 million contract, and Chicago
Bulls star Michael Jordan to earn $33 million.
</P>
<P>
   If and when an agreement is reached, teams say they need at
least three weeks to sign free agents and get players in shape.
Commissioner David Stern has said he is against a regular season of
less than 60 games.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setback, Hunter said Feerick's ruling doesn't
drastically change his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the same position today as we were Monday: We're not
on strike; we're locked out,'' he said. ``We're not inclined to
back down. But if owners continue to antagonize fans the way they
are doing, players being forced to miss a few paychecks may be the
least of all our worries. Our product may suffer enormous,
irreparable damage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 0802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 08:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6385 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     10-20 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD BYE TIME: COWBOYS HAVE EXTRA WEEK TO FIND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Just how good are the Dallas Cowboys? And what
can be done about Kevin Smith's slumping play at cornerback?
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey plans to answer those questions and
more about the 4-3 Cowboys, who head into the bye week looking for
an ``identity'' after a 13-12 loss Sunday to the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' next game is against the Eagles on Monday night,
Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most teams around the .500 mark have an
identity,'' Gailey said. ``We are potentially a good team. How good
can we get? I don't know. It's going to take a little while longer
for us to establish ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   While the question of how good the Cowboys can get looms, at
least one question has been answered.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman, who has been out the past five weeks
with a broken collarbone, will re-establish himself as the starter
against the Eagles. And the Cowboys will use the bye week to try to
eliminate issues such as offensive inconsistency on third down and
in the red zone, issues that contributed to their downfall against
the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   However, the question that seems to be most troubling is what to
do about Smith. A week after saying Smith was not in jeopardy of
losing his starting spot, Gailey said the team will use the bye
week to evaluate Smith's role.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is becoming a repeated target of opposing quarterbacks,
who are shying away from throwing toward All-Pro cornerback Deion
Sanders. The Bears completed six passes against Smith on three
scoring drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's obvious that Kevin's situation has come up,''
Gailey said. ``We will address that when the time comes with our
staff and with him. We will take a good hard look at where we are
and what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer acknowledged that
Smith, once considered one of the league's top cornerbacks, has
lost confidence. Smith has not had an interception in 19 games.
However, Zimmer does not favor making a change, saying the Cowboys
have to let Smith play through his bad time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to bench the guy,'' Zimmer said. ``Yes, I'm
concerned. But I don't care if I got Darrell Green over there. They
are not throwing at Prime. I told Kevin to keep his head up. I
believe in him 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys make a change, their first option is reserve
cornerback Kevin Mathis, who plays in nickel situations and has an
interception this season. However, the second-year Mathis is
inexperienced, and at 5-foot-9 might struggle as an every-down
player.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey and Zimmer said Smith's problem is mental. Pointing to
Smith's near interception of a touchdown pass to Chris Penn, Zimmer
said Smith improved against the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   The team hopes to continue improving in the second half of the
season as well. Though the Cowboys have the same record in 1998 as
they did after seven games in 1997, when they finished 6-10,
fullback Daryl Johnston said he has a better feeling about where
they are and where they can go.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, one of two teams in the league to rank in the top
10 in total offense and total defense, have seemingly answered many
preseason concerns _ especially on offense at wide receiver and on
the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much different feeling at 4-3,'' Johnston said. ``We've
improved in a lot of categories offensively. And we still have a
lot of room to improve. We are still trying to find ourselves as a
team. But we have the potential to be a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping fuel that confidence is the expected return of Aikman,
who said he must get re-acclimated to the system after a five-week
hiatus. Though the Cowboys are happy with the job backup Jason
Garrett did in leading them to a 3-2 record, they believe that
Aikman can take them to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is we're playing with Troy from now on,''
Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin said. ``Jason did a great job. My
hat's off to him, and we're glad to have him on our team. But we're
getting our quarterback back. We'll just have to see where we go
from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is somewhat pleased that the Cowboys have a one-game lead
in the NFC East. What seems to be frustrating, however, is knowing
that they could be 5-2 if not for the mind-boggling loss to the
Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like the bye to have been here at 5-2,'' Gailey said.
``But we are not. We are not pleased with 4-3, but we don't need to
be ashamed of 4-3.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
