<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES HAVE STARS ALTERING STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Injured center Joe Nieuwendyk, the Dallas Stars'
most valuable player last season, returned to practice full time
Monday and could return to game play as early as Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Nieuwendyk's return was overshadowed by an intense practice
that stressed strategic adjustments designed to reduce turnovers in
the defensive zone.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock presided over an early morning video session
then put players through 75 minutes of hard skating in preparation
for Tuesday's 7:30 game against the Calgary Flames at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not meant to be a punishment day; it was meant to be
a hard practice,'' Hitchcock said of the workout that came on the
heels of a disappointing 4-3 loss to the Chicago Blackhawks on
Saturday. ``Today was a competitive, positional practice. Once our
competitive juices got flowing, I'm sure some guys had fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars players agreed, saying they needed the wakeup call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team does, and we're no different,'' veteran defenseman
Craig Ludwig said. ``You get caught up in all the talent that's on
our team, but talented teams lose all the time. We have to stay
with what makes us win, and that's hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock specifically points to the team's play while hunting
the puck and moving it out of the defensive zone after an
opponent's dump-in. With rule changes that pushed the goal line two
feet farther from the back wall to 13 feet and cracked down on
defending teams who were holding up forecheckers (one of the Stars'
strengths), the NHL is almost begging teams to dump the puck
instead of trying to make slick passes through the neutral zone and
into the offensive zone.
</P>
<P>
   With the puck dumped behind the net more, goalies more tentative
about going back to get it because of the extra space and opposing
forecheckers free to skate at full speed, defensemen now are under
more pressure than ever. They have to outrace forecheckers, get
possession of the puck and try to move it out from behind their
goal in the face of mounting pressure without making a mistake. One
wrong move and an opponent likely will get a prime scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams are playing `red line and in,' and that makes
for a hellish time for defensemen,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's a much
more difficult game that we're in, much more.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hitchcock set about Monday to teach and prod his forwards
into helping the defensemen. Now, the first forward back often will
go after the puck as hard as the defenseman to ensure that
possession is gained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forward has to go right back to help out; there can be no
hesitation,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's got to go back with the
assumption that the defenseman is not going to win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   That means forwards likely will cheat to the side of the
defense, breakouts will materialize slower and offensive
opportunities could be down. But Hitchcock and the players said
that doesn't have to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know and what we have to get back to is that we create
our best opportunities off strong defense,'' Ludwig said. ``We want
to be the team that's forechecking hard in the other zone and
keeping the puck in their end. That's where our offense comes
from.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as important as knowing assignments and changing
positioning, Hitchcock said Monday players have to learn to be
aggressive in completing those assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game gets nasty and a little ugly, you have to want
to play in those games,'' he said of the Stars' tendency to shy
away from the battle against the Blackhawks. ``You can't run and
hide; you can't hope it's not there. You have to go out and compete
and have fun doing it.'' ALMOST HEALTHY
</P>
<P>
   Both Nieuwendyk and fellow center Brian Skrudland went through
full practices Monday. Nieuwendyk had reconstructive surgery on
both knees in the summer and has been working his way back. His
right knee is responding slower than his left, but Hitchcock said
he would like to test the knee this morning and push for a return
Thursday against the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland had arthroscopic knee surgery two weeks ago. He said
he'd like to return Thursday, as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
