<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEL NO PITY FOR THE SICKLY MR. SUNSHINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Somehow, the idea of Kevin Brown puking his guts out
makes me smile.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, it probably makes me a bad person, but I just can't help
it. It's a Pavlovian response, conditioned from spending years
trying to exchange a few pleasantries with the former Rangers
right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: ``Hey, Kevin, how are you today?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown: ``That's a stupid (bleeping) question.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: ``OK, nice to see you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So now that the 1998 World Series has moved from one corner of
the country to the other, I admit I'm not exactly heartbroken to
hear that Brown is sick again _ it's his annual Fall Classic malady
_ except that it may provide him an alibi _ again _ for choking at
the worst possible time for his team.
</P>
<P>
   This autumn health crisis of his is becoming as automatic as
Brown sniping at the media for having the audacity to occupy the
same planet that he does.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Brown pitched the Marlins into the World Series last
year, too, but when they desperately needed him to win a couple of
games in the Fall Classic, he was having his temperature checked.
</P>
<P>
   With a baby thermometer, we can only hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins won it anyway, but it was despite Brown's 0-2 record
and abysmal 8.18 earned-run average, not because he was the rock
they'd hoped he would be.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, Brown was ill with flu symptoms that left him weak
and shaky and as ornery as a 2-year-old who missed his nap time.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch that last one. That's Brown's attitude ``all'' the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone must have a voodoo doll out on me,'' Brown told
reporters after he gamely struggled through 61/3 innings in Game 1
of the Series and left with a 5-2 lead, only to see the Padres'
bullpen blow it almost before he'd had time to bite anyone's head
off. ``My timing has been really \Rlousy\S. It would be nice to
know what it's like to be healthy to start a World Series game.''
</P>
<P>
   Now don't start checking for Kevin Brown voodoo dolls stuck full
of straight pins in my luggage. I swear, somebody else is playing
pin-the-tail-on-the-donkey with him this time, and the list of
potential suspects, considering how many enemies he's made over the
years, is as long as that interminable flight from New York to San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd search Tom Schieffer's office first.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the Padres had better hope the sadist lets up soon,
because without Brown winning at least two games, they don't have a
prayer of beating the Yankees in this World Series. They may not
even get it back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is now debatable whether Brown will be well enough to start
Games 4 and 7 _ if the Pods can take it that far _ each time on
just three days' rest, though you know he'll go to the mound if
they have to wheel him out on a gurney.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever said the man isn't a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Brown come down with a bug, he has also spread it
among the Padres' pitching staff, proving what some of us have
claimed for a long time _ he should be kept in strict quarantine at
all times.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't think a guy who soaks his heart in vinegar every
night could get sick so often.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Brown entered the Series, much as he did last
October, being heralded as perhaps the best pitcher in the game at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Not Roger Clemens. Not Pedro Martinez. Not Randy Johnson or Greg
Maddux or John Smoltz or any of those other hotshots.
</P>
<P>
   James Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   And he deserved it.
</P>
<P>
   Then came that relief appearance against the Braves in Game 5 of
the NLCS, when San Diego manager Bruce Bochy ignored his regular
relievers and brought his ace starter in from the bullpen to try to
nail it down, right then and there. It seemed like sound strategy
until Michael Tucker drove a Brown fastball into the right-field
seats for a three-run homer that wiped out the Padres' lead and
suddenly made Brown seem mortal again.
</P>
<P>
   He battled the Yankees in Game 1, despite admitting later to
being terribly fatigued from the first inning on, but he clearly
didn't have his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sank the ball, and he's obviously a good pitcher,'' a
Yankees official said, ``but we didn't see any of that 97 mph
fastball he's supposed to have. He certainly wasn't any better than
Clemens or Martinez or some of the guys we have on our staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold that thought, but if Brown is 100 percent Wednesday night,
the Yankees may yet see the pitcher who went head to head with
Johnson in the divisional series and totally dominated the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it, though. He has a track record now, one that
says after Oct. 15, or thereabouts, the most likely place to find
Kevin Brown is on his knees, worshipping at the porcelain throne.
</P>
<P>
   Just to be sure, I'm on the way to the store right now to top
off my supply of straight pins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
