<HEADLINE>
LOCKOUT? NOT WHERE DR. J HOLDS COURT
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, you're not happy about the NBA lockout. You've got a
Basketball Jones that flares up this time of year and simply won't
go away.
</P>
<P>
   Well, NBA.com (www.nba.com), the NBA's official site, apparently
isn't about to let a suspension of games affect its production of
fresh online content. Until the lockout is settled, expect a lot of
feature content.
</P>
<P>
   And as boring as it sounds, that might not be a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have a fairly aggressive development schedule,''
said Stefanie Scheer, director of Internet services for the NBA.
``We'll roll out special features as we have them ready _ whether
or not the lockout continues.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA.com is prepared to satiate the average professional
basketball fan with an enhanced history section, improved
multimedia features and up-to-date coverage of negotiations between
players and owners.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it might not be as exciting as watching Michael
Jordan dunk or witnessing a new Dennis Rodman hairstyle, but it's
going to have to do.
</P>
<P>
   NBA.com was braced for this. Earlier this month, NBA.com
launched the history section in conjunction with NBA Hall of Fame
induction ceremonies. The section includes profiles of inductees, a
history of the game and multimedia features that bring the section
to life.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Erving is scheduled to participate in a live chat at 2:30
p.m. today as part of the history series. Former U.S. Sen. Bill
Bradley, another NBA legend, plugged his book during a chat this
month.
</P>
<P>
   NBA.com also is using the game-less opportunity to work more
closely with its television counterpart, ``Inside Stuff'', to show
footage that doesn't make it on the air.
</P>
<P>
   NBA.com plans to make more use of streaming video _ live video
and audio that can be accessed with the proper plug-ins _ beginning
this week. (''While it isn't new, it's the first time we've used
it,'' Scheer said.)
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of the lockout includes live news conferences and
transcripts of negotiations. Streaming video is also being used on
WNBA.com, the NBA-produced site for the Women's NBA, to market that
league's championship series video.
</P>
<P>
   Once the games begin, more technology will kick in, including
enhancements to the real-time courtside section (where play-by-play
and statistics are produced) and a feature that tracks milestone
achievements. OTHER NBA SITES OF INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   Those who want a more independent and less antiseptic voice for
their NBA fix can try Alleyoop.com (www.alleyoop.com) or On Hoops
(www.onhoops.com).
</P>
<P>
   Alleyoop.com is billed as the ``basketball page for thinking
fans'' and has a collection of editorials written by site author
John Hollinger. On Hoops, created by Arjun Metre and Adam Sussman,
also has a bunch of cutting-edge rants about the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And for those nights when one starts waxing for a good Allen
Iverson drive, consider the Basketball Penalty Directory
(www.teleport.com/~aeneas/basketball.shtml). This page tracks
suspensions, fines, probations, arrests, convictions, penalties and
violations of NBA players, officials and personalities since 1990.
CHAT HIGHLIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   On the 'Net: Pittsburgh Steelers quarterback Kordell Stewart is
the scheduled guest on NFL.com's Quarterback Club at 7 p.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On America Online: Kansas City Chiefs quarterback Elvis Grbac is
the scheduled guest on AOL (keyword: nfl) at 8 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other chats: Baltimore Ravens quarterback Eric Zeier, 8 p.m.
Thursday, NFLPlayers.com ... Kevin Kennedy, ESPN baseball analyst
and former Rangers manager, 12:30 p.m. Tuesday, ESPN.com ... former
baseball great Pete Rose, 3 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
