u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     10-20 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MATT SHEPARD'S FUNERAL, THE CLEANSING SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune  
CASPER, Wyo. _ Matthew Shepard's beating death became the week's
media event. And Shepard became a national symbol.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A hundred reporters gathered in front of St. Mark's Episcopal
Church Friday in order to tell the nation about the funeral of this
young gay man who had been pistol-whipped and tortured and strung
up like a scarecrow on a buck-and-rail fence.
</P>
<P>
   They came to report on the anti-homosexual religious louts from
Kansas and Texas who picketed outside the church with placards
stating ``God hates fags.'' They came to see if Wyoming is really
only ``guns, chew and brutality.'' The Easterner's stereotype of
the West: Marlboro Man turned psychopath.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's family and friends came to mourn the death of a young
man whose life was ended so abruptly and brutally. They will miss
the person, his dreams, his smile, his touch, his presence, his
passion for life.
</P>
<P>
   In death, Shepard has become a symbol of the victimized
homosexual _ the reason he was chosen for the deadly assault. His
killers saw only a one-dimensional Shepard, Shepard the queer. The
nation now sees him as the one-dimensional gay victim.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1,000 others from Wyoming and surrounding states
flew or drove into Casper to mourn for Matt Shepard, the symbol.
They did not know Shepard, the person. They learned from media
reports that he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   Some mourned because they, too, are homosexuals. They mourned
not merely because they understand the fear Shepard must have felt
in his last hours, they mourned for themselves. They know his fate
could be theirs _ living in a society that treats gays and lesbians
as deviants, as pariahs.
</P>
<P>
   Some mourned because of their sense of common humanity. What
befell Shepard befalls all of us _ gay or straight.
</P>
<P>
   Others mourned for the brutal death of a young man _ in a way,
to help ease the guilt some Wyoming people feel about this
travesty.
</P>
<P>
   In three days, the Casper newspaper received nearly 300 letters
and e-mails from all over the world concerning Shepard's death.
</P>
<P>
   Letters from individuals outraged by the way Shepard was killed.
The image of him tied to a fence like a scarecrow and left to die _
imbedded in the psyche like a Jungian archetype.
</P>
<P>
   Letters from gay and lesbian advocacy groups calling for Wyoming
to pass hate crime legislation and join the ``civilized world'' _
as if it would cure America's addiction to violence. Texas has
numerous hate-crime statutes, yet it was in that state recently
where some white thugs tied a black man behind a pick-up and
dragged him until his body disintegrated into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Hate crime legislation does not stem the violence that arises
out of hate and fear. Not even murder charges stop these vicious
assaults. Hate crime legislation is a symbolic response to the
death of Shepard, the symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Letters lambasting the people of Wyoming. Or filled with the
pain of identifying with Shepard. Or full of sorrow for the human
condition. For our stupidities and prejudices and murderous hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Letters arrived denouncing statements made by anti-homosexual
church groups.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the courage of a fine young Casper reporter
Jason Marsden who, in response to his friend Shepard's death,
writes a column for his newspaper to reveal his own homosexuality.
And calls his grandparents to tell them before they read it or
heard about it. And explains it to his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   In a climate of brutality, he has made himself a target.
</P>
<P>
   Juxtapose Marsden's courage over the sordid, hateful fax
messages from the members of the Westboro Baptist Church of Topeka,
Kan., who call themselves Christians: ``Fag Matt in Hell,'' ``No
tears for queers,'' ``Fags burn in Hell.'' Some of this
congregation came to Casper to insult Shepard's parents by
picketing with placards across the street from where the funeral
service was held. Purposefully ignoring the deep sorrow his mother
and father suffer and their need for privacy, ignoring common
decency, ignoring the dignity that each person deserves in death,
at least.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn by the media's focus, a few anti-gay church-goers from the
God Said Ministries of Mt. Enterprise, Texas, joined the Topeka
picketers with their own brand of Christian hate.
</P>
<P>
   And snow fell. Wet snow. All day. A veil of silence descended,
surrounding the mourners and the demonstrators. White silence. To
clean the air. To wrap us in privacy. The kind of silence that
cousins sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   And the picketers of hate left for shelter or dry cars or motel
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   A 21-year-old man with all the promise of youth tied to a fence
and left to die, propped up like a scarecrow. And now the snow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-19-98 1712EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
