<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Oct. 20, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATE-NAMES (San Francisco) _ Three candidates for local
office have sued the city for leaving their Chinese names off
thousands of absentee voter booklets. The suit argues that
monolingual Chinese voters will be deprived of a full choice of
candidates unless corrected booklets are prepared. By JULIE CHAO
and RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-RELIGION (San Francisco) _ Republican Attorney General Dan
Lungren has entered the final two weeks of the gubernatorial
campaign like he started it _ by injecting the thorny topic of
religion into politics. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   DEMENTIA-CREATIVITY (San Francisco) _ A mew study finds that
patients with frontotemporal dementia, which attacks the front
parts of the brain, sometimes exhibit surges of creativity that
often seemed to come out of nowhere. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHOOTINGS (San Francisco) _ Hoping to discourage
revelers from shooting guns in the air in celebration, two San
Francisco supervisors have proposed banning the sale of ammunition
within city limits for the seven days before the New Year's Eve and
the Fourth of July holidays. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMUTER-TRAIN (San Francisco) _ The Altamont Commuter Express
train zipped about 700 commuters into Silicon Valley on its first
day, prompting cheers from riders and high-tech business leaders.
Planners say it won't make a dent on traffic congestion because the
real problem is that housing growth in the South Bay hasn't kept
pace with the job boom there. By TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DREADS-SUMMIT (Houston) _ The young woman solemnly stood up in
front of the audience that gathered here. ``My name is Courtney
Wilson, and I'm a perm addict,' said the 20-year-old nursing
student. The room dissolved in laughter and nods of agreement.
After a lifetime of having their hair permed, pulled, fried,
frizzed and fashioned in unnatural ways, those who gathered for the
National Dreadlock Summit were thankful to say they were free at
last. By CLIFFORD PUGH.
</P>
<P>
   MULTIPLE-SCLEROSIS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Aurora Turk is facing the
uncertainty of living with multiple sclerosis, a debilitating,
chronic and sometimes disabling disease of the nervous system.
Though MS isn't fatal, some people die of complications. Unlike
many illnesses, there's no clear prognosis and MS varies in
severity and symptoms from person to person. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARBAGE-MUSIC-REVIEW (Houston) _ Shirley Manson tried, she
really did, to play the part of sophisticated pop diva during a
sold-out Garbage show. But after ripping through a few songs from
the band's dance-driven rock catalog, the fiery redhead announced
she'd had enough. With that, Manson pulled her hair back into a
ponytail and traded her heeled boots in for a pair of Nike tennis
shoes. By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   FAINT-DANCE-REVIEW (Houston) _ It's different, offbeat, a trifle
goofy _ well, what would you expect of a piece titled ``Maria the
Storm Cloud,'' performed by a dance group called 33 Fainting
Spells? By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SERIES (San Diego) _ The New York Yankees are two victories
away from winning the World Series for the 24th time. The only
thing in their way is a San Diego franchise that has won one World
Series game in 30 seasons of existence. Now it's San Diego's turn.
By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ State District Judge Mike
Westergren, a Democrat running for the Texas Supreme Court, is
definitely swimming against the tide in this election season. It's
tough enough that the underfunded Westergren is trying to unseat a
Republican incumbent, Craig Enoch. But Westergren also has kind
things to say, sort of, about lawyers. By CLAY ROBISON
</P>
