<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Amnesty International has caught the not
inconsiderable shortfalls and lapses in our criminal justice
structure. Many are now built into what passes for the system.
(Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Only 8 percent of graduate degrees in
physics are awarded to females. To Jadwiga Sebrechts this is a
gender gap. It's obviously a statistical difference _ you could
even say a gaping one _ but is it necessarily evidence of
injustice? Are young women not going into physics and chemistry
because the environment conditions them to look elsewhere? (Skube,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ In 1951, I spent part of my
seventeenth summer on a dairy farm in upstate New York with my
friend Alice and her grandparents. One morning over freshly picked
raspberries and real cow cream, her 88-year-old grandmother
admonished her 93-year-old mate: ``Clarence, don't speak in
cliches. It ages one.'' Pretty funny, I thought at the time, for
folks of so considerable a vintage to be concerned with such
things. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ ``Every governor's race since 1920
has been about education,'' said Garry Mauro, jacket slung over his
chair, sidewalk-worn shoes resting for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   One may go back those 78 years and find taxes, highways or water
high on the issues list. But since public schools are the state's
chief responsibility, Mauro's statement is safe. This race for
governor will not break the string. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
