<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallowing in the muck of cliches _ when appropriate, of course
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ In 1951, I spent part of my seventeenth
summer on a dairy farm in upstate New York with my friend Alice and
her grandparents. One morning over freshly picked raspberries and
real cow cream, her 88-year-old grandmother
</P>
<P>
   admonished her 93-year-old mate: ``Clarence, don't speak in
cliches. It ages one.'' Pretty funny, I thought at the time, for
folks of so considerable a vintage to be concerned with such
things.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've come to appreciate the wisdom of such
advice. Antiquated thought is evidenced in archaic expression, but
having made that disclaimer, and with apologies to Alice's
grandmother, I'm going to ignore her advice and wallow in a
hackneyed image or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't beat 'em, join 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   We've all heard that one, as in: ``Well, if everybody else is
jumping off of the jetty here in Shark Harbor, I might as well join
in.'' Does that translate to yet another old saw: ``Better dead
than different?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. And I'm sure there are times when conventional wisdom
dictates: ``Don't make waves.'' Like the time my friend Jeanne and
I stumbled into an all-night diner in the Florida Keys looking for
a cup of coffee and found instead a convention of motorcycle mommas
in no mood to deal with a couple of old broads in Birkenstocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatta' you think?'' Jeanne muttered. ``Fight or flight?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Better safe than sorry,'' I allowed. We bugged.
</P>
<P>
   But compliance and avoidance aren't always ``just the ticket.''
``There comes a time'' when we have to ``dig in our heels'' and
``just say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Now is that time.
</P>
<P>
   Hustler huckster Larry Flynt is offering $1 million to anyone
who can hock up proof of an ``adulterous sexual encounter with a
current member of the United States Congress or a high-ranking
government official.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, in the past 10 months the American public has been
bombarded with ``sick'' (our President caviling his way around the
truth), ``sicker'' (Linda ``The Wire'' Tripp proclaiming to the
press in a trembling voice: ``I'm just like you. I'm an average
American who found herself in a situation not of her own making,''
and now ``sickest'' (Flynt, a greedy smutmonger looking to cash in
on
</P>
<P>
   our nation's embarrassment).
</P>
<P>
   ``Warts on the backside of humanity,'' my father would have
sneered.
</P>
<P>
   My teen-age peers and I would have put it a little more crudely:
``Urp! Slop! Bring the mop!''
</P>
<P>
   During the '60s and '70s when protesting became
state-of-the-art, I was busy being a wife and later, a mother, so I
never had time to demonstrate against anything except maybe a
feeble in-house rebellion when the diaper service was late. (For my
younger readers, those were the days before diapers came in a box
</P>
<P>
   and ended up in a landfill.) But now I have the time and it's my
turn:
</P>
<P>
   To all of the liars, Larrys, Lindas, and Monicas out there:
``Get a life'' and ``get outta' my face'' because ``I've had it
with you.'' Crawl back under your rocks. I'm not going to buy your
crummy magazine or your sleazy books. I'm boycotting your tasteless
drivel, refusing your rubbish. ``Get the picture?'' I don't like
your kind and I refuse to donate to your retirement fund. This
</P>
<P>
   sickening cycle of crime/punishment/publish/prosper must be
brought to a ``screaming halt'' and the only way I can think of to
do it is by keeping my plastic in my pocket.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Alice's grandmother would have agreed and maybe even
added a couple of more cliches: ``What the hell? It's worth a
try.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
