</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: For governor, two at a chalkboard
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Every governor's race since 1920 has been about
education,'' said Garry Mauro, jacket slung over his chair,
sidewalk-worn shoes resting for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   One may go back those 78 years and find taxes, highways or water
high on the issues list. But since public schools are the state's
chief responsibility, Mauro's statement is safe. This race for
governor will not break the string.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there's more to Mauro's differences with the governor than
that. He asserts that Bush goes too soft on polluters, that he
erred in allowing plans to proceed for a nuclear dump in West
Texas. He points out that the numbers defy Bush's 1994 promise to
end felons' early release _ with 60,000 getting out early since
then. (That's fewer than under his predecessor, Bush's people will
say.)
</P>
<P>
   But education is the subject of most of this campaign discourse.
At a time when candidates can fudge their differences almost to
indistinction, the differences here are downright stark.
</P>
<P>
   The key distinction is on what to do for schools with the
state's projected $8 billion budget surplus. Mauro would raise
teachers' salaries across the board by $6,000 to bring Texas to the
national average for teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants the lion's share of the surplus _ $2 billion _ to go
to school property tax relief, which, presumably, would give school
districts wiggle room to raise money through ad valorem levies. In
addition, Bush supports directing $1 billion back to school
districts to use for teacher pay hikes and to meet other needs such
as smaller class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro would take Bush's ante on class sizes and raise it
considerably, borrowing $2 billion from the Available School Fund
to loan to schools to build more classrooms to lower class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   After making that money available, he said, he'd hold school
districts' feet to the fire to meet the state-required 1-to-22
teacher-student ratio for kindergarten through Grade 4. Too many
are evading it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Mauro's teacher pay plan say that an across-the-board
raise would skirt accountability issues like rewarding teachers
based on merit or targeting extra pay where teacher shortages are
great, such as math, science and bilingual classes.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro counters that the state awarded teachers an
across-the-board raise in 1985's landmark H.B. 72, which
dramatically changed the landscape of public education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to put the pay-raise ball in school boards' hands.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also warns that increasing pay across the board will
unsettle a delicate equity formula in which property wealthy
districts get less from the state than do property-poor ones.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro calls that a ``specious'' dodge by those who don't want
all teachers to get a raise.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is bullish on charter schools and authorized an
expansion on the handful of charters first authorized in 1995,
Mauro urges that Texas put on the brakes, at least until it sees
whether those charter schools created make any difference in
achievement. Early results _ some will call them premature _ have
not been glowing for charter schools as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   As for school vouchers, while Bush supports a pilot project for
vouchers, the concept is conspicuously downplayed in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said he supports choice within school districts, but
vehemently opposes vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro urges that Texas ``seize the initiative'' provided by the
current good economic times to make some dramatic investments in
public schools. ``This time will not last.''
</P>
<P>
   Submitted: two ``pro-education'' candidates with a lot of chalk
on their hands. On Nov. 3: a show of hands by the voters.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
