<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-HUME21-COX     10-20 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-HUME21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hume part of equation in Ireland's elusive peace
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ About 15 years ago, John Hume _ who last
week won the Nobel Peace Prize _ built a little stone cottage on a
spit of land overlooking the River Foyle in Donegal, just a few
miles over the Northern Ireland border. The chances of his being
assassinated were somewhat diminished on this remote and windswept
promontory.
</P>
<P>
   Hume liked to sit in his yard and watch ships ply the Foyle on
their way to and from Derry. He smoked too many cigarettes while he
stared out to sea. I sat with him in his yard a few times. He told
me more than once that this was the last bit of Ireland seen by
emigrants as they sailed to America and Canada. How sad, he would
say, that after almost everybody was driven out of Ireland, those
few who remained took to killing each other.
</P>
<P>
   To get to his cottage, Hume had to pass through British army
checkpoints on the road from Derry. The guards knew him; he was a
member of Parliament, after all, one of the most highly visible men
in Ireland and Britain. Still, every time he reached a checkpoint,
the soldiers asked for an ID.
</P>
<P>
   ``To show us our proper place, I guess,'' he would say of the
British soldiers. ``But they're not the enemy. The enemy is
ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Hume's enemies were the people who threw firebombs and
bricks through the windows of his Derry home. He was a moderate,
therefore a target.
</P>
<P>
   Those enemies who didn't resort to weapons employed verbal
bombast. Hume's enemies _ virtually everybody on any side of the
Irish question _ used to say he was nothing but a wily politician
interested in just one thing: winning the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Hume loved that twisted line of reasoning. The illogic brought a
smile to his face, a rarity, because John Hume and Northern Ireland
didn't have much to smile about.
</P>
<P>
   If a prize is awarded for peace, then a state of peace must
exist, he would say. Any award would be incidental to the real
prize. Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Hume liked to say that to live in Northern Ireland is to live in
a land where up is down, left is right. It's a place where language
_ even music and art _ are weapons. And when the spoken word fails
to sway your opponent, there's always the bomb and the bullet.
</P>
<P>
   It's been that way since Henry II gave chunks of Ireland to his
Norman lackeys in the 12th century.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially been that way since 1968, when British troops
came to Northern Ireland to keep the peace, another inversion of
logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been so many lows in the last 30 years,'' his wife,
Pat, said Monday. ``We have bulletproof glass on the windows now.
Maybe we can take it down soon. And we don't get up to the cottage
as much as we'd like. John could use the quiet. He's worked hard,
you know, so hard. He earned this award, but it's Ireland's.
Ireland struggled all those 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hume spent those three decades stalking peace with the same
bulldog determination his enemies spent stalking him.
</P>
<P>
   His political theory was simple, if impractical: ``Ireland's
people must learn to share Ireland, must respect their differences,
must harness their strengths, must stop the killing.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew this prescription was easier said than done, especially
in such Catholic ghettos as the Bogside area of Derry, where he
lived as a child and where the economic pulse is easy to take
because there is none.
</P>
<P>
   Hume sought to make changes by becoming a master of the
political back room, sometimes literally.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting a Derry City Council meeting in 1989, he
adjourned to an anteroom with two councilors. One, a former IRA
member, had served time in prison for blowing up the council
chambers years earlier. The other, a strident Unionist, had once
cheated death when an IRA bomb strapped under his car fell off when
he hit a pothole. In private, over many cigarettes and strong tea,
Hume got them to reach agreement on a jobs resolution. He knew
these men had to tell their constituents what they wanted to hear,
but he believed that fair deals struck in private could _ slowly
and over time _ be sold to the public.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, Hume, in his rumpled suits and baggy sweaters,
preached his message of peace. Few listened. He grew old before his
time, face creased, shoulders down, streaks of gray in his
once-black hair. Irish-American politicians preferred to be
photographed with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams because it played
well to voters back home. But it was common knowledge in Ireland
that Adams was powerless to call off the dogs of war.
</P>
<P>
   Hume and Nobel co-winner David Trimble _ a Protestant and
Unionist _ did what the terrorists on all sides could not: They
brought everybody to the negotiating table. They stopped the
killing. They made progress, a word that had no meaning in Irish
politics for generations.
</P>
<P>
   They sought peace and found it.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in Strasbourg, where he is a member of the European
Parliament, Hume said Monday: ``The award shows unified
international support for the peace process. That's important for
Ireland. With support the process can continue, must continue.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rocky hills near Hume's Donegal cottage, there's a little
restaurant named St. John's. Over dinner at St John's one dreary
night in June 1988, Hume and I tallied the month's mayhem: 12
children injured when the IRA blew up a school bus, six British
soldiers bombed near Belfast, a policeman shot dead in front of his
family, another cop shot seven times in the back while visiting his
widowed mother, seven dead in a bus bombing in Omagh, an old man
and child hit by snipers firing at a British soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The killing will go on until we learn to talk with each
other,'' he said. ``First talk, then action, then peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Right about then, the composer Phil Coulter walked into the
restaurant. Coulter wrote The Town I Love So Well, theme song of
the Irish peace movement. The place was nearly empty. Coulter came
right over to Hume, asked about the family, told him to keep up the
effort. Hume told Coulter that his music was a beautiful and a
calming influence on roiling tempers and seething hatreds.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter told Hume: ``You give voice to the meaning of my
music.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hume got his prize. Peace. Who else but a wily politician
could pull that off in Ireland?
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
