<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK21-COX     10-20 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When running with the dogs, stick with program
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dogs of the Dow are living in interesting times.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when both broad and narrow market indices raced
ahead, the 10 ``dog'' stocks were left far behind. You would have
done better buying an index fund than the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when the market was in the tank, the dogs won, in a
way. At least they didn't lose nearly as much value as did the
overall market.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, with the market streaking ahead again, the dogs
lagged.
</P>
<P>
   All this raises once again the question of whether a strategy
can be so simple and so appealing _ and still work well? To put it
another way, if it's all that good, why isn't everybody doing it?
And why aren't they all rich?
</P>
<P>
   The dogs of the Dow rationale is indeed an appealing one: You
buy the stocks of big, sturdy, well-known companies when they are
out of favor and thus unnaturally cheap. When your stocks come back
into favor, you sell them for a pleasing profit and invest the
money in the next round of ``dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   The technique also is appealing, partly because it is easy to
understand and partly because it is entirely mechanical. Follow the
formula and you win.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: You go through the 30 stocks in the Dow
Jones industrial average and pick the 10 that have the highest
dividend yields. You invest an equal number of dollars in the
shares of each of the 10. At the end of one year _ or whatever time
period you select _ you sell any stocks that are no longer in the
top 10 and replace them with the newest dogs. You repeat the cycle
without fail for as long as you want to invest in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   You are assuming that all of the Dow 30 stocks are sound
companies, able to weather just about any storm and thus are
conservative investments. You pick the high-yield stocks among them
on the theory that a lot of people are worried about those
companies' prospects and thus their prices are unnaturally low.
</P>
<P>
   More years than not, the Dow dogs have outperformed the broad
market, as the chart indicates. Mutual funds have sprung up to
appeal to dog investors. Brokerages sell unit investment trusts
that invest only in dog stocks. And discount brokerages have made
it cheaper for do-it-yourself investors to buy and sell the stocks
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Investors have put an estimated $20 billion into
dogs of the Dow investments.
</P>
<P>
   Does it still work? Skeptics point out that the dogs' most
impressive returns were not just in bad market years but also in
years past, before it became popular. ``It's a very good
strategy,'' said Susan Dziubinski, editor of the Morningstar
FundInvestor magazine. ``But once everybody's in on the secret, the
success of the system tends to break down.''
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts counter that the dogs have been tested back to 1929
and have beaten the market 64 percent of the time. ``It will take a
long time before the dogs have had their day,'' said Jim
O'Shaughnessy, founder of a mutual fund that puts one-third of its
assets into the dogs. ``It's not a matter of opinion. It's a matter
of whether it makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to pursue ``dogs'' investing, here are some things
to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   _ Expenses matter. Annual sales will run up transaction costs,
as will the resultant taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide on a mutual fund or unit investment trust, look
carefully at the expense ratios and other fees you will have to
pay. I wouldn't want to pay much more than, say, 1 percent a year
to the manager of a passive investment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Timing is important. Make sure you hold your investments for
at least one year and a day, or you won't qualify for the lowest
capital gains tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   You should think carefully about opening a dogs program at the
first of January. A lot of other investors might be buying or
selling dogs right then, skewing the prices. Eastman Kodak went up
5 percent on the first trading day this year, at least in part
because it joined the dog pack.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Dow dogs is a rigid, long-term strategy. In any given
year, some of the dogs are really stinky, making them hard to buy.
Some will become really successful, making them hard to let go.
</P>
<P>
   _ For more information on the Internet, check out
http://www.dogsofthedow.com/ or http://www.fool.com/school.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail:hezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
