<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUY-STOCKS-NOW?-2-KIPLINGER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PART II: BUT WHICH MUTUAL FUNDS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (This is the last article in a 2-part series. To publish this
``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased. For purchase
information _ or to find out how to get a free trial of the
``Kiplinger's Money Power'' package _ call New York Times Syndicate
sales representative Connie White at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) 
 FREE TO KIPLINGER'S MONEY POWER CLIENTS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 BY STEVEN T. GOLDBERG 
 ADAPTED FROM ``BUT WHICH MUTUAL FUNDS?'' by STEVEN T. GOLDBERG  
 Copyright 1998 The Kiplinger Washington Editors, Inc. 
 Published by Kiplinger Books  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the stock market's recent nose dive, it's easy to put
together a solid portfolio of mutual funds to meet your investment
needs. What's more, you can do it without knowing much about funds.
</P>
<P>
   Listed below are suggestions for ready-made portfolios (groups
of funds) that work together _ and that are suited to your
individual needs. The reason for owning a portfolio of funds is
that some types of funds will do well when others do poorly.
</P>
<P>
   The previous article helped you determine how much to invest in
stocks and lower-risk investments. The biggest factor in that
decision is how far you are from needing your money. Another
important factor is how much risk you can tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   To judge whether you have a low, moderate or high tolerance for
risk, just think it through for a minute: Are you the type of
person who can handle declines in your stock funds? Or are you
likely to panic and sell during bad times?
</P>
<P>
   If you have some trouble with risk, you're a low- or
moderate-risk investor. Otherwise, you're a high-risk investor.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need the following tables to assemble your portfolio of
funds.
</P>
<P>
   HOW MUCH OF YOUR MONEY TO INVEST IN STOCKS FOR RETIREMENT OR
WHILE IN RETIREMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The column on the left represents the number of years until
retirement or your age in retirement)
 &UR; .........................TOLERANCE FOR RISK &QL; 
 &UR; ........................LOW...............MODERATE.........HIGH &QL; 
 &UR; More than 15 yrs.........100 percent....100 percent....100 percent &QL; 
 &UR; 10 to 15 yrs..............70.............80............100 &QL; 
 &UR; 6 to 10 yrs...............60.............70............100 &QL; 
 &UR; 0 to 6 yrs................40.............50.............85 &QL; 
 &UR; Early retirement (age 65-75).35..........45.............60 &QL; 
 &UR; Late retirement (over age 75).30.........40.............50 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW MUCH TO INVEST IN STOCKS FOR ALL GOALS EXCEPT RETIREMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The column on the left represents the number of years until
you'll need the money)
 &UR; ....................TOLERANCE FOR RISK &QL; 
 &UR; ....................LOW............MODERATE............HIGH &QL; 
 &UR; More than 15 yrs....80 percent........100 percent.....100 percent &QL; 
 &UR; 10 to 15 yrs........60.................80.............100 &QL; 
 &UR; 6 to 10 yrs.........55.................70..............90 &QL; 
 &UR; 4 to 6 yrs..........30.................40..............60 &QL; 
 &UR; 2 to 4..............10.................25..............35 &QL; 
 &UR; 0 to 2...............0..................0...............0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next step is selecting a portfolio of funds that work in
sync. Owning a diversified mix of stock funds (and usually some
bond funds) minimizes the fluctuations of your overall investments.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind that the funds in this article are not necessarily
going to be the top performers in their categories. But they are
proven, solid funds that work well together. That's what any
investor should search for.
 &UR; USING INDEX FUNDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before looking at portfolios of actively managed funds, here's a
really simple alternative _ one that I have found is easier for
many people to actually implement.
</P>
<P>
   This approach employs index funds, which mirror the entire stock
market (or bond market). Because they do, index funds can give you
exposure to all segments of the markets.
</P>
<P>
   These funds strive to track a market index or average _ rather
than to excel. At first blush, that may sound like a losing
strategy, but it's not.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that most fund managers fail to beat the averages.
Adding to the simplicity of index funds, you don't have to monitor
them once you buy them. That's because virtually anyone can manage
an index fund.
</P>
<P>
   Further adding to their advantage, index funds charge lower
annual expenses of investors than do actively managed funds.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard (800-635-1511) has fine, low-cost index funds. You can
build a great, long-term stock portfolio with just two:
</P>
<P>
   _ Vanguard Index Total Stock Market, which tracks all U.S.
stocks, not just large ones.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vanguard Total International, which gives you the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Following are portfolios using these funds, as well as bond
funds when needed.
</P>
<P>
   FOR RETIREMENT 0 TO 50 YEARS AWAY _ OR ANY OTHER GOALS SIX OR
MORE YEARS AWAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Invest 75 percent of your stock money in Vanguard Index Total
Stock Market and 25 percent in Vanguard Total International.
</P>
<P>
   If the tables say you need to keep some of your money out of
stocks, invest that portion in Vanguard Index Total Bond Market. If
you're in the 28 percent tax bracket or higher and are investing
outside a tax-deferred account, put your bond money in Vanguard
Municipal High Yield.
</P>
<P>
   FOR EARLY RETIREMENT (UP TO AGE 75) OR ANY OTHER GOALS FOUR TO
SIX YEARS IN THE FUTURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Invest 90 percent of your stock money in Vanguard Index Total
Stock Market and 10 percent in Vanguard Total International.
</P>
<P>
   Invest your bond money in Vanguard Index Total Bond Market. If
you're in the 28 percent tax bracket or higher, though, instead
divide your bond money evenly between Vanguard Municipal High Yield
and Vanguard Municipal Intermediate.
</P>
<P>
   FOR LATE RETIREMENT (AGES 75 AND OVER) OR ANY OTHER GOALS TWO TO
FOUR YEARS AWAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Put all your stock money into Vanguard Index Total Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   Put half your bond money in Vanguard Bond Index Short Term,
leaving the remainder in Vanguard Index Total Bond Market. If
you're in the 28 percent bracket or higher, instead divide your
bond money between Vanguard Municipal Intermediate and Vanguard
Municipal Limited Term.
</P>
<P>
   FOR GOALS TWO OR FEWER YEARS AWAY (EXCEPT FOR RETIREMENT) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Divide all your money between Vanguard Bond Index Short Term and
Vanguard Money Market Prime. If you're in the 28 percent tax
bracket or higher, substitute Vanguard Municipal Limited Term for
Vanguard Bond Index Short Term.
 &UR; ANOTHER APPROACH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using index funds, you can invest in T. Rowe Price
Spectrum Growth (800-638-5660) and T. Rowe Price Spectrum Income.
Both are low-cost ``funds of funds'' _ in other words, they
themselves invest in other T. Rowe Price funds.
</P>
<P>
   Consulting the tables, use Spectrum Growth in place of all stock
funds and Spectrum Income when stock funds are not called for. When
you are two years from needing your money, shift it to T. Rowe
Price Prime Reserves.
</P>
<P>
   That's all there is to it.
 &UR; CHERRY-PICKING FUNDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's only a little more bother to gather a portfolio of actively
managed funds from more than one fund family. There's more
paperwork and such, but it may be worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Like the previous portfolios, each of the these will give you
ownership of U.S. and foreign stocks, stocks of large companies and
stocks of small companies, as well as stocks of fast-growing
companies and stocks of cheap, beaten-down companies. As you get
closer to needing your money, the portfolios provide you with less
aggressive funds.
</P>
<P>
   In most instances, they'll also give you exposure to different
corners of the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   FOR RETIREMENT IN 10 OR MORE YEARS _ OR ANY OTHER GOALS 15 OR
MORE YEARS AWAY:
</P>
<P>
   _ Skyline Small Cap Value Plus (15 percent of your stock money;
800-458-5222).
</P>
<P>
   _ Berger New Generation (10 percent; 800-333-1001).
</P>
<P>
   _ Harbor Capital Appreciation (25 percent; 800-422-1050).
</P>
<P>
   _ Selected American Shares (20 percent; 800-243-1575).
</P>
<P>
   _ Artisan International (30 percent; 800-344-1770).
</P>
<P>
   Put any non-stock money into Loomis Sayles Bond, which you'll
have to buy through a discount broker such as Charles Schwab
(800-435-4000). If you're in the 28 percent tax bracket or higher
and investing outside a tax-deferred retirement account, substitute
Vanguard Municipal High Yield (800-635-1511).
</P>
<P>
   FOR RETIREMENT 0 TO 10 YEARS AWAY OR ANY OTHER GOALS 10 TO 15
YEARS AWAY:
</P>
<P>
   _ Berger New Generation (10 percent)
</P>
<P>
   _ Third Avenue Small Cap (10 percent; 800-443-1021)
</P>
<P>
   _ Harbor Capital Appreciation (25 percent)
</P>
<P>
   _ Babson Value (25 percent; 800-422-2766)
</P>
<P>
   _ Artisan International (30 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Divide your non-stock money between Loomis Sayles Bond and
Harbor Bond (800-422-1050). If you're in the 28 percent bracket or
higher, instead use Vanguard Municipal High Yield and Vanguard
Municipal Intermediate.
</P>
<P>
   FOR EARLY RETIREMENT (UP TO AGE 75) OR ANY OTHER GOALS SIX TO 10
YEARS IN THE FUTURE:
</P>
<P>
   _ T. Rowe Price Equity Income (35 percent; 800-638-5660)
</P>
<P>
   _ Yacktman (35 percent; 800-525-8258)
</P>
<P>
   _ T. Rowe Price Small Cap Stock (10 percent; 800-638-5660)
</P>
<P>
   _ Tweedy Browne Global Value (20 percent; 800-432-4789).
</P>
<P>
   Divide your non-stock money between Loomis Sayles Bond and
Harbor Bond. If you're in the 28 percent bracket or higher, instead
use Vanguard Municipal High Yield and Vanguard Municipal
Intermediate.
</P>
<P>
   FOR LATE RETIREMENT (AGES 75 AND OVER) OR ANY OTHER GOALS FOUR
TO SIX YEARS AWAY:
</P>
<P>
   _ T. Rowe Price Equity Income (60 percent)
</P>
<P>
   _ Royce Premier (20 percent; 800-221-4268)
</P>
<P>
   _ CGM Realty Fund (20 percent; 800-345-4048).
</P>
<P>
   Invest one quarter of your bond money in Northeast Investors
Trust (800-225-6704). Put the remainder into Harbor Bond or
Vanguard Municipal Intermediate (800-635-1511) depending on your
tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   FOR GOALS (EXCEPT RETIREMENT) TWO TO FOUR YEARS AWAY:
</P>
<P>
   _ Greenspring (65 percent; 800-366-3863)
</P>
<P>
   _ Fidelity Real Estate (35 percent; 800-544-8888)
</P>
<P>
   Divide your bond money evenly among Harbor Bond, Loomis Sayles
High Yield (again, you'll have to buy the fund through a discount
broker) and Vanguard Short-Term Corporate (800-635-1511). If you're
in the 28 percent tax bracket or higher, use Loomis Sayles High
Yield, but substitute Vanguard Municipal Intermediate and Vanguard
Municipal Limited-Term for the other two funds.
</P>
<P>
   FOR GOALS FEWER THAN TWO YEARS AWAY:
</P>
<P>
   Split your money equally between Strong Advantage (800-368-1030)
and Vanguard Money Market Prime (800-635-1511).
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This article is adapted from ``But Which Mutual Funds?'' by
Steven T. Goldberg, published by Kiplinger Books. The book is
available for $24.95 at bookstores or by calling 800-280-7165.
Goldberg is the ``Saving &AMP; Investing'' columnist for the
``Kiplinger's Money Power'' package, distributed by The New York
Times Syndicate.)
