<SLUG> BC-MULTIPLE-SCLEROSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MS PATIENTS FIND DRUG TREATMENTS HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Aurora Turk was relieved when she found out she
had multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Thank you, God.' I thought I had some lethal
tumor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For six months, no one had known what was wrong. Turk, 29, had
just married. She was under a lot of pressure at her job as an
executive assistant in Washington, D.C. She was dead tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, one day, I woke up and I was getting this
numbness in my leg,'' said Turk, who now lives in suburban Albany
with her husband. ``Then, five days later, this numbness spread to
both legs and I could hardly walk.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a year ago. Today, Turk is facing the uncertainty of
living with multiple sclerosis, a debilitating, chronic and
sometimes disabling disease of the nervous system. Though MS isn't
fatal, some people die of complications. Ask about the challenges
of living with MS, and people will often talk about the
unpredictability of the disease. Unlike many illnesses, there's no
clear prognosis and MS varies in severity and symptoms from person
to person.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the few generalizations you can make:
</P>
<P>
   _ Some 350,000 Americans have multiple sclerosis, with nearly
200 new cases diagnosed every week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Onset occurs most often between the ages of 20 and 40, and
symptoms may include tingling, numbness, slurred speech, blurred
vision and muscle weakness. Fatigue is often a constant struggle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Women are twice as likely as men to get the disease. For
reasons unclear, it's most common among people who live in colder
climates, where it affects 69 of every 100,000 people. In the
South, it's about half that number.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure and no one is sure what causes the disease.
Researchers believe the body's immune system attacks the myelin, or
fatty tissues, that protect nerve fibers and help conduct
electrical impulses.
</P>
<P>
   When myelin is destroyed or damaged, the ability of the nerves
to conduct electrical impulses is disrupted and people may develop
new or aggravated symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the trigger is,'' said Dr. Neil Lava, a
neurologist at the Albany Medical Center here. ``Why does someone
have two attacks in one year and another have no attacks in three
years?''
</P>
<P>
   Using drugs such as Avonex, Capoxone and Betaseron diminish the
frequency and severity of those attacks at a price _ a year's
supply can cost more than $2,000 in insurance co-payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's night and day,'' Lava said. ``Prior to five years ago
what did we have to offer patients but moral support, physical
therapy and some medicines?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning. There are going to be bigger
changes down the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the latest research is looking at ways of preventing
nerve damage in the first place. Another line of research is
looking at methods of repairing damaged nerves by re-growing
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex disease,'' Lava said. ``There's not going
to be one treatment that makes everything go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Hanlon, 60, credits Avonex, one of the newest medicines,
with helping her cope. She's been living with MS for 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better today than I was 20 years ago,'' said Hanlon, of
Averill Park, a community east of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Though grateful for her good health, she still experiences rough
days, when she has trouble walking or is especially fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   Hanlon has learned how to listen to her own body. She swims
twice a week and often naps. ``I expected to be in a wheelchair or
a nursing home at this age,'' she said. ``I never thought I'd be as
well as I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Turk is also optimistic about her future, though she is still
adjusting to the uncertainty of living with MS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different kind of illness,'' she said. ``People, they
don't know much about it. They look at you and they say, `She's
fine.' I'm not fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``MS is so silent. It's difficult to deal with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
