<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR &LR;      10-20 1664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FOREIGN POLICY ON CONGO INSPIRED KINGSOLVER NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Barbara Kingsolver was 7, her family moved from its home in
Kentucky to central Africa, where her parents did public health
work for a year. Her father, a physician, wanted to go where he
could be most useful, and no place needed him more than the Congo,
a country struggling with new independence and old rivalries, a
place on the brink of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingsolvers stayed there just long enough for Barbara to
miss second grade. She returned to the United States with memories
of life in an African village, an understanding of what it meant to
be a minority, and an interest in the Congo that would draw her
over the years to stories about its ongoing political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 30 years later, she has written a novel that is rooted in
her time in Africa. ``The Poisonwood Bible'' (Harper Flamingo, $26)
is the story of renegade Baptist missionary Nathan Price, who in
1959 takes his family from its home in Georgia to the Congo, where
he is determined to convert people and save souls. Narrated by
Nathan's wife, Orleanna, and each of their four daughters (they
range in age from 5 to 15), it is Kingsolver's most political
novel, built around the violent struggle for power in the Congo and
the role American interests played in it.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsolver does not apologize for this, although the insistent
social and political messages in her previous books (``Animal
Dreams,'' ``Pigs in Heaven'') drew criticism from some reviewers.
She will continue to write on such subjects, she says, and she
encourages others to do the same. With her advance for ``The
Poisonwood Bible'' she has founded the Bellwether Prize for
Fiction, an award of $25,000 (plus guaranteed publication) given
each year to an emerging writer whose manuscript ``addresses issues
of social justice and the impact of culture and politics on human
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingsolver lives in Tucson, Ariz., with her husband, Stephen
Hopp, and daughters, Camille, 11, and Lily, 2. In a recent
interview, she talked about her politics, her art and her great
commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: Did it take a lot of energy to write this book?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: Energy, plus blood, sweat and tears. It was by far the
hardest thing I've done. But that's OK. I try to do something new
with each book, and (begin itals) have, (end itals) but somehow it
hasn't been as evident to people in the past as it seems to be now.
Everyone has said, ``What in heaven's name got into you?'' This
book is so different.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you begin?
</P>
<P>
   A: I suppose the grain of sand that started this book was U.S.
foreign policy, something I've been interested in my whole adult
life, ever since I moved to Tucson and began noticing what the U.S.
was doing in my name and with my tax dollars to other countries,
mostly Latin America. I think what the U.S. did in the Congo stands
for so much in terms of cultural, economic, and spiritual
arrogance. I wanted to ask not what happened, but more than that:
What do we make of it now, and how do we move forward?
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did your brief time in the Congo play into it?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm sort of hesitant to mention it. I wage a constant battle
against people's assumptions that everything I write is
autobiographical. My own family, I'm happy to say, was very
different from the one in this book. But since I was 8 I've had a
personal interest in the Congo, so of course I felt the weight of
its tragedy, year after year, just in the small bits of information
that came through to us.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are many of the details of ``The Poisonwood Bible'' from your
time there?
</P>
<P>
   A: I came home with powerful memories. And I kept a journal. The
day we left for the Congo was the day I began keeping a diary in
earnest, so I guess in some ways I can trace my writing life back
to that day. I knew, in the way that you know when you're a kid,
that I was about to embark on an experience that would so change me
that everything would be different from then on. I wanted to record
that, to peg it to the paper somehow, so I started a journal. I
still have those journals. They're woefully inadequate. There are
whole weeks when I wrote nothing more significant than ``I had a
fight with my brother.'' But then there would be a day when I
wrote, ``The witch doctor came today and there was a lion in the
village.'' Nothing as complete as I would have liked, but enough to
help me remember.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You use five narrative voices in this novel. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: I always begin with theme, and then I construct characters
who can play out that theme. There were many viewpoints on what
happened in the Congo. My task was to identify those points of
view, fine tune them and assign each one to a character with
physical and emotional characteristics that would make her point of
view work. I needed to get people emotionally involved, make them
care. That's the artist's job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The voices are very different. Orleanna, the mother, is very
mature, capable of deep love and sorrow. Rachael, the oldest
daughter, is almost irritatingly shallow. Did you like both of
these characters?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, I loved them! I loved them all. You can't write a
character that you don't believe in. I think Orleanna is the
conscience of the novel, but oddly enough, Rachael's voice was the
easiest to write, even though I'd like to believe that she's the
most different from me. Streams that move that fast don't run very
deep. She's a cultural cliche _ I lifted her voice straight out of
``Life'' magazine from 1959. All I had to do was page through the
ads, and there she was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you write the novel straight through?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, I don't write a book in a linear way. First I construct
an outline, and then I layer things in. I write layers and layers
of detail so that I can go back and make everything fit together.
In this case, the end of the book was written long before I
finished.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does criticism of your political themes bother you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Any writer in this culture who wants to address issues of
social change and responsibility runs the risk of being called too
political. It's very provincial. In just about all the rest of the
world, social justice and the ways that economics and culture
affect human relations are considered the fundamental domain of
art. Look at who has won the Nobel Prize. Nadine Gordimer.
Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn. John Steinbeck. Sometime in the 1950s we
suddenly were provided with this artificial split between art and
politics and we've never gotten over it. It doesn't bother me at
all because it's irrelevant and will pass. People will look back on
this someday as a real stupid time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you write what you want to write?
</P>
<P>
   A: I write what I (begin itals) have (end itals) to write. It's
not a choice for me. I'm a cultural and social realist in my art. I
write about the world that I see and understand, and I've never
lived in a world that doesn't have racism and sexism and cultural
imperialism in it. I can't imagine that world. Evidently some
people do live in that world, but I don't.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't you leave the United States right after the Gulf War
because you objected to the patriotic fervor that broke out here
then?
</P>
<P>
   A: That was an important process for me. I got disgusted and
left, but after a while came to realize that to dismiss the problem
by running away is a coward's solution. To love something enough to
change it is a more heroic goal. If the problems are here, the
solutions are here, too. The funny thing is, there were millions of
people who felt the way I did about the Gulf War. We just didn't
get a voice in the media, and so we were manipulated into believing
in our own isolation. If you envision anything other than a
full-throttle grind towards profit, you don't see that vision
reflected anywhere. But it's there. The amazing thing is that I
write what I write, and people read it. These books are successful
beyond my wildest dreams. That makes me joyful, not because I want
to be a famous novelist _ on the contrary, I'd rather be anonymous
_ but because it's proof that I'm not alone, that my vision is
shared by other people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Talk a little about how you've coped with your success.
</P>
<P>
   A: The gift I want to give the world, and that I have enough
time to really choose and wrap and know that it's what I mean, is
the (begin itals) book. (end itals) The ``me'' part of the package
_ the Barbara Kingsolver who does interviews and goes on Rosie
O'Donnell _ is so incidental. To be accountable to the world as a
personality is a scary prospect. I'm always afraid I'll say the
wrong thing and there it will be, on national TV forever. I have
this terror that I'm going to undo the good I've done in the world
by saying the wrong thing on the Rosie O'Donnell show. I know it
sounds ungracious. But I've witnessed my society's capacity to
embarrass people beyond belief, to pick apart things people say and
herald them as evidence of character flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But what about the people who love your books?
</P>
<P>
   A: The way I see it is that I'm carrying on this enormous
conversation with people all over the world, and most of the time
I'm completely unaware of it. So when I go out into the world on a
book tour, it reminds me of this conversation and I take pride in
it and I see all of those people who are conversing with me. It
completes the circle in a satisfying way, and it's good to bring
that back home and bear it in mind a little when I write the next
book.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What books have you read lately?
</P>
<P>
   A: The best books I've recently read are no surprise to anybody.
Arundhati Roy's ``The God of Small Things'' just knocked me over.
And Charles Frazier's ``Cold Mountain.'' Wonderful books, by people
who show the real world through their characters. It's great when
the writers you love turn out to be good people, isn't it? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
