<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6836 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      10-20 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WALTZING THE CAT &QL; 
 &UR; Pam Houston (Norton, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to four years of college and I should know better,
but I love it when he calls me baby.'' That's the defining line in
Houston's first book, ``Cowboys Are My Weakness,'' a collection of
stories about smart, daredevil women who are attracted to
less-than-enlightened, daredevil men. ``Cowboys'' was a funny, edgy
book, and the memory of it might confuse you in the early pages of
this new volume of 11 interconnected stories. They are narrated by
Lucy O'Rourke, whose voice and bad experiences with men are
reminiscent of those of the women in ``Cowboys.'' But does this
voice translate from river-running country to the big city, where
33-year-old Lucy has come to reinvent her life? Not really, so some
of the material seems stale and somber by comparison. But just when
you think Houston is stuck on a gimmick, she proceeds to dazzle
you. It happens first in the title story, in which Lucy deals with
her feelings for her parents, barely mentioning the men she has
loved ``who raised dogs and smelled like foreign places.'' Instead,
she portrays the enduring friction between parents and grown
children, that reckoning for past sins that must be tempered by the
knowledge that there is only so much time for forgiveness. The book
includes action stories _ rough rivers and hang-gliding come into
play _ and they are harrowing and fun to read. But Houston's
triumph is that she has come to know the quieter adventures of the
heart. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WHY SINATRA MATTERS &QL; 
 &UR; Pete Hamill (Little, Brown, $18)
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy Cannon, Murray Kempton and William B. Williams are
dead,'' Hamill writes. ``So are Jilly Rizzo and Sugar Ray Robinson
and all those others who once seemed so vividly alive that I could
not imagine them leaving the world. Now Sinatra is dead too, and
it's like a thousand people have just left the room.'' This is no
fawning tribute set to the tune of ``My Way.'' Hamill knows that
the true Sinatra was earlier Sinatra, and that our fascination with
him has a lot to do with his influence over an important era in our
lives. Hamill was friendly with Sinatra for a while, and came close
to writing the singer's autobiography. It didn't happen then, but
does here, in an abbreviated way. The result is an after-hours
book, just as Sinatra's songs were after-hours music, smoky
reflections on a man, his voice and their effect on people. Sinatra
himself would have liked it, and as tributes go, it beats ``My
Way.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AS TIME GOES BY &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Walsh (Warner, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, please. Rick Blaine as a Jewish gangster whose real name is
Yitzik Baline? Everyone loves the classic film ``Casablanca'' _
except Walsh, who has admitted that he didn't think much of the
movie, and the people at Warner Books who asked Walsh to write this
sequel/prequel. The book works backward and forward from the point
at which Ilsa Lund and Victor Laszlo fly off into the fog above
North Africa, leaving Rick on the tarmac. ``Traces of her tears
remained on her cheeks,'' Walsh writes. ``She didn't want to wipe
them away. They were all she had left.'' But wait! Ilsa and Rick
meet again in London, where they behave like bunnies until Ilsa
leaves for Prague to help assassinate an evil Nazi commander. And
there are hints of _ gasp! _ (begin itals) a happy ending. (end
itals) Here's the straight skinny: If it were not tied to the film,
this would be a lame book with a small audience. Instead, Walsh
messes with Rick and Ilsa and stands to make a killing. Buy it if
you will. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PRETTY GOOD FOR A GIRL &QL; 
 &UR; Leslie Heywood (Free Press, $24)
</P>
<P>
   It's overwritten, but this memoir of an Arizona high-school
track athlete is a fascinating story about obsessive
competitiveness that leads to fanatical weight control and
emotional and physical burnout. It's all the more disturbing
because Heywood was so young, yet focused with such steely
intensity on being the best in an athletic community that
patronized girls. Eventually, her body broke down and she was
forced to alter her goals, but she poses valuable questions here
for parents of competitive daughters. ``Can we revise people's
ideas about girls enough,'' she writes, ``so that my ghost will
give up having to prove herself, and the other girls running in her
place won't have to erase whole worlds inside themselves just so
someone will notice them, just so they can stand out and win?''
Heywood has an MFA in poetry from the University of Arizona. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE BODY PROJECT &QL; 
 &UR; Joan Jacobs Brumberg (Vintage, $13)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is Brumberg's disturbing look at how women's
and girls' attitudes toward their bodies have changed over the past
century, and not for the better. Drawing on diary excerpts and
media images from 1830 to the present, she traces our attitudes
toward breast size, hair, clothing and cosmetics, and looks at the
shift from a focus on character in the Victorian years to our
current obsession with appearance. The corset days, it seems, were
not so bad after all. This is both enlightening and entertaining,
even as it points out an unsettling trend in our way of looking at
ourselves. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Correspondent Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
