<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN21-COX     10-20 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Making tracks across Europe
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY RAIL ACROSS SPAIN _ Given the choice, I like being on the way
to somewhere better than being somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Right now I'm on the way to Barcelona, having spent a couple of
nights in Madrid and before that, Paris, setting out to travel
Western Europe by rail on a $500 tourist ticket that will take me
most anywhere I want to go, night or day, for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea was to see a different city every day and do
my sleeping on night trains between destinations.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good idea. The only problem is that it came to me too
late _ some 35 years too late.
</P>
<P>
   At age 57, I'm way too old for such a vigorous schedule.
Constant motion is something akin to constant pain.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that after an overnight train to Madrid I rested for a
couple of days at a hotel frequented by bullfighters in the trendy
Santa Ana district, not far from the bars and cafes where Hemingway
is remembered.
</P>
<P>
   One waiter, whose home is in Pamplona, made famous for its
running of the bulls in Hemingway's ``The Sun Also Rises,'' related
in his limited English that he has a photograph of his grandfather
with the great Ernesto.
</P>
<P>
   Was his grandfather still alive?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied, sadly. Here English words failed him.
``Rat-a-tat-tat!'' he exploded, his pistol finger fanning the air.
</P>
<P>
   There's a story in there somewhere, hunkered down behind the
language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on a day train to Barcelona, I'm seeing the Spanish
countryside for the first time. As it turns out, I've seen it all
before. Probably you have, too
</P>
<P>
   This is spaghetti western country, the stuff that old Clint
Eastwood movies were made of, a geographical paella of Arizona, New
Mexico and West Texas, good, bad and ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. I'm more interested in the movie playing itself out
inside the train coach.
</P>
<P>
   A young couple is seated in the row in front of me. She's fair,
he's dark. She's pretty, he's handsome. She's in love, he's in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Understand I'm just making this up as we go along. But I have to
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   She can't stop smiling a dreamy smile. That's how much in love
she is. I'm not sure she'd be pretty except that she's in love.
</P>
<P>
   He's too quiet, and not nearly so interested in her as he is in
her video camera. (I say it's her camera. It's just a feeling I
have.) He keeps it pointed out the window. If he's taken any shots
of her I haven't noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier when a club car attendant pushed a snack cart through
the coach, she bought a pack of gum. She paid for it herself. He
never offered.
</P>
<P>
   Something else. He has his feet propped up on the seat across
from them. The conductor has warned him once.
</P>
<P>
   For awhile, he took off his sneakers. That seemed to satisfy the
conductor. Sock feet on the seat is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the conductor is gone, the shoes are back on, the feet
are back up.
</P>
<P>
   Something about this fellow I don't like. But maybe it's just
me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm the father of daughters. Fathers of daughters can be overly
harsh in their judgment of darkly handsome young men.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, I have other concerns. In Barcelona, a hotel room will
be all but impossible to come by. There are 1,000 dentists in town,
I'm told, for the world convention of dentists.
</P>
<P>
   Already I'm wishing I were somewhere else, or at least on the
way there.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
