<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GENDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK DOESN'T RELIEVE SENSE OF TESTINESS BETWEEN GENDERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MAIDEN KING &QC; 
The Reunion of Masculine and Feminine &QC; 
By Robert Bly and Marion Woodman &QC; 
Holt, 264 pp., $25 &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Maiden King'' argues that male and female are opposites
that need not be in opposition, let alone mortal combat. As Robert
Bly and Marion Woodman see it, the war between the sexes is an
inner war of psychological maturity each of us needs to work out on
our own.
</P>
<P>
   For a collaborative work on the reunion of masculine and
feminine, the book is strangely compartmentalized. The authors
write separate parts of the book, joining only in a short preface
and the transcript of a telephone conversation at the end. When
they cite each other's work, they use first and last name. This
levels the playing field a bit, offsetting the fact that Bly, the
poet and Moses of the men's movement, is famous, while Woodman, a
Jungian analyst and author, is not. The formality lends the book an
unnatural stiffness, however, and hardly eases the sense of
testiness between male and female in our culture.
</P>
<P>
   Bly, author of the 1990 bestseller ``Iron John'' as well as many
books of poetry, does cast the larger shadow on these pages, which
in some respects form a thoughtful coda to ``Iron John.'' In that
much-maligned work, Bly urged men to reunite with their masculine
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he says that they must do so with their feminine sides as
well. Indeed, the task of integrating masculine and feminine, the
authors write, confronts all men and women, gay or straight. When
Bly and Woodman discuss masculinity and femininity, they are
talking less about gender than about forces in the human psyche.
When a man and woman, or two men, or two women ``are together, four
are present,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the book consists of back-to-back essays unpacking a
Russian folktale, ``The Maiden Tsar,'' in which a young man, Ivan,
is reunited with his inner feminine. A jealous stepmother puts Ivan
to sleep before a magnificent maid to whom he is betrothed; he
quests after the maid and in time succeeds, thanks to help from a
fierce old woman. This is a tale in which the men gather as well as
hunt, and the women hunt as well as gather.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bly's emphasis is on myth and the evils of literalness, as
well as the integration of male and female, Woodman, true to her
training, mines the story for its psychological insight. Her piece
is a call to reclaim our projections outward of the ``shadow''
within. Surprisingly, one highlight of ``The Maiden King'' is a
chapter in which she offers a stunning analysis of the mythic
dimensions of the life and death of Diana, Princess of Wales.
Contrasting the princess and the Maiden Tsar, Woodman hails Diana
as a fully feminine yet androgynous hero who fuses female
empowerment and male independence. The burst of grief at her death
represented a yearning for a queen figure who rejects perfectionism
and female subservience, who integrates masculine and feminine into
a stronger whole. As a man, I simply did not get what the fuss was
about Di. Now I get it.
</P>
<P>
   While sometimes penetrating, Bly's analysis, like his calls for
the summary execution of oppositional thinkers, can be tedious. His
section is a melange, part essay on thinking in mythic rather than
literal terms and part loosey-goosey social tractate, ruminating on
the difference between corn and corporate cultures and offering
nuggets such as ``The fact that judges in England still wear wigs
implies that women once decided matters of law.'' (Compared with
``The Maiden King,'' ``Iron John'' was a work of rigorous
scholarship.) Yet for all his pedantry, Bly has two things going
for him. He is often funny and often right, as when he holds that
contemporary culture infantilizes men and women.
</P>
<P>
   It is noteworthy that Bly defends ``Iron John,'' which he writes
was not meant to ``demonize'' women. It helps to recall the context
of that book: In the beginning, there was the truth, and only men
defined it. Then women said, ``We are not men.'' After a long time,
people accepted this notion, and by the 1980s in America,
contemporary culture had shifted toward the feminine. Then men,
noticing this, said, ``We are not women.'' And everyone seemed to
think that was strange. Drumming in the forest was equated with
misogyny.
</P>
<P>
   Bly writes that he was urging men ``to take a conscious part in
their own growth by respecting the wild part of themselves ...
rather than letting 19th-century masculinity, as defined by bishops
and businessmen, simply happen to them.'' When, as men or as women,
we let our gender consciousness ``simply happen'' to us, Bly and
Woodman write, we fall asleep as the Maiden Tsar approaches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
