<HEADLINE>
SAN DIEGO CAN'T COMPETE WITH THE BRONX ZOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Adds dropped material after 27thgraf: Padres history.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Tony Gwynn, 38 and feeling like a kid, took the No.
4 subway line from Manhattan to the Bronx last week. Finally, after
eight batting titles and nearly 3,000 hits, he was making his first
trip to Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn dropped off his bags in the San Diego Padres clubhouse and
made a beeline for Monument Park in center field. More than 400
feet from home plate, Gwynn walked among the monuments to Babe
Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Mickey Mantle and Miller Huggins. Behind the
monuments is a wall covered with 16 plaques commemorating assorted
other New York Yankees history makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first player you see is Babe Ruth, and that hit me like a
ton of bricks,'' Gwynn said. ``You think, `This is baseball.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Stadium has been the center of the baseball universe for
so many Octobers. The stadium is 75, and it has been in the middle
of 35 World Series. If they win this series, it would be the 24th
time for the Yankees. The only thing in their way is a San Diego
franchise that has won one World Series game in 30 seasons of
existence.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees aren't the only ones involved in this World Series
who are steeped in tradition. The Padres have a history, too, and
it's one well worth stacking up next to the Yankees for
perspective's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Gehrig facing a crippling and fatal
disease, telling packed house that he is ``the luckiest man on the
face of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is former owner Ray Kroc, the McDonald's
magnate, grabbing a microphone during a game and telling the fans,
``Ladies and gentlemen, I have never seen such stupid ballplaying
in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is acquiring Ruth because Boston Red Sox owner
Harry Frazee was desperate for cash to finance a play, ``No, No,
Nanette.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres history is trading Ozzie Smith for Garry Templeton, who
once explained his refusal to attend an All-Star game this way:
``If I ain't startin', I ain't departin.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Ruth calling his shot in the 1932 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is manager Dick Williams trying to decide
whether to call the bullpen or 911 in the 1984 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Robert Merrill belting out the national
anthem in full operatic voice.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is Roseanne grabbing her crotch after singing
the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Mickey Mantle belting 18 home runs in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is no starting pitcher lasting longer than five
innings in the five-game 1984 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is first baseman Don Mattingly becoming
``Donnie Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is first baseman Steve Garvey attempting to
become the father of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Reggie Jackson coming in to be ``the straw
that stirs the drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is Kurt Bevacqua winning a big-league bubblegum
blowing contest.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Roger Maris hitting 61 in '61.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is Nate Colbert hitting cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Reggie going deep three times to win the
final game of the 1977 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Padres history is Bevacqua blowing kisses to the fans after
hitting a three-run homer in the team's only World Series victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is shortstop Phil Rizzuto winning the 1950
American League Most Valuable Player award.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is shortstop Enzo Hernandez driving in 12 runs
in 549 at-bats in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees history is Mel Allen in the announcer's booth saying,
``How about that?'' and Rizzuto exclaiming, ``Holy Cow!''
</P>
<P>
   Padres history is former Yankee infielder Jerry Coleman, in the
announcers booth talking about picther Randy Jones' ``Karl Marx
hairdo'' or informing his audience that ``Rich Folkers is throwing
up in the bull pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Mickey Mantel, Whitey Ford and Billy Martin
at the Copacabana.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is pitchers Eric Show, Dave Dravecky and Mark
Thurman joining the John Birch Society.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Joe DiMaggio roaming center field with
style and grace.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is former team president Chub Feeney spotting
four fans carrying a banner reading ``Scrub Club'' and giving them
the finger. On Fan Appreciation Day.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is third baseman Graig Nettles making diving
stops in the 1978 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is third baseman Chris Brown missing a game
with a bruised tooth root.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is pitcher Goose Gossage snarling at hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is Kroc's widow, Joan, banning beer in the
clubhouse, prompting Goose Gossage to accuse her of ``poisoning the
world with her hamburgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is the classic pinstripe uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Padres history is a mustard-yellow and brown uniform not worthy
of the Hamburgler.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego tradition is a famous zoo that houses elephants and
lions, polar bears and koalas. New York history is The Bronx Zoo
populated by Thurman Munson and Sparky Lyle, Reggie Jackson and
Catfish Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nettles once observed that every little boy dreams of joining
the circus and playing in the big leagues. ``I've done both,''
Nettles said.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is pitcher Ed Whitson getting knocked out in
the first inning of the franchise's only World Series victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is juggling the rotation so that Whitson
pitches road games to spare him of getting booed at home.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is signing Dave Winfield in the prime of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Padres tradition is losing Dave Winfield in the prime of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees tradition is Joe McCarthy and Casey Stengel guiding the
team to World Series after World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Padres history is manager Jack McKeon refusing to walk out the
the mound to make pitching changes because his pants made him look
fat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
