<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND GOP VETERAN TESTS THE LIMITS OF A TREND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Newt Gingrich's charges in the House and Trent
Lott's minions in the Senate aren't the only Republicans running
away from the revolution they attempted to foment after taking over
Congress four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As always, veteran GOP crusader Ellen Sauerbrey is testing the
limits of a political trend, which ultimately reaches absurdity
itself.
</P>
<P>
   And because American election campaigns often resemble farce
more than drama, she might just pull it off and become the first
Republican governor since another champion of expediency, the late
Spiro T. Agnew, pulled the wool over Maryland's eyes 32 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, for example, the veteran legislator with the
worst record on environmental issues seen around these parts in
modern times showed up in Baltimore to oppose a new port facility
to receive imported cars and prepare them for shipment to dealers.
Sauerbrey did so, she said, in the interests of a fragile local
environment.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, she was actually shilling for an existing
facility, but the stunt was revealing.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Sauerbrey was a classic exemplar of in-your-face
conservatism in 1994, when her first campaign for governor came
just a few thousand votes (disputed by her for nearly two months)
of defeating Democrat Parris Glendening. And she was just as
in-your-face as a leader of the minority Republicans in the state
Legislature for the previous decade.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a movement conservative, she gave higher priority to
private property ``rights'' and business development in years of
confrontations with environmentalists. She opposed the state's
basic clean water law and its basic clean air law. She opposed
nearly every measure to protect the majestic Chesapeake Bay that
came her way as a legislator. And she has become the darling of
real estate developers and chicken processors for her stands
against wetlands protection and other enivironmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, her financial disclosure records show a large stock
portfolio worth nearly $2 million; nearly $400,000 of it is in
energy companies, whose liability from oil spills in the bay she
has voted to limit.
</P>
<P>
   The Ellen Sauerbrey of 1998, however, is symbolized by her
resignation a few weeks ago from the six-member board of Frontiers
of Freedom. Run by Malcolm Wallop, the former Republican senator
from Wyoming, this energy industry front is a key player in
movements to put property interests ahead of public health and to
get rid of pesky restrictions like the Endangered Species Act and
limits on drilling and mining in the vast Alaska wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the campaign to re-elect Glendening homed in
on the environment like a laser last month in a late start at
preventing Sauerbrey's strong effort to unseat him from getting
traction. And the protection of Chesapeake Bay became its symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bay is the state's symbolic soul,'' the popular lieutenant
governor, Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, told me as she staked out a
traffic island in rush hour here last week, in between dashes into
traffic to put bumper stickers on the cars of willing commuters.
``It is fishing and tourism and recreation, but it is above all
what makes Maryland special.''
</P>
<P>
   The bay also symbolizes what was probably Glendening's finest
hour in an otherwise ho-hum term when an outbreak of the dangerous
microbe pfiesteria in waterways from Maryland to the Carolinas
threatened fish and public health.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his counterparts to the South, Glendening pounced,
closing waterways to business discharges of waste. The crisis
resulted in virtually no damage to the state, in contrast to huge
fish kills and outbreaks of illness elsewhere. Through it all,
Sauerbrey criticized Glendening's moves, especially on behalf of
her poultry business supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, or so she says now.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the environment the only area where she campaigns as if
she had no past. In fact, very much like the congressional
Republicans, Sauerbrey has been tossing key elements of the
movement conservatives' revolutionary dogma _ antiabortion
positions, public school voucher advocacy, and opposition to gun
control of any kind _ overboard like so much ballast.
</P>
<P>
   The only exception to this self-abandonment has been on tax
cuts, though even here her position for another round has been
undercut by the absence of specific proposals for compensating
budget cuts, making her vulnerable to fears that higher property
taxes would be the eventual result of her program.
</P>
<P>
   What will keep Sauerbrey in position to win down the stretch,
however, is a factor that always matters _ an unpopular incumbent.
A remote figure, famous for ever-changing positions, Glendening has
only exacerbated the normal problems a New Democrat has in getting
strong party support.
</P>
<P>
   And Glendening has made his problems worse by first shunning and
then embracing President Clinton as the House was deciding to begin
its impeachment inquiry. The Republican right hates him anyway; the
damage from this Glendening flip-flop was from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   If Sauerbrey were running again as her 1994 incarnation _ her
evidence-lacking challenge of the '94 vote was even supported by
National Rifle Association money _ she wouldn't have a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   By running away from her record and beliefs, she remains in the
hunt, but the Sauerbrey campaign is an apt metaphor for what has
happened to the revolution. Winning is the new ideology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
