<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-RECONCILIATION-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANK TALK ABOUT RACISM SPURS RECONCILIATION IN TEXAS TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Four months ago, civic leaders here bristled
when their East Texas town of 8,000 was labeled the ``town that
shamed America'' after the dragging death of a black man named
James Byrd Jr. Officials proudly noted the swift arrest of three
white suspects in the Byrd case, and then reeled off benchmarks of
racial progress in Jasper _ a black mayor, two black school
principals, a black chamber of commerce president, and a black
administrator of the town's largest hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Great strides, they said, for a southern town 45 percent
African-American and 55 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, the town has gained a new perspective on
itself, this time from its own residents.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of 20 introspective town hall meetings, Jasper has
opened up to discuss what was never publicly discussed before _
racism. Blacks speaking at the neighborhood gatherings, sponsored
by the Mayor's Task Force 2000 committee, made it uncomfortably
clear that they see two Jaspers, separate and unequal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an eye-opener,'' said Nancy Nicholson, a white
councilwoman and a task force leader. ``I did not know the depth of
their sorrow and pain.''
</P>
<P>
   After Nicholson expressed how the revelations astonished her,
black minister John Hardin told her, ``I just wish you could live
in my shoes for one week and see what we go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's brutal killing, it seems clear, has spurred
reconciliation efforts such as the task force, as well as attempts
by individuals to repair past wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Williams, a former school administrator and football
coach, said at a task force meeting that a white auto mechanic
recently apologized for having sold him a used muffler as a new one
years earlier, said the Rev. Michael Foshage, a Catholic priest.
The apology was accepted, but a refund was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   At another meeting, a white mother told how she casually
described a black man with a derogatory term, then confronted her
own racism when her teen-age daughter dressed her down, saying that
the man had caused no offense, Foshage recalled.
</P>
<P>
   A 17-year-old boy, known to use the N-word and disparage blacks,
was so moved by a Byrd memorial service that he tracked down his
church's youth director, Michael Hallam, to tell him, ``I no longer
have a drop of racism in my body.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Thursday night, 180 Jasper residents of all races
assembled on the courthouse lawn in a moving ``unity'' prayer
vigil, joined hands and sang hymns and the civil rights anthem ``We
Shall Overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How long would it have taken in the natural course of
progression to get a group like this together without this tragedy?
Maybe never,'' said Mike Ratcliff, a white attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Black City Council member Clyde Williams Jr., the task force
chairman who was a classmate of Byrd's, said that whites, until
recently, had been blithely unaware of the thinking within Jasper's
black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racial tensions are like graph lines on a heart monitor,'' he
said. ``Whites only notice when it goes off the chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be realistic. If Jasper had not had this incident, we
would not be having this task force.''
</P>
<P>
   At a town hall meeting on the street where Byrd was slain, a
number of African-Americans maintained that they have been treated
differently by law enforcement officers and county officials. They
cited difficulty getting loans, jobs and equal treatment in stores
and car lots.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in questionnaires if racial discrimination was
``widespread'' or ``isolated,'' many of the blacks underlined
``widespread,'' penciling in that they had been subjected to verbal
insults or made to feel unwelcome in stores with ``unfriendly
facial expressions.''
</P>
<P>
   Few whites marked ``widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret people feel that way,'' Police Chief Harlan
Alexander said of remarks critical of law enforcement personnel.
But he said efforts are being made to show that such views are no
longer valid.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the sheriff and I have told our staffs to take a few
minutes to talk to people to dispel these ideas. `Stop when you see
someone mowing and ask what can we do for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such a suggestion, as well as proposed diversity training for
police officers and city workers, might help make clear that the
city no longer condones treating minorities as second-class
citizens. Convincing the black community that its long-held beliefs
might be outdated might require a communitywide effort, however.
</P>
<P>
   When a black woman complained that there were no blacks in the
county courthouse, a white assistant district clerk invited her to
stop by, Nicholson said. The black woman showed up one day and was
introduced to the two black probation officers and other black
courthouse employees.
</P>
<P>
   Both black and white community leaders have spotted remarkable
changes in this Piney Woods community since June.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first month after the murder, I thought it was a put-on
for the media,'' the Byrd family's pastor, the Rev. Kenneth Lyons,
said of the outpouring of concern and wholesale disavowal of
prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here we are in October, and relations between blacks and
whites are continuing to improve,'' Lyons said. ``People are trying
to bring about sincere harmony in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force and its neighborhood meetings, Lyons said,
``might serve as an example for other communities in East Texas.
It's a sincere effort in Jasper, one that I've never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes that Lyons has witnessed range from a heightened
level of common courtesy between the races _ holding a door at the
post office and stopping for a friendly chat _ to the appointment
of the first black drum major in the high school marching band and
a decision by the city to tear down the highly emblematic fence
dividing white graves from black in the Jasper cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Texas towns, Jasper had a segregationist past that
pervaded nearly all social contacts.
</P>
<P>
   It has come a long way from the days when the old Texas Theater
had a separate ``colored'' section, when it was disrespectful for a
black to make eye contact in the street with a white. As late as
the early 1970s, a bear of a white police chief named Alton Wright
would grab a black man for sporting a goatee, warning him not to
show his face in town until it was clean shaven. Most blacks knew
to cross the street when he approached, or to request a grocery
sack _ even for a single bar of soap _ to avoid arrest for theft by
Wright, both blacks and whites recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The senior prom was not held for a decade after the high school
was integrated in 1967, said Herman Wright, a black who won
community-wide respect while serving as school board president for
17 years. The traditional baccalaureate service in church before
graduation quietly resumed two years ago after being halted for
nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Among suggestions made at the town meetings are providing
sensitivity training for teachers and local government employees,
including police and sheriff's deputies; efforts to ensure fair
employment; better communications between the races; and a public
swimming pool open to all.
</P>
<P>
   But what has already been achieved is a new willingness to
discuss once-touchy racial issues, said Williams, Nicholson and
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you have talked like this to me if we didn't have the
task force?'' Nicholson recalled asking a black member of the
panel, Delfine Summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No'' was the frank reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear everyone's stories,'' Nicholson said of the
generations of personal hurts that have been aired at the town hall
gatherings. ``How can we deal with it unless we hear? Just the
telling can be powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
