<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSPECTIVE OF THE YOUNG REPRESENTED AS FRIDGE ART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't you just love kids? There's never a dull moment in
parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest son was around 5 years old when he presented me with
his latest artistic masterpiece one afternoon. He'd been coloring
for hours at the kitchen table. I took the sheet of construction
paper, smiled and held it at arm's length while I tried to figure
out what the heck he had drawn. It looked like a spoon standing on
a rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sweetie!'' I exclaimed. ``This is so pretty. I love the
brilliant colors, the orange and brown and green. Wow! It's so
vivid. The bold strokes give it such depth. This is clearly some of
your finest work. I'm going to put it on the refrigerator so
everyone can see it, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for grandma,'' he said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great. She'll love it. We'll mail it to her tomorrow. She'll
probably put it on her refrigerator.''
</P>
<P>
   I was about out of room on my refrigerator anyway. There were so
many masterpieces there already that I could barely find the door
handle.
</P>
<P>
   Then my son asked, ``Doesn't grandma have one of those?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmmm, I don't think so. She'll be so excited.''
</P>
<P>
   He frowned and responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all of my friends have one. Why doesn't grandma have one?
I thought she had one, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh dear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, son, Grandma doesn't have one like this one is what I
mean. Hers is a different color. She has one like ours. And what
color is ours anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   He looked at me like I was the stupidest mother he had ever had,
and then he started laughing. This was my first child, and I was
unaccustomed to being laughed at by my offspring. Now, of course,
I'm very accustomed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy, do you know what it is?'' he asked suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, sure I do. It's ... a flower? A flower in a garden,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a dragon eating a carrot?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, he was rolling on the floor, doubled over in merriment.
I had to laugh along with him. A child's giggle spreads faster than
chicken pox at a day care.
</P>
<P>
   Then my husband came into the kitchen and said, ``What are you
guys so tickled about?''
</P>
<P>
   I gave him the picture and he said, ``That looks like a spoon on
a rock.''
</P>
<P>
   My son said, ``Right, daddy! See, Mommy, Daddy knew what it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if my mother really had a spoon on a rock. It must be
one of her gardening tools.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I kept that picture for years until it was accidentally
destroyed during our move to Texas. I used it to remind me that
children have a unique way of viewing the world. Innocence paints a
pretty picture of the world even when it is just a spoon on a rock.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
