<HEADLINE>
OUT ON A LIMB OVER THE NAME OF A TOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the term ``monkey wrench''?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.M.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: That question inspired the title of Vince Staten's 1996 book
``Did Monkeys Invent the Monkey Wrench?'' _ a book of hardware
lore.
</P>
<P>
   The term appears to come from Solymon Merrick, a machinist who
patented the wrench in 1835.
</P>
<P>
   Staten told Gannett News Service in 1996 that the earliest use
of ``monkey wrench'' he found dates to 1840 in Springfield, Mass.,
when Merrick devised a movable-arm wrench.
</P>
<P>
   This new wrench was manufactured for Merrick by a workman named
``Monkey'' White. ``Soon, other workers were calling the tool
`Monkey's wrench,''' Gannett reported.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a beautiful French Provincial baby grand piano made by
Ivers &AMP; Pond of Boston. I have never heard of this brand. Can you
find out more about this piano and how old it might be?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.B., Euless, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Ivers &AMP; Pond, founded in 1880, was one of Boston's better
piano makers for decades, according to Renato Pereira, a clerk with
the piano restoration company Premier Piano. President Kennedy
owned one in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   To determine the age of your piano, look for its serial number.
Ivers &AMP; Pond issued these numbers sequentially _ those below 77500
are for pianos built before 1930.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worth of a piano depends on the name _ Ivers &AMP; Pond is a
good one _ and the playability,'' Pereira said. ``It might be worth
$200 or might be worth $4,000. The only way to find out is to have
a piano technician look at it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other piano makers, Ivers &AMP; Pond was out of business
by the 1960s, but the brand name was bought by another pianomaker.
The last Ivers &AMP; Pond piano was produced in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call Premier Piano at (800) 742-6639
((800) PIANO-39) or visit the Web site www.premierpiano.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to the actor Hugh Grant?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.S.G., Fiskdale, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Grant in care of Creative Artists Agency, 9830
Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who turned 38 on Sept. 9, will portray a compulsive
womanizer in the upcoming Columbia Pictures film ``American
Neurotic.'' Other current credits include ``Mickey Blue-Eyes'' with
James Caan and Jeanne Tripplehorn, and ``Notting Hill'' with Julia
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
