<HEADLINE>
DREADLOCKS WEARERS FEEL FREE AT LAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  with art slugged dreadlocks 
 
By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He shall be holy and shall let the locks of the hair of his
head grow.'' _ Numbers 6:5.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A young woman solemnly stood up in front of the audience that
gathered in a building near downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Courtney Wilson, and I'm a perm addict,'' said the
20-year-old Prairie View A&AMP;M nursing student.
</P>
<P>
   The room dissolved in laughter and nods of agreement. After a
lifetime of having their hair permed, pulled, fried, frizzed and
fashioned in unnatural ways, those who gathered for the National
Dreadlock Summit were thankful to say they were free at last.
</P>
<P>
   Free from chemicals that burned their scalp and neck.
</P>
<P>
   Free from hot combs and brushes that pinched their thick hair.
</P>
<P>
   Free from tight, heavy bathing caps they had to wear while
swimming because the relaxer on their hair didn't mix with water.
</P>
<P>
   Free from fashion magazines that dictate that bouncy, bubbly
hair is the only American ideal of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Free to get back to their roots and be themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``God did not give me a permanent when I came into this world,''
Wilson explained. ``I just love my natural hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallelujah, come on, get nappy!
</P>
<P>
   That was the message of the gathering of about 50 women of color
and a smattering of men at a seminar about the beauty of
dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   Organizer Darlene Hosea planned the summit and an accompanying
youth arts festival to encourage creativity and individuality and
to discuss how to redefine what beauty means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embracing our natural beauty begins with the hair on our
heads,'' Hosea said. ``Straightening our hair to emulate our white
sisters' standard of beauty just doesn't work for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people link dreadlocks solely with the Rastafarians of
Jamaica. But speakers at the Dreadlock Summit explained that
ancient Egyptians and such East African tribes as the Masai long
wore their hair in such a way.
</P>
<P>
   Dreadlocks result when the hair is so tangled that it naturally
assumes the shape of a rope. For many African-Americans and other
people of color, the hair naturally takes the form when washed and
dried without a comb or brush.
</P>
<P>
   After several months, the strands of hair become permanently
``locked'' and can only be removed by cutting them.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Bartolomey, a Houston child-care provider who has worn
locks for three years, said it took about seven months for her hair
to become locked. Maintenance is easy, she said, because all she
has to do is wash and condition her locks, which are about 4 inches
to 6 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to make a political statement. I just think
locks are beautiful,'' she said. ``You don't have to have a perm to
be beautiful. Natural hair is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Other women have discovered a feeling of empowerment from
wearing their hair in a natural way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so happy my hair is nappy,'' said Barbara Smith, a
Philadelphia-area television talk-show host who has spoken at
similar seminars around the country. ``I wish I could have said
that at an early age.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Smith discovered she had breast cancer. She
underwent surgery to remove the cancerous tumor and several rounds
of chemotherapy, in which her shoulder-length hair fell out,
leaving her bald.
</P>
<P>
   When the tiny strands of hair began to reappear, Smith decided
it was time to ``lock it on down'' because she didn't want to put
up with relaxers or other chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we need to be doing is to put anything into our
bodies that will make it difficult for us to survive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She rejoiced as her hair slowly grew back. Each strand was
precious because it symbolized the great gift of life that had been
given back to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so amazed watching it come in that I didn't want to do
anything with it. I was afraid if I combed it, it would fall out,''
she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   As her hair grew longer, she gently twisted the curls until they
locked. Now she wears her locks in a chic style of varying lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Locking gave me energy,'' Smith said. ``The longer the locks
went, the better my sleep (became), and my appetite increased. My
visions and dreams became so powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cemora Slatten, who has worn her hair in locks for about a year,
said she, too, feels a great sense of energy and well-being from
her hairstyle.
</P>
<P>
   She said co-workers at Johnson Space Center, where she works as
a word processor for a NASA subcontractor, have noticed the
difference since she clipped off her braids and changed her style
to dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened up a dialogue,'' said Slatten. ``I think people feel
better about me because there's an energy. They sense something
special.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, people sometimes want to touch her
dreadlocks, but she doesn't allow that because it dissipates the
energy.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, however, Slatten was not sure she wanted to
wear her hair in dreadlocks because she worried that co-workers
would not consider it a professional look.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there have been no repercussions at her office,
Slatten thinks she might not have been hired if she had applied for
a job with her current hairstyle because it seems threatening to
some people.
</P>
<P>
   Other participants agreed that they are often judged negatively
because of their hairstyle. One woman with well-kept dreadlocks
said that every time she goes through customs after returning to
the United States from a foreign country, she is taken aside and
often strip-searched for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyha Shabazz, a Houston teacher and owner of an import store,
said he was stopped by Houston police two months ago and quizzed
because of his hairstyle.
</P>
<P>
   He said officers asked, ``What are you, some kind of
revolutionary?'' and took him to jail because he didn't have his
driver's license with him. Once in jail, he said officials cut
shells out of his dreadlocks and made disparaging remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so humiliating,'' Shabazz said. ``After all, it's just
hair.''
</P>
<P>
   A judge threw out the charge, but now Shabazz hides his hair in
a cap when he's driving to avoid drawing attention.
</P>
<P>
   A number of participants said some of the most heated criticism
comes from members of the African-American community, particularly
from parents and family members who worry that locks connote a
political statement and will hinder job prospects.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who hails from Nigeria said that whenever she returns to
her home country, her parents constantly badger her to cut her
locks and tease her that they will snip them while she is sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   She was consoled by Mbali Umoja, a poet and lecturer who has
worn dreadlocks for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Umoja, who has thick dreadlocks that flow past her shoulders,
said her parents went ``buck nuts'' for the first seven years over
her hairstyle. But gradually they came around when they saw her
qualities of strength, beauty and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that standing firm makes a difference,'' Umoja said.
``Your strength and beauty and determination will bring them
around. You've got to take them along, sister, because you can't
leave them behind.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
