<SLUG> BC-FAINT-DANCE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARIA THE STORM CLOUD' OFFERS UNPREDICTABLE SYMBOLISM _ BUT WHAT
DOES IT MEAN? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (HOUSTON) It's different, offbeat, a trifle goofy _ well, what
would you expect of a piece titled ``Maria the Storm Cloud,''
performed by a dance group called 33 Fainting Spells?
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based troupe usually consists of
dancer/choreographers Dayna Hanson and Gaelen Hanson. For their new
work, which premiered with weekend performances at DiverseWorks in
Houston and will play again Friday and Saturday, the team expands
to include Peggy Piacenza as the third performer and co-creator.
</P>
<P>
   The deadpan, unpredictable tone is set in a brief opening image.
The three women pose downstage wearing cutout cardboard clouds,
their bare shoulders and legs suggesting there's nothing else
behind the clouds _ recalling that old image of someone wearing
only a barrel. Each also wears a ``Hello'' name tag where the lapel
would be, if cutout cardboard clouds had lapels. Shyly, yet
winsomely, two of the women point to the ``Hello'' as if greeting
the audience. The third _ who plays odd-girl-out at several points
in the evening _ seems ill at ease and won't point to ``Hello.''
Blackout.
</P>
<P>
   I still don't know if I get it or not. Welcome to postmodernism.
</P>
<P>
   The evening progresses to dance sequences that often have the
women resourcefully exploiting three swivel stools _ posing on
them, spinning on them, lying back on them. Sometimes they lean
against the stools in three sharp diagonals, each propped against
the stool by one arm. A frequent device is to have two figures
moving in unison, with a third in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   A striking sequence makes use of restricted movement _ the three
women on their stools, facing away from the audience, moving in
contorted postures as their wrists test the limits of fabric
wrapped around them (which turns out to be the tops the woman will
pull over their bare backs before turning around).
</P>
<P>
   The trio renders the piece's muscular and eclectic choreography
with precision and drive.
</P>
<P>
   An early scene, set to chintzy lounge music, finds them playing
with martini glasses like kids acting out their elders' high jinks.
One steals an olive from the glass of another when the latter is
not looking. This I interpreted as a symbol of untrustworthiness
and competitiveness in contemporary relationships.
</P>
<P>
   One scene finds the three standing before microphones,
struggling to speak but too bashful to do so. An expression of
dancers' awkwardness in switching to language? A later dialogue
scene has two of the dancers giving the third a makeover: decking
her out in a platinum-blond wig, giving her a guitar to play and
telling her how she should feel. Perhaps a parody of daytime TV
talk-show blather?
</P>
<P>
   I found some of the visual and verbal non sequiturs moderately
interesting and mildly amusing but cannot say the work ever engaged
me fully. A lot of it exhibits the sort of deadpan hip that makes
you wonder if you're missing something or whether the whole thing
is just one long exercise in pulling the audience's leg.
</P>
<P>
   Yet performing-arts fans seeking something intimate and
idiosyncratic may wish to check out ``Maria the Storm Cloud.'' If
you don't like the dancing, you can always spend the evening trying
to figure out the significance of the meteorological title. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
