<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIRLEY MANSON PUTS GARBAGE IN THE GROOVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Shirley Manson tried, she really did, to play the part
of sophisticated pop diva during Saturday night's sold-out Garbage
show at the Aerial Theater at Bayou Place.
</P>
<P>
   But after ripping through a few songs from the band's
dance-driven rock catalog, the fiery redhead announced she'd had
enough. With that, Manson pulled her hair (which she claimed had
been bothering her all night) back into a ponytail and traded her
heeled boots in for a pair of Nike tennis shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The action perfectly illustrated Manson's appeal. She coyly
flirted with the crowd one minute, asking what they thought of her
dress or telling one love struck male near the stage that he had
``a fabulous smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, she was jamming with the guys on her guitar or
commanding a slew of enthusiastic fans to ``Shut it, then!'' while
she told a story.
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, Manson is equally unpredictable. She's seductive and
yearning on ``You Look So Fine,'' strikingly self-assured on ``I'm
Only Happy When It Rains,'' and in kitten-with-her-claws-out mode
on ``Push It,'' the band's recent single that samples from the
Beach Boys and Salt 'n Pepa
</P>
<P>
   From the opening beats of ``Temptation Waits,'' Garbage rode an
electric groove that enveloped everything within striking distance
during its 105-minute set. Manson, her band, the music and the
crowd-surfing fans who lusted after their sweet-and-sour rock vixen
all swayed to the sinfully stylish sound.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a lot of variation in Garbage's sound, just a
constant battle between heavy guitar riffs and glitter-ball
grooves. It was most apparent on songs from the band's second
album, ``Version 2.0,'' which pulses with an aggressive
infectiousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Think I'm Paranoid'' was a seductive blend of distorted
vocals and seductive lyrics; ``Special,'' the group's new single,
was anchored by Manson's girl-group vocal stylings; and ``Push It''
benefited from searing guitar work and a hyped-up chorus.
</P>
<P>
   The musical evolution displayed in songs from ``2.0'' did
nothing to dampen the effect of songs from Garbage's debut album.
``Queer'' simmered with a sly sense of energy, and Manson bopped
around the stage to the chugging beats of ``Stupid Girl,'' one of
the band's best singles.
</P>
<P>
   Garbage briefly gave up the groove for a folksy flavor near the
end of the set on ``Supernatural,'' a mournful ballad from Vic
Chesnutt. Manson urged fans to show their appreciation during the
song, which was being recorded for release in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't go overboard,'' Manson joked when the crowd threatened
to drown out her delicate vocals. ``We're not that desperate.''
Judging by the fervent reaction Garbage received throughout the
evening, Manson and her crew probably won't have to worry about
that for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Girls Against Boys opened the show with thunderous rock beats
and an animated stage presence. Lead singer Scott McCloud was
appropriately emotive on songs from the group's major-label debut
album, ``Freak On Ica.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyboardist/bassist Eli Janney nearly stole the show, jumping
around the stage and banging on his instruments like a caffeinated
jackrabbit. His enthusiasm was a welcome change from the somber
stylings that mark so many painfully cool rock acts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
