A6932 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-20 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH LAWYERS', LITIGANTS' MONEY BANE TO COURT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ State District Judge Mike Westergren, a Democrat from
Corpus Christi running for the Texas Supreme Court, is definitely
swimming against the tide _ if not trying to climb a waterfall _ in
this election season.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough enough that the underfunded Westergren is trying to
unseat a Republican incumbent, Craig Enoch, in what is shaping up
as a watershed GOP year. But Westergren also has kind things to
say, sort of, about lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that Westergren is campaigning at a time when many
people seeking public office believe that they can attract almost
as many votes bashing lawyers as they can saying bad things about
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers have always _ as long as I can remember, anyway _
received more than their share of suspicion, sometimes even more
than news reporters and columnists.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' lawyers compounded the problem by spending millions
of dollars on judicial races in the 1980s. They succeeded in
electing a Texas Supreme Court that departed from Texas'
conservative tradition and rewarded them with decisions upholding
huge damage awards for their clients _ and large paydays for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their tactics produced a backlash from doctors, insurance
companies and the business community _ the defendants who had to
pay the large damages _ and Texas soon had a defense-oriented
Supreme Court again.
</P>
<P>
   The business interests and their defense lawyers fought fire
with fire, making large donations of their own to defense-oriented,
mostly Republican judicial candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The ``reformers'' _ including some litigants and potential
litigants before the court _ insisted that they were rescuing the
Texas judiciary from the excesses of ``evil'' plaintiffs' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the word, ``plaintiff,'' got dropped in all the
rhetoric, but business contributors to Supreme Court candidates
definitely knew the difference between being a plaintiff and a
defendant, or being a plaintiffs' lawyer or a defense law
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer-bashing that became prevalent during the Supreme
Court's makeover _ and in legislative debates over civil justice
reform _ may have produced a curious result. It may have made it
more politically acceptable in today's conservative climate for a
potential party to a lawsuit _ someone with the most to gain from a
court's decision _ to make a large political donation to a judge
than for a lawyer to do so.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make sense to Westergren, and he is trying to
challenge that notion in his longshot race for the high court.
Since he is not the favored candidate of the big contributors to
judicial races, though, he hasn't been able to raise enough money
to get his message across to many voters.
</P>
<P>
   Westergren, who has been a trial judge for 15 years, accepts
campaign money from lawyers, but he said he refuses donations from
litigants, the people appearing in his court whom lawyers
represent. A contribution to a judge from a litigant, Westergren
believes, is a ``far more pernicious thing'' than a donation from a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   A litigant, he explained, has a direct interest in the outcome
of a case _ perhaps a multimillion-dollar interest _ while a lawyer
is a professional who, win or lose, will likely represent clients
before the court in a number of other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Enoch, the Republican justice whom Westergren is challenging,
said his Democratic opponent has a point.
</P>
<P>
   He called Westergren's comments ``fairly accurate'' and said he
also felt more comfortable, as a judge, raising money from lawyers
than from the parties they represent in court.
</P>
<P>
   But Enoch said he tries to raise no more than about half of his
campaign money from attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the remainder _ and Enoch is swamping Westergren in
fund-raising _ comes from business-oriented groups.
</P>
<P>
   Enoch believes the public is more concerned about judges
accepting contributions from lawyers than from businesspeople and
other litigants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with the public's perception of the court,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it's a perception that ``reform''-minded candidates, such
as Enoch, helped to perpetuate with their bashing of plaintiffs'
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the entire system of electing judges in partisan
elections and allowing them to accept large campaign contributions
from both lawyers and litigants is ``pernicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Enoch and most, if not all, of his colleagues on the present
high court favor changing the system. But they continue to play by
it, racking up thousands of dollars in special interest donations,
because the Legislature _ aside from setting generous donation
limits _ has refused to change it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone is going to have to say, `No,' somewhere,'' laments
Walt Borges, a consumer advocate who monitors the court.
</P>
<P>
   That's a worthy thought, but it would mean unilateral
disarmament, a concept considered more pernicious by most judges
and would-be judges than the system itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
