   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Cedar Rapids, Iowa) _ The vice president
campaigns in seven cities at start of three-day trip to four
states, concentrating on competitive races. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   VAIL-FIRES (Vail, Colo.) _ As Vail, the nation's most popular
ski resort, seeks to expand, it finds itself embroiled in battles
on several fronts. Environmentalists want to stop expansion of ski
trails in the back country and wealthy land owners are fighting a
plan to build lower income housing for people who work in Vail. At
the same time, an arsonist has set eight fires in mountaintop
restaurants. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-POLICE-SHOOTING (Houston) _ Civil rights groups call for
federal civil rights investigation after a grand jury indicts a
police officer for the misdemeanor of criminal trespass after he
and other officers burst into a Mexican immigrant's house and shot
him 20 times, 12 times in the back. Police claimed that they had
evidence that he was involved in drug trade, but it was a mistake.
By Rich Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GAY-RALLY (New York) _ Folo on the gay rally in Midtown
Manhattan that resulted in a confrontation with police and the
overnight arrest of 130 protesters.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BLOOD (New York) _ The New York Blood Center says there may
have been problems in blood testing from January 1991 to December
1996, and is asking anyone who received a transfusion at a New York
or New Jersey hospital to be tested for HIV and hepatitis. By
Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit surged in
August to a record high as the global financial crisis depressed
exports for a fifth straight month. The trade gap widened by a
hefty $2.2 billion, to $16.77 billion, the Commerce Department
said, leading some economists to make a downward revision in their
forecasts for economic growth for the rest of the year. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The second day of the Justice
Department's antitrust case against Microsoft. By Steve Lohr and
Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Microsoft reports earnings.
By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:55 p.m., the industrial average was up
168, the Nasdaq index was up 38. Elsewhere, prices were off 1.8
percent in Tokyo and down 0.4 percent in Hong Kong. They rose 3.7
percent in Frankfurt, 2.9 percent in London, 3 percent in Brazil
and 1.5 percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long
bond was down 44/32 at midday, with the yield at 5.05 percent. By
