<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6936 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS-BOS &LR;      10-20 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATIVE JOURNALIST BECOMES PART OF THE STORY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should a reporter continue to cover a story when he or she is
drawn into that story as a participant, rather than an observer?
</P>
<P>
   Boston defense attorney Cheryl M. Cronin answers with an
emphatic no. She maintains that WBZ-Ch. 4 reporter Joe Bergantino
ignored a conflict of interest in reporting the outcome of a state
hearing at which he was forced to testify _ with a sometimes-testy
cross-examination by Cronin _ and in which a previous Bergantino
story was the sole piece of evidence introduced.
</P>
<P>
   But Channel 4 news director Peter Brown fired back yesterday at
Cronin, asserting that the attorney's criticism is simply ``an
attempt to get Joe off the story ... push him out of bounds'' to
spare her client, state Representative Emmanuel Serra, from further
probing by Bergantino.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is the latest chapter in an investigative story that
has featured some memorable moments, including footage of
Bergantino chasing Serra through a parking garage and down a State
House sidewalk, calling after him: ``Why are you running away, sir?
Gus, why are you lying about where you live?''
</P>
<P>
   In that story July 13, Bergantino reported that Channel 4's
investigative unit had discovered that Serra, while purporting to
live in a house in East Boston, was actually living in an apartment
in the North End, outside the district Serra represents, in
violation of state law.
</P>
<P>
   But the current sparks are flying over Bergantino's follow-up
story on Sept. 28, which reported the findings of a state Ballot
Law Commission hearing on the matter, at which Bergantino
testified. In Cronin's view, it was an ``extremely unfair'' story
that raised questions about ``the appropriateness of a member of
the news media purporting to cover a story as if they were an
objective observer, when in fact they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bergantino contended Monday that his reporting was not
colored by the fact that he testified on a minor point, essentially
authenticating a tape of his reporting. ``I don't believe my
answering a couple of questions tainted my objectivity or
influenced the way I reported the story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, several media ethicists contacted by the Globe
said Channel 4 should have assigned a different reporter to do the
follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   Bergantino's original report caught the notice of James R.
Loring, Serra's Republican opponent. Loring filed a challenge to
Serra's candidacy with the Ballot Law Commission, arguing that
Serra ``lacks the legal qualification for the office he seeks''
because he allegedly lived outside the district. Bergantino was at
the commission's Sept. 28 hearing with a Channel 4 cameraman,
intent on a follow-up story.
</P>
<P>
   Bergantino told the Globe Monday that he did not know he would
be called on to play another role, that of witness, though he said
that before the hearing, he did talk to an attorney for CBS,
Channel 4's owner. ``Being under instructions not to testify, I
didn't think it would be an issue'' to cover the follow-up story,
said Bergantino. ``If the lawyer had said, `Yeah, you're going to
have to testify,' I would have gone to Peter Brown and said,
`Peter, I think you should have someone else cover this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once the hearing began, Bergantino was called as a witness
anyway. He told the panel he was willing to authenticate the
videotape of the July 13 story for the commission, but balked at
testifying beyond that. At that point, commission chairman Robert
Hallisey threatened Bergantino with contempt and a stiff fine.
</P>
<P>
   During a recess, Bergantino called Brown, the news director, and
an attorney. It was decided that Bergantino would authenticate the
tape for the commission but go no further, and not answer questions
about the news-gathering process. Brown acknowledged Monday that at
that point, he weighed whether Bergantino should continue to cover
the story: ``Did that go through my mind? Sure it did. But I
decided it was not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It was to Cronin. Though Bergantino stuck to his guns and
largely confined his testimony to saying that the tape in evidence
was indeed the story he reported, he and Cronin sparred during the
cross-examination over whether any other elected official besides
Serra had ever refused to answer his questions. They also had a
contentious exchange over how many times the I-Team's camera had
been set up outside the North End apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the cross-examination ended, the commission
rejected Loring's challenge to Serra.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cronin, Bergantino then ``scurries over to me with
a microphone in his hand, and a camera facing me, and asks me to
describe my reaction to the commission's decision. It occurred to
me at this moment that he actually intended to continue to cover
this story as if he could offer the viewers an objective
perspective, despite the fact he had just been a witness in the
case and subject to cross-examination.'' She said that ``it was
clear from the report that aired that night that Mr. Bergantino was
very unhappy with the commission's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergantino, however, says ``the same objectivity that guided us
in the first story guided us in the second story,'' and that the
core of the story was the commission's decision, not the fact that
he was called to testify. Brown agrees, saying it was ``a fair and
balanced piece.''
</P>
<P>
   The report Bergantino aired that night described the decision by
the commission, with a sound bite from Cronin, brief remarks from
Hallisey and Loring, and a replay of the Serra-chase footage. At
the end, Bergantino raised the question of why the state Republican
Party did not send an attorney to represent Loring, and suggested
that one reason could have been the fact that Serra supported
Republican acting governor Paul Cellucci, adding, ``By the way,
there are reports that in return, Serra will get a high-paying job
at Massport.'' Bergantino said Monday that the speculation about
Serra's job prospects was ``based on several sources.'' Serra could
not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the Sept. 28 report, Channel 4 anchor Liz Walker
told viewers that the Ballot Law Commission had required Bergantino
to testify, and that he had authenticated the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that disclosure, the ethicists contacted said the
possibility of the commission's questioning Bergantino should have
prompted Channel 4 to assign another reporter to the Sept. 28
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the journalist becomes an issue, the station should
remove the journalist from the story,'' said Marvin Kalb, director
of Harvard's Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and
Public Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thistle, director of broadcast journalism at Boston
University and former news director at WCVB-Ch.5, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practice in my news operation was that if you were part of
a story for whatever reason, someone else would cover the story,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
