<SLUG> BC-COMMUTER-TRAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES PRAISE ARRIVAL OF SILICON VALLEY COMMUTER TRAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The first commuter trains rolled into the
booming Silicon Valley this week, bringing hope for the region's
technology companies that the ride will reduce stress from grueling
drives on crowded highways.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area transportation planners also applaud the Altamont
Commuter Express service, which runs 85 miles from Stockton to San
Jose, but say it won't make a dent on traffic congestion because
the real problem is that housing growth south of San Francisco
hasn't kept pace with the job boom there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good news, bad news kind of thing. It's good that
(the train) is there, but its bad that it has to be there,'' said
Bill Hein, deputy director for the Metropolitan Transportation
Commission. ``This is an example of trying to solve with
transportation a problem that shouldn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that problem is that people are fleeing, going to the
(Central) Valley to find housing for jobs in Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Carl Guardino, president of the Santa Clara
Valley Manufacturing Group, a consortium of Silicon Valley's
biggest companies, said the new rail line was cause for
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the champagne on ice, thousands of employees in line
and we're very excited about this service,'' Guardino said.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara Valley Manufacturing Group has been pushing for
the commuter train for five years, in an effort to get employees to
work in less time and with less stress.
</P>
<P>
   Two trains a day will leave Stockton, at 4:12 and 5:22 a.m., and
arrive in San Jose about two hours and 20 minutes later, after
making stops in Manteca, Tracy, Livermore, Pleasanton, Fremont and
Santa Clara. Buses and company shuttle vans will deliver riders to
their jobs. Evening return trips will depart from San Jose at 4:15
and 5:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The train could provide real relief for some of the 50,000
Silicon Valley workers Guardino estimates now commute from homes in
the Central Valley and Tri-Valley areas.
</P>
<P>
   One of those workers, Dave Simpson, has been driving a 140-mile
round-trip commute from his home in Manteca to his job at Intel in
Santa Clara. Simpson was delighted to finally have an alternative
to the grueling drive over the Altamont Pass and down clogged
Interstate 680, the Bay area's second-most congested corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna give my car to my oldest son. It's a ploy to make
certain I use the train,'' he said. ``If the train does not work, I
have no backup plan. This is a man almost in desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Altamont train, known as the ACE, was working fine on its
inaugural day Monday. Brian Schmidt, manager for maintenance and
equipment for the ACE Authority, the government agency that runs
the service, said the two trains carried nearly two-thirds of their
total combined capacity of 1,200 riders. Almost 90 percent of those
riders had already bought monthly passes _ which range in price
from $59 to $279, depending on the distance travelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting off with two trains,'' he said, ``but as demand
increases, we're looking into increasing the frequency of
service.''
</P>
<P>
   The train offers commuters an alternative to crowded freeways,
said Colin Jones, a spokesman for Caltrans, the state
Transportation Department. But, he admits, it won't actually take
that many cars off the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to help, but it's not going to solve all the
traffic problems. It's still kind of a drop in the bucket,'' he
said. ``You'd have to run definitely a few more trains to see a
dent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
