<HEADER>
A6949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-MEMOIR-BOS &LR;      10-20 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-MEMOIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMOIR OR FICTION: BOOK ON DEATH CAMP SPARKS DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Masterpiece or masterful hoax? The question, swirling around an
award-winning memoir set in the Nazi death camps, is sparking
debate among Holocaust scholars over the veracity of the book's
author and the validity of ``recovered memory'' marketed as
historical truth.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``Fragments: Memories of a Wartime Childhood,'' by
Binjamin Wilkomirski, was published in Germany by Schocken Books in
1995 and appeared in English translation a year later. Critics were
effusive in praising Wilkomirski for his bloodcurdling portrayal of
Nazi atrocities _ including the murder of his father _ as witnessed
by the author, then a young Jewish boy from Riga, Latvia.
Wilkomirski, who was adopted by a Swiss family after the war,
credits psychotherapy with helping him excavate memories so
brutally detailed that as one critic was moved to write of
Wilkomirski, ``his sanity seems a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The book became an instant classic of its genre, in part because
the narrator is so young and vulnerable. Quoting from the Kirkus
Review, the book's dust jacket calls ``Fragments'' an
``extraordinary memoir'' and ``a real-life Grimm's fairy tale.''
But are the memories therein authentic? Not according to Swiss
writer Daniel Ganzfried, who reported in a Swiss periodical this
summer that Wilkomirski never set foot in the Auschwitz or Majdanek
concentration camps he claims to have inhabited as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, according to documents found by Ganzfried, Wilkomirski
was born out of wedlock in Switzerland in 1941 and adopted by a
family named Doessekker. Bruno Doessekker, as the boy was named,
grew up in Zurich and Biel. While ``Fragments'' may make for
unforgettable reading, Ganzfried says, it should properly be
labeled fiction, not autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fragments'' has been both an international bestseller and a
critical triumph. Translated into a dozen languages, the book has
won a National Jewish Book Award and the Prix de la Memoire de la
Shoah, among numerous honors.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkomirski's publisher is standing behind the book's
authenticity, at least so far. And Wilkomirski himself, a musician
and violin maker, has put forth the defense that he is a victim of
bureaucratic foul-ups by the Swiss. Readers have always been free
to view his book as either literature or memoir anyway, Wilkomirski
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, he neither disavows the labeling of his book
as nonfiction nor concedes it has been misrepresented to a
worldwide audience.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers have been unsettled, to say the least, by this
blurring of the line between fiction and history, especially with a
subject such as the Holocaust, in which an estimated 6 million Jews
died. It was not long ago, for instance, that filmmaker Steven
Spielberg dedicated profits from ``Schindler's List'' to a project
that documents memories _ real, verifiable memories _ of survivors
who outlived Hitler's Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read this book as a remarkable novel and was surprised when
Wilkomirski said it was a memoir,'' says retired Simmons College
professor Lawrence Langer, an authority on the Holocaust, who
encountered Wilkomirski at a conference last spring at the
University of Notre Dame. ``This is now a scandal of large
proportions. I'm getting e-mail from survivors now saying, `What
else are they going to do to us? Now they're making up stories
about us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Langer is concerned about what he calls ``cranks'' using the
scandal to discredit Holocaust memories in general, and about the
gullibility of publishers who would accept a work like this on face
value _ without supporting documentation.
</P>
<P>
   Brandeis University professor Anthony Polosky, who has edited
several volumes of Holocaust diaries, agrees that in a world where
Holocaust remembrances can be ascribed by some fringe elements to
``a Jewish plot,'' scrupulousness must be the first line of defense
against historical distortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You first must ask, is this genuine?'' says Polonsky. ``Then
you must ask, why did the Swiss and Germans swallow this hoax?
Finally, what should the Jewish community's reaction be? I feel
they should say this is deplorable, no matter the book's literary
merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Polonksy's comments stand in sharp contrast to sentiments voiced
by the Jewish Book Council in New York, which awared ``Fragments''
a prize for autobiography. Director Carolyn Hessel declined to
comment on the controversy last week, except to say the council's
board had agreed the award had been given ``with the best of
intentions'' and now, as Hessel put it, ``It's time to move on.''
But move on where?
</P>
<P>
   Academics who have used ``Fragments'' in courses certainly seem
divided on where to proceed. Bentley College English professor
Alicia Nitecki, who recently returned from Germany, where debate
over the scandal's implications is particularly heated, says she
feels duped by Wilkomirski and betrayed by his publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like apologizing to my students,'' says Nitecki,
adding, ``Scandals like this feed into Holocaust denial. This one
is spectacular because the book was so highly acclaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   Historian Deborah Lipstadt of Emory University, on the other
hand, thinks there is room for ``Fragments'' on her bookshelf
because she uses it as a companion to other Holocaust novels, and
did so well before the current controversy erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must realize,'' says Lipstadt, ``that whether this is fact
or fiction makes no difference in the history of the Holocaust.
Nobody writes the history of Auschwitz based on one memoir, or two
or three. In that sense, it adds nothing to those who want to deny
the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt also notes that Wilkomirski is hardly on a par with
Elie Wiesel, the Holocaust survivor and author honored with a Nobel
prize for his work. Others point to Wilkomirski's work in
``recovered memory'' therapy _ a process called into question in
many high-profile cases involving child abuse charges _ as one more
reason to be cautious about the author's motives.
</P>
<P>
   Says Lipstadt, ``I think he may even think it's the truth. That
doesn't make it history, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
