<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6963 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-SHOOTINGS-HNS     10-20 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-SHOOTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD BAN AMMO SALES DURING TWO HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two city supervisors have proposed banning the
sale of ammunition within city limits for the seven days before the
New Year's Eve and the Fourth of July holidays to discourage
revelers from firing guns in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is designed to save lives and stop further
violence in San Francisco,'' Supervisor Michael Yaki said. ``We
believe that this is something that can make the holidays safer for
passersby.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaki said he would encourage neighboring cities to approve
similar legislation to create an ``ammunition-free zone'' in the
region during the two holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Bullets fired into the air during celebrations have fallen back
to the ground, sometimes causing fatal injuries as well as property
damage, Yaki said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco police have not kept statistics on how many
injuries have occurred from falling bullets. Still, the police
said, the concern is real. A study conducted by King-Drew Medical
Center in Los Angeles tallied 118 injuries and 38 deaths from the
unrestrained firing of guns during a seven-year period there.
</P>
<P>
   The city police and the U.S. Park Police support the legislation
proposed by Yaki and Supervisor Mark Leno. The park police have
primary jurisdiction over Ocean Beach, the favored spot in San
Francisco for gun enthusiasts who like to fire their weapons on the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big problem at the beaches in San Francisco,'' said
police Capt. James Smith. He said stray bullets have hit cars and
condominium apartments in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Only two stores in the city sell ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Laws such as the one Yaki and Leno propose already exist in Los
Angeles and two other Southern California cities, Compton and
Solana Beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
