<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BMOC-CHANGE-BOS &LR;      10-20 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMOC-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD TO FIND THE BIG MAN ON CAMPUS ANYMORE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No heads turn when the football captain strolls across Harvard
Yard to his government class. ``None,'' Brendan Bibro testifies.
``That's the total truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibro is a big man _ 6 feet, 250 pounds sans cleats and pads _
but he is not a Big Man, not the way he would have been back when
the gridiron king was a tin god around Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Harvard is coming off its best season in three
decades and Bibro is the first man in modern times to be captain
for two years, he's just another passing face. ``I would say 99
percent of people here have no idea who I am,'' Bibro says. ``And
the other 1 percent play alongside me.''
</P>
<P>
   What used to be called the BMOC _ the Big Man on Campus, the
stereotypical football star with Betty Coed on his letter-sweatered
arm at a fraternity party _ has vanished, certainly at colleges
around Boston.
</P>
<P>
   With student bodies now coeducational and dramatically more
diverse than they were in the '50s and '60s, the Big Man has been
supplanted by a dozen or more mid-sized BMOCs (and increasingly,
BWOCs) who operate in decidedly narrow orbits.
</P>
<P>
   They run student governments. They edit the newspaper. They run
interfraternity councils. They direct volunteer organizations. They
perform in singing groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more egalitarian,'' says Kevin Duffy, Boston College's
vice president of student affairs. ``There are microcommunities on
campus now, each with their own leaders.'' BC hasn't had a classic
BMOC since Doug (Little Big Man) Flutie, the quarterback who led
the Eagles to unexpected glories in the early '80s and won the
Heisman Trophy as the nation's top football player.
</P>
<P>
   The most familiar face on The Heights these days probably
belongs to Patrick McMahon, who made himself ubiquitous while
getting himself elected undergraduate government president last
spring. ``I was out there in a T-shirt, handing out fliers and
trying to shake everybody's hand,'' shrugs McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   The campuses are so multi-culti now, with dozens of activities
from Caribbean culture clubs to ultimate Frisbee teams, &UR;  &LR; that the
likelihood of one person's being viewed as a BMOC is remote. ``I'm
not sure there'd be that widespread agreement about what the
standard would be,'' says Bobbie Knable, dean of students at Tufts
University.
</P>
<P>
   The standard used to be whatever 21-year-old white males agreed
it should be. But the rich diversity of student bodies now _
racially, ethnically, geographically, culturally _ has made the
very idea of a Big Man moot. ``Unless you can identify with the
BMOC,'' says Maia Heyck-Merlin, a Tufts senior, ``he's not going to
be a BMOC to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyck-Merlin, president of the Leonard Carmichael Society, the
umbrella group for the 700 students who do volunteer work, may come
as close as anyone at Tufts. Since the Carmichael Society is the
biggest organization on campus, she has ex-officio visibility. But
Heyck-Merlin is just as happy to stay out of the limelight. ``I'm
behind the scenes,'' she says. ``I'm like the woman behind the
curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when colleges stress inclusion and group activities
and teamwork are prized, few students want to be seen as the Great
Oz. If you're head and shoulders above the crowd, you might get
your block knocked off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered, but I don't think BMOC is a title I would
want,'' says McMahon of BC. ``I would hate for students here to
think that I thought I was this big popular guy that everyone
wanted to be with. It would be a little too arrogant, a little too
pompous.''
</P>
<P>
   The BMOC came from a time before the Great War, a product of
Gothic towers and ivy-covered stadiums and secret societies and
prep-school values, ``... that worship, seldom named, never really
admitted, of the bogey Big Man,'' as F. Scott Fitzgerald observed.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Man was the embodiment of everything collegiate America
admired. He was athletic, handsome, sociable, heroic, democratic,
intelligent (but not intellectual) and, most importantly,
conformist. ``Play the game as others are playing it,'' an
upperclass clubman advises Dink Stover, embryonic Big Man, in
``Stover at Yale.'' ``It's a big game and it'll follow you all
through life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobey Baker, Princeton University's blond and graceful demigod,
was the model for the BMOC. ``There at the head of the white
platoon marched Allenby, the football captain, slim and defiant,''
Fitzgerald wrote in ``This Side of Paradise,'' ``as if aware that
this year the hopes of the college rested on him ....''
</P>
<P>
   Baker was Princeton (and America) in 1914, just as Pete Dawkins
was West Point (and America) in 1958. Dawkins, a dentist's son from
Detroit, was football captain, class president, first captain of
the cadet corps, and a Rhodes scholar. Everyone wanted to be Pete
Dawkins _ until Vietnam turned campuses upside down.
</P>
<P>
   With students burning draft cards, marching in demonstrations,
holding deans and Dow recruiters hostage, and taking strike votes,
nobody cared who the football captain was. ``There was an emphasis
on what was happening outside the university,'' says Duffy of BC,
``as opposed to what was happening on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   The BMOC now headed Students for a Democratic Society, wore a
headband, and made non-negotiable demands through a bullhorn.
``Alma mater died between 1968 and 1972,'' says Sol Gittleman, the
Tufts provost, ``and the idea of the BMOC went with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleges went coeducational and coresidential. Admissions
offices searched coast to coast and beyond for blacks, Latinos,
Asians, and Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College was a male commuter school in 1968. Now, it has
an Asian Caucus, a Club Latino Espanol, a Philippine Society, and a
Cape Verdean Association. Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
once the bastion of the buzz-cut white male nerd, is more than 40
percent female and nearly a third Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts, whose 4,600 undergrads now come from more than 100
countries, has four recognized a cappella groups _ male, female,
coed, and Jewish. ``It'll never look like the yearbook of 1955
again, and you wouldn't want it,'' says Gittleman. ``It's a
different country.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Cramer walks into Jay's Deli, and the counterman says
``Sing on, brother.'' He strolls across the quad, and passersby say
``Great job last night!'' ``The president gives me a hug every time
he sees me,'' marvels Cramer. ``Who else gets a hug from the
president?''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer is president of the Beelzebubs, Tufts's legendary a
cappella group. Almost everybody has squeezed into Goddard Chapel
to hear the 'Bubs. Their CDs and tapes are on sale at the
bookstore, and they have their own Web site (www.bubs.com). ``I'm a
soloist,'' says Cramer, ``so I'm a recognizable face.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Marvin Venay, a Boston University senior from Pittsburgh
who has brought back the NAACP campus chapter after a 15-year
absence and broadened it beyond its African-American base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our definition of color does not just consist of black,''
Venay says. ``We're multicultural. I'm very visible, so I'm pretty
well known.''
</P>
<P>
   Visibility and diversity are the keys to being a BMOC or a BWOC
now that campuses have been atomized into dozens of microgroups.
``Once classes are over, everyone goes everywhere,'' says Erica
Pfister, an MIT junior. ``People belong to two or three groups, but
nobody belongs to the same two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   So the students whose names and faces are known either run one
thing that lots of people care about or get involved with several
things, like Susan Rushing does.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing, an MIT senior who was a Miss Maryland contestant (``I
was the interview winner'') and spent last semester singing opera
in Milan, runs a peer counseling group on health issues, was on the
ballroom dancing team, and may join the new cheerleading squad.
</P>
<P>
   She's as well known as any of the faces floating along the
``infinite corridor'' beneath the Dome. ``But I would never have
thought of myself as a BWOC,'' Rushing says. ``That's pretty funny,
actually.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rushings and Cramers and McMahons and Heyck-Merlins smile
when they hear the B-word applied to them. It's so old school, as
they say on campus. So sis-boom-bah.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the gridiron king is just another gov major from
Pittsburgh. Harvard's football captain glances at a framed
photograph showing the stadium filled to the colonnade in 1915,
when everyone on campus knew who the Big Man was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at that picture, and it's amazing,'' Brendan Bibro
says. ``They don't come across the bridge too often now _ unless
Yale's in town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
