u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAMA-MARRIAGE-BOS &LR;      10-20 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAMA-MARRIAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY DYSFUNCTION TAKEN TO THE BREAKING POINT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MARRIAGE OF BETTE AND BOO
</P>
<P>
   Play in two acts by Christopher Durang.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Marcus Stern. Set, Molly Hughes. Costumes, Karen
Eister. Lighting, John Ambrosone. Produced by the American
Repertory Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Have you always disliked ``Long Day's Journey Into Night''
because you couldn't get past the ``It's a Wonderful Life''
optimism? Did you walk out of ``The Butcher Boy'' because it seemed
like such a wistful evocation of the innocence of childhood? You
stopped watching ``Married ... With Children'' because Al and the
family were too darned likable? Did you put down ``Angela's Ashes''
in disgust because too few of Frank McCourt's siblings died?
</P>
<P>
   If so, the American Repertory Theatre has the play for you, a
revival of Christopher Durang's ``The Marriage of Bette and Boo.''
Durang takes family dysfunction to the breaking point, but the
problem is that when this bough breaks, down comes ``Bette,''
babies and all. ``The Marriage of Bette and Boo'' is an abject (to
say the least) lesson in how bleak chic can seem like the cat's
meow of hipness when written, but turn into a self-contented,
bloated pussycat when the years show how little talent lies behind
those claws.
</P>
<P>
   Bette and Boo are a Punch and Judy for our times. Bette's a nag
who delivers one dead baby after another (save for Durang stand-in
Matt). Boo takes after his boorish drunk of a father, who uses his
dimwitted wife like a dishrag. Bette's parents aren't any shining
lights themselves. One of Matt's sisters is a religious maniac, and
the other is a Norman Bates wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   In his notes to the 1985 autobiographical play, Durang says,
``Unless you go through all the genuine angers you feel, both
justified and unjustified, the feelings of love that you do have
will not have any legitimate base and will be at least partially
false. Plus, eventually you will go crazy.'' In itself, that's an
astute psychotherapeutical assessment about recovering from the
neuroses of family life and is, in this context, a refreshing break
from the trendy, and moronic, view that families have little to do
with how one turns out.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the artist's job to get beyond therapy, to coin a
phrase, to give us more than a primal scream of discontent. Edward
Albee's ``Three Tall Women'' is a case study of taking the detritus
of dysfunction and, through an act of artistic imagination,
infusing it with a rich, theatrically poetic life of its own. Using
a similarly surreal vernacular, though Durang owes more to Ionesco,
``Bette and Boo'' is too purgative to be either poetic or
cathartic.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe that the fault is with the ART production
and cast, as talented a collection of darkly comic pranksters as
Durang could hope for. Thomas Derrah, Will LeBow, Paula Plum, and
Karen MacDonald are as dependable as ever, while Caroline Hall (as
Bette), Kristin Flanders, and, most of all, Remo Airaldi equal the
more established veterans and maybe even take things up a notch. If
the object is to get us to like these basically unlikable
characters in spite of ourselves, only Randall Jaynes's drunken Boo
fails to deliver. Matt Chiorini as Matt, who also narrates, is
blandly effective. That seems to be as much as Durang has asked of
his stand-in, who, like Durang, is trying to make order out of
chaos, but unlike the character's hero, Thomas Hardy, finds only
chaos. Director Marcus Stern's confident staging and Molly Hughes's
delightfully sloping set provide a suitably disorienting framework.
</P>
<P>
   Airaldi as the heartless, and homosexual, Father Donnally, makes
the most of his physical humor, especially his imitation of bacon
sizzling on the griddle. He also summarizes Durang's credo: ``Why
didn't they think before they got married? Why does no one ever
think? Why did God make people stupid?''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond wallowing in a ``Married .... With Idiots'' cry of
the heart, Durang gives us too little in the way of honed dialogue,
imaginative metaphor, or blackened humor to make us want to see
Bette and Boo renew their disavows. There are times when the
exaggerated characters represent the heartbreak that all families
mete out for varied reasons and in varied doses. For the most part,
though, Bette and Boo are Durang's cross to bear. If his family is
anything like that, then we can only congratulate him for
channeling his problems into playwriting rather than bloodletting.
So to end on a positive note, who says theater can't save lives?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
