<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLOWEEN IS NOT JUST FOR CHILDREN ANY MORE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, Halloween was almost exclusively for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, though, it's also a holiday for adults _ and a $2.5
billion bonanza for merchants selling party supplies, beer, candy,
and costumes to baby boomers who like to dress up as characters
from such recent movies as ``Austin Powers,'' ``The Mask of
Zorro,'' and ``Scream 2.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Oct. 31 falling on a Saturday this year, 1998 could be
the best-selling Halloween to date, some retailers predict.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween has ``turned into an adult celebration,'' said retail
manager Terry Anderson of Boston Costume Co.
</P>
<P>
   Two explanations are offered for the sudden surge in Halloween's
popularity _ Hollywood hype and baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many movies today include a Halloween costume line as
part of their promotional marketing and licensed tie-ins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies and TV shows are really driving the product,'' said
Mark Arvanigian, whose family owns several Halloween Outlet stores,
including stores in Framingham and Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   And while children and young adults have always been eager to
dress up for trick-or-treating, baby boomers seem especially
susceptible to marketing pitches for high-rent costumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers may have grown up but they still want to have the
same amount of fun,'' said spokesman Chris Strano of Spencer Gifts
Inc., a chain that bills itself as Halloween headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Forget generic witches and goblins. The rule of costuming these
days seems to be: If it's licensed, people will wear it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``Teletubbies'' and ``Blue's Clues'' costumes, many
catalog retailers such as Learn &AMP; Play feature costumes based on
corporate icons.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, discerning trick-or-treaters can masquerade as the
Pillsbury Doughboy or Tony the Tiger this Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet perhaps, costumes inspired by the McDonald's
fast-food menu are available for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these costumes, the whole family can dress up like an
Extra Value Meal,'' said Mary Miller, vice president of global
marketing for McDonald's Corp. ``One person can be the shake,
another the fries, and somebody else can be the Big Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Miller, costumes are a ``logical extension'' for
the fast-food chain because both McDonald's and Halloween are about
``family, children, and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In the annals of marketing synergy, the folks at Spencer Gifts
may have outdone themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The retail chain, which also operates Dapy stores, is a
subsidiary of Universal Studios. And when Universal released
``Bride of Chucky'' over the weekend, a much-anticipated event for
film fans of the splatterfest genre, Spencer already had updated
Chucky products ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   If Hollywood studios are cashing in on stimulating demand for
Halloween merchandise, nightclubs and radio stations have learned
that Oct. 31 can be a windfall for them, too.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that middle-aged trick-or-treaters are not all dressed
up with no place to go, many clubs and restaurants now throw some
version of a costume ball.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Massachusetts Bay Line offered just one Halloween
harbor cruise; this year, it plans to offer three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Halloween is one of those holidays that people like to go out
and celebrate,'' said Shane Lemay, the cruise line's marketing
director. ``It's not like Thanksgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating Halloween in costume can be a thirsty business for
the adult party animal, and for that reason brewers have seen a
nice jump in October beer sales in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a spike-up in October,'' said senior vice president
Frank Walters of Impact, a newsletter that tracks the beverage
industry. ``A large part of that percentage comes from the
promotions that beer makers run around Halloween.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewers shipped 1.2 million barrels of imported beer to US
retailers last October, a nearly 9 percent increase over shipments
for the previous October, Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just costumes and beer that are Halloween big sellers;
it's also spooky home decor, scary music, and strings of orange
Christmas-style lights that Martha Stewart devotees can use to
complement the old jack-o'-lantern.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a scarecrow that a home decorator can stick
outside, said Dennis Oberholzer, seasonal merchandise manager at
Bradlees Inc., the Braintree-based discount chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scarecrows are a blowout this year,'' he said of sales.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's gotten to the point that home decorating at
Halloween is ``almost as elaborate as Christmas,'' he said.
``Driving home, I'm amazed at all the orange lights up on people's
homes and all the elaborate paraphernalia.''
</P>
<P>
   Candy, of course, is a major seller. According to a consumer
survey from American Express, Americans bought $950 million of
candy at Halloween last year, and retailers that benefit most from
Halloween sales are discount chains and drugstores.
</P>
<P>
   For years, American Express has been doing sales surveys around
Christmas and the back-to-school season. For the first time, it has
conducted a Halloween sales survey.
</P>
<P>
   From a retail standpoint, Halloween has gotten too big to
ignore, explained American Express spokeswoman Judy Tenzer.
</P>
<P>
   Of adults interviewed, 45 percent said they plan to celebrate
Halloween with at least as much vigor as New Year's Eve, and they
plan to spend an average of $81 each on partying and Halloween
knickknacks.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Retail Federation, spokesman Scott Krugman said
Halloween ``started to get on our radar screen in 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   What showed up on that radar screen was a proliferation of
stores such as those in the Halloween Adventure chain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Halloween Adventure consisted of two brothers selling
novelties in Philadelphia parking lots. Today the company opens
about 140 stores in August and September on short-term mall leases,
then shuts them down a day or two after Halloween, said chief
operating officer Joe Purifico.
</P>
<P>
   Two such stores, at CambrideSide Galleria and the Northshore
Mall in Peabody, sell ``Saturday Night Live'' conehead costumes and
clown outfits for the family dog, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   According to Purifico, such seasonal stores fill crucial
vacancies for big mall operators looking to maximize profits.
</P>
<P>
   At Hallmark Cards Inc., Halloween is only the eighth-biggest day
of the year for exchanging greeting cards, but one of the
fastest-growing. From 1994 to 1997, the industry saw sales rise 23
percent to $39 million, said spokeswoman Michelle Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   At Spencer Gifts, meanwhile, key operatives are already gearing
up for Halloween 1999, said spokesman Spano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a full crew that works all year-round,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because most costumes are made in China, factories need long
lead times. As a result, it can be tough to respond nimbly to
instant trends, such as when Monica Lewinsky was elevated to the
status at which some Halloween revelers may wish to impersonate her
at some of this year's tonier costume balls.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, said Anderson of Boston Costume. ``Our Monica
masks just arrived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
