</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, October 21,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday,
October 21, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ WASHINGTON _ The latest developments out of the
Middle East peace talks taking place at the Wye Plantation on
Maryland's Eastern Shore between Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-HUME _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ About 15 years ago, John
Hume _ who last week won the Nobel Peace Prize _ built a little
stone cottage on a spit of land overlooking the River Foyle in
Donegal, just a few miles over the Northern Ireland border. The
chances of his being assassinated were somewhat diminished on this
remote and windswept promontory. Hume liked to sit in his yard and
watch ships ply the Foyle on their way to and from Derry. He smoked
too many cigarettes while he stared out to sea. I sat with him in
his yard a few times. He told me more than once that this was the
last bit of Ireland seen by emigrants as they sailed to America and
Canada. How sad, he would say, that after almost everybody was
driven out of Ireland, those few who remained took to killing each
other. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp.'s attorneys make
opening arguments Tuesday in the federal government's antitrust
suit, and the government's first witness, Netscape chief James
Barksdale, takes the stand. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUDGE _ Last December, when Microsoft Corp. insisted
that the Windows 95 operating system wouldn't work without its
Internet browser, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
decided to find out for himself. With help from a courtroom
technician, the judge was able to ``uninstall'' his own Explorer
Internet browser in about 90 seconds. So Jackson ordered the
software giant to begin selling Windows 95 separate from its
browser. While that order was overturned on appeal _ Jackson's dive
into the technical aspects of the case is indicative of his
approach to law. (Regan, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Reporting on the White House sex
scandal was largely accurate but there were shortcomings, a study
of six major lines of coverage by the Committee of Concerned
Journalists said Tuesday. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM-STUDY _ Nearly two-thirds of telecom leaders say that
the Federal Communications Commission is doing its job and the
landmark 1996 Telecommunications Act doesn't need to be reopened,
according to a survey by the Small Business Survival Project.
(Regan, Cox News Service 300).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   HAVE-NOTS _ WASHINGTON _ More Americans view themselves as
``have-nots'' rather than ``haves,'' according to a new Gallup poll
designed to measure American perceptions of fairness and
opportunity. A decade ago, only 17 percent considered themselves
``have-nots,'' and today it's 25 percent. Today, according to the
poll, the number of Americans reporting economic deprivation ranges
from 11 percent who said they did not have enough money for food,
18 percent for clothing and 22 percent for health care. Still, in
general, Americans are more positive and more optimistic than they
have been in any of Gallup's seven previous measurements, beginning
in 1964. (Shepard, Cox News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   HAVE-NOTS-DATA _ Highlights of the poll. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-STANDARDS _ WASHINGTON _ A new poll says that nearly 82
percent of American parents think academic standards at their
childrens' schools are too low, says the Council for Basic
Education. In addition, most parents said it would be easier for
them to know if local schools were performing well if they had
greater access to model standards written by national experts.
(Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NON-VOTERS _ SEATTLE _ The young and the poor are the least
likely Americans to vote, and the participation gap is widening. A
look at the causes and the effects. (Shepard).
</P>
<P>
   NON-VOTERS-DATA _ A statistical look at non-voters.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SCHOLARSHIPS _ WASHINGTON _ A bill that will allow
employers to hire more foreign high-tech workers will also
establish new job training programs for American workers and
scholarships for low-income students. The National Science
Foundation, which now only awards grants, says the implementation
of a new scholarship program will be a daunting task. (Monroe, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLASMOKE _ MIAMI _ Second day of opening arguments in the class
action lawsuit against tobacco companies. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD _ Today's main likely to focus on cleanup barring more
intense weather. Governor will try again today to tour the area.
(Lindell, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CUERO _ As floodwaters roll toward the Gulf, Cuero is among the
cities hardest hit. Officials consider evacuating the state prison
just north of there. (Rivera, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   RESCUE _ Divers are going to search for the two children who
were in the suburban. Search also resumes for 6-year-old missing in
Comal. (Perkes, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE _ News of the day in case of three men shot in the head
in their hotel room at the Atlanta Hilton. (Longa, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TIMELINE _ Trying to put together timeline of the last two days
of the three men who were shot to death in the Atlanta Hilton.
(Longa, Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REACT _ In fending off questions about the safety of downtown
Atlanta, Mayor Bill Campbell said Monday, ``Interestingly enough,
there were tens of thousands of people in downtown for the Saints
game with the Falcons, or just coming to enjoy a pleasant weekend
in Atlanta. I don't think any of them saw or heard, or felt unsafe
while they were here. This tragedy is, I think, an individual act
that must be seen in that context.'' Maybe some of those thousands
coming for the next Falcons game will feel a bit more unsafe now
that it turns out three men who came to town for the Falcons game
were shot in the head. Following reaction of downtown businesses
and hotel industry. (Charles/Campos, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STATEHOUSE _ Amid this lackluster year for federal campaigns,
the most aggressive and hard-fought battles are being waged in
state Capitols around the nation, particularly in the South.
Republicans and Democrats are battling for control of legislative
chambers from North Carolina to Georgia to Texas. The fierce
competition is an extension of the transformation that swept
Congress in the early 1990s, when Republicans gained control of
most of the Congressional delegations in the South. The off year
elections unfold in the shadow of the 2000 census, making
statehouse races _ and the 36 governors' races _ especially
important since the ground is being laid for the 2001
reapportionment. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constiution). 30. WITH
MAP (showing majority in southern state legislatures).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA _ After more than a decade, three state officials will
decide Thursday whether to grant an operating permit for a
low-level nuclear waste disposal site near the tiny town of Sierra
Blanca in West Texas. What factors will the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission consider in making its decision? Story will
pay particular attention to the geology of the site and the
socioeconomics of the region, two objections raised by
administrative law judges in their recommendation to deny the
permit. What's at stake? How did we get to the point, and what's
the next step? (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-QA _ Answers to commonly asked questions about the
low-level waste facility. (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-TRANS _ Although Sierra Blanca is a remote site, people
all across the state worry about the routes that will be used to
truck low-level radioactive waste to West Texas. What are the
transportation plans? What's the track record on hauling low-level
waste? (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-STATES _ Three other facilities currently accept
low-level waste, and several others have been closed. What's their
track record? (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   LAND-COMMISH _ The race for Texas Land Commissioner has seemed
to be about houses. Yes, houses. At times in recent weeks, it has
seemed, David Dewhurst and Richard Raymond are battling a race
against obscurity for an obscure job, as much as anything. For
without the bickering reminiscent of the old-time, name-calling
contests that years ago were an election-year staple in Texas, both
campaigns concede that voters would probably have paid far less
attention to who will be the state's 27th land commissioner, a job
created 161 years ago when Texas was still a republic. Here's a
look at the two men who want the job. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
