<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY-TRADERS FIND THEIR MONEY GONE ALONG WITH COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today the little storefront on Chauncy Street is empty, the
banks of blinking computer terminals gone. Gone too are the amateur
stock traders who once thought they could play with the big boys on
Wall Street _ and so is their money.
</P>
<P>
   What the storefront is, say state regulators, is a testament to
just how risky day trading can be.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Massachusetts Division of Securities became the
first regulator in the country to file an action against a
day-trading firm and one of its most publicized players, Blocking
Trading Inc., the now-defunct Houston concern that not long ago
relished its reputation as ``The Bad Boys of Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   While Block Trading hyped itself as the little guy's alternative
to the sophisticated trading advantages enjoyed by the big Wall
Street players, the reality turned out to be something very
different, regulators say. The one thing that the restaurant
managers, medical technicians, and grandmothers who paid to trade
stocks in Block Trading's Chauncy Street office shared was this:
Every one of them lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading, propelled by the long bull market, gained in
popularity the last few years by catering to individual investors
who buy and sell stocks full-time over sophisticated computer
systems at the firms' offices. Day traders make rapid-fire
transactions, holding a stock for a minute, two minutes, maybe
four, looking to make one-eighth or one-quarter point _ 12.5 cents
or 25 cents _ on a stock and then hopefully bailing out with the
profit.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide has turned against the day-trading firms, which
have seen their profits slashed by new competitors and
deep-discount Internet brokers as well as a shaky stock market. At
least three day-trading firms have failed recently, including Block
Trading, which ceased trading three weeks because it could not meet
the capital requirements of the stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts complaint filed Monday charges that Block
Trading and its current and former executives engaged in deceptive
marketing to attact investors; allowed customers to improperly
allocate profits and losses to different accounts; and improperly
encouraged customers to borrow money from the father of one of
Block Trading's founders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.4l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The division is seeking to revoke Block Trading's right to do
business in Massachusetts, and is seeking fines against the firm
and its executives. The regulators said they launched their
investigation last year shortly after the Block Trading operation
was featured in a page-one Boston Capital column. The Boston office
closed earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State William Galvin, who oversees the Securities
Division, called day trading ``a perversion of technology,'' used
to lure in unsophisticated investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hold all the cards,'' Galvin said of the day-trading
firms. He added: ``We're anxious to put out the word that day
trading is not something we want to see in Massachusetts until or
unless there is a more honest system.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher M. Block, chief executive of Block Trading in
Houston, said his company, which once had 24 offices and revenues
of about $20 million a year, ``is looking at bankruptcy.'' He
defended the concept of the little guy as day trader, but
acknowledged making money was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't anything people were compelled to do,'' Block said
in a telephone interview. ``It was their decision when to start and
when to stop trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Jennings of Indiana University, who along with academics
at Notre Dame and the University of Delaware has studied the effect
of day trading on the stock market, was cautious about the
prospects for amateur traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who still make a decent living day
trading, but for the average person today that's probably going to
be the exception rather than the rule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts complaint also charged that Block Trading, in
violation of federal rules, encouraged its customers to borrow
money for trading, including money from Dr. Gene Burke, a Houston
doctor who is the father of Jeffrey S. Burke, president of Block
Trading.
</P>
<P>
   Block Trading customers were typically required to have $50,000
to $100,000 in capital to begin trading. The complaint says that of
the 68 accounts at the Boston Block Trading office, 44 used
borrowed money for trading. At least one couple filed a complaint
saying they had lost about $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Block, the firm's chief executive, said loans of $10,000
to $100,000 from the elder Burke ``were not uncommon on a daily
basis'' to customers. But he said the lending ``was completely
separate and apart'' from the firm. ``We never encouraged it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Block and its key Houston executives, the Massachusetts
complaint also named Jeffrey Bowman, who managed the Boston office,
and an associate, Adam Baruchowitz. The complaint says Baruchowitz
was the only trader who ultimately made money at the Boston office.
Neither Bowman nor Baruchowitz, both recently working as traders in
New York, could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
 &UR; boscap(AT)globe. &QC; 
 &LR; com or at 929-2902 or 929-2918, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
