<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMIC-OPTIMISM-HNS     10-20 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMIC-OPTIMISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ANALYSTS ARE BETTING ON A SLOW-LEAK RECESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For decades, economists said that another massive
depression was impossible because of protective measures that
nations took after World War II to tame financial speculation and
keep trade flowing in tough times.
</P>
<P>
   Then, unforeseen shocks starting last year with financial panic
in parts of Asia and the threatened collapse of Japan's seemingly
invincible banking system revived fears that a Great Depression
might happen again after all.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, opinion among some analysts has begun to swing
back. Many of them, while accepting the possibility that a
recession may be on the way, insist that recent events show it will
be kept within manageable limits.
</P>
<P>
   They explain their comparative optimism by noting that after a
hesitant start, inter-governmental institutions like the
International Monetary Fund, which bails out shaky national
economies, the U.S. government, which has the resources that make
it vital to global prosperity, and big individual banks have
recognized the need for large-scale action and are beginning to
move.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, critics derided a conference of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank in Washington for failing to come
up with emergency measures to halt the downward slide. Instead, the
meeting dealt chiefly with proposals for steps to shore up the
global economy at some later date.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some experts now are revising their views, contending that
the conference, although short on fresh ideas, put the world
economies on notice of the need for immediate changes to keep an
unpromising situation from worsening.
</P>
<P>
   As former French finance minister Edmund Alphery put it: ``The
boom is over, but that doesn't mean a `bust' is inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   He foresees a period of lower prices, slightly declining
international trade and much less spectacular economic expansion
than that of the mid-1990s. But he said none of this would lead to
greater political instability or ``bread lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Paris-based financial consultant Frank Satsumi noted that
several influential European banks had dismissed their top
officials, signaling the changes now underway. The United Bank of
Switzerland, for instance, axed its four senior executives in the
same week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fired for big losses incurred through imprudent
lending,'' Satsumi said. ``It was a warning shot to international
bankers to alter their ways _ or else. Private lending from now on
will avoid the kind of excessive risk that caused such trouble in
Indonesia and other Asian countries. But that doesn't mean a credit
crunch, which would dry up international trade, will result. A
middle way can and will be found.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there may be moves to liberalize trade further and faster
than otherwise expected, according to Frank Allyn, a adviser to the
British finance ministry. ``The United States has begun to put
pressure on the (15 nation) European Union to loosen its
restrictions on imports from Asia and Latin America,'' he observed.
``It's hard to see how Europe can oppose the idea as strongly as it
might have done if a recession wasn't threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   Allyn also credits the Clinton administration for keeping a
steady eye on Latin America to insure there is not another Mexican
peso crisis. ``The problems of Brazil and Argentina will be
contained (by Washington),'' he predicted, ``thereby providing
another safety net against a depression.''
</P>
<P>
   These analysts say U.S. and other markets will continue a
gradual downward trend, sporadically interrupted by upward spurts.
But they all discount the likelihood of a 1929-style market plunge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
