<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7024 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS &LR;      10-20 0325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR SAYS CONTAINING HATE CRIMES WILL TAKE EXTRA WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A federal law enforcement official said that
authorities must prosecute signs of prejudice among seemingly
mundane assault and vandalism cases to contain hate crimes like the
one in Wyoming in which a gay college student died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to carry them as an assault than to look
further,'' William Blagg, the U.S. attorney in San Antonio, said
Monday at a seminar on hate crimes sponsored by the Department of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of stricter laws against hate crimes point to Laramie,
Wyo., where Matthew Shepard, 21, was found after being beaten and
bound to a fence. He died Oct. 12 and two young men have been
charged with his murder.
</P>
<P>
   The police say robbery was a motive but that Shepard was singled
out because he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   Blagg's prosecutors are handling a civil rights case in El Paso,
Texas, where they've charged two sisters and a husband with holding
a deaf family as indentured servants.
</P>
<P>
   Blagg said his office hasn't handled any cases involving hate
crimes since he assumed control of Texas' Western Division almost
three years ago, a record that isn't necessarily cause for
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you haven't prosecuted any doesn't mean there
aren't any,'' Blagg said.
</P>
<P>
   No city is immune to outbursts of bias, said Jimmie Jones, a
director of the not-for-profit Facing History and Ourselves in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   His associate, William Johnston, a former deputy police
superintendent in Boston, said every law-enforcement agency needs a
staff member who can recognize the difference between a barroom
brawl involving a white and a black man, and a case involving
racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time we let it go by it escalates,'' Johnston said. ``All
of a sudden someone is tied to a fence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7027 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-20 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT ETHICAL TO LIE ABOUT AGE ON JOB APPLICATION?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE LEWIS 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1982 film ``Tootsie,'' actor Dustin Hoffman donned a wig
and a dress, assumed a falsetto voice, and plastered enough makeup
on his face to suffocate most women.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman was playing the role of a desperate actor who was so
difficult to get along with that the only way he could get work was
to disguise himself as a woman. The disguise worked. Hoffman, who
played actor Michael Dorsey, did not just get a job. His female
character became the darling of daytime soaps and a cult figure.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward 16 years to the real-life case of Kimberlee Kramer,
also known as Riley Weston, formerly a top Hollywood writer who did
what some critics are surely calling unthinkable: She lied about
her age, her name, and her life to land a highly coveted position
as a TV writer for the WB network's new hit ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's lapse of ethics is not rare. If a 1997 workplace survey
about ethical and moral conduct is any indication, then hundreds of
professional employees are grappling with right and wrong, and some
are failing miserably.
</P>
<P>
   Coauthored by the Ethics Resource Center, in Washington, and the
Society for Human Resource Management in Alexandria, Va., the
survey of 747 human resource professionals found that nearly 50
percent had compromised ethical standards because of financial
pressures or overly aggressive business objectives. Their ethical
lapses ranged from falsification of reports to theft, office
crimes, and outright lying.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer attributed her own actions to her desire for the job, as
well as the creation of a persona she had routinely used to secure
acting roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an accepted practice for actresses to lie about
their age,'' The Wall Street Journal quotes Kramer as saying. ``In
my desperation to find work as an actress I adopted an age
appropriate for my physical appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kramer's make-believe persona, initially created to help her
secure acting roles, continued after her talent and her ``age''
propelled her into a position as a much sought-after script writer.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer is 32 and, by all accounts, quite talented, but in the
tinseled halls of Hollywood a preoccupation with youth forced her
to make a terrible choice. She said she was 19, telling studio
officials she was home-schooled when, in fact, she had graduated
from high school. She said she was single even though she is
divorced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a problem when women are judged not on the
merits of their work, but by their age,'' says Vivien Labaton,
codirector of the Third Wave Foundation in New York, a national
organization for young women age 15 to 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age discrimination is endemic to Hollywood,'' adds Labaton.
``This bears itself out in everything from the consistent pairing
of older men and younger women in movies to the sexualization of
young girls in the media. Part of what it means for a woman to be a
hot commodity in Hollywood today is to be young.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this mindset is not limited to Hollywood, and neither
are ethical lapses and moral indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Mark Braverman, cofounder of CMG Associates in
Newton, says many of us take on false roles to advance at work or
in society at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have to put on masks,'' says Braverman. ``We have to be
the right shape, the right weight, the right color, and the right
age. But what do you get when you succeed in being other than
yourself? Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could take the case of (Kimberlee Kramer) as, perhaps, an
example,'' he continues. ``She was fired not because her work was
not of high quality, but because of the way she had been marketed
and the fact that, without the false persona and age, she
no &UR;  &LR; longer fit the image.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Diane E. Lewis is a member of the Globe staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
