<P>
   SOUTHERN-ITALIAN-COOKING (Undated) _ For generations, southern
Italian cooking in the United States has been reduced to a
red-sauced shadow of its true self. But today, chefs are reaching
for authentic ingredients and preparations, and we are seeing a
cuisine that's as interesting and sophisticated as the one from the
north. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-DINING (Undated) _ There is no bad food in Italy. That may
be an exaggeration, but after 3 weeks of traveling through Italy at
the height of the tourist season I have come to believe it is true.
In small towns and big cities, I ate well everywhere. Unlike the
grander cuisines of the world, which rely on the chemistry of
combination and transformation, Italian food is of the earth.
People eat locally and with great simplicity; you find the same
ingredients, prepared in much the same manner, again and again. A
critic's notebook by Ruth Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT-JITTERS (Undated) _ The restaurant industry, in
full-boom expansion, faces a less certain future. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE-BISCUITS (Undated) _ Baskets full of end-of-season
bounty from the garden left me with a delightful problem: how to
make the most of it? My assistant, Sarah Carey, and I wanted to
make something a little different, and first considered baking
vegetable breads. But then I started to think about biscuits. By
Barbara Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
