<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7029 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-20 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT CASE IS ONE THE GOVERNMENT CANNOT AFFORD TO LOSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ?????  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The case against Microsoft Corp., which began Monday, is a rare
specimen of a fascinating sort of drama. In all the 20th century,
only a handful of times has the government attempted to reach so
deeply into an industry as to change its structure.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns have been couched in the impersonal language of
industrial organization _ usually the argot of the antitrust laws.
But each time the target has been a system, and usually the person
who designed it.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard Oil case was one such. John D. Rockefeller and his
brilliant business manager C.T. Dodd invented the trust form of
organization in the 1870s, and within a few years they controlled
90 percent of America's oil refining capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Private suits charging monopolization succeeded in busting the
trust, so Rockefeller reorganized his interests as a holding
company. Not until 1911 did the government finally break up
Standard Oil, thus creating the quintessential oligopoly _ an
industry dominated by a few giant corporations, competing with each
other in stately fashion _ but competing.
</P>
<P>
   The one-two punch aimed at the J.P. Morgan banking interests was
another such campaign. It, too, lasted thirty years, and required
special legislation when the Sherman Antitrust Act couldn't be made
to serve.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Act of 1913 curbed Morgan's power as the
lender of last resort among American bankers by establishing the
system of 12 regional banks owned by their members and the central
bank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was followed by the Glass-Steagall Banking Act of 1933, which
established federal deposit insurance _ and, not coincidentally,
broke Moragan's bank in two by decreeing that banking and commerce
should forever after be seperate asctivities.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the DuPont family's hold on General Motors in 1956 was
a third such campaign. It proceeded on the grounds that, by selling
paint to its automotive subsidiary, the chemical giant enjoyed too
great an advantage over its competitors. Pierre S. DuPont, who had
bought control of GM, died in 1954. The leaderless family agreed to
divestiture _ in exchange for a generous tax break.
</P>
<P>
   The decision provided some discipline for conglomerates during
the merger movement of the 1950s and 1960s. Various dodges were
permitted to shelter corporate earnings _ the acquisition of
insurance companies, in particular _ but never again was vertical
integration attempted on such a giant scale.
</P>
<P>
   Two quite different cases marked the 1970s, against IBM Corp.,
the computer collosus, and American Telephone and Telegraph, a
highly regulated monopoly which was known as the Bell System.
</P>
<P>
   The cases culminated on the same remarkable day in 1982, when
the Justice Department withdrew its complaint against IBM, but
through a consent decree forced the telephone system to agree to be
broken up into competitive operating companies.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful telecommunications revolution has run its course in
the 15 years since, vindicating the government's mistrust of the
orderly system that had been devised in the 1880s to spread
telephone service across the nation. Concentration again has been
increasing rapidly among the providers of telephone service _ but
only after a binge of competition has changed the technology
practically beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Not even in the IBM case can the government be said to have
failed to achieve its purpose. The relentless badgering by the
Antitrust Division and a sympathetic judge for 13 years made the
company nervous as a cat about violatiung the law. The result was
that it contracted out for the operating system for its new
personal computer _ and signed a licensing agreement that has since
made Bill Gates the richest man in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the Microsoft case is whether Gates has used his
enormous market power to muscle in on the new businesses of others,
buying them out or competing them out of business, thus shutting
off potential avenues of innovation. The case will almost certainly
be decided by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   But the outcome is a foregone conclusion. These are cases the
government cannot afford to lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
