<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7038 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEA-IVEY-SPI &LR;      10-20 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEA-IVEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEA CHIEF UPBEAT ON ARTS FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By R.M. CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past several years, the National Endowment for the Arts
has been teetering on the brink of execution, surrounded by
enemies, deserted by friends.
</P>
<P>
   Those dark days are over, William Ivey, the agency's new
chairman, emphatically declared in a phone interview from his
office in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every conversation I've had with members of Congress,'' he
said, ``has been very positive. This is a new beginning. Votes held
on appropriation measures in both the House and Senate have been
very lopsided in favor of the NEA. We have the basis to move
forward with a budget increase for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ivey said he could not release any details until 1999,
he added he anticipated some small changes in the allocation
process to ensure that everyone has access to the endowment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the endowment's budget was slashed to 1977
levels, just below $100 million. Last fall, the House voted no
money for the endowment, although ultimately, with the Senate
behind the measure, $98 million was appropriated. This summer, the
House voted 253-173 to retain the current level of financing next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this quantum change in the political
environment, Ivey said, are several.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is strong and the budget is balanced. Supporters
of the NEA are better organized, a result of the national effort to
save the agency. It is is strong and well-organized with a staff
that is mean and lean. We have changed the way we do business.
Also, the politics of anger against the NEA haven't held up and
don't seem to be playing so well. The bipartisan center has
reasserted itself. Slade Gorton is a great example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican senator from Washington, at one time no friend to
the endowment, played a key role, as chairman of the Senate
interior appropriations subcommittee, in saving the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few months into his chairmanship, Ivey is part of the
Washington political establishment. Even some of the agency's most
vigorous opponents are shaking his hand happily. His nomination was
unanimously confirmed in late May.
</P>
<P>
   Some have speculated part of the enthusiasm in Washington
political circles for Ivey stems from his non-Eastern, non-high art
background. Born and reared in Michigan, Ivey was educated at the
University of Michigan and Indiana University. He has degrees in
history, folklore and ethnomusicology. From 1971-1998, he was
director of the Country Music Foundation in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps. One never knows. I'll turn it around. My background
in country music and folklore, my work for a real arts organization
in Middle America, preserving and studying a form of grassroots
American music, does have some appeal to members of Congress. Every
conversation I had during my confirmation indicated that my
background was seen as positive. There was concern the endowment
paid too much attention to big arts organizations with a focus on
fine arts and that it not expend 15 percent of its budget in any
one state (that is, New York), which never happened anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey has no question his some 27 years in Nashville help prepare
him to run the endowment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the first NEA chairman who had run a not-for-profit arts
organization, which has given me valuable experience of moving
forward and shaping a future in a complex economic environment.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey also has a long history of involvement with the endowment,
having chaired or served on 15 different grant panels and acted as
a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work at the foundation gave me a rare opportunity to learn
more about the power of one part of America's cultural spectrum,
which is good starting point for an examination of America's
cultural heritage. One of its great strengths is the process of
cross-fertilization. This sense of accommodation and borrowing, one
tradition to the next, to create new art forms is one of the great
energizing aspects of art in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Cultural diversity is a principal theme of Ivey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honoring our diverse traditions must be a given. We have to
look for value in each tradition. The key thing in looking at
America's cultural life is the way in which different art forms
from different sources live side by side. In our democracy, there
is the ideal that no matter where you are from, whether you are
rich or poor, your cultural heritage has standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey is very much a part of the new intellectual fashion that
holds all arts are equal, that Beethoven and the Beatles posssess
the same value to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``In each art form there runs the gamut from schlock to
excellence, but all art forms themselves are of equal value. The
NEA has to line up all the great cultural traditions on our shores
to see what is best in each tradition. It is the great challenge in
a democracy to nurture not one single culture but all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the luxury of blowing anyone off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey does not like the terms ``high'' art or ``low'' art because
they are pejorative by nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our language about culture is inadequate. Art is a
marginalized term. People say art is for someone else. It is too
easy for people to use those words and talk past one another.''
</P>
<P>
   The big challenge for the endowment in the future, he said, is
to make the case for a permanent commitment to American culture in
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much too easy for the agency to get defined in terms of
what it did instead of what it represented for society. A problem
with a grant would be converted in weeks into a discussion about
the very existence of the agency. There must the commitment to
debate issues without threatening the larger commitment. The arts
strengthen our society. They are the internal defense agency that
keeps our cultural heritage alive. If I could leave the endowment
with that kind of image in the federal government, I would be
happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-ITALY-$ADV22-     10-20 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-ITALY-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: WHAT COUNTRY IS THIS, ANYWAY?
 &HT;    With photo mug of Holmes placed in the International folder on
the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Oct. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Like shipping rice to China, coals to Newcastle, steel to
Pittsburgh .... Viagra to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra in Italy?
</P>
<P>
   What use could there be for the little blue ``love pill'' in a
country renowned for its romantic ardor and sexual prowess?
</P>
<P>
   This is the land that bred the likes of Casanova, Marcello
Mastroianni and Alberto Tomba. Trying to sell Italians on the need
for Viagra must be like trying to convince them to drive slower.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute, just below the front-page story in my Rome
newspaper about Viagra's October debut is this headline: ``Drivers
Urged To Slow Down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the country that gave us the Lamborghini and the Maserati, a
new public-service campaign wants motorists to ease off the pedal.
</P>
<P>
   Check the plane tickets, did I land in the right country?
</P>
<P>
   I did. Here's the News Flash: Italians are not great lovers, at
least not ALL of them. And they may like to drive their sleek
sports cars like the wind, but speed kills them, just as it does
Americans in their Fords and Chevys.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the facts get in the way of long-cherished
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   With no one else to hold accountable, I blame the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the coalition of countries has brought stability to the
continent, eliminating the grave worries of earlier this century --
things like the march of fascism and world wars.
</P>
<P>
   But the EU also is serving to homogenize Europe -- creating
uniform standards, open borders and, in the near future, common
banknotes and coins. Brussels is to Europe what Washington is to
America, telling them how they should live and what's good for them
and not.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, Italy becomes less Italian, needing the help
of modern science to make love and driving Ferraris at a
school-zone crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Next, they'll tell us that the French no longer find Jerry Lewis
funny.
</P>
<P>
   Yet images die hard and Italians have an abiding taste for the
good life, and not necessarily what's good for them.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey showed that only 20 percent of Italian motorists
regularly buckle up a decade after the mandatory seat-belt law was
introduced. One entrepreneur has made a small fortune manufacturing
white t-shirts printed with a black stripe running diagonally,
meeting one that runs horizontally at the bottom -- to fool police
into thinking the belt is buckled.
</P>
<P>
   Such evidence suggests that Italian motorists will not be
slowing down anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Viagra, never underestimate the power of sexual
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Health authorities say there are some five million impotent
Italians who could use the drug. But they fear there are millions
more who simply may want it as a hedge against performance anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the pressure on Italian men, who have an entire national
identity to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   A public opinion poll earlier this year found -- to the
disappointment of the Italian food company which commissioned it --
that female tourists from Europe and the United States cite hopes
of ``passion'' as their number one reason for visiting the country.
Enjoying the pasta and chianti were second place.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizio Alicico's pharmacy in downtown Rome has been flooded
with calls from men who mistakenly think the pill is an
aphrodisiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being Italians, they feel very macho. The sexual persona they
feel very much,'' Alicico says of the callers he has turned away.
``It is clear Viagra will have higher sales in Italy because of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the myth lives.
</P>
<P>
   Italy also remains firmly Italian in other arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The country resolutely lacks anything resembling a consensus on
how the place should be run. In Rome this week, they are trying to
form a new coalition government after the last one fell earlier in
the month.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 56th change of leadership since World War II, and
actually prompted some political pundits in Rome to express concern
that Italy's European partners will not take them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, Italy should be Italy, the European Union be damned.
With 40 different political parties, serial governments have become
a way of life and yet another icon of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Corriere della Sera commented: ``Heaven only knows
what new political concoction will be dreamed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Roma ... that's more like it.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
