<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED TO CUT COSTS HAVING WIDE EFFECT ON MEDICARE SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At first glance, the recent misfortunes of Sheryl
Williams, Mary Enos, Rita Blanter, and Jeffrey Otten seem to have
little in common.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 50, is an emergency room nurse who has lost her job.
</P>
<P>
   Enos, 87, a retired textile worker, is wondering how she will
pay for her medications come Jan. 1, when her insurance company
plans to slap limits on prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Blanter is coping with a 30 percent cut in the money she has to
care for her home health care agency's 200 patients.
</P>
<P>
   And Otten, a hospital president, must figure out how to take $10
million out of his budget over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   But their woes have roots in the same place, the federal
Balanced Budget Act of 1997. The law was designed to eventually
eliminate the federal deficit &UR;  &LR; and includes provisions &UR;  &LR; to cut
wasteful spending and ensure the financial viability of the federal
Medicare program for the elderly and disabled. The act cut
projected Medicare spending by $112 billion over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a year later, it is wreaking havoc in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are laying off workers. Home health agencies are
shutting down, paring back services, or turning away patients. And
Medicare health maintenance organizations are reducing benefits for
seniors or pulling out of the state altogether. All say they are
coping with lower-than-expected Medicare reimbursements, a direct
result of the budget act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is telling us how difficult it is to cut expenditures for
a program like Medicare,'' said Stuart Altman, professor of
national health policy at the Heller Graduate School at Brandeis
University. ``Critics can blithely talk about waste, but one
person's waste can be another person's vital organs.''
</P>
<P>
   The complex 1,000-plus page act has yielded some unexpected and
unpleasant consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a stealth attack on the Medicare program,'' said
Michael Miller of Health Care For All, a consumer advocacy group in
Boston. ``It flew under the radar screen and only now are we
beginning to wake up to the fact that something radical has
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, federal law did more than just cut projected
spending. It also established funds to subsidize state efforts to
provide health insurance for children. And it gave teaching
hospitals direct access to millions of dollars in teaching and
research money.
</P>
<P>
   But overall the law has caused hardship on the state's health
care providers, seniors, and disabled citizens, leaving many
scrambling to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Blanter is doing what she can to adjust to a 30 percent cut
in reimbursement from Medicare to her agency, Jewish Family &AMP;
Children's Services in Boston, where she is the director of senior
services.
</P>
<P>
   Blanter is haunted by a decision she was forced to make in
August when another agency asked whether she could take on a young
woman crippled by multiple sclerosis. The woman, who did not want
to be identified, needed help getting up in the morning, eating,
bathing, and dressing. She also needed a nurse twice a day to
change the dressing on her wounds and give her medication, as well
as physical therapy three times a week. The cost of her care
exceeded $2,000 a week, but the agency was reimbursed just $4,000 a
year from Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It was an untenable situation, and one Blanter thought her
agency could not take on. So the woman has moved into a nursing
home. It was a traumatic change for a woman who once practiced law
and has intact her full mental abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we're living with,'' Blanter said. ``I get goose
bumps thinking about her, but I can't afford to take her. It would
be financially irresponsible to our other patients.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jewish Family has been forced to cut services and turn
down patients, other agencies have simply ceased to offer home
health care. These include the Assabet Valley Home Health Agency
Inc. in Marlborough and Easter Seals of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Though Medicare cut reimbursement of home health care
nationwide, the effects in Massachusetts are particularly severe,
said Patricia Kelleher of the Home Health Care Association of
Massachusetts. That's because Medicare reduced reimbursement across
the board, so states like Massachusetts that have kept costs low
were told to cut further, while states with inflated home health
costs had more room to trim.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Massachusetts agencies received $111 million less in
1998 than in 1997. To soften the blow, Congress this week agreed to
restore $1.6 billion of the projected $16 billion in reimbursement
cuts nationwide for home health care. It also agreed to delay a
further 15 percent cut scheduled to take place Oct. 1, 1999, to
2000.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs are also getting squeezed. Aetna US Healthcare has said it
will pull out of Massachusetts and five other states on Jan. 1. The
company cited reduced Medicare payments among its reasons. The move
will force 58,000 seniors _ 17,000 in Massachusetts _ to find
another HMO.
</P>
<P>
   One of those seniors is Edward Hoffman, 88, in Hyannis. Because
he just switched from Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts
to Aetna in January, the prospect of having to change yet again
frightens him. ``To be told in September to go elsewhere was just
too much,'' said Hoffman's daughter and caretaker, Lois Boemer.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman recently switched to Secure Horizons, which is sold by
Tufts Health Plan of Waltham. But come Jan. 1, he and more than
200,000 other seniors in the state may &UR;  &LR; have to cope with yet
another change, courtesy of the Balanced Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   Several HMOs in the state, including Secure Horizons, have said
they will limit prescription drug benefits, despite a 1994 state
law requiring HMOs to offer unlimited drug coverage for seniors.
Massachusetts is the only state mandating such unlimited coverage.
HMOs argue that the budget act exempts them from the state mandate.
As a result, seniors could lose &UR;  &LR; their unlimited drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, Senator Edward M. Kennedy was trying to insert
language in the national budget in a last-minute attempt to
preserve the state mandate. Also, state officials are suing to
force HMOs to continue to offer unlimited drug coverage. The case
is pending in federal court in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mary Enos of New Bedford is already trying to figure
out how she will make ends meet if she must pay part of her drug
bills on her tiny $8,000 annual income. Enos takes eight
medications to treat multiple ailments, from glaucoma to heart
disease. ``It's going to make it difficult for everyone, not just
me,'' Enos said.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away in Stoughton, Sheryl Williams is feeling a
different kind of hurt, one resulting from the loss of her job as
an emergency room nurse at Carney Hospital. Her job is among 56
positions being eliminated at the Dorchester hospital. Again, the
budget act is to blame; Carney cited a $4 million cutback in
projected Medicare reimbursements in 1999 as its principal reason
for the layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not angry at the hospital,'' said Williams. ``They're just
doing what they have to do. But it's unsettling that this is what
health care has come to.''
</P>
<P>
   Carney isn't the only hospital cutting staff. In recent months,
St. Vincent Hospital in Worcester, St. Elizabeth's Medical Center,
Southcoast Health System in New Bedford and Fall River, North Adams
Regional Hospital, and Quincy Hospital have announced cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing hospitals and home health care agencies
instituting layoffs to a degree unseen for a few years,'' observed
David Schildmeier, spokesman for the Massachusetts Nurses
Association.
</P>
<P>
   At Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, Jeffrey Otten is
struggling to trim $10 million from the next two years' budget
projections. One-quarter of Brigham's patient care revenue comes
from Medicare, far less than the average hospital, which derives 40
percent of revenue from Medicare. Still, the cuts in projected
payments are forcing painful decisions for Otten, the hospital's
president. He has initiated a hiring freeze. The result, he knows,
will mean patients may have to wait longer to get care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to have some impact on our ability to provide
services at the level people have come to expect,'' Otten said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hollander, president of the Massachusetts Hospital
Association, voiced an opinion shared by many who have been
affected by the budget act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balanced Budget Act represents the biggest changes in
Medicare since the inception of the program,'' Hollander said.
``But it is a strictly budget-driven document. There's very little
health policy in it. There's no plan for what seniors will need and
how we will pay for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
