<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7064 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOFFA-TEAMSTERS-BOS &LR;      10-20 1851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOFFA-TEAMSTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES PHILLIP HOFFA RUNNING HARD FOR TEAMSTERS CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATICK, Mass. _ It is a rain-soaked Sunday morning when James
Phillip Hoffa strides into Amvets Post No. 79, but his undaunted
supporters are out in force, buoyed by a sense of energy and
vindication.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, son of former Teamsters president Jimmy Hoffa, &UR;  &LR; sprints
up the hall's center aisle, a husky, middle-aged former quarterback
heading for the goal line. ``We'eeere Back!'' he shouts, stopping a
few feet from the stage to slap a fan's hand.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd explodes: ``HOF-FA! HOF-FA! HOF-FA!''
</P>
<P>
   It's October, and Hoffa is on the campaign trail. &UR;  &LR; That's where
he has been ever since a fund-raising scandal invalidated the 1996
re-election of Teamsters president Ron Carey and forced a new
runoff from which Carey was barred.
</P>
<P>
   These are heady times for Hoffa, who lost to Carey in his first
bid for the presidency of the 1.4 million-member International
Brotherhood of Teamsters. With mail ballots set to go out Nov. 2
and a ballot count scheduled to begin Dec. &UR;  &LR; 3, Hoffa and challenger
Thomas W. Leedham, a union official from Oregon who represents
400,000 warehouse workers, are each vying for one of the most
powerful positions in labor.
</P>
<P>
   The 57-year-old Hoffa is running for Teamsters president amid
echoes of his father's controversial past, the taint of the recent
Teamsters election scandal, and fractious internal politics over
the union's future. Critics doubt whether the younger Hoffa, a
Detroit lawyer who didn't come up through the ranks like most union
leaders, has the political savvy and experience to lead in a modern
world where unions are struggling to make a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   It is an election that will not only transform the country's
biggest private sector union, but will likely focus attention on
the success _ or failure _ of the government's lengthy struggle to
reform what has been long regarded as a crime-ridden labor
organization. Hoffa, who was fined for his own fund-raising
irregularities in the 1996 vote, also must allay fears that his
election will return the Teamsters' old guard to power and reverse
the US labor movement's current direction.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Though described as the front-runner, Hoffa is not guaranteed
a victory. ``Right now, there is an existing organization of
reformers in the field that is far broader than many people think,
and that organization is behind Leedham,'' says Nelson
Lichtenstein, a labor historian at the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoffa has quite a few union local officials that are backing
him, and they can deliver their own locals,'' he continues. ``The
question is, `Can they deliver others?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa has strong backing from union locals in the Midwest and
has garnered support from such influential Teamsters officials as
Chuck Mack of San Francisco and Carroll Haynes, president of a
23,000-member public service local in New York. And he has
attracted some Carey defectors to his unity slate.
</P>
<P>
   Though relatively unknown, Leedham is expected to draw support
from workers in the food processing and airline industries as well
as United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   Leedham has been endorsed by Teamsters for a Democratic Union,
Carey's dissident reform wing, which says it wants to clean up the
union and increase opportunities for rank-and-file workers. But
Hoffa has the Hoffa name, a significant draw for a union in which
James P. is fondly referred to as ``Jimmy'' and ``Junior.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, James P. Hoffa is firmly entrenched in the
middle &UR;  &LR; class and has never held an elective &UR;  &LR; union office, but the
elder Hoffa's blue collar roots and hard-knuckled climb from
Detroit union boss to president of the biggest and most notorious
union &UR;  &LR; has given his son an unmistakable aura.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were John Smith, his name would go nowhere,''
acknowledges Teamsters lawyer George Geller, a Hoffa supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Hoffa contends the name and his father's background are
more important to the press than to rank-and-file Teamsters. ``It's
not about the name,'' he insists. ``People want something new. They
want their union back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa may have a point. In the Amvets hall, Teamsters dressed in
jeans and jackets with the union's logo say they want higher wages
and a stronger union. They've been battered by deregulation and the
trucking industry's increasing reliance on nonunion drivers.
They're angry about Carey's fund-raising scandal &UR;  &LR; and they think
their union is sinking fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy Hoffa isn't running on his father's name,'' says Ralph
Tobey, a Springfield trucker and a card-carrying member of the
Teamsters since 1962. ``He's running on getting the Teamsters back
to where it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds 52-year-old Dick Fredette of Local 257 in East Providence:
``We're tired of lousy contracts and givebacks.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Members join a union because they want financial security,''
Hoffa says in an interview. ``They want to retire with dignity and
with an outstanding pension.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also an underlying theme in his campaign: Us vs. Them;
blue collar vs. liberal elite. That theme dominates interviews with
Hoffa and his supporters, who clearly resent the union's liberal
reformers, or so-called new guard.
</P>
<P>
   John Murphy, the South Boston Teamsters official who dug
up &UR;  &LR; information that unraveled the Carey administration and forced
him to step down, refers to the liberals and reformers who backed
Carey as ``a cabal of the eastern liberal establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   That Teamsters reform movement helped Carey win a first term in
1991. He then won narrowly over Hoffa two years ago, but the
results were thrown out _ and Carey was barred from running in this
year's repeat electon _ after evidence emerged that nearly $1
million in union funds were diverted &UR;  &LR; to the Carey campaign. The
scandal dealt a blow to the union's reform movement, and Carey was
expelled from the union in July.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Hoffa is disdainful of Carey and the
reformers. ``They are liars. Their unholy alliance with the corrupt
Ron Carey is coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carey divided us into two camps: old guard vs. new guard. He
created a hatred among brothers and sisters. My plan is to end the
civil war and pull the union together.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked to spell out his plans to revamp the union, Hoffa
is vague. He promises to increase the union's bankrupt treasury
without hiking dues, and then shies away from revealing where the
money would come from. He is reluctant to give details, he says,
because his detractors might try to undermine or steal his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a new and innovative idea for raising $3 &UR;  &LR; million
to $5 million per year without a dues increase,'' says Hoffa.
``After I win, I'll disclose how we plan to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa also promises to rebuild the union's lobbying fund and
develop ``an innovative and aggressive interaction'' with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Hoffa adds, he will ask Congress and, if necessary,
the president, to boot the federal government out of the union's
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1989 consent settlement of racketeering charges, the
federal government agreed to monitor the union's elections to rid
it of corruption and mob ties. Under the settlement, an Independent
Review Board was set up in 1992 and charged with ongoing oversight
of the union.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa's pledge to rid the union of the feds appeals to many
rank-and-file Teamsters. Some think Carey's reforms widened
divisions within the union. Others, who lost money and power under
Carey, &UR;  &LR; object to federal oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Notes Dane Passo, the 45-year-old leader of Hoffa's campaign in
Chicago: ``We should be running our union, not the government.
Right now, our membership sees us being eaten up. We don't have
power anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Passo controlled Local 705, a powerhouse local with 18,000
members and a pension fund valued at just under $1 billion, until
he lost to a reformer earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Amvets hall, Boston Globe driver Tim Dunn of Local
259 auctions off two vintage Life magazines sporting black and
white cover photos of James Riddle Hoffa. Evoking memories of the
Teamsters' glory days, Dunn sells the two for $125 and quickly
contributes the money to the Hoffa campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he feels about the attention the Hoffa name brings,
Hoffa shrugs: ``My father was a great man. He did a lot for this
union. People haven't forgotten that, and they shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   At 57, James P. Hoffa is hardly a carbon copy of his father.
James, the younger, received a bachelor's degree in economics from
Michigan State University in 1963. His father's education ended in
the ninth grade, but he rose from a rank-and-file Teamster to union
president who helped build what was then the world's largest labor
union.
</P>
<P>
   The year his son entered the University of Michigan Law School
in 1964, the elder Hoffa was convicted on jury-tampering and
mail-fraud charges. After losing a string of appeals, he began
serving a prison sentence at Lewisburg Prison in 1967 _ the year
his son began working as an aide to members of the Michigan State
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Flamboyant and hard-driving, the elder Hoffa admitted having
dealings with the mob and reportedly stated that a labor leader
could not just stand by and allow his enemies to use the mob
against him. The junior Hoffa has denied any connections with
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Hoffa has been criticized for participating in the
1970s in &UR;  &LR; a limited partnership that invested in a real estate deal
along with Allen Dorfman, the son of a leading mobster. Hoffa says
he ended his participation &UR;  &LR; as soon as he became aware of Dorfman's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fixation on Dorfman, who died 16 years ago, is an attempt
to tie Hoffa to the controversial past of the union,'' says Geller,
the Teamsters lawyer. ``Yet the essence of Hoffa's connection with
Dorfman was that they were both passive investors in a real estate
investment trust. They did not work with each other; they didn't
cooperate with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about his youth, and Jimmy Hoffa will tell you that
union rallies and union halls were an integral part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the weekends, and he worked almost every weekend, my father
would take me down to the union hall,'' recalls Hoffa. ``We'd go
for family rides and, invariably, we would end up at the picket
line and I'd be standing near a fire barrel with men on strike. I
basically grew up at union halls.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa attended public school in Detroit, and then went on to
Michigan State, where he played football until, according to a New
York Times Magazine article, his father demanded he give it up to
concentrate on his studies.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charge Hoffa is not a real Teamster. Sensitive to the
charge, Hoffa points to legal clinics he ran at union halls and a
union trucking job he held one summer in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being president (of the Teamsters) was always in the back of
my mind,'' Hoffa says, minutes before taking the stage at the
Amvets hall. ``That's because I really love this union.''
</P>
</TEXT>
