<HEADER>
A7077 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMENTIA-CREATIVITY-H     10-20 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMENTIA-CREATIVITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAIN DISEASE MAY SPUR CREATIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ People with a form of dementia that attacks the
front parts of the brain sometimes exhibit surges of creativity
that often seem to come out of nowhere, a study released Tuesday
shows.
</P>
<P>
   A stockbroker traded in his conservative attire for vivid
fabrics and started painting precise, detailed pictures. A
53-year-old car stereo installer was fired and began painting
scenes from his New Mexico childhood. A housewife began to withdraw
socially at the same time she took up art, making realistic copies
of famous pictures and rural scenes from her past.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a degenerative brain disease began to rob them of their
ability to speak, understand words or enjoy social contact, each
turned intensely to the visual arts, in some cases creating
award-winning canvases.
</P>
<P>
   Their stories and similar ones are told by a researcher at the
University of California at San Francisco and his colleagues in
Tuesday's edition of the Journal of Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce L. Miller has been studying people with frontotemporal
dementia and found that some of his patients experienced sudden
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, the left, or more logical, side of the brain was
more affected. And the front part of the temporal lobes, which are
involved in social behavior, also suffered more damage than rear
portions. The frontal lobes, which control complex thought and
planning, were also relatively untouched.
</P>
<P>
   His work suggests that the more social aspects of ourselves may
inhibit creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it, we usually do turn off our social
brain and do creative things in solitude,'' Miller said. ``Maybe
these individuals, in a more permanent way, turned off their social
brain.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a hypothesis that jibes with anecdotal evidence about some
highly creative people.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled painter Vincent van Gogh was thought to have a form
of epilepsy that attacked the temporal lobe of the brain. The
composer Maurice Ravel also may have had a form of the brain
disease. He died while doctors tried to infuse air into the left
side of the brain, which had atrophied.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, researchers have noted that some forms of injury to
the brain cause people to lose their capacity for imagination.
Still, the links between creativity and brain circuitry are poorly
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Frontotemporal dementia, he said, is believed to affect as many
as 100,000 to 200,000 people _ about 10 percent of all dementia
cases.
</P>
<P>
   It tends to strike people in their 50s and is believed to have a
strong genetic component. Researchers have identified a gene
mutation that is thought to be at work in some cases linked to
family inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Only a fraction of the people with the disease exhibit the
creative surge that Miller described. And not everyone who had more
left-side and frontal temporal lobe damage became creative. He said
it could be that the disease, rather than causing creativity,
unlocks talents and inclinations long-hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who has been working on the disease for 10 years, first
noticed the link to creativity when the son of one of his patients
told him that his father was drawing, and that his drawings had
improved as other signs of his dementia increased. Miller asked to
see copies and was impressed with the man's talent. One of his
pictures won an art award.
</P>
<P>
   ``In neurology, we never seem to focus on the strengths of our
patients,'' Miller said. ``Now, I ask in a more systematic way
about strengths as well as weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of Miller's patients also have demonstrated other
late-in-life creative talents, including one man with no musical
background who began composing quartets. Another received a patent
on a chemical detector.
</P>
<P>
   Some had demonstrated artistic talent earlier in their lives,
and it persisted even as the dementia claimed their social and
thinking skills. In people with Alzheimer's disease, which attacks
the brain more uniformly, creative skills decline along with
memory, thinking and language.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so striking is that it begins to wrest from us our
notions about how the brain works,'' said Dan Geschwind, a
neurologist at the University of California at Los Angeles who
works on the genetics of the disease and previously has
collaborated with Miller. ``Who would imagine you'd improve in some
areas while your brain is degenerating?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the latest study, Miller focused on five people with visual
talents, the most common form of creativity he has seen. Most had
never demonstrated prior interest in art.
</P>
<P>
   Besides loosening social conventions, the disease could be
eating away at part of the brain that inhibits visual information.
Images from the retina feed into the brain from the rear, an area
that is less damaged by this type of dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said it was difficult or impossible to talk to his
patients about the changes they were going through. They usually
can't speak well or at all, and most lack self-awareness, another
characteristic of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   He also thinks many people who are chalked up as eccentric or
suffering Alzheimer's disease actually have frontotemporal
dementia.
</P>
</TEXT>
