<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NAMES PODESTA AS NEW CHIEF OF STAFF 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday named John Podesta to
replace Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles who leaves the White House
next week after two years in one of Washington's toughest jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles' departure is another sign of the staff turnover that
usually marks a president's second term, but one that comes at a
critical period with Clinton facing an impeachment inquiry by the
House Judiciary Committee next month for lying and covering up an
extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta, currently Bowles' deputy, also is the chief staff
member coordinating Clinton's defense of impeachment allegations
before the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``As many of you know, he and his family have a taste for riding
roller coasters. That will certainly serve him well here,'' Clinton
said during a sunny Rose Garden ceremony to introduce Podesta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is brilliant. He has a tough hide, a dry wit, a lot of
patience in dealing with the president, hard-won wisdom and a
genuine compassion for improving this nation,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles, a North Carolina businessman, helped broker the 1997
balanced budget agreement that ended decades of red ink and, most
recently, negotiated the budget deal that is allowing Congress to
adjourn this week. Bowles will return to his home state where he is
expected to run for governor in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Bowles a ``gifted manager and an inspiring
leader, the world's best negotiator and a great personal friend.''
Podesta will be Clinton's fourth chief of staff in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Also leaving in recent weeks was Rahm Emanuel, Clinton's senior
policy adviser, who will return to his hometown of Chicago. In the
running to replace Emanuel is Houston native and longtime aide Paul
Begala.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, Clinton's press secretary, left earlier this month
and was replaced by Joe Lockhart. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
