<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-SURVEY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLL BACKS DELAYING BABY BELLS' ENTRY INTO LONG-DISTANCE MARKETS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly two-thirds of telecommunications experts say
regulators are on the right track by denying regional telephone
companies access to long-distance markets unless they do more to
open local markets, according to a survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan survey, conducted by the Democratic-affiliated
Peter D. Hart Research Associates and the Republican-affiliated
Tarrance Group, was sponsored by the Washington-based Small
Business Survival Committee, a non-profit group representing 48,000
companies, including small telecom firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been question and confusion about why there's still no
choice at the local level,'' said Karen Kerrigan, president of
Small Business Survival. ``From this survey, we see most people
think we're headed in the right direction, but it's going to take
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of respondents to the poll agreed with the
Federal Communications Commission's recent decisions to turn down
local phone companies' applications to move into long-distance
because they hadn't done enough to open their own markets.
</P>
<P>
   While 68 percent of respondents ranked implementing the 1996
Telecommunications Act to encourage competition in local phone
service as extremely important, only 36 percent said amending the
act to make it easier for local ``Baby Bell'' companies to move
into long-distance service was important.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very comfortable with this act, and they don't want
to open it up again,'' Hart said. ``But they realize it's going to
take time to implement.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bolger, vice president of communications for the United
States Telephone Association, criticized the survey for being too
selective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that there is competition at the local level, and
the regional Bells are opening their markets to competition,'' he
said. ``The problem is that there are some serious flaws with this
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Other key findings of the poll include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sixty percent of respondents said the Telecommunications Act
provides the right framework for introducing competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only 10 percent of the opinion leaders said they believed
local phone companies would be allowed into long-distance this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The polling firms interviewed 250 top telecom experts, including
congressional staff members, state legislators and regional telecom
experts, between Sept. 23 and Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
