<P>
   REACT _ In fending off questions about the safety of downtown
Atlanta, Mayor Bill Campbell said Monday, ``Interestingly enough,
there were tens of thousands of people in downtown for the Saints
game with the Falcons, or just coming to enjoy a pleasant weekend
in Atlanta. I don't think any of them saw or heard, or felt unsafe
while they were here. This tragedy is, I think, an individual act
that must be seen in that context.'' Maybe some of those thousands
coming for the next Falcons game will feel a bit more unsafe now
that it turns out three men who came to town for the Falcons game
were shot in the head. Following reaction of downtown businesses
and hotel industry. (Charles/Campos, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STATEHOUSE _ Amid this lackluster year for federal campaigns,
the most aggressive and hard-fought battles are being waged in
state Capitols around the nation, particularly in the South.
Republicans and Democrats are battling for control of legislative
chambers from North Carolina to Georgia to Texas. The fierce
competition is an extension of the transformation that swept
Congress in the early 1990s, when Republicans gained control of
most of the Congressional delegations in the South. The off year
elections unfold in the shadow of the 2000 census, making
statehouse races _ and the 36 governors' races _ especially
important since the ground is being laid for the 2001
reapportionment. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constiution). 30. WITH
MAP (showing majority in southern state legislatures).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA _ After more than a decade, three state officials will
decide Thursday whether to grant an operating permit for a
low-level nuclear waste disposal site near the tiny town of Sierra
Blanca in West Texas. What factors will the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission consider in making its decision? Story will
pay particular attention to the geology of the site and the
socioeconomics of the region, two objections raised by
administrative law judges in their recommendation to deny the
permit. What's at stake? How did we get to the point, and what's
the next step? (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-QA _ Answers to commonly asked questions about the
low-level waste facility. (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-TRANS _ Although Sierra Blanca is a remote site, people
all across the state worry about the routes that will be used to
truck low-level radioactive waste to West Texas. What are the
transportation plans? What's the track record on hauling low-level
waste? (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-STATES _ Three other facilities currently accept
low-level waste, and several others have been closed. What's their
track record? (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   LAND-COMMISH _ The race for Texas Land Commissioner has seemed
to be about houses. Yes, houses. At times in recent weeks, it has
seemed, David Dewhurst and Richard Raymond are battling a race
against obscurity for an obscure job, as much as anything. For
without the bickering reminiscent of the old-time, name-calling
contests that years ago were an election-year staple in Texas, both
campaigns concede that voters would probably have paid far less
attention to who will be the state's 27th land commissioner, a job
created 161 years ago when Texas was still a republic. Here's a
look at the two men who want the job. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
