<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGETABLE-BISCUITS-2T     10-20 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETABLE-BISCUITS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING BISCUITS FROM A GARDEN BOUNTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARBARA KAFKA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baskets full of end-of-season bounty from the garden left me
with a delightful problem: how to make the most of it? My
assistant, Sarah Carey, and I wanted to make something a little
different, and first considered baking vegetable breads. But then I
started to think about biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the sweet-potato biscuits that have long been a
tradition in the American South, I had never really eaten vegetable
biscuits or seen recipes for them, so I began to get excited about
creating new ones.
</P>
<P>
   A few of our experiments failed, and we had to play around with
temperature, with the proportion and kind of fat, and with the
timings. We finally came upon techniques that work (and that are
easy for anyone to follow) and that result in beautiful, delicious
biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   We made beautiful ruby red beet biscuits, bright green sweet pea
biscuits and for a special treat, banana biscuits. I don't expect
anybody to make all of these biscuits at once, but the array of
colors is smashing, and arranged together on a platter they would
make a spectacular addition to a buffet.
</P>
<P>
   With any of these, a bit of leftover puree can be creamed with a
little butter and some seasonings and spread on the hot split
biscuits. All would be good with chowders and vegetable soups.
</P>
<P>
   The beet biscuits are slightly denser than the other two, and do
not rise as high.
</P>
<P>
   With the pea biscuits, using frozen peas works just fine. The
banana biscuits, when made in the smaller, two-inch-diameter size,
would be good served with curries or with the chicken and peanut
butter soup that is popular at Kwaanza celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   In the larger three-and-one-quarter-inch size, they make a
lovely base for a banana short cake; split the biscuits and slather
them with a combination of sliced bananas and whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Now for our baking tips: In the recipes here, pureed vegetables
or fruit serve to partially replace the flour and the liquid in
regular biscuit recipes. As these semi- or non-starchy purees have
no gluten, the stretchy protein that develops when dough is
kneaded, it is better to use all-purpose flour, which develops more
gluten, than the softer cake flour normally used for biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Although expert bakers _ or seasoned biscuits makers _ might be
able to whip these up effortlessly to achieve a flaky result, those
of us who are less practiced should keep in mind that it is
important to keep the butter cold by working quickly; after adding
the butter to the flour, place it in the freezer for 10 to 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And once the dough and vegetable puree are combined, the dough
should be kneaded lightly on a flour-dusted surface. The kneading
wakes up the gluten. The dough should be patted out rather than
rolled, as one might have to add too much flour to roll it, making
the biscuits heavy and cakey.
</P>
<P>
   The dough can be patted out and cut ahead of time, then
refrigerated until just before baking. If the biscuits are
refrigerated, especially if they are baked on a cold tray, they
will take slightly longer.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional baking pans are shiny and reflect a lot of heat at
the bottom of the biscuit, which can easily over-brown.
Alternatives are black pans or the air-cushioned sheets often
recommended for cookies, which result in more even baking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   BEET BISCUITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 small beets (two-thirds pound), scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   \ cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) cold unsalted butter, cut into \-inch
cubes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan, cover beets with water by 2 inches.
Bring to a boil, lower heat and simmer for 30 to 45 minutes, or
until tender. Add water as necessary to keep beets covered. Remove
from water and cool until easy to touch. Rub off the skins and cut
beets in quarters. In a food processor, puree beets; there should
be 1 cup puree. Whisk in the buttermilk.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a rack in center of oven and preheat oven to 450
degrees. In a medium mixing bowl, sift dry ingredients. Cut in the
butter; the largest pieces should be the size of small peas. Place
bowl in freezer or refrigerator until butter is hard, 10 to 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Scrape beet puree into flour mixture and stir with a wooden
spoon, just until the dough comes together around the spoon. This
will be a very moist sticky dough; there should be whole pieces of
butter visible in the dough.
</P>
<P>
   4. Turn dough out onto a well-floured surface. Knead about 10 to
15 times, until smooth, incorporating enough flour so that dough no
longer sticks. Keep board well floured.
</P>
<P>
   5. Pat dough out {-inch thick. Cut into 2-inch rounds. Gather up
scraps of dough and gently press them together, and cut again.
Place on an ungreased air-cushioned cookie sheet or a heavy sheet
pan, preferably black. Bake for 13 to 15 minutes, or until cooked
through. Remove from oven. Let sit for a few minutes, then serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 16 biscuits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BANANA BISCUITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 medium bananas, peeled
</P>
<P>
   \ cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) cold unsalted butter, cut into \-inch
cubes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a blender, puree bananas with buttermilk; there should be
1\ cups.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat oven to 450 degrees. In a medium mixing bowl, sift
together the dry ingredients. Cut in the butter; the largest pieces
should be the size of small peas. Place in freezer or refrigerator
until butter is hard, 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Scrape banana puree into the flour mixture and stir with a
wooden spoon, just until the dough comes together around the spoon.
There should be whole pieces of butter visible in the dough.
</P>
<P>
   4. Turn dough out onto a well-floured surface. Knead 10 to 15
times, until smooth. Keep board well floured so that the dough
doesn't stick. Pat the dough out {-inch thick. Cut into 2-inch or
3\-inch rounds. Gather up scraps and press them together to be cut
again. Place on heavy ungreased sheet pan, preferably black, or an
air-cushioned cookie sheet. Bake 12 to 15 minutes for small, 13 to
16 minutes for large, or until top browns and biscuit is cooked
through.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 16 small or 4 to 5 large biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   PEA BISCUITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 10-once package frozen tiny peas, defrosted in a sieve under
warm running water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons (1 stick) cold unsalted butter, cut into \-inch
cubes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a blender, puree peas with milk. There should be 1\ cups.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a rack in the middle of the oven and heat oven to 450
degrees. In a medium mixing bowl, sift together the dry
ingredients. Cut in the butter; the largest pieces should be the
size of small peas. Place bowl in freezer or refrigerate until the
butter is hard, 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Scrape pea puree into the flour mixture and stir with a
wooden spoon, just until the dough comes together around the spoon.
There should be whole pieces of butter visible in the dough.
</P>
<P>
   4. Turn dough out onto a well-floured surface. Knead 10 to 15
times, until smooth. Keep board well floured so that the dough does
not stick.
</P>
<P>
   5. Pat dough out {-inch thick. Cut into 2-inch rounds. Gather up
scraps and press together to be cut again. Place on heavy ungreased
sheet pan, preferably black, or an air-cushioned cookie sheet. Bake
for 12 to 15 minutes, until the top browns and the biscuits are
cooked through.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 16 biscuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
