</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH'S AMON CARTER MUSEUM TO BE REBUILT TO EXAND SPACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Most of Fort Worth's Amon Carter Museum will
be replaced by a new structure that will triple exhibition space
and will more dramatically showcase the Carter's superb collection
of American art, museum President Ruth Carter Stevenson announced
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal must be approved by the museum's board of trustees
at its meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, only the original 1961 memorial to business
leader and newspaper publisher Amon G. Carter Sr., with its
commanding plaza and view of the downtown skyline, would remain.
</P>
<P>
   The new building _ approximately 107,000 square feet with 27,000
square feet of gallery space _ has been designed by New York
architect Philip Johnson, working with partner Alan Ritchie.
Johnson also designed the 1961 structure and both additions, which
include a total of about 9,000 square feet of gallery space.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials haven't estimated the cost. Plans for
fund-raising and groundbreaking, and a completion date probably
won't be determined until trustees meet again in April.
</P>
<P>
   Originally designed to house Amon Carter's collection of
artworks by Frederic Remington and Charles Russell, the Carter
almost immediately began evolving into a museum of American art,
spanning the mid-19th century to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes iconic paintings by Georgia O'Keeffe,
Thomas Eakins and Stuart Davis, as well as an internationally known
photography collection and important prints, drawings and modernist
sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter's announcement comes at a time when officials of the
neighboring Modern Art Museum are refining plans for a new
building, scheduled for completion in 2002. Also, the Kimbell Art
Museum is awaiting arrival of its new director, Timothy Potts, who
is expected to develop a master plan for that museum's expansion on
adjacent property in the Cultural District.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, completion of all three projects would result in a
sequence of museum buildings in a parklike setting west of downtown
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson made her announcement to family, friends and museum
patrons gathered Monday night at the Carter for a celebration of
her 75th birthday. She characterized Johnson's plan as a birthday
gift.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson has been president of the museum since it opened and
has been instrumental in its development. Johnson, too, has a long
history with the Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started out to be a small museum,'' Stevenson said. ``My
brother Amon and I thought it would be Dad's best memorial. But
somehow the collection began to grow, and we became a museum of
American art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's obvious that this is what we need, and we're lucky to
have the man who started it around to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad always used to say, `Let him dig the potatoes who planted
'em, cause he knows where they're at,'' she said during an earlier
interview, with a mischievous glance at Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he conceived the 1961 building as a monument to
Amon Carter, not as a great art center. The new building will
finally give the Carter the exhibition space it has so long needed,
including 5,330 square feet of galleries for special exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Galleries with strictly controlled light levels will be devoted
to works on paper and photography. Only the George Eastman House in
Rochester, N.Y., and the Museum of Modern Art in New York have as
much space for displaying photographs.
</P>
<P>
   A new auditorium, lab space for a paper conservation program, a
new library and bookstore, and cold storage for photographs will
also be housed in the new structure.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 1961 building, its ground floor will be devoted to
Amon Carter's collection of Remington and Russell paintings,
bronzes and sketches; the mezzanine galleries will house the
museum's collection of art of the American West. The museum
carpenter shop and book storage were moved off-site a couple of
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to expand the museum were first discussed in 1992-93,
during Jan Keene Muhlert's tenure as director. The idea then was
simply to add modest pockets of space without significantly
altering the structure.
</P>
<P>
   But when Rick Stewart was appointed director in 1995, he
proposed that space requirements be researched and analyzed. After
two years of study, a new architectural program was forwarded to
Johnson. In April, Johnson proposed that the addition be clad in a
dark stone that would set off the 1961 building.
</P>
<P>
   From demolition to inauguration, the project would take almost
two years. Stewart said he didn't know whether the 1961 structure
would have to be closed during construction. If so, he said: ``We
will talk with the board in November about how we can maintain some
sort of exhibition presence. We don't want to just go away for 24
months.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
