<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ Prospects for a negotiated
settlement in the Middle East remain uncertain as Clinton cancels a
two-day campaign swing in California to keep pushing Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
Jordan's King Hussein also joins the talks at a conference center
in eastern Maryland. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ The House is poised to approve a
huge spending package that would conclude the business of the
current Congress, just two weeks before the election. The Senate is
likely to approve the $500 billion in spending _ the product of
arduous negotiations between Congress and the White House _ on
Wednesday. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STAFF (Washington) _ President Clinton names John
Podesta, a deputy to Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles, to replace
Bowles. The departure of Clinton's longtime friend is a sign of the
staff turnover that usually marks a president's second term, but
one that comes at a critical time for the White House. By NANCY
MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PEANUTS (Washington) _ Peanut lovers are about to win a major
victory as Congress prepares to cancel a government directive
limiting peanuts on airplanes. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GLENN (Washington) _ President Clinton plans to go to
Cape Canaveral, Fla., next Thursday to watch the scheduled launch
of space shuttle Discovery, which will ferry Sen. John Glenn, the
fabled Mercury astronaut, into space. By JOHN DRAKE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-FLOOD (Undated) _ The rain is relenting, but rivers are
still cresting in a flood that may be the state's most widespread
ever. Sixty Texas counties are flooded and that number is expected
to grow, and at least 20 people are confirmed dead. The flooding
comes on top of the worst drought in decades and other brutal
floods that hit South Texas over the summer. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIAN-SPAT (Houston) _ Olympic gymnast Dominique Moceanu, 17,
has filed a lawsuit asking to be certified as an adult because her
parents' financial mismanagement has allegedly left her broke. The
gold-medal hopeful says she has been a professional since age 10
and has earned ``substantial sums of money'' that are apparently
lost. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CONTROVERSY (Houston) _ A 27-year-old Louisiana woman
awaiting a heart transplant received an abortion in Houston after
being denied the procedure in her home state, where a law prohibits
the use of public funds for abortions. By RUTH SoRELLE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-HOTLIST (Undated) _ Want to use the Web to keep up
with the twists and turns in the Microsoft trial? Hotlist offers
the best sites for antitrust watchers. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMIC-OPTIMISM (Paris) _ For decades, economists said another
Great Depression was impossible because of protective measures that
nations had taken to tame financial speculation and keep trade
flowing in tough times. Last year, with financial panic in Asia,
fears of economic collapse revived, but now analysts are swinging
back to their earlier optimism. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS (Hebron, West Bank) _ Salem Rajab Sarsour
doesn't fit the typical profile of a Palestinian likely to stage an
attack against Israel. The man who reportedly confessed to Monday's
grenade attack at a crowded bus stop is the father of five, had
steady work and did not live in a refugee camp. But Palestinian
security agents say he is a well-known Israeli collaborator and
maybe a double agent. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) - The down-to-the-wire congressional
battle over including prescription contraceptives in civilian
federal employee heath insurance plans shows that the old gender
double standard is alive and well. Women finally won but were
nearly denied this health benefit at a time when Congress is
rushing to spend $50 million on Viagra prescriptions. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-SERIES (San Diego) _ Coverage of Game 3 of the World
Series, where the New York Yankees will send big-game specialist
David Cone to the mound in an effort to take a 3-0 lead over the
San Diego Padres. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
