<HEADLINE>
FANTASIES AND GHOSTS AND WITCHES ALL CLOSE AT HAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will they return? The Alien Supremes at last year's Fantasy Fest
in Key West. The fun begins Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a haunting thought: If you're after some frightening
times, Massachusetts is the place to be. And we're only noting a
few of the haunted happenings in the Bay State. But just in case
you're looking for more ghosts and witches, we've found a few
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Home to the spirits of Halloween is Salem on Boston's North
Shore, which earned its reputation in 1692, when the town was rife
with witch hysteria. Hundreds of people were accused by friends and
family of practicing witchcraft, and several were killed for their
alleged crime.
</P>
<P>
   Salem offers Haunted Happenings, a three-week celebration of the
ancient tradition in which the town is transformed into a veritable
hotbed of horror. The happenings include a Monster Bash, a costumed
dog show, haunted houses, the Hall of Illusions, and more. On
Halloween there's a festival of food, dancing, and shopping. For
Haunted Happenings information, call 800-298-2929. Salem is home to
the Witch Dungeon Museum, the Salem Wax Museum of Witches and
Seafarers, and the Salem Witch Museum, which are all open all year.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, there's Spooky World (508-838-0200), which is known
to send a chill up a few spines with its three haunted houses,
haunted hay-ride, horror musum, and celebrity hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Deerfield's annual Supernatural Sunday celebration
takes place in the 300-year-old Western Massachusetts village on
Oct. 25. This is a family event highlighting the myths, legends,
and history of Halloween, and the afternoon program is appropriate
for visitors 6 and older. There will be magic, music, storytelling,
a ghost walk of Old Deerfield, and a special program in the Andrews
Planetarium at Deerfield Academy. The event is included in the
general admission to Historic Deerfield. For information, call
413-774-5581.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you'd like to join in a ghostly tour of Boston's famed
Freedom Trail. On Thursdays through Saturdays, Oct. 22-25 and Oct.
29-Nov. 1, the Freedom Trail players will tell tales of the
revolutionary patriots as they lead you by lantern light to the
Granary Buring Grounds. The tours, from 5:30 p.m. to 7 p.m., meet
at King's Chapel and are $10 for adults, $6 for children under 10,
and $7 for students and seniors. Tickets are on sale at the Boston
Globe Store (617-367-4000) and the Visitor Center on the Boston
Common. For information, call 617-227-8800.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 31, you can take a guided tour of Boston's Beacon Hill
that highlights its rich heritage of mystery and suspense. Sites
include the home where George Parkman was murdered, Boston Common
where Quakers were hanged, stops on the Underground Railway, and
more. For information, call 617-367-2345.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the state, Plymouth Colonial Lantern Tours, Oct.
16-30, will feature walks on Plymouth's darker, more macabre past.
The tour ends up at Burial Hill, to enhance the Halloween spirit.
On Martha's Vineyard, the Haunted Playhouse runs Oct. 29-31 in
Vineyard Haven, and a Happy Haunting Weekend will brew up some
spirits in Edgartown on Oct. 30-31.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 25 in Lowell's Tsongas Arena, Olympic medalist Nancy
Kerrigan will lead an all-star cast of skaters as they perform in
full Halloween costume to macabre music inspired by the day.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, a Latino tradition honors the dead with altars
and memorials throughout the city. The Day of the Dead celebration
is just one the city's Halloween treats. In addition, you could
catch Bram Stoker's ``Dracula'' on stage, join the Halloween
Spooktacular at SeaWorld or the Fright Fest at Six Flags Fiesta
Texas, catch the Coffins on Parade on the famed River Walk, or join
in a Zoo Boo at the zoo. For information, call the San Antonio
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at 800-447-3372.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, St. Augustine has reportedly been home to ghostly
visitors for hundreds of years. This year, a family celebration,
Old Haunts in the Old City, takes place Oct. 30 and 31 from 6 to 10
p.m. Admission is $20.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Universal Studios Florida in Orlando, hundreds of
Universal horror experts have been working nearly a year creating
``Halloween Horror Nights VIII: Primal Scream.'' The chills opened
Oct. 3 and continue Oct. 21-25 and 27-31. For information, call
407-22-HORROR.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 20th anniversary of Fantasy Fest, Key West's annual
10-day (Oct. 23-Nov. 1) outrageous masking and costuming festival.
This year's theme is ``Fright Night on Bone Island'' (Spanish
explorers originally named Key West ``Cayo Hueso'' or ``Island of
Bones'' after finding skeletal remains of Indians). There will be
parties, parades, street fairs, and masquerade balls. The big day
is Oct. 31, when the spectacular Coors Light Fantasy Fest Parade
steps off at 7 p.m. For information, call 800-LAST KEY.
</P>
<P>
   If you want your chills at sea, the Big Red Boat is offering a
haunted ship cruise Oct. 30 from Port Canaveral to the Bahamas.
Everything from a psychic fair to trick-or-treating will take place
on the three-night journey. For information, call Premier Cruises
at 800-990-7770.
</P>
<P>
   Or, how about a haunted ``L'' train? In Chicago, ghosts and
storytellers ride the L around the Loop every Saturday afternoon.
It's a great way to learn about some of Chicago's most famous
unseen residents, and it's free. Tickets are available at the
Visitor Information Center in the Chicago Cultural Center. For
information, call 312-744-2400.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Destination Europe is offering a $257 round-trip fare on
American Airlines to London from Boston or New York from Nov. 1 to
March 31. Travel on Dec. 12-24 is excluded. Destination Europe,
based in Portland, Maine, accepts last-minute bookings, and can
offer hotels in England from $54 a person per night as well as
rental cars starting at $189 a week. For information, call
800-835-1555.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Tucson feast is featured at Martha's Herbary, which Travel &AMP;
Leisure describes as ``the Caprilands of the nineties,
sophisticated, breezy and fun.'' The two-night package at $199 a
person includes accommodations, the meal, and cooking lessons from
Martha Paul in her kitchen. The package is offered Nov. 6, 7, 13,
and 14. For information, call 860-0009.
</P>
<P>
   A great getaway is offered at the Four Columns Inn in Newfane,
Vt., From Nov. 1 through Dec. 23. This classic inn offers a
two-night ``Celebrate the Season'' package, with accommodations and
a gourmet dinner in its four-diamond fireplaced dining room. Chef
Greg Parks, now in his 22d year at the inn, features Asian flavors
with fresh Vermont-raised products. The package includes shopping
discounts and a welcome basket filled with Vermont-made specialty
products. For information, call 800-787-6633. Packages begin at
$340 a couple.
</P>
<P>
   An Angler's Paradise package is being offered midweek at the
White Barn Inn in Kennebunkport, Maine. The package, in conjunction
with The Northeast Angler, offers two nights' accommodations,
dinner, breakfast daily, a four-hour fly-fishing lesson by a
licensed instructor, and all fishing gear. The package is $712. For
information, call 207-967-2321.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The people of Keene, N.H., are out to beat themselves at the old
pumpkin game. The town already holds the Guinness World Record of
``13,432 Jack-o'-Lanterns in One Place at One Time.'' On Oct. 24,
Keene is out to top its record with a day of fun activities. There
will be a parade, street vendors, food, performers, costumes,
trick-or-treating from 10 a.m.; at 4 p.m., the pumpkins will begin
flickering, and at 6 p.m. the official count begins. This all began
modestly with 600 pumpkins in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Room, the legendary New York symbol of glamour and
sophistication, is closing. For 66 years, visitors have dined,
danced, and romanced in the room atop the Rockefeller Center. The
BE Restaurant Group has decided not to renew its lease for the
space in 1999, but rather move on to new restaurant development and
operations. The Rainbow Room will close on Dec. 19. So you have
only a few weeks to enjoy the creation of Joe Baum and David Emil,
the food of Chef Waldy Malouf, and the cocktail creations of Dale
DeGroff, the entertainment, and the views.
</P>
</TEXT>
