<HEADLINE>
SPOOKY THINGS CAN HAPPEN WHILE TRAVELING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's Silly Travel Photo features Ken MacDermid getting
into the Halloween spirt during a tour of the Budweiser brewery in
St. Louis. MacDermid is formerly of Brookline and Milford and now
of Fort Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Kate Morgan had checked into Room 3502 of the
Hotel del Coronado in Coronado, Calif., to meet with her estranged
husband. But he never showed, and several days later Kate's body
was found on the hotel steps. That occurred in 1892, yet today
people who stay in Room 3502 sometimes report odd noises, spirited
breezes, strange faces, and the ghostly figure of a young woman in
a black dress. Kate, perhaps, is still waiting for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just one example of people from the past refusing to
leave one of the Historic Hotels of America, a collection of more
than 125 historically significant lodging places. Halloween is
approaching, so let's tell some more tales:
</P>
<P>
   _When studying in Europe in the 1890s, Thomas Rowe met the love
of his life, a young woman named Lucinda, whom he would meet by a
fountain. But her parents forbade their relationship, and a
downcast Rowe returned to America. In 1925, he included a replica
of that fountain when he built the Don CeSar Beach Resort and Spa
in St. Petersburg Beach, Fla. And although the fountain no longer
exists, hotel employees still tell of seeing a couple walking hand
in hand into the hotel and suddenly vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   _As a welcome respite from the heat of Washington, D.C., Mary
Todd Lincoln and her children spent two summers at the Equinox in
Manchester Village, Vt. But their plans to return in 1865 were
changed after the assassination of Abraham Lincoln. Today, hotel
workers report seeing images of a woman and child on the third
floor that are consistent with descriptions of Mary Lincoln and one
of her sons. Are mother and child trying to recapture their
carefree days before the tragedy?
</P>
<P>
   _Guests in one room at Georgia's Jekyll Island Club Hotel
sometimes find that their coffee appears to have been sipped and
their newspaper read. It's the room that was used by Samuel Spenser
when he stayed at the exclusive hunt club, and he would always sip
a cup of coffee while scanning the Wall Street Journal. Maybe he's
still doing so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  Where will you find the Kalahari Desert?
(Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In a name: &LR;  You've probably heard of the term ``bumped,'' which
means you've lost your seat on an airplane because of overbooking.
When you lose your hotel room, however, the hotel people say you've
been ``walked.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In a phrase:  &LR; The term ``Seven Wonders of the World'' was
created in the second century BC by tourism companies hoping to
attract customers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  Ad for a hotel in Spain:
``The provision of a large French widow in every room adds to
visitors' comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``Never mind the fun in the sun: I want to slouch on
a couch!'' _ William Bendix as a vacationing Chester A. Riley in a
1951 ``Life of Riley'' radio broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vroom: &LR;  Salt Lake City has more households (37 percent) owning
three or more vehicles than any other US city.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Museum of the month: &LR;  At the newly opened Kellogg's Cereal City
in Battle Creek, Mich., you can create your own box of cereal with
your face on the front, tour a simulated factory production line,
and even meet Captain Kangaroo. After all, who among us hasn't sat
down at the breakfast table with a bowl of cereal, read the back of
the box, and dug in to find the premium! Admission is $6.50 for
adults, $5.50 for seniors, $4.50 for children 3-12, and free for
those 2 and younger. The theme for weekends this month is ``A
Bowlful of Fright.'' For more information, call 616-962-6230.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Snappy slogan: &LR;  One of the lounges at the Mount Washington
Hotel in Bretton Woods, N.H., is called The Cave because of its
narrow entrance and stone walls. But a sign outside advises, ``No
Miners in The Cave (must be 21).''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Advice to go: &LR;  Airlines often have weekly fare specials on the
Internet; they're espcially helpful if you can make weekend plans
on the spur of the moment. Here are the Web addresses of some
airlines that offer on-line specials: American Airlines,
www.americanair.com; &QC; 
America West, www.americawest.com; Carnival, www. &QC; 
carnivalair.com; Continental, www.flycontinental.com; Northwest,
www.nwa.com; US Airways; www.usair.com. Or you might check out
www.smarterliving.com, which each Wednesday will e-mail you for
free the airlines' weekend specials, or the listings at
www.boston.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  The Kalahari Desert is in Botswana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Tidbits is compiled from wire-service reports, news
releases, books, magazines, and the deepest recesses of the
author's mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits,
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to
carpenter(AT)globe.com. Include your name and community.
</P>
</TEXT>
