<HEADLINE>
STEAM-POWERED PADDLEWHEELERS SOON TO APPEAR ALONG ATLANTIC COAST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A familiar look for new vessels
</P>
<P>
   A new line of coastal ships will include Boston and other New
England ports as a major part of planned itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta Queen Steamboat Co., America's oldest cruise company
that currently operates authentic, steam-powered paddlewheelers
along waterways in the heartland of America, will soon take another
chapter out of shipping history and replicate coastal ships such as
those of the once-famed Fall River Line that provided service
between Boston and New York. That company was known as ``the only
way to travel'' between 1847 and 1937.
</P>
<P>
   The new vessels will be even grander, more comfortable, and will
be state-of-the-art diesel-driven vessels with period furnishings,
luxurious amenities, and the latest in safety technology. Each of
the planned five coastal ships will accommodate 226 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-foot-long vessels will have 114 staterooms with 101
outside. There will also be two single-occupancy and two
wheelchair-accessible staterooms.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts for the first two vessels are expected to be signed
Nov. 12, said Scott Young, president of the line, at a recent
meeting in Boston. The vessels are expected to cost between $30
million and $35 million each. Launch of the first ship is set for
June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Young said the company will offer eight-day, seven-night cruises
from Portland to Boston and 10-day, nine-night cruises from Boston
to New York City. Other Eastern ports where the vacations will
begin or end include Halifax, Nova Scotia; Philadelphia; Baltimore;
Washington; Norfolk; Jacksonville; and Miami. Itineraries are also
being developed for the Pacific Northwest and northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vacations will be heavily destination-oriented, and shore
excursions will bring passengers to some of America's most historic
and beautiful places,'' said Young. The new cruises will
``capitalize on Delta Queen's reputation for showcasing the
history, heritage, and magnificent scenery that abounds across our
country,'' Young added.
</P>
<P>
   The new vessels will join the Delta Queen Steamboat Company's
existing fleet: the National Historic Landmark Delta Queen, the
Mississippi Queen, and the American Queen, the world's largest
steamboat. The paddlewheelers offer three- to 14-night cruises on
10 inland American waterways. These boats are ``enjoying an annual
occupancy of 91 percent, repeat passenger counts of up to 37
percent, and we have successfully absorbed a 74 percent increase in
capacity since the American Queen's launch in 1995,'' said Russel
Varvel, vice president of sales for the line.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of models and memorabilia on the Fall River Line
can be seen at the Marine Museum near Battleship Cove in Fall
River. The museum also has a 28-foot model of the Titanic built for
a 1952 movie. For information, call 508-674-3533.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise catalog
</P>
<P>
   Magellan's, which has been supplying travel needs for vacations
around the world, is now offering a catalog devoted just to cruise
needs. You name it _ suntan, garment bags, seasickness treatments,
and more _ can be found within its pages. Each item comes with a
detailed explanation of the benefits for the cruise traveler. For a
free copy, call 800-962-4943.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
