<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 25) 
(JT) 
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Learning German in Zurich &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in Zurich in the first half of 1999 and would like
to learn German there. Where can I take German lessons in or near
the city? _ Maryann Schultz, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since Switzerland has three official languages _ German,
French and Italian _ it is a great place to improve one's fluency.
So much so that each year, Switzerland Tourism, 608 Fifth Ave., New
York, N.Y. 10020, (212) 757-5944, publishes the booklet ``Language
Courses in Switzerland.'' While the courses it lists are aimed at
teen-agers, there are at least a few schools in Zurich that serve
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The best known is probably Berlitz Language Schools, which has
two branches in Zurich, including one at 7 Seefeldstrasse, 8008
Zurich, (41-1) 261-6807, fax (41-1) 261-9304. Sabina Graf, the
assistant manager there, said the courses are open-ended and
offered from two to five times a week. Price depends on the number
of students: about $13 a lesson for classes of five to eight
students, to about $35 for classes of two students.
</P>
<P>
   You can sign up for classes before leaving the United States.
For details, contact Lorenzo Diaz at the Berlitz office at 40 West
51st St., New York, N.Y. 10020; (212) 765-1001, extension 638.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice might be Klub-schule Migros Zurich, Oerlikon
Center, 305 Hofwiesenstrasse, 8050 Zurich; (41-1) 311-5088, fax
(41-1) 311-5030. This school offers an intensive approach _ four
hours a day for a month _ with sessions starting every month. It
offers courses at 12 levels of fluency. The cost is about $510 a
month. English-speaking students should ask for Jacqueline
Assaintrangir.
</P>
<P>
   A third option is the Alpha Sprachstudio, 10 Stadelhoferstrasse,
8024 Zurich; (41-1) 252-4994, fax (41-1) 262-3706. This school has
been around since 1975 and offers courses on 12 levels, from twice
a week to a half-day daily. Intensive courses start each month.
Prices range from about $515 to $605 a month for daily lessons, or
$25 a night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Visiting the Canaries &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to go to the Canary Islands with a friend in
February. Are there package deals? And are there tours to learn
about the original inhabitants of the islands? _ Halli Moskowitz,
New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. While the Canary Islands are part of Spain and have long been
a popular vacation destination, especially for Europeans, they are
only about 70 miles off the coast of Africa and more than 600 miles
from the Iberian Peninsula. The seven major islands of the Canaries
_ essentially the peaks of an undersea mountain range that in
ancient times were thought to be the remains of Atlantis _ have
been described as having a climate that is perpetual springtime,
with highs mostly in the 70s and the 80s. You can be comfortable at
the beaches at any time, sometimes while gazing at snow-covered
mountain peaks.
</P>
<P>
   There are no direct flights to the Canary Islands from the
United States, according to the Tourist Office of Spain, so the
easiest and most common way to visit the islands is by chartered
tour. Two New York tour operators, Canary Island Tours and Spain
Tours and Beyond, offer identical packages to Tenerife, the largest
island, and say they can put together individualized or standard
side trips to other islands for an extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   The tours from New York to Tenerife are on Air Europa via
Madrid, and offer choices of 12 hotels, from three- to five-star
establishments, in the resort areas on the south side of the island
or on the north coast in Puerto de la Cruz. The fares, $759 to
$1,649 in February, include hotel for five nights, daily buffet
breakfast, transfers, casino entry and a night's stay in Madrid
returning.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally, the islands owe much to both Europe and Africa, with
the influences of Hispanic, Portuguese, French, Italian and Berber
immigrants. But before these people arrived, the Guanches _ tall,
blond cave dwellers of unknown origin _ led a Stone Age existence,
leaving behind cave paintings on the islands of La Palma and El
Hierro, and embalmed bodies. On Gran Canaria Island, experts have
reconstructed a Guanche city, Mundo Aborigen, using life-size
figures.
</P>
<P>
   It is in the Ayaguares National Park about three and a half
miles from from Playa del Ingles Beach. It is open daily 9 a.m. to
6 p.m. Admission is about $14.50, $4.35 for children 13 and
younger. Group tours in English are available except Monday and
Tuesday by calling (34-928) 17-22-95.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to go directly to Gran Canaria, you will have to
book an individual trip. Spain Tours and Beyond says air fares in
February to Gran Canaria via Madrid on Iberia Airlines are about
$760 to $810, and three- and four-star hotels range from $60 to
$100 a night, based on double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Spain Tours and Beyond, is at 261 West 70th St., New York, N.Y.
10023; (212) 595-2400, fax (212) 580-8935. Canary Islands Holidays,
part of Spanish Heritage Tours, is at 116-47 Queens Blvd., Forest
Hills, N.Y. 11375; (888) 767-8822, fax (718) 793-4278.
</P>
<P>
   For general information, contact the Tourist Office of Spain,
666 Fifth Ave., New York, N.Y. 10103; (212) 265-8822, fax (212)
265-8864.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Washington Millennium &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Six couples would like to celebrate the millennium in
Washington. Can you provide information on events there on and just
before Jan. 1, 2000. _ George N. Havens, Bratenahl, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   A. Hard as it may be to believe, there are a lot of promises
coming out of Washington but few concrete plans for that weekend,
now 432 days away.
</P>
<P>
   There should certainly be a number of events, since 2000 is not
only the end of the millennium but also the 200th anniversary of
the White House, the Capitol, the Library of Congress and of
Washington itself as the nation's capital. But a spokeswoman for
the Washington Convention and Visitors Association says it doesn't
expect to start getting details from businesses or government until
at least December. The association has a Web site, www.washington.
org/, that can help in planning a visit, and offers tourism
information at (202) 789-7069.
</P>
<P>
   Another place to check is the White House Millennium Council,
which will coordinate many activities. Sue Vogelsinger, the
council's spokeswoman, said galas, parades and family events
(including fireworks) on the Mall are planned. The council's Web
site, www.2000.whitehouse.gov, is supposed to list events as they
are announced. You can also call the council at (202) 456-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
