<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-ITALY-$ADV22-     10-20 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-ITALY-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: WHAT COUNTRY IS THIS, ANYWAY?
 &HT;    With photo mug of Holmes placed in the International folder on
the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Oct. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Like shipping rice to China, coals to Newcastle, steel to
Pittsburgh .... Viagra to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra in Italy?
</P>
<P>
   What use could there be for the little blue ``love pill'' in a
country renowned for its romantic ardor and sexual prowess?
</P>
<P>
   This is the land that bred the likes of Casanova, Marcello
Mastroianni and Alberto Tomba. Trying to sell Italians on the need
for Viagra must be like trying to convince them to drive slower.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute, just below the front-page story in my Rome
newspaper about Viagra's October debut is this headline: ``Drivers
Urged To Slow Down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the country that gave us the Lamborghini and the Maserati, a
new public-service campaign wants motorists to ease off the pedal.
</P>
<P>
   Check the plane tickets, did I land in the right country?
</P>
<P>
   I did. Here's the News Flash: Italians are not great lovers, at
least not ALL of them. And they may like to drive their sleek
sports cars like the wind, but speed kills them, just as it does
Americans in their Fords and Chevys.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the facts get in the way of long-cherished
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   With no one else to hold accountable, I blame the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the coalition of countries has brought stability to the
continent, eliminating the grave worries of earlier this century --
things like the march of fascism and world wars.
</P>
<P>
   But the EU also is serving to homogenize Europe -- creating
uniform standards, open borders and, in the near future, common
banknotes and coins. Brussels is to Europe what Washington is to
America, telling them how they should live and what's good for them
and not.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, Italy becomes less Italian, needing the help
of modern science to make love and driving Ferraris at a
school-zone crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Next, they'll tell us that the French no longer find Jerry Lewis
funny.
</P>
<P>
   Yet images die hard and Italians have an abiding taste for the
good life, and not necessarily what's good for them.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey showed that only 20 percent of Italian motorists
regularly buckle up a decade after the mandatory seat-belt law was
introduced. One entrepreneur has made a small fortune manufacturing
white t-shirts printed with a black stripe running diagonally,
meeting one that runs horizontally at the bottom -- to fool police
into thinking the belt is buckled.
</P>
<P>
   Such evidence suggests that Italian motorists will not be
slowing down anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Viagra, never underestimate the power of sexual
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Health authorities say there are some five million impotent
Italians who could use the drug. But they fear there are millions
more who simply may want it as a hedge against performance anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the pressure on Italian men, who have an entire national
identity to uphold.
</P>
<P>
   A public opinion poll earlier this year found -- to the
disappointment of the Italian food company which commissioned it --
that female tourists from Europe and the United States cite hopes
of ``passion'' as their number one reason for visiting the country.
Enjoying the pasta and chianti were second place.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizio Alicico's pharmacy in downtown Rome has been flooded
with calls from men who mistakenly think the pill is an
aphrodisiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being Italians, they feel very macho. The sexual persona they
feel very much,'' Alicico says of the callers he has turned away.
``It is clear Viagra will have higher sales in Italy because of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the myth lives.
</P>
<P>
   Italy also remains firmly Italian in other arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The country resolutely lacks anything resembling a consensus on
how the place should be run. In Rome this week, they are trying to
form a new coalition government after the last one fell earlier in
the month.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 56th change of leadership since World War II, and
actually prompted some political pundits in Rome to express concern
that Italy's European partners will not take them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, Italy should be Italy, the European Union be damned.
With 40 different political parties, serial governments have become
a way of life and yet another icon of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Corriere della Sera commented: ``Heaven only knows
what new political concoction will be dreamed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Roma ... that's more like it.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
