<P>
   JASPER-RECONCILIATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Four months ago, civic leaders here bristled
when their East Texas town of 8,000 was labeled the ``town that
shamed America'' after the dragging death of a black man named
James Byrd Jr. Officials proudly noted the swift arrest of three
white suspects in the Byrd case, and then reeled off benchmarks of
racial progress in Jasper: a black mayor, two black school
principals, a black chamber of commerce president, and a black
administrator of the town's largest hospital. Great strides, they
said, for a southern town 45 percent African-American and 55
percent white. But in recent weeks, the town has gained a new
perspective on itself, this time from its own residents. By BARRY
SHLACHTER. Story will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
