<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7271 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV25-     10-20 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Oct. 25)  
 
 Florida Keys Try To Put Georges Behind  
 Longfellow's House Closing for Repairs  
 Britannia's Gangplank Lowers for the People  
 Airports: A New Rate For Short-Term Parking  
 Mysterious Art of West Mexico  
 
(JT) 
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only two weeks after the evacuation of the Florida Keys _ when
Hurricane Georges swept through the island chain on Sept. 25,
causing $250 million in losses and cutting off access to popular
tourist spots _ visitors had begun trickling back. It's too soon to
know whether they'll be back in their full numbers, tourism
officials say, especially since the hurricane struck during the off
season. But airports, the Port of Key West, and most hotels and
attractions are now fully operational, they hasten to point out,
and big events like the Halloween Fantasy Fest in Key West, which
began Friday, have not been affected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourism infrastructure is in excellent shape,'' said Andy
Newman, a spokesman for the Monroe County Tourist Development
Council. The tourism agency is spending $2 million to spread the
word that the Keys are far from devastated.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane did, however, uproot trees, defoliate areas,
damage or destroy more than 1,500 houses, including much of the
collection of floating homes known as Houseboat Row in Key West,
and keep some destinations closed. Little Palm Island, a resort of
thatched-roof villas off Little Torch Key, has combined hurricane
cleanup with several renovation projects and does not plan to
reopen until mid-December, officials said. Several state and county
parks with beaches, such as Bahia Honda, Indian Key and Sombrero
Beach, are not welcoming visitors until sometime in November.
Hotels like the Best Western Key Ambassador in Key West have just
partly reopened. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For details about specific properties and the latest
information, tourism officials advise calling (800) 352-5397 or
visiting the Keys' Web site, www.fla-keys.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Longfellow House in Cambridge, Mass., will close today for a
yearlong construction program designed to preserve this
240-year-old National Historic Site.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The house, built in 1759, was not only the home of the poet
Henry Wadsworth Longfellow from 1837 until his death, in 1882, but
also George Washington's headquarters in the early months of the
Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service plans to install environmental
controls in the basement and wine cellar to preserve and house more
than 600,000 historic documents and artifacts. Alterations to the
adjacent carriage house will provide new facilities for education
programs, exhibits and workshops. Wheelchair access to the first
floor of the Longfellow House will be added, and the landscaped
grounds will be restored. The house is expected to reopen sometime
next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, world leaders like Nelson Mandela, Tony Blair
and Mahatma Gandhi have been entertained aboard the Britannia, the
luxurious vessel used by Queen Elizabeth and her family around the
world. On Oct. 26 the 412-foot yacht, which has recently been
refurbished, will be opened to the public for tours at the port of
Leith, two miles from the center of Edinburgh.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Britannia, launched on April 16, 1953, was decommissioned
last Dec. 11. Technically a Royal Navy ship, the yacht has sailed
more than a million miles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Budgetary constraints have much to do with the Britannia's new
role as a tourist attraction. British taxpayers spent $160 million
maintaining the yacht over the last 10 years, and a major refit
would have prolonged her life for only a few more years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors reach the ship through a visitor center designed by Sir
Terence Conran. Its centerpiece will be the yacht's 41-foot tender
floating in a pool. Britannia's original wheelhouse will also be
displayed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once on board, visitors will be guided around Britannia's five
decks by an audio tour. The bridge, the state dining room, the
drawing room and the Royal Apartments _ as they were when occupied
by the royal family, with white walls, bronze metalwork and dark
mahogany woodwork _ will be viewed through door-sized glass panels.
The engine room, the captain's cabin and the galleys are also on
the tour.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Britannia will be open daily except Christmas. A shuttle bus
will run from Princes Street and from Waverley Station in
Edinburgh. Tickets will be $11, $6.35 for children, and must be
booked in advance at (44-131) 555-5566.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's cheaper these days to make a quick stop at any of New
York's major airports and to park long-term at La Guardia.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those picking somebody up or dropping somebody off _ the reason
most people drive to airports _ will find there is a new parking
rate for up to 30 minutes. Daily parking at Kennedy, La Guardia or
Newark now costs $2 for up to half an hour (the previous minimum
rate was $4, for anything up to four hours). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month several other changes took effect at the
airports, including the introduction of long-term parking rates at
La Guardia. Six hundred spaces in Lot 3 are now reserved for
long-term parking. The cost for the first day is $24, the same as
in the daily lots, but each additional day is now only $10, not
$24. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everything is cheaper: long-term parking at Kennedy costs $2
for the first 12 hours and $2 every additional two hours to a
maximum of $8 a day, up from $7. At Newark, the maximum per day in
Lots D and E (served by the monorail) has increased to $12 from $7.
The maximum daily rate at Lots G and H (served by shuttle bus) has
gone up to $8 from $7. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The expected result: 80 percent of customers will pay less or
the same, according to the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey, the agency that manages the airports. More information is
available at www.panynj.gov. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   West Mexico has been, relatively speaking, terra incognita in
the cultural world. Though long known for ceramic sculptures, the
present-day states of Jalisco, Colima and Nayarit are only recently
coming into their own for the imposing architecture and complex
society that flourished there between 200 B.C. and 800 A.D. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ancient West Mexico: Art of the Unknown Past'' _ at the Art
Institute of Chicago through Nov. 22, then at the Los Angeles
County Museum of Art from Dec. 20 to March 29 _ brings together
more than 225 objects that provide a window on the ceremonial life,
everyday customs, economic and agricultural systems, and
architecture of this early civilization. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As archeologists, anthropologists and art historians have
discovered in the past few decades, the region of mountains,
plateaus and basins between the Rio Santiago canyon and the Pacific
Coast was densely populated and rich in creativity. The inhabitants
expressed their beliefs and commemorated family lineages in
mysterious earthenware pieces with a shared imagery but distinctive
local styles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They buried these terra-cotta sculptures and vessels, along with
some jade pieces and shell jewelry, in deep shaft tombs connected
to ceremonial centers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The figures depict men and women feasting, warring and wooing,
and fanciful animals and plants of many kinds; they show festivals,
ritual sports and family gatherings. The show explores esthetic
character, symbolic meaning, function and religious connections,
relating them back to the West Mexican civilization's
4,000-year-old roots and forward to its influence on 20th-century
artists like Diego Rivera, Frida Kahlo, Rufino Tamayo and Henry
Moore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Art Institute of Chicago is open daily. Suggested admission
is $8, and $5 for children, students and seniors. Tuesdays are
free. Information: (312) 443-3600. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Museum of Art is open daily except
Wednesday. Admission is $7, $5 for seniors and students, $1 for
children 6 to 17. Information: (323) 857-6000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
