<HEADLINE>
WYNN'S CABERNET SAUVIGNON   FROM AUSTRALIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wynn's Cabernet Sauvignon 1995, Coonawarra, Australia. About
$14. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers from South Australia like to send out samples of the
red soil from the Coonawarra region to help explain the character
of their red wines. They are redolent of plums, are both soft and
intensely rich and, at their best, have a pleasingly long
aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   The South Australians have described their 1995 vintage as
``challenging,'' but not to worry; Coonawarra is probably that
continent's best source of cabernet and this particular example is
a good wine at a good price.
</P>
<P>
   No one will ever mistake an Australian cabernet for a wine from
America or Europe, for which we should be grateful. The
homogenization of wine styles around the world proceeds apace and
is depressing to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian style is proudly different, just like the people,
and worth getting to know.
</P>
</TEXT>
