<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PRESS GOT IT MOSTLY RIGHT IN SCANDAL COVERAGE, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    680&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the blue dress to the cigar, the mainstream
news media have been mostly accurate in chronicling the White House
sex scandal, but sometimes reporters were not skeptical enough
about sources, a watchdog group concluded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to White House accusations, those doing the bulk of
the original reporting did not ferry false leaks and fabrications
into coverage of the Clinton-Lewinsky story,'' reported the
Committee of Concerned Journalists, a consortium of reporters,
editors, producers, publishers and academics. ``But in some
important cases, the press leaned on the suspicions of
investigators that did not hold up and downplayed the denials of
the accused.''
</P>
<P>
   While Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's impeachment referral
to Congress has substantiated much of the initial reporting, ``it
is an oversimplification to say the press has been vindicated,''
said Bill Kovach, chairman of the committee and the former editor
of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``The Clinton-Lewinsky Story: How Accurate? How
Fair?'', identified threads of the story that went to the crux of
whether the affair occurred and whether the president obstructed
justice and tampered with evidence to cover it up. It also examined
other aspects of the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The report examined major media outlets, including nightly
newscasts on ABC, NBC, CNN, and PBS, and reporting in the New York
Times, Washington Post, Los Angeles Times, USA Today, Time and
Newsweek. This media universe was expanded by searches on the Nexis
text archiving system and Hotline, a daily electronic political
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The findings included:
</P>
<P>
   _ The blue dress: ABC was accurate in reporting first that
Lewinsky had kept a blue dress stained with the president's semen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The talking points: News media emphasized the importance of a
document titled ``points to make in an affidavit'' that Lewinsky
gave her friend Linda Tripp, with whom she discussed the affair.
The news reports said the document could be the smoking gun proving
witness tampering. However, Starr's referral barely mentioned the
talking points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vernon Jordan: The news media failed to adequately consider
that Lewinsky might have misled Tripp about what she told Jordan,
the president's friend. That turned out to what happened, according
to Lewinsky's testimony. Some stories overstated what Lewinsky told
Tripp about whether Jordan told her to lie about her affair with
Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Currie: Holding up well was the initial New York Times
story that the president's secretary told investigators that
Clinton called her in and led her through what eventually shown to
be a false account of his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _ The cigar. Starting with an Internet posting on the Drudge
Report and advancing to Jay Leno's late-night monologue, the nation
was abuzz with rumors that Clinton and Lewinsky had used a cigar as
a sex toy long before the mainstream media did more than vaguely
mention ``kinky sex.'' Although the initial Drudge Report was wrong
on some details, the Starr Report confirmed use of a cigar in a sex
act near the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   _ Third-party witnesses: From the start of the scandal, there
were media reports that some third-party witness had seen Clinton
and Lewinsky in a compromising act. Some stories indicated that
such a witness would diminish the need for Starr to grant immunity
to Lewinsky. Starr's referral did not establish such a third-party
witness. Thus, the media could have been used by investigative
sources who wanted to pressure Lewinsky into cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   _ A second intern: Although speculation about other women was
often raised on television talk shows, there was no mention of a
so-called second intern in Starr's report or in most of the
mainstream media.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starr's dealings with the press: ``If the coverage at certain
points showed a penchant to reflect the suspicions of prosecutors
... out of balance with the denials of the accused, this would
hardly be unusual,'' the report cautioned. This is ``a growing
tendency of media coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Kovach, now curator of the Neiman Foundation at Harvard
University, and other journalists expressed concern about the
``increasing role of the argument culture'' in coverage of the
scandal involving President Clinton's cover-up of an affair with
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in television talk shows, ``the principle of keeping
fact separate from suspicion and analysis separate from
agenda-setting is no longer clearly honored,'' the report warned. A
``new class of activist pundits'' who are ``provocateurs'' rather
than journalists or news sources ``may be undermining the reporting
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The competitive pressure from 24-hour cable news channels such
as CNN, Fox News and MSNBC and from Internet sites may have also
pushed some mainstream media into prematurely reporting some
aspects of the scandal, said some members of a committee panel. The
urge to get rumors or salacious details _ ``what's out there'' _ on
the air or into print often had to be resisted, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
