<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINDBERGH-DAUGHTER-BO     10-20 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDBERGH-DAUGHTER-BOS </SLUG>
  
 iT ISN'T EASY BEING LINDBERGH'S DAUGHTER 
REPEATING FOR ALL NEEDING &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BARNET, Vt. When Reeve Lindbergh was a child, she dreamed that
her father was God. After all, she rationalized, she and her
brothers and sisters ``called him `father,' when all of our friends
called their fathers `daddy.'''
</P>
<P>
   And of course, she could find him in the ``Encyclopedia
Britannica'' as Charles A. Lindbergh, the all-American hero, the
man who, over the course of a lonely 33 1/2 hours in May 1927,
became the first to fly solo across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 71 years after that still awe-inspiring &UR;  &LR; flight (which
took place 18 years before her birth), Lindbergh smiles and tosses
her head back at a question about that childhood dream, which she
relates in her just-published memoir, ``Under A Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he was like that,'' she said. ``He was big and he had an
amazing presence. Piercing blue eyes. And everything he said was
right.'' But then, ``He was also different from that. He could
relax and be quite silly, tumbling with us on the floor, carrying
me piggy-back around the house.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, she thought, ``an inside view and an outside view.''
Outside, in public, ``I had the feeling that my father would put on
a uniform, the Lindbergh uniform,'' she said, ``but then at other
times, he would dissolve into a warm human being.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lindbergh, 53, it is an extraordinary legend to carry
through life. While she dealt with some aspects of it in her 1993
novel, ``The Names of Mountains,'' the memoir is her first effort
to deal with it directly.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents rarely spoke to their children about the public
events that made their lives so legendary. For the flight to Paris,
Lindbergh would refer the children to his book about it, telling
them, ``It's all in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, the kidnapping and death of her parents' first-born
in March 1932 was a closed subject. And, Reeve Lindbergh says now,
``The things they didn't talk about are still painful. They hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In a chilling parallel to her parents' tragedy, Reeve Lindbergh
lost her son from her first marriage, Jonathan, to infantile
encephalitis in 1985 before his second birthday. He was the age
that her brother was when he was kidnapped. Her mother, Anne Morrow
Lindbergh, now 92, was with her the night her son died, Lindbergh
said, and insisted they sit with Jonathan's body until the medical
examiner came. ``I never saw my son's body,'' she told her
daughter. ``I never sat with my son this way.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The intertwined triumph and tragedy of the Lindbergh legend is
well known, particularly among those of a certain age. She said
that people constantly want to tell her their connection to the
legend. At a children's book event _ Lindbergh has written 13 books
for children _ author and illustrator Maurice Sendak told her that
his nightmare memory of the kidnapping, which occurred when he was
4, is the psychological basis for his classic children's tale,
``Where the Wild Things Are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a nightmare for people of that age,'' said Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   But for younger generations, the legend is dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   She laughs about the reaction of Eli and Sam, the teenage sons
of her second husband, Nathaniel Tripp, whom she married in 1987.
``They knew it was a big deal,'' she said. ``But not what kind of a
big deal. I think they were more excited about my teenage daughters
_ Elizabeth and Susannah _ moving in with them.''
</P>
<P>
   For herself, whatever burden the Lindbergh legend may be, it
appears one she has learned to live with.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; After 30 years in Vermont _ she moved there after graduating
from Radcliffe in 1968 with her first husband, Richard Brown, a
Harvard classmate _ she has the outdoorsy look that comes with
too-short summers and snow-laden winters.
</P>
<P>
   She has graying blonde, tousled hair that becomes more so as she
runs her fingers through it while pausing to recollect during
several hours of conversation. She is often described as slight of
build. It is a slightness that resembles her mother's in the
memorable photograph in which, dressed in aviator's flight gear,
she is standing next to her husband. The smile is the same.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh lives now in far up-country Vermont with Tripp and
their son, 11-year-old Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   The farm, a mile and a half in from the state highway at the end
of a dirt road, is not in gentrified country. It is the kind of
back-country farm where once you might have found derelict cars
behind the barn and broken appliances on the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, there are chickens and a flock of 16 sheep. There is
also an old cow and an old horse that ``don't serve any purpose,''
Lindbergh said. ``Just hang out.'' Tripp figures ``the maximum this
farm could produce is $3,000 to $4,000 a year _ gross.'' Which is
why, he said, ``we produce books'': Lindbergh's children's books,
the 1993 novel, this memoir, and Tripp's ``Father, Soldier, Son; A
Memoir of a Platoon Leader in Vietnam,'' published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As for their 1840s farmhouse, it has the rumpled look of one
whose occupants care more about the living than the appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Although his sons and her children are grown and gone _ the only
one still at home is Benjamin, a visitor might think the house is
full of children.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen is a large, hand-drawn poster looking much like
an illustration from one of Lindbergh's children's books, setting
out various rules of the house: no more than three in the bathtub
at a time, including animals; no using the washing machine when
someone is taking a shower; and no racoons or peacocks allowed
inside the house. A World War II board game that Ben is playing
sprawls across the living room table.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh works in a small room off the kitchen, where the
clutter, extraordinary even by the usual standards of authors'
offices, swamps her computer. But there is a idyllic view up a
hillside meadow where several bluebird houses have been set out on
poles. Occasionally, deer appear out of the early morning fog at
the edge of the nearby woods. Their visits are rare enough,
Lindbergh said, ``that there is still a kind of magic in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly absent from the house is any noticeable Lindbergh
memorabilia. The only things she has, Lindbergh says, are personal
items _ like a little green eraser of her father's, a wooden ruler
on which her mother had written her initials, ``and the little
glasses case my father gave my mother to hold when she was in
labor'' and in which he had written the names of all the children
as they came along, from the kidnapped Charles through Jon, Land,
and Scott to Anne and then Reeve.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a family like ours,'' she said, ``it's the personal things
that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But with her memoir and with ``Lindbergh,'' a biography of her
father by A. Scott Berg also published this fall, it's the family
legend that's drawing new attention.
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who began working on the biography in 1990, spent
considerable time with all surviving family members, but
particularly with Reeve, whom he saw as the gatekeeper of the
family's extensive _ and never before opened _ archives. ``We had a
symbiotic relationship,'' he said. ``She'd send me chapters of her
memoir as she finished them. I don't think I used anything from
them, but I got a lot of attitudes from it.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Lindbergh worked on her memoir, originally begun as a
memorial to her sister Anne, who died in 1993, Berg became a
source. ``I'd call him for dates,'' she said. ```Scott,' I'd say,
`what was I doing in 1953?'''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time when Berg came up to Vermont around
Christmas in 1992, a time chosen, Lindbergh said, because the
family, including Anne Morrow Lindbergh and all the children, would
be gathered for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   One night after dinner, she said, Berg sat down at the piano and
started playing Cole Porter tunes. After a bit, he came to
``Anything Goes'' and when he did, ``All of a sudden, my mother got
up from where she was sitting, all curled up, and walked over
toward the piano. And every time he got to the chorus, she would
sing in a tiny voice, `Anything Goes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Morrow Lindbergh was 86 that year and, as her daughter
said, ``she was pretty frail and lots had gone for her, but she
still remembered `Anything Goes.'''
</P>
<P>
   From her childhood, Lindbergh remembers the lists of misdeeds
that her father would confront his children with on his return from
extended trips overseas or around the country: ``rake left out in
the rain,'' ``reading comics,'' or lapses in the ``freedom and
responsibility'' category.
</P>
<P>
   But looking back now, what she remembers is ``knowing him at a
good period in his life'' when he would come up to Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Lindbergh the aviator _ including some 50 World War II
missions in the South Pacific as a civilian _ had become Lindbergh
the conservationist. And, she said, he was ``more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how much the country meant to him,'' she
said. ``But he would come up and reminisce about varities of corn
and ways of raising sheep. These were things that were clearly in
his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   (AT)5SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   Aviator's biographer had access to family archive &QC; 
(AT)7 A major challenge for A. Scott Berg in writing his
just-published biography of hero-aviator Charles A. Lindbergh was
retelling the story of the incredible 33 1/2-hour solo flight
across the Atlantic in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston to promote ``Lindbergh,'' Berg said, ``I had a lot to
compete with, including Lindbergh himself, who did it so well'' in
his 1954 Pulitzer Prize-winning account, ``The Spirit of St.
Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   But in trying to recapture the atmosphere and excitement that
surrounded the event, Berg had the good fortune of hearing an
account from actor Jimmy Stewart, who played Lindbergh in the 1957
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the loveliest account I had,'' said Berg. The flight
occurred on Stewart's 17th birthday, Berg said, and he had stayed
up most of the night waiting for news. ``He talked about it to me
as if it was just the day before.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg, 49, lives in Los Angeles. He began work on the Lindbergh
biography in 1990. His biography of editor Maxwell Perkins won the
National Book Award in 1979. Following that, he wrote a biography
of film mogul Samuel Goldwyn.
</P>
<P>
   An equally great challenge, Berg said, was providing a
definitive account of the kidnapping of Lindbergh's infant son _
the ``crime of the century'' when it occurred in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   Having secured permission from Lindbergh's widow, Anne Morrow
Lindbergh, Berg had access to previously unexamined family
archives, including letters that family members wrote to each other
during the three years between the kidnapping and the murder trial
and conviction of Bruno Richard Hauptmann.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
