<HEADER>
A7278 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHO'S-MONICA-KAN &LR;      10-20 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHO'S-MONICA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY ISSUE IGNORED IN CONGRESSIONAL CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ (his impeachment.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can certainly consider it a high crime and
misdemeanor by lying to the American public,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy has been more low-key on the issue, although she has
called the president a liar and said he should be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   But in more competitive races, neither candidate typically says
much. In Missouri's high-profile Senate race, for example,
Republican Kit Bond and Democrat Jay Nixon have thrown brickbats at
each other over all sorts of issues _ but not over the president.
</P>
<P>
   Bond's top campaign aide, David Israelite, said polling
indicates that Republicans will benefit as a result of Clinton's
troubles. And he acknowledged that consultants have urged Bond to
run against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite that evidence,'' Israelite said, ``Kit has not made it
a focus because he believes that he should focus this campaign on
issues important in the Senate race.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nixon's camp, campaign manager Chuck Hatfield says much the
same thing, although he admits that Nixon might begin criticizing
the GOP more forcefully in the campaign's final two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking Republicans in a state with a strong Democratic
tradition such as Missouri is one thing. But in GOP-rich Kansas,
another approach might be better.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why 3rd District congressional candidate Dennis
Moore, a Democrat, isn't criticizing Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People bring it up, but it doesn't affect their views of the
candidates here because they don't see it as relevant to this
race,'' said Moore spokesman Mark Nevens.
</P>
<P>
   Moore sometimes isn't even asked about the controversy at some
events, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president lied. He lied to the public. He lied to his
daughter, his staff,'' Nevens said. ``That doesn't change the level
of disappointment whether you're a Democrat or Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's opponent, Vince Snowbarger, also isn't risking
alienating swing voters. Snowbarger was one of the first members of
Congress to call for the president's resignation. But he, too,
hasn't made Clinton an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a Republican in New Hampshire, you can pretty much
skewer the president and be in good shape,'' said Snowbarger aide
Kevin Yowell. ``That's not the case here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
