<SLUG> BC-SENATE-CHOICES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS HAVE CHOICES BEYOND BOND, NIXON FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Republican Kit Bond and Democrat Jay Nixon
have won most of the attention in the race for U.S. Senate, but
Missouri voters have three other choices when they go to the polls
Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Libertarian nominee Tamara Millay of St. Louis wants to end the
war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party nominee James F. Newport of Blue Springs wants to
pressure the banking industry to beef up safety at automated teller
machines, which are common sites for crimes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Taxpayers Party nominee Curt Frazier of Springfield wants
to all but scrap the nation's public education system.
</P>
<P>
   All three are waging low-key campaigns. They have little money
and argue that a choice between Bond and Nixon isn't really a
choice at all.
</P>
<P>
   Millay was a virtual spectator during a televised debate earlier
this month that featured repeated charges between Nixon and Bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were so focused on insulting each other,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Money is one of a few signs that the campaigns for all three
alternative candidates are mostly symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   Bond has reported raising about $6 million for his campaign,
while Nixon has raised about $2 million. Newport, Millay and
Frazier plan to spend about $17,000 combined, enough for each to
have one 30-second TV ad in Kansas City during ``60 Minutes'' or
``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if all three are long shots, they have lengthy campaign
agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Millay, 31, is a recruiter for the computer industry. She said
she favors making Social Security a private enterprise, opposes
gun-control laws and says citizens are unfairly required to help
finance public schools. Charter schools and home schooling should
be encouraged, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Millay said one of her key proposals is to end the nation's war
on illegal drugs. Drugs should be legalized with restrictions
similar to laws that govern alcohol, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the drug laws create far more harm than the
drugs themselves and are responsible for much of the crime we
see,'' Millay said.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching young people to avoid drugs primarily should be the
responsibility of parents, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Millay also favors abolishing the federal income tax. She said
revenue from existing excise taxes would finance the only services
the federal government should provide, such as a national defense
and law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that taking money away from people's earnings is
really an unfair way to fund the government since it punishes
people for being productive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Newport, a 43-year-old steel company employee, has staked out a
wide range of stands.
</P>
<P>
   He said requiring 911 access at all automated teller machines is
one of his primary goals.
</P>
<P>
   Newport said the banking industry has failed to recognize that
it must protect customers at ATMs. Holdups at the machines would
decline if customers had handy access to an emergency telephone, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In international policy, Newport proposed using sophisticated
missiles to combat possible threats from Second- and Third World
countries. Otherwise, actions by nations like Afghanistan could
become the spark that ignites World War III, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newport said environmental problems deserve more attention. He
argues that society hasn't used all the tools at its disposal to
combat documented problems. For example, he said the technology
already exists to replenish the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who wants to know how to do it _ I will tell them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newport said all health-insurance premiums should be
tax-deductible. And while he generally agrees with the stances of
the National Rifle Association, Newport believes gun owners have a
duty to secure their weapons from children.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, a 42-year-old Springfield physician, said public
education has been a ``colossal failure'' and that schools should
be controlled by local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Students today are taught multiculturalism and other ideas that
destroy their hearts and minds rather than getting instruction in
morals and the nation's Christian heritage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government has no constitutional authority in the
realm of education,'' Frazier said.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the reliance on property tax revenue as a key
source for public education funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has overstepped its bounds in invading personal
property rights of its citizens,'' Frazier said.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said Congress has unconstitutionally surrendered its
powers to unelected officials, the United Nations and others and
subverted American freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose our sovereignty, we lose all of our God-given
rights,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
