<SLUG> BC-CALIF-RELIGION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION IS A TRICKY ISSUE IN CALIFORNIA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Attorney General Dan Lungren has entered
the final two weeks of the gubernatorial campaign in much the same
way he started it: by invoking religion.
</P>
<P>
   Where earlier he tried to open a discussion of religious values,
the Republican candidate is now using his Catholic faith to justify
his staunch opposition to abortion and to deflect criticism from
Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic nominee who favors abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Using religion as an issue in the political arena comes with
some baggage. Lungren has been accused of being hypocritical
because he supports the death penalty, which the Catholic Church
also opposes.
</P>
<P>
   In a 60-second radio spot now running, Lungren's wife Bobbi
says: ``Gray Davis is using the emotional issue of abortion as a
divisive wedge issue. He should have more respect for the deeply
held personal beliefs of others. As life-long Catholics, Dan and I
have deeply held religious and moral convictions, and we have
always been pro-life.''
</P>
<P>
   Religion can be a tricky issue for a politician. Kathleen Brown,
a Democrat who ran and lost against Gov. Pete Wilson in 1994, was
criticized for citing her Catholic faith as the basis for her
opposition to the death penalty. Yet she supported abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren has opened himself up to scrutiny for the same kind of
contradiction. The Catholic Church is opposed to both abortion and
the death penalty, but Lungren has said he would work diligently to
clear a backlog of 450 death row inmates, and he was the first
attorney general since 1977 to oversee an execution.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion, Lungren has said, kills innocent children, but the
death penalty is reserved for those who take a life. ``If you don't
understand the difference between innocent life and non-innocent
life, then you have missed a fundamental proposition of not only
the teachings of the Catholic Church, but the fundamentals of
American democracy,'' Lungren said in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church is fairly forgiving about members who differ
from church dogma, but theologians say Lungren cannot use the
church to justify one position while ignoring the same fundamental
tenet: that life is sacred from inception to grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll find many Catholics who pick and choose among which
beliefs they will hold, just as many politicians do,'' said the
Rev. Joseph Daoust, professor of religion and society at the Jesuit
School of Theology in Berkeley. ``One should _ just to be logical,
much less faithful _ be opposed to both.''
</P>
<P>
   Daoust said Lungren could hold an anti-abortion stance, but the
``rationale cannot be that he's Catholic. It's got to be because of
the fundamental values that underlie church teachings.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis told the editorial board of the San Francisco Examiner
that the biggest hole in Lungren's argument was ``something called
the separation of church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he was willing to go against the church when it came
to policies he disagreed with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has helped shape me as a person,'' Davis said of his
Catholic faith. ``I have empathy for people who are dealing with
problems and need some assistance. ... I guess the answer would be
my religion would not affect the judgments I make on behalf of the
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
