<SLUG> BC-WHO'S-MONICA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY ISSUE IGNORED IN CONGRESSIONAL CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Monica?
</P>
<P>
   Monica who?
</P>
<P>
   Although no news story has so dominated Washington this year,
most congressional candidates in the Heartland are barely
mentioning impeachment, much less President Clinton's now-infamous
former intern, Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It's the big issue that's disappeared faster than you can say,
``House Judiciary Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got back from a 17-city tour in southwest Kansas,''
said Paul Feleciano of Wichita, the Democratic U.S. Senate
candidate. ``I didn't have one question about it. Absolutely zero.
It's a non-issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The great irony is that the November election is being viewed in
some quarters as a referendum on the president's future. According
to the theory, if Republicans pick up a boatload of House and
Senate seats, Clinton is toast.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of how, or whether, Congress should discipline
the philandering president is hardly ever raised by candidates,
especially those in competitive races. They prefer for the audience
to initiate the subject, rather than risk appearing too eager to
score points on such a divisive issue.
</P>
<P>
   And that's one big reason candidates are avoiding the topic. The
question of impeachment is polarizing. Polls show the country split
on the question of whether the House did the right thing by
launching an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also are sharply divided on what should happen next.
Should Clinton apologize or resign if he lied under oath? Should
Congress censure him, impeach him or drop it altogether?
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they're weary of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no one who really wants to hear one bit more
about it,'' said Burdett Loomis, a University of Kansas political
scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Republicans could criticize Clinton for his
transgressions. They could point out that electing Democrats
further insulates the president from punishment.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats could bang on Republicans for prolonging the
matter through the open-ended impeachment inquiry they approved.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, candidates are gambling because they risk alienating
voters who believe differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they see a potential gain, they're worried about the
potential risk and down side of using it,'' said Stuart Rothenberg,
editor of the Rothenberg Political Report. ``Nobody sees it as a
home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, candidates are sticking to more traditional concerns:
HMO reform, Social Security, health care, taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But there are exceptions, particularly among long-shot
challengers who have little to lose. They tend to talk much more
bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   Take Cecilia Noland, a Republican from Osage Beach, Mo., who is
challenging Rep. Ike Skelton of Lexington in the state's 4th
District. Clinton, she says, should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, he lied under oath and that's
perjury and that's where the impeachment process comes in,'' Noland
said.
</P>
<P>
   She usually introduces the subject with audiences and rarely
regrets it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I get the biggest applause,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenger, Republican Penny Bennett of Independence,
who is challenging incumbent Democratic Rep. Karen McCarthy, also
has made impeachment a top issue. She has repeatedly implored
McCarthy, of Kansas City, to demand Clinton's resignation or insist
upon his impeachment. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
