A7291 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-20 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PET PEEVES FALL INTO TWO CATEGORIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most linguistic pet peeves fall into one of two categories.
There are the clear transgressions _ we can all agree that Go
Patriot's, which reader Janice Aviza must endure at her workplace,
is nonstandard punctuation. Then there are the less clear-cut (and
more numerous) cases: You may have learned, as I did, that forte,
meaning ``strength,'' should be one syllable, but the arguments for
FORT over FOR-tay are strained at best.
</P>
<P>
   Some pet peeves, though, seem to come out of nowhere. One of
these is the resistance to some in the sense of approximately, as
in a recent Globe story about ``some 75 air traffic controllers''
coping with a computer malfunction. David Chirlin of Nashua wonders
whether some, used this way, is ``simply an excuse for sloppy
writing or laziness in fact gathering.'' And several Globe copy
editors share his feeling that there's something shady about some,
and routinely change it to about or approximately.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where the distaste comes from, because some in this
sense is no tacky modern invention; the Oxford English Dictionary
has a citation from the year 888 _ yes, with three digits _ as well
as examples from Shakespeare, Dryden, Ruskin, and other worthies.
You may not like the American twist that came along three decades
ago _ the inversion twenty-some years, which led straight to
thirtysomething and its variations _ but that neologism should not
retrospectively taint the older some.
</P>
<P>
   Myself, I'm very fond of some. Approximately is a real mouthful,
the rhythmic equivalent of five potholes in a row; about may do the
job, but often it's needed for other purposes in a nearby sentence,
and besides, one syllable may work better than two.
</P>
<P>
   As for the question of laziness, that's a judgment to make case
by case: For blood sugar levels or batting averages, precise
numbers matter; but when the point is to show a bunch of air
controllers in a tense situation, nailing down the number _ 73, 75,
77 _ may not be the most important part of the job. (An excess of
precision can even be distracting; rarely does the reader care
whether a 45-year-old is barely 45 or on the brink of 46.)
</P>
<P>
   There is another, more recent some discussed in the usage books.
This is the some immortalized by E.B. White, of Strunk &AMP; White
fame. In his book ``Charlotte's Web,'' Charlotte saves her friend
Wilbur's bacon by weaving the words ``SOME PIG!'' above his head.
This some is a colloquialism, perhaps best used in pigsties and
other informal settings. But the ancient usage deserves to go its
way unhindered, after some 11 centuries of faithful service.
</P>
<P>
   (AT)5Reasonably seasonable
</P>
<P>
   (AT)7 The gray weather that's been gloom-ifying what should be
New England's best month prompted me to pull out a note from Henry
B. Schoenberger of Laconia, N.H. _ written several months ago,
probably in response to the equally dispiriting dampness of May _
questioning the bona fides of the word seasonable. ``Does it mean
that the weather outside today is `able' to be a `season'?''
Schoenberger inquired. ``When weatherpersons talk about seasonable
weather, wouldn't they be more correct talking about seasonal
weather?''
</P>
<P>
   No question about it, seasonable looks odd next to most of its
able-suffixed siblings. If it were parallel to lovable or crushable
or understandable, it would mean ``able (or worthy) of being
seasoned'' _ but it doesn't. If it were like perishable, it would
mean ``able to season''; wrong again, though it did have that
meaning centuries ago. But there is a group of -able words that,
while they aren't so easily analyzed, are perfectly respectable.
The dictionaries give them a broad description _ ``having qualities
of'' (comfortable), ``tending or inclined to (peaceable,
knowledgeable). Seasonable, meaning appropriate to the season, will
simply have to squeeze in somewhere under this spacious umbrella;
we've been using the word to talk about the weather since at least
the 1300s, and it's too late to banish it now.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal, meanwhile, simply means ``of the season''; we see
seasonal variations in consumer spending, and seasonal sales when
too much remains unsold. Both words, of course, are useful only if
we have identifiable seasons. If climate change turns out to be a
real phenomenon, both seasonal and seasonable may have to go into
the deep freeze till we know what we can expect of a day in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7295 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-RACE-KAN &LR;      10-20 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-RACE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND, NIXON SHARE MANY GOALS, DIFFER ON HOW TO REACH THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ (financial lifeline.)
</P>
<P>
   Their dispute revolves around whether Bond actually means what
he says. Nixon said that Bond, through Senate votes and a candidate
questionnaire, has opened the door to using some of the surpluses
to cut taxes or retire the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Bond denies fudging, saying he agreed with President Clinton
last January that only when Social Security is on sound footing
should the surpluses be eyed for tax cuts or debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity that should not be passed up or wasted
by political posturing,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they pledge to rescue Social Security, Nixon and Bond
said the nation's schools need more money for teachers, buildings
and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Bond is touting a ``Direct Check for Education'' program that
would send an additional $13 billion to schools. Only $1 billion of
that would be new money; the rest would come from savings by
consolidating programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you eliminate the bureaucratic steps in Washington and
Jefferson City, there will be more money at the end of the
pipeline,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon isn't impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind numbing to talk about `direct check' when there's no
money behind it,'' Nixon said. ``It's an amazing election-year
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said more money is needed, but he didn't say how much.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting drugs was high on the list of Bond and Nixon and they
both focused on the methamphetamine problem in Missouri. Both want
more money for meth efforts, but Bond is more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Bond proposed giving $2 million to the Missouri Department of
Conservation for meth cleanup and also thinks money should be
available from the federal Superfund that is set aside for
toxic-waste cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more money to fight meth, Nixon said there needs
to be broadened cooperation between state and federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   To that end and other crime-fighting efforts, Nixon said
Congress must continue toward a goal of helping pay to put 100,000
more officers on local police forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing fights crime better than making sure we have more
officers on the street,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prefers to let local police departments decide how to use
any additional money.
</P>
<P>
   On taxes, Bond and Nixon both favor simplifying the tax code and
reducing the number of deductions that result in many forms and
myriad tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax code has become far too much of a social engineering
project, that's why it's so complicated,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said the deductions for mortgage interest and charitable
donations should remain and that deductions for premiums the
self-employed pay for insurance should be allowed. Nixon agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Bond also would like to end what he said is a tax penalty for
getting married. A single person should not have to pay more taxes
after marriage if nothing else about his or her tax status changes,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon did not indicate specific tax-code changes but said, ``I
would maintain some deductions, certainly.'' Nixon said people are
too confused about what they owe and when they owe it.
</P>
<P>
   One issue where Nixon and Bond are in sharp disagreement was
tabled earlier but may make a comeback: Campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was an outspoken supporter of a Senate bill aimed at
people and groups that skirt election laws to help pay for a
candidate's campaign advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations, unions and wealthy individuals are known to give
large sums to national political parties to run commercials that
mention candidates by name but stop short of urging that voters
support them at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Limits on how much can be given to individual candidates do not
apply to what is given to national parties, and that can result in
substantial sums being used indirectly to benefit the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bond opposed a Democratic bill that would have regulated such
spending and required it be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bond's vote to kill the bill is yet another case of him voting
to protect special interests and coddling big-money donors,'' Nixon
said after the Senate vote last month.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said voting for the bill would restrict free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, ``We have an ineffective enforcement system, and
we haven't been able to get the cooperation of the administration
on how many laws were broken.'' As an example, he cited foreign
contributions to President Clinton's re-election campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to convert his goals to accomplishments in the Senate,
Bond said his experience will be an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said a senator's experience is less important than whose
interest he or she is representing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if you're a veteran or a young senator,''
Nixon said. ``It's a question of what side of the fight you're
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
