<HEADLINE>
BOND, NIXON SHARE MANY GOALS, DIFFER ON HOW TO REACH THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Kit Bond and Jay Nixon are asked to name the
four or five most pressing issues they will face if they win this
fall's race for the U.S. Senate, they sound a lot alike.
</P>
<P>
   Both mentioned reforming managed health care, saving Social
Security, spending more money on education and fighting crime,
especially drug traffic. Bond added tax-code reform to the list.
</P>
<P>
   But their shared goals do not beget shared solutions. And on
issues neither put on their priority list, such as campaign finance
reform, they are especially divided.
</P>
<P>
   Republican incumbent Bond says there has been far too little
attention to issues in the campaign. Bond has put out a series of
papers since mid-August detailing his views, but he says they have
been all but ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Nixon, on the other hand, has drafted no formal set of
position papers. But, ``I don't think it's very difficult to say
where I stand on the issues,'' said Nixon, who has been Missouri's
attorney general for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates' key issues have something in common: They tend
to affect the daily lives of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the things they want resolved,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   One such issue, Bond and Nixon said, is the managed health-care
system that covers about 160 million Americans who are in some form
of health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Participants pay a flat fee for coverage, giving HMOs an
incentive to keep costs as low as possible. Patients complain that
this limits their treatment options and access to specialists and
emergency services.
</P>
<P>
   Bond and Nixon want to give patients more choices, but they
differ in how far the government should go in that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bond wants to limit some of the key changes to about one-third
of the nation's HMO participants _ those in self-insured,
employer-sponsored plans subject to federal regulation. States
would regulate the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon likes the Democratic proposal that would cover all plans
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of whether a patient should be able to sue the HMO,
not just the physician, for malpractice, Nixon says they should.
Bond disagrees but says patients should be able to appeal to a
board if denied coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 56 new reasons for trial lawyers to sue under the
(Democratic) bill,'' Bond said, noting that trial lawyers often are
major political contributors. ``No wonder Mr. Nixon is for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said a patient's right to adequate treatment should extend
to the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anybody to have to sue. I want them to get the
health care they need,'' Nixon said. ``If an HMO denies them
options, yeah, they should have the right to sue.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, neither the Republican nor Democratic plan
passed Congress this year. But discussion is expected to resume in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Another matter left unsettled is what to do with an estimated
$70 billion budget surplus this year and a projected $1.6 trillion
surplus over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Nixon and Bond are in basic agreement that any budget
surpluses should go directly into the Social Security fund that
could go broke in about 30 years if Congress doesn't toss it a
financial lifeline. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
