<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT WAY, WRONG SPEED FOR PARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Change is coming, but it's slow: so slow in fact, that at the
current rate it'll take until 2064 for gender parity on Fortune 500
boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change is in the right direction, but it's small and has
been painfully slow,'' said Mary Mattis, vice president for
research and advisory services at Catalyst, which for the last six
years has monitored the progress of America's major corporations.
</P>
<P>
   According to this year's census released Thursday, only 11.1
percent of Fortune 500 companies have at least one woman on their
board of directors. That's up from 10.6 percent in 1997 and 8.3
percent in 1993, when Catalyst did its first survey.
</P>
<P>
   While 71 Fortune 500 companies _ including five in Missouri _
still don't have any women directors, 188 companies have more than
one woman board member, and last year Golden West Financial Corp.
reached gender parity.
</P>
<P>
   The two Kansas Fortune 500 companies on the list _ Sprint Corp.
and Yellow Corp. _ both have at least one woman. In Missouri,
neither Farmland Industries nor Interstate Bakeries have any women
directors, according to the census.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest frustration, Mattis said, is that there's no
excuse not to have a woman director because there are plenty of
qualified candidates. Catalyst's Corporate Board Placement has
identified at least 2,000 potential women directors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the obstacles, said Mattis, is that boards are shrinking
and have little turnover. But companies are slowly recognizing that
they need women directors because not only are women consumers and
stockholders, women offer a different perspective that enriches a
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do women bring special skills and experience to a
board, they do things in a different way,'' Mattis said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why boards with women appear to be doing better
than those without.
</P>
<P>
   The top 100 Fortune 500 companies are twice as likely as those
at the bottom 100 to have women directors. And the top 10 companies
all have at least one woman. The top eight of these have at least
two, and General Motors, the No. 1. ranked company, has three.
</P>
<P>
   While we need more CEOs and boards reaching out to women, women
also have a responsibility to develop their careers so that they
get the experience necessary for these positions.
</P>
<P>
   Mattis emphasized that women need to take more risks in their
careers. That means women need to make sure they get a well-rounded
experience and take on projects that are challenging and may
require relocating.
</P>
<P>
   Women also need to sit on the boards of small companies and
larger nonprofits because that's where they'll get the experience
they need and the opportunities to meet the people who will
eventually appoint them to larger boards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
