<HEADLINE>
ABSENTEE BALLOTING SNAFU SPARKS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO and RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three candidates for local office have sued the
city of San Francisco for leaving their Chinese names off thousands
of absentee voter booklets.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Monday in Superior Court, accuses the
Department of Elections of not translating into Chinese the names
of Supervisor Mabel Teng; Victor Marquez, a candidate for the Board
of Supervisors; and Carlota del Portillo, an incumbent candidate
for the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that Chinese voters who read only Chinese will be
deprived of a full choice of candidates, the lawsuit asks the
elections office to send a correction sheet to those who have
received a ballot and allow those who have already voted to cast
another ballot if they so choose.
</P>
<P>
   About 47,000 absentee ballots have been sent out. John
Whitehurst, Teng's campaign manager, said about 5,000 of those
voters had Chinese surnames, though it is unknown how many cannot
read English.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Nishioka, acting director of the Department of Elections,
said last week the omission was not an error, as the lawsuit
alleges. She said the candidates in question had declined her offer
to have their names printed in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   At the Board of Supervisors meeting Monday, Supervisor Michael
Yaki tried to push through an emergency resolution that asked the
elections officer to mail out corrected absentee ballots with a
letter of explanation.
</P>
<P>
   But using a procedural maneuver, Supervisor Leland Yee blocked
passage of the resolution and forced the measure to be sent to
committee for a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Yee said he had concerns that the Department of Elections was
being blamed for a problem that might have been the fault of the
individual campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to be concerned about the problem, then I
think we have to know exactly how it was caused,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Leslie Katz suggested that henceforth, elections
officials translate every candidates' name into Chinese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
