<HEADER>
A7341 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGAS-RELIGION-INDEPE     10-20 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGAS-RELIGION-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAS VEGAS: FASTEST-GROWING CATHOLIC DIOCESE IN THE WORLD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS -- Is there a God in Las Vegas? This is a town,
surely, where money is the only true religion, and religious ritual
is more about quickie weddings and divorces than any true
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? Those monumental gambling houses and casinos along the
Strip may look like cathedrals, but in fact the healthiest,
best-observed religion in town is also the most old-fashioned --
that occasionally fusty institution of catechism, rosewater and a
ban on divorces, the Roman Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   For Vegas, among its many other peculiarities, is the
fastest-growing Catholic diocese in the world. Of the 5,000 new
residents who descend on this frenzied southern Nevada mecca each
month, roughly one-third are Catholic and a few dozen more convert
once they arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The priests of the diocese can't build new churches fast enough
-- five have gone up in the last few years, and another five are
planned for the next 12 months alone. Still the faithful keep
pouring in, causing traffic jams in the churchyard and leaving
standing-room only inside.
</P>
<P>
   At Our Lady of Las Vegas, one of the older parishes in town (it
was founded in 1958), no fewer than eight masses are performed each
Sunday, on top of the two to four on the other days of the week.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not talking a few old ladies sitting politely in the
front rows; the 750-seat church is packed to capacity every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell this is an older church because these days nobody
would consider building one with less than 1,200 seats,'' explained
the pastor, the Rev. Dave Casaleggio. ``Our neighboring parish has
1,500 seats and still gets swamped. We would build even more
churches than we have, except we can't find the clergy to run
them.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be tempting to see this phenomenal success as some kind
of counterweight to the gambling industry -- God striking back
against Mammon. But in fact it is more to do with Las Vegas'
phenomenal growth and the natural inclination of many Americans to
turn to their church as a source of community spirit and social
life -- particularly when they have just moved to somewhere new.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its long traditions, the Catholic Church is
particularly well placed to provide an anchor for new arrivals from
a huge variety of ethnic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people here are from Las Vegas,'' explained Father
Dave. ``The church is what gives them a sense of identity. You
should see the quantity of e-mails I receive from people about to
relocate to this area. They want to know about church activities,
church schools, and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   The casinos do not really enter into the equation. If anything,
the church and the gambling industry co-exist with remarkable ease.
``Once in a while I'll go to a casino and spend 10 or 15 dollars. I
don't think it's a sin, it's fun,'' Father Dave admitted cheerily.
</P>
<P>
   Many casino-owners are themselves Catholic and contribute large
sums both to their parishes and to the community at large. One
Catholic priest in the Las Vegas area has even been known to say
mass in a casino, his liturgy clashing unashamedly with the hoots
and flashing lights of the slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   On closer inspection, churches like Our Lady of Las Vegas appear
to have been infected with some of the same Vegas spirit as the
monster resort hotels on the Strip. When space first became an
issue at Our Lady 10 years ago, the diocesan leaders of the time
chose simply to build a larger church next door -- in much the same
spirit as the owners of the Aladdin casino, who blew up their
property last year to make way for a bigger, better version.
</P>
<P>
   A bit like Caesar's Palace, which boasts a lifesize model of
Michelangelo's David in its shopping arcade, Our Lady of Las Vegas
has a replica -- in marble -- of the Pieta sitting in some
shrubbery overlooking the main road. That's almost as good as the
neighboring parish of Saint Joseph, Husband of Mary, which has a
similarly proportioned Pieta, but in bronze.
</P>
<P>
   There are some limits, however. Divorce is still frowned upon,
and couples wanting to get married in a hurry won't get any joy
from a Catholic priest. Father Dave insists on six months'
preparation, including classes for the bride and groom, or four
months as an absolute minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are more liberal around here, it's true,'' he said,
``but we're still the Catholic Church.``
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
