<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOCOLATE-BOOK-REVIEW     10-20 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTING CHOCOLATE AS SOPHISTICATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By POLLY FROST   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it possible that there can be too much of something as
perfect as chocolate? Countless writers from cooks to psychologists
have tried to offer the final word on this divine substance.
</P>
<P>
   And even the stodgiest restaurants attempt to outdo each other
with versions of ``death by chocolate,'' which usually turns out to
mean mud cake sludge. Awash in this excess, it can be impossible to
truly appreciate chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Which is all the more reason to welcome Nick Malgieri's
deliciously sophisticated ``Chocolate: From Simple Cookies to
Extravagant Showstoppers'' (HarperCollins, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Malgieri, the director of baking at the Peter Kump Cooking
School, offers 380 recipes for pies, drinks, custards, sauces,
candies and even blueprints for cookie houses. After a week of
baking, my love affair with the cocoa bean has been renewed.
</P>
<P>
   True chocoholics know that chocolate is a universe of flavors,
textures and pleasures that's as complex as wine or cheese. What's
most rewarding about Malgieri's book is the way he opens back up
the range of what chocolate can do, and then sorts it out for you.
</P>
<P>
   The bittersweet, milk and unsweetened chocolates in his triple
chocolate cheesecake, for example, don't run together, provided you
follow his mixing instructions. Instead, they bring out each
other's characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   There's a fine foursquare recipe for chocolate cake with stewed
prunes _ a combination that may strike the modern reader as
strange, but that once wasn't so uncommon. No, it doesn't taste
like a cake that has fallen on top of a hospital breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The dried fruit beautifully underscores the richness of the
chocolate. And I'm grateful for the recipe for chocolate mayonnaise
cake, something I haven't had since I was a child. ( Malgieri
writes that using mayonnaise this way was an idea thought up 60
years ago by the wife of a grocer.)
</P>
<P>
   It's a light, yet substantial cake, just as I remember, and I
love the way the bitterness of the cocoa begs for a dusting of
confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Malgieri also shows that chocolate doesn't always have to be the
diva of the dessert cart. It performs very nicely even in a
supporting role. In his rugelach recipe, Malgieri uses a cream
cheese dough and a filling of brown sugar and cinnamon. Then he
lets fly with the semisweet chips. Yes!
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that Malgieri's baking instructions are sometimes
sketchier than they should be. One cookie recipe calls for putting
two pans in the oven at the same time, in the upper and lower
thirds of the oven.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't add that you should switch the sheets midway to
insure even baking. After you've made the supernatural brownies, he
asks that you cover them up and leave them alone until the next
day, without explaining why. That's Torture-by-Brownie. The reason,
as I discovered for myself, is that they'll turn into fudgey
melt-in-your mouth bars, and cut better, too.
</P>
<P>
   Beginners who don't own expensive kitchenware will find plenty
within their reach, like the chocolate biscotti. And cooks eager to
stretch their skills will find Malgieri an inspiring coach.
</P>
<P>
   His guidelines for tempering _ the process of melting chocolate
and then cooling it and then reheating it so that it coats smoothly
and seamlessly _ are the least anxiety-producing that I've yet
read. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUPERNATURAL BROWNIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Chocolate: From Simple Cookies to Extravagant
Showstoppers'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus overnight resting &QL;
</P>
<P>
   16 tablespoons unsalted butter, plus additional for buttering
pan
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces bittersweet or semisweet chocolate, cut into \-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups ({ pound) walnut or pecan pieces (optional). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Set a rack at the middle level of the oven and preheat to 350
degrees. Butter a 13-by-9-by-2-inch pan, line it with parchment
paper or foil and butter the parchment or foil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring a medium saucepan of water to a boil and turn off heat.
In a large, heatproof bowl, combine butter and chocolate and set
over pan of water. (A double-boiler may also be used.) Stir
occasionally until melted.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large bowl, whisk eggs until thick and lemon-colored,
then whisk in salt, sugars and vanilla. Stir in chocolate and
butter mixture, then fold in flour.
</P>
<P>
   4. Pour batter into prepared pan and spread evenly. Bake for
about 45 minutes, until top has formed a shiny crust and batter is
moderately firm. Cool in pan on a rack. Wrap pan in plastic wrap
and let rest overnight at room temperature or refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   5. To cut brownies, bring to room temperature, unmold onto a a
cookie sheet, remove paper and place a second cookie sheet on top.
Turn brownies right side up and trim away edges. Cut brownies into
2-inch squares.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 24 brownies.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Brownies are best stored individually wrapped, in a tin or
plastic container with a tight-fitting cover, or in the freezer. If
you have a 12-by-18-inch half-sheet pan, you may double this recipe
easily. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
