<HEADER>
A7401 &Cx1f; gen-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BUDGETTHISISTH     10-20 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR OCT.
20, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- BART. In what BART officials called a
``disappointing'' level of federal funding, Congress is set to
approve $40 million for BART's extension to the South Bay. The
Clinton administration had requested $74 million, and Burlingame
Mayor Mike Spinelli, a BART opponent, said he thinks the regional
subway system will have to request more money from already-pinched
state and local governments. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- FEC. Sen. Christopher J. Dodd had $2.3 million in
the bank at the end of September. His Republican challenger, Gary
Franks, had $20,000, according to reports filed with the Federal
Election Commission. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. (Working.) Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- BUDGET. The massive federal budget approved by the
House on Tuesday means Hoosiers will see a significant increase in
federal dollars. (Working.) Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA -- LAND. President Clinton signed into law Monday the
Southern Nevada Public Lands Management Act, which will allow
federally owned land to be sold under an auction process. Sen.
Richard Bryan, D-Nev., said this is the most important legislation
for Nevada that Congress passed this year. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEW MEXICO -- BANDELIER. Legislation to expand Bandelier
National Monument, is expected to be debated Tuesday night. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- OHIO-BREAKFAST. National participation in the School
Breakfast Program set records in the spring of 1998, as more than
six million low- income children received breakfast at school,
according to the Food Research and Action Center. But only 45.5
percent of Ohio schools participate, ranking it 45th of the 50
states. A school breakfast program in Springfield, Ohio, was
praised as a model program. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- OXLEY-FEC. Rep. Mike Oxley's campaign warchest dwarfs that of
Paul McClain, his Democratic challenger for Ohio's 4th
congressional seat. As of Sept. 30, the Findlay Republican had
$267,000 left to spend, while McClain only has $8,900, according to
their latest filings with the Federal Election Commission. Will
also include Navarre Republican Ralph Regula's FEC report. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
