<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-STANDARDS21-CO     10-20 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-STANDARDS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFORM GROUP PRESSES FOR NATIONAL SCHOOL STANDARDS
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly 82 percent of American parents think
academic standards at their children's schools are too low, the
Council for Basic Education said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The finding in a nationwide poll by the independent reform group
may reflect the fact that most parents do not have access to model
standards written by national experts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The council also released a list of what it called the best
educational standards in the country.
</P>
<P>
   President Christopher Cross said it did so to ``open up a
dialogue'' and help school districts, teachers and parents
determine if their academic standards are rigorous enough.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, nearly every state or school district sets its own
academic standards. However, Cross said the guidelines vary widely
and are sometimes too vague.
</P>
<P>
   One state guideline for fourth-grade English, for example, says
students should learn to ``discover language through fun writing
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The council said a better standard would require specific skills
such as writing narratives, composing responses to literature and
crafting reports that draw from more than one source of
information.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a national set of academic standards has been
criticized by some people who say rigorous standards can hurt
weaker students who already do poorly in school.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cross said most students don't feel they are challenged
enough. He said standards for students in low-performing schools
should be just as high as students in better schools.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, nearly three-quarters of parents strongly
believed schools in different parts of the country should have very
similar academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
