<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT &LR;      10-20 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 OLD MENUS AND FOOD BOOKS; PEACE CANDY; POSITIVELY PROSCIUTTO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A menu printed early this century from Luchow's, a
German restaurant that was on East 14th Street, lists Champagne at
$4 a bottle. Books printed in Venice in 1581 and Paris in 1682
illustrate how to disjoint a turkey. And ``Opera Venetia,'' a book
by Bartolomeo Scappi that was printed in 1596, illustrates a fork,
a newfangled tool back then. These items are in ``You Are What You
Read,'' an exhibition at the New York Academy of Medicine, 1216
Fifth Ave. (103rd Street), through Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The books and menu are among 5,000 items given to the academy in
1929 by Margaret Barclay Wilson, who was a professor of physiology
and hygiene at Hunter College, a fellow of the academy and an avid
collector of food books and menus. The earliest printed book on
view dates from 1486. The works are displayed chronologically, with
explanations. The exhibition, in the library on the third floor, is
open weekdays from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Bar for Peace
</P>
<P>
   Whoever thought that buying a candy bar could lead to world
peace? Ten percent of the price of the Wafa bar, which costs 79
cents to $1, is donated to Seeds of Peace, a nonprofit organization
that educates young people about coexistence. The candy is made by
Arabs and Israelis in a cooperative venture in Israel, and is
distributed by Peaceworks Inc., a Manhattan-based company. An
approximate English translation of ``wafa,'' an Arabic word, is
``fidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for laudatory goals. What does the Wafa bar taste like?
A crisp cookie with hazelnuts and a milk-chocolate coating, it is a
notch above other chocolate bars of this ilk. It is sold at
Zabar's, Broadway and 80th Street, and at Garden of Eden, 314 Third
Ave. (15th Street) and 162 W. 23rd St., among other shops.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the Ham?
</P>
<P>
   Ask an American what beef prosciutto is, and this is the answer
you'd probably get: dried beef sliced paper thin and perhaps served
with figs or melon. But an Italian would be perplexed: In Italian,
``prosciutto'' means ``ham,'' any ham, not just the air-cured kind
from Parma. Beef ham?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is such a thing. Positively gourmet-brand beef
prosciutto, made from lean Argentine top round, is being introduced
this week in New York shops. It is pleasant and very mild, with
neither the salty intensity of other dried beef products, like
Italian bresaola or Swiss buendnerfleisch, nor the sweet nutty
complexity of Italian prosciutto di Parma. It has almost no fat and
is relatively low in sodium, with 50 calories and 290 milligrams of
sodium in a one-ounce serving. It is cured for 90 days and contains
potassium nitrate and sodium ascorbate.
</P>
<P>
   The product, made by Beef Prosciutto, a company in Jupiter,
Fla., is about $20 a pound at Murray's Cheese Shop, 257 Bleecker
St. (Cornelia Street); Fairway, 2127 Broadway (74th Street) and
2328 12th Ave. (132nd Street); Grace's Marketplace, 1237 Third Ave.
(71st Street), and Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Ave. (79th
Street). It is also at Citarella, 2135 Broadway (75th Street) and
1313 Third Ave. (75th Street); both Citarella locations will serve
samples this Saturday and on Nov. 7 and 14, from 1 to 5 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
