<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGING IT OUT IN THE RATINGS  
 GUNS, BUTTER AND TV 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who is getting more air time during the World Series? Stars of
the Yankees or stars of Fox?
</P>
<P>
   Call it a tie. But Fox, like other networks before it, believes
it can only help to show off its stars in the stands at famed
temples of baseball like Yankees Stadium, or Qualcomm Stadium in
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Fox is even trying to squeeze some promotional
value out of the national anthem. Lisa Nicole Carson of ``Ally
McBeal'' is singing it before the game. The anthem is not
automatically part of the pregame festivities in a network's
coverage, but Fox will arrange the schedule to get Ms. Carson's
performance in front of the big prime-time audience.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting stars and shows is one way a network tries to get its
money's worth from the millions of dollars it spends to acquire the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Fox executives were feeling as if they got some extra
bounce for Monday's episode of ``Ally McBeal,'' which scored the
highest rating in the show's history in the country's 40 biggest
cities. Could it have helped just a little that the World Series
games played over the weekend included a promotion for the show
featuring Calista Flockhart's Ally, in a fantasy sequence, leaping
onto a guest star, John Ritter, and wrapping her micro-miniskirted
legs around his head?
</P>
<P>
   The World Series has helped Fox to its best ratings of the
season, though the network still finished behind both NBC and CBS.
NBC, despite a sizeable falloff in its Thursday-night lineup, still
easily led the other networks in every ratings category, from total
viewers to young-adult viewers. (Viewership for the World Series,
by the way, was down 4 percent from last year for the first two
games.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of Fox's promotion during the games is devoted to the
network's shows lined up for the November rating sweep, which
begins on Oct. 29. Fox hopes to create enormous anticipation for
events like the first television showing of ``Jurassic Park II: The
Lost World'' on Nov. 1 and the season premiere of ``The X-Files''
on Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Those two Sundays are shaping up as the biggest showdowns of the
sweep month. On the night of Nov. 1, for example, NBC is countering
dinosaurs with soul music with the first part of a mini-series
about the career of the Temptations, while ABC is offering a potent
movie double-header with ``101 Dalmatians'' at 7 and the Oprah
Winfrey-produced remake of ``David and Lisa'' at 9.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 8, against the return of Mulder and Scully on ``The
X-Files,'' CBS is bringing out its sequel to ``Roots,'' called
``Mama Flora's Family,'' and NBC is reuniting Chris Noth with
characters from ``Law and Order,'' playing his old role of
Detective Mike Logan in a movie called ``Exiled.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   GUNS, BUTTER AND TV
</P>
<P>
   To most Americans, market news once meant hikes in hamburger
prices. Now, the market means first and foremost the stock market,
and viewers are following it more closely than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence? On Monday, CNN will more than double the number of
stock market updates that it carries from its financial-news sister
channel, CNNfn, to 19 a day from 9. The two-minute updates will run
twice an hour on CNN from 8:15 a.m. until 4:15 p.m., as well as a
report at 7:30 a.m. and a wrap-up at 6:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Also, CNN has begun carrying a corner-of-the-screen graphic
updating Dow Jones and NASDAQ stock market averages all day. The
Fox News Channel carries those two and the Standard &AMP; Poor Index.
MSNBC carries the Dow only.
</P>
<P>
   Since CNN's ``Moneyline News Hour,'' with Lou Dobbs as anchor,
expanded to a full hour from a half-hour last June, its Nielsen
ratings have increased 20 percent, to an average of 420,000
households daily.
</P>
<P>
   And CNBC, the business-news cable channel owned by NBC and
operated with Dow Jones, has seen its average Nielsen ratings swell
to 80 percent higher this fall than at the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC has been adding layman-friendly features like a ``ticker
guide'' explaining how to read the stock-market ticker and primers
on understanding mutual funds; the network is also preparing a
glossary of financial terms for its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple reason is that people are now managing their
retirement funds through what's called a 401(k) plan,'' said Bill
Bolster, president of CNBC. ``So people at the $75,000 income or
asset level get involved, and are interested in various company's
profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs of ``Moneyline'' also points out that the most important
news stories today are often about economics. ``Most engagements
globally now are economic rather than political or military,'' he
said. ``Economics is not just a market story; it's a social
story.''
</P>
<P>
   As the market falls, business-news viewership rises: CNBC hit
its highest level ever on Aug. 31, the day the Dow Jones industrial
average dropped 512 points. That day one million households tuned
in to CNBC's ``Market Wrap,'' a number that does not include
out-of-home viewing in offices, and an average of 440,000 homes
tuned in between 5 a.m. and 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   During market hours, 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m., CNBC's average in
September was 382,000 households, an increase of almost 100 percent
from September 1997. For CNNfn, the going is tougher because it
reaches only 10 million homes, while CNN is in more than 75 million
homes and CNBC in more than 65 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, we could neatly define stories as consumer or business,
finance or market,'' said Dobbs, who is also president of CNNfn.
``They are inextricably entwined now _ in reality and also in the
understanding of most viewers or readers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1741EDT &QL; 
