<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-MILLENIUM-PROPHETS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MILLENIUM -- A CHANCE TO SCARE PEOPLE INTO HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Are You Y2K OK?'' So runs this week's ad for National Y2K
Action Week. ``Y2K'' refers to a computer bug -- a programming
problem.
 &HT;    If programmers do not fix billions of lines of code, it is
possible that on Jan. 1, 2000, some of the world's computers will
either fail or issue bad information. Since many public services
and private industries are computerized, Y2K could prove anything
from annoying to disruptive or potentially disastrous. Thus, some
have dubbed this bug the ``millennium bomb.''
 &HT;    For many months, apocalyptic techno-prophets have urged citizens
to stockpile supplies, pull money out of banks and the stock
market, and prepare for disaster. The Internet is ablaze with
end-of-the-world scenarios about, in the words of one, ``The
biggest problem that the modern world has ever faced.''
 &HT;    Among the most hysterical are conservative Christians -- the
folks usually associated with the political religious right.
Christian talk radio, full of anti-Clinton tirades, also
reverberates with Y2K doomsday fears. Pat Robertson's television
program frequently covers Y2K issues and maintains a Y2K Web site.
 &HT;    The Christian Y2K propaganda threatens everything from world
bankruptcy to nuclear disaster.
 &HT;    Quoting computer experts, secular journalists, and the Bible,
these prophets caution: ``Be ready -- even to head for the hills!''
The religious right has been oddly quiet this election year;
perhaps they are too busy stocking supplies in the basement to
vote.
 &HT;    As the world nears the new millennium, I anticipated some
apocalyptic fervor to grip society. After all, Christian societies
have periodically suffered millennial anxiety: around 1000, and
again in the 1300s, the early 1500s, the mid-1800s, and the late
1900s.
 &HT;    Millennial fever is nothing new -- especially in the United
States where various fundamentalist groups have predicted the end
in every decade since the World War II.
 &HT;    What I could not predict, however, was the form this anxiety
would take. With the decline of Soviet communism, all the good
candidates for Antichrist disappeared. No single person or event
seemed powerful enough to plunge us into global crisis. That is, of
course, until Y2K transmuted itself into a (potential)
technological Great Tribulation. What's next? A cyber Antichrist?
 &HT;    While some Christians fear apocalypse, they also use it to their
advantage. Scaring people into heaven is an effective evangelistic
technique -- and an age-old Christian tradition.
 &HT;    From reliefs on medieval cathedrals depicting the fate of the
damned to hellfire-and-brimstone sermons and Halloween ``Judgment
Houses,'' a particular strand of Christianity emphasizes the power
of human fear over divine love. Play on anxieties -- especially
about loss, illness and death -- and people will give money and get
saved.
 &HT;    Few strategies so directly contradict Jesus' teaching. Although
later Christian writers interjected the Gospels with apocalyptic
fears, Jesus himself preached against such concerns. He overtly
resisted attempts to make him an end-of-the-world Messiah.
 &HT;    Instead, he preached on loving God and one's neighbors --
insisting the long-hoped-for millennial kingdom would not come in
glory but as a mustard seed. His kingdom's soil is love -- not
fear.
 &HT;    Don't try telling that to the Y2K prophets. Under the guise of
Christian concern, they are selling salvation through donations and
speaker's fees. Fear is, after all, a robust commodity.
 &HT;    And Y2K? Yes, we -- human beings -- have created an inconvenient
nuisance. Y2K probably will not be a technological Armageddon.
However, no one can really predict what will happen on January 1,
2000.
 &HT;    A colleague of mine recently guessed, ``On that morning, I'll
wake up and the world will be the same as the day before.'' That's
one prediction I'm willing to bet on.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
