<HEADER>
A7491 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN21-COX     10-20 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Applewhite is UT's best bet under center
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Even though the NBA players remain locked out of
their training camps, the first slam dunk of the year comes this
week.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Texas football coach Mack Brown must decide whether
to keep redshirt freshman Major Applewhite or bring back fifth-year
senior Richard Walton as his starting quarterback against Baylor on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Logic, common sense and proper attention to the future, as well
as the last four games, dictate that Applewhite takes the first
snap, as I believe he will. The upside is too great to do anything
else. That should not be construed as a slap at Walton, who it says
here can produce numbers _ and maybe even won-lost records _
similar to those of his previous understudy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's just a tremendous vote of confidence for a
freckle-faced rookie with uncanny accuracy, great touch on the deep
ball, poise beyond his years and a perpetual deadpan expression on
his boyish face.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Walton has yet to prove he is 100 percent recovered
from the broken finger in his right hand, and he has had lingering
soreness in his wrist and forearm. Walton deserves to be treated
with respect for his loyalty to the program and his abilities and
should be given every chance to wrest the job from Applewhite.
Until he does so in practice or Applewhite falters on game day,
though, Walton will have to contribute as a reserve this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of fans get excited any time there is a quarterback
controversy,'' Brown said playfully. ``It's like a dog around raw
meat. This is good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he and offensive coordinator Greg Davis will make the
``hard decision'' at some point this week and will base their final
choice on what's best for the team. That should be the sole factor
behind the decision.
</P>
<P>
   I've never been one to agree with coaches who automatically
return the quarterback's job to an injured incumbent once he
recovers. Minnesota's Randall Cunningham has replaced Brad Johnson
and thrown 12 touchdown passes without a single interception, but
Vikings Coach Dennis Green vows to put Johnson under center when
he's healthy. HELLO _ if Johnson were Brett Favre, that idea might
have some merit.
</P>
<P>
   Few will second-guess Chan Gailey for removing Jason Garrett for
a mended Troy Aikman, Garrett's 3-2 record notwithstanding. And if
Walton were, say, a more proven James Brown, then the decision
becomes harder.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Mack Brown should give the job back to Walton _ who
started the first two games _ to properly reward the veteran who
has paid his dues or risk sending a wrong message to other players.
However, doing that would send a wrong signal to the quarterbacks'
teammates. To start anyone other than the best player for the
position is to do a disservice to every player who busts his tail
Monday through Friday to work his way up the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Walton is a good quarterback with a 2-2 record in four career
starts and five games of eligibility remaining. Applewhite is a
good quarterback who has led Texas to a 3-1 record and has three
years of eligibility left after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started our comeback against UCLA with Richard, and he had
a great third quarter,'' Brown said. ``We scored 66 points in the
opener with him. They're not two bad players.''
</P>
<P>
   At his weekly press conference Monday, Brown even took an
informal poll of 16 sportswriters. Fifteen voted to keep Applewhite
as the starter, with one abstention.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite brings big-time instincts, a big-enough arm and a
big-game presence without having grown a big head. Even though he
ranks 17th nationally in pass efficiency after four consecutive
200-yard passing games, he'd give himself ``probably a C'' for a
midseason grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just average,'' he said. ``Not outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Major. You haven't done one thing remotely average. Since
Applewhite, as a high school junior, first noticed Walton and his
strong arm during warmups for the 1996 Sugar Bowl, he has looked up
to Walton. If ever two people could co-exist at this one
high-profile position, it's Applewhite and Walton. Both are classy,
up-front players who put their team above personal goals and
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not be mad if Richard was the starting quarterback,''
Applewhite said. ``I'd be more than glad to take the second-team
role for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unlikely scenario, he won't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
