<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ WASHINGTON _ The latest developments out of the
Middle East peace talks taking place at the Wye Plantation on
Maryland's Eastern Shore between Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-HUME _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ About 15 years ago, John
Hume _ who last week won the Nobel Peace Prize _ built a little
stone cottage on a spit of land overlooking the River Foyle in
Donegal, just a few miles over the Northern Ireland border. The
chances of his being assassinated were somewhat diminished on this
remote and windswept promontory. Hume liked to sit in his yard and
watch ships ply the Foyle on their way to and from Derry. He smoked
too many cigarettes while he stared out to sea. I sat with him in
his yard a few times. He told me more than once that this was the
last bit of Ireland seen by emigrants as they sailed to America and
Canada. How sad, he would say, that after almost everybody was
driven out of Ireland, those few who remained took to killing each
other. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp.'s attorneys make
opening arguments Tuesday in the federal government's antitrust
suit, and the government's first witness, Netscape chief James
Barksdale, takes the stand. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUDGE _ Last December, when Microsoft Corp. insisted
that the Windows 95 operating system wouldn't work without its
Internet browser, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
decided to find out for himself. With help from a courtroom
technician, the judge was able to ``uninstall'' his own Explorer
Internet browser in about 90 seconds. So Jackson ordered the
software giant to begin selling Windows 95 separate from its
browser. While that order was overturned on appeal _ Jackson's dive
into the technical aspects of the case is indicative of his
approach to law. (Regan, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Reporting on the White House sex
scandal was largely accurate but there were shortcomings, a study
of six major lines of coverage by the Committee of Concerned
Journalists said Tuesday. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM-STUDY _ Nearly two-thirds of telecom leaders say that
the Federal Communications Commission is doing its job and the
landmark 1996 Telecommunications Act doesn't need to be reopened,
according to a survey by the Small Business Survival Project.
(Regan, Cox News Service 300).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   HAVE-NOTS _ WASHINGTON _ More Americans view themselves as
``have-nots'' rather than ``haves,'' according to a new Gallup poll
designed to measure American perceptions of fairness and
opportunity. A decade ago, only 17 percent considered themselves
``have-nots,'' and today it's 25 percent. Today, according to the
poll, the number of Americans reporting economic deprivation ranges
from 11 percent who said they did not have enough money for food,
18 percent for clothing and 22 percent for health care. Still, in
general, Americans are more positive and more optimistic than they
have been in any of Gallup's seven previous measurements, beginning
in 1964. (Shepard, Cox News Service 700).
</P>
<P>
   HAVE-NOTS-DATA _ Highlights of the poll. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-STANDARDS _ WASHINGTON _ A new poll says that nearly 82
percent of American parents think academic standards at their
childrens' schools are too low, says the Council for Basic
Education. In addition, most parents said it would be easier for
them to know if local schools were performing well if they had
greater access to model standards written by national experts.
(Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NON-VOTERS _ SEATTLE _ The young and the poor are the least
likely Americans to vote, and the participation gap is widening. A
look at the causes and the effects. (Shepard).
</P>
<P>
   NON-VOTERS-DATA _ A statistical look at non-voters.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SCHOLARSHIPS _ WASHINGTON _ A bill that will allow
employers to hire more foreign high-tech workers will also
establish new job training programs for American workers and
scholarships for low-income students. The National Science
Foundation, which now only awards grants, says the implementation
of a new scholarship program will be a daunting task. (Monroe, Cox
News Service)
</P>
