<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION SEES LITTLE CHANCE OF WINNING IN MEXICAN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A leader of the center-left Democratic Revolution
Party, or PRD, virtually conceded defeat Tuesday in the
gubernatorial election scheduled Sunday in the northeastern state
of Tamaulipas.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Ortega Martinez, national secretary-general of the party,
said the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, has
employed a high-rolling strategy of lavish spending for the
campaign of its candidate, Tomas Yarrington Ruvalcaba.
</P>
<P>
   And Ortega accused the PRI of using state-owned vehicles to give
away food, medicines and building materials in Yarrington's name to
influence voters.
</P>
<P>
   Yarrington said in a recent interview that he had heard rumors
about the alleged food giveaways, and he denied the charges made by
the PRD, dismissing them as dirty politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously at a disadvantage,'' Ortega said at a news
conference at party headquarters here. ``But we do expect to obtain
a good showing for our party.''
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Hernandez Correa is the PRD candidate for governor.
Besides Yarrington, the other principal candidate is Gustavo
Cardenas Gutierrez, from the center-right National Action Party, or
PAN.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released by the University of Guadalajara last week
showed Yarrington leading Cardenas 56 percent to 18 percent, with
Hernandez at a distant 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tamaulipas is now governed by the PRI's Manuel Cavazos Lerma. He
is barred by law from running for another term.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega said his party is at a disadvantage because state
vehicles are used to pass out cooking oil, beans and rice, and
building materials to the state's desperately poor residents. Such
practices violate Mexican campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders in Tamaulipas have allegedly uncovered at least
two warehouses where such supplies are kept, and two weeks ago, a
state-owned truck in the southern port city of Altamira was
discovered carrying giveaway food and Yarrington campaign
literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is what we know about, you can imagine what they are
doing all over the state,'' Ortega said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega said the party would file charges with the Mexican
federal attorney general's office based on the discoveries, and
called for PRI candidates in areas where such irregularities occur
to be removed from the ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
