<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GLENN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO ATTEND GLENN'S LIFTOFF ABOARD DISCOVERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN DRAKE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will travel to Cape Canaveral
next week for the scheduled liftoff of the shuttle Discovery with
Sen. John Glenn aboard, but his presence shouldn't add any
additional pressure to have a launch, NASA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants ``to recognize Sen. Glenn's historic return to
space and to recognize the importance of our nation's space program
and the hard work of the men and women that make that program
possible,'' Joe Lockhart, White House press secretary, said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio senator, who is retiring this year, was also a key
congressional ally, defending Clinton and other Democrats during
hearings about the 1996 campaign fund-raising scandals.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the president's presence might put pressure on
mission managers to stretch safety guidelines to ensure liftoff,
Seymour Himmel, a member of NASA's Aerospace Safety Advisory Panel
replied: ``No way. It's going to be within the boundaries that are
allowed or it ain't going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time a U.S. president has watched a launch was when
President Nixon witnessed the takeoff in 1969 of Apollo 12. The
rocket was struck by lightning twice as it passed through storm
clouds after liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   After his stop at Cape Canaveral on Oct. 29, the president will
attend a fund-raising reception for Congressman Peter Deutsch and
Lt. Gov. Buddy McKay, in West Palm Beach. He will return to
Washington late that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd have to dig really deep to find something wrong
with the president going down and celebrating this great
achievement, both for NASA and for Sen. Glenn,'' Lockhart said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
