<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Wednesday, Oct. 21. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Wye Mills, Md.) _ With King Hussein of Jordan
joining President Clinton at the Middle East peace talks, optimism
rose on Tuesday that at least a partial settlement will be reached
between Israelis and Palestinians after more than 19 months of
stalemate and six days of talking here. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-CLINTON-CRITICISM (Washington) _ Responding to waves of
grousing in the nation's military about President Clinton's affair
with Monica Lewinsky, military leaders have begun warning officers
and enlisted personnel that they could well face punishment for
public denunciations of the commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Stinging from the
government's opening statement, the Microsoft Corp. forcefully
defended its chairman, Bill Gates, in federal court Tuesday. By
Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SIBERIA (Yakutsk) _ To the Russians crazy enough to live
there, summer in the Siberian Arctic is merely a deep breath before
the next winter, a few weeks of melted ice and midnight sun in
which to gird for the next deep freeze. Either they use those weeks
to haul in enough food and fuel to make it to the next thaw, or
they shiver and starve through the coming months of darkness. It is
easy to call Russia's travails political or fiscal crises. But here
in the Siberian republic of Yakutiya, where a bad debt can condemn
thousands to months of hunger, they can be a matter of survival. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GAY-MARCHERS (New York) _ For some of the younger marchers
who took to the streets on Monday night to protest the killing of a
homosexual college student in Wyoming, it was their first time in a
big demonstration. For some of the older marchers it was it was a
return to street protests after a long absence, a chance to revive
the chants of years past and practice the old street skills.
</P>
<P>
   Eds., TRADE in early editions, YANKS later:
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The Commerce Department on Tuesday
provided a surprisingly alarming measure of the effects the global
economic downturn is having on the American economy, reporting that
the nation's trade defict widened by $2.2 billion in August to a
record figure of $16.77 billion. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-YANKS-PADRES (San Diego) _ Yankees-Padres, Game 4. 8:10 p.m.
ET staart. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   Eds., these will be NYT Page 1 refers:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ The House is expected to give
final approval to a budget deal Tuesday afternoon; Senate to vote
on Wednesday. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JONES (St. Paul, Minn.) _ The 8th Circuit Court of
Appeals hears arguments in the appeal of the dismissed Paula Jones
suit against President Clinton. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
</TEXT>
