u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEANUTS-HNS &LR;      10-20 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AND CLINTON ARE SET TO KILL PEANUT RULE ON AIRPLANES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Peanut lovers who fly are among the winners in the
$500 billion spending bill that President Clinton is expected to
sign later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will crunch a U.S. Department of Transportation
order requiring the nation's 10 largest airlines to provide
peanut-free zones of at least three rows on an aircraft whenever
passengers notify the airline that they suffer from peanut
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT order in August was inspired by concerns that passengers
with peanut allergies could have adverse reactions to airborne
peanut particles. The order was based on the 1986 Air Carrier
Access Act, a federal law guaranteeing access to airlines for the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from peanut-growing states led the move in Congress to
cancel the order.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard C. Shelby, R-Ala., who hails from a
peanut-producing state and chairs the Senate transportation
appropriations subcommittee, led the charge, arguing that a
government order assigning passengers to peanut-friendly or
peanut-free seats ``is not only failing to use common sense, it is
an absolutely ludicrous response to a problem that there is little,
if any, evidence to substantiate its existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The DOT order is one reason ``why so many people have come to
resent and distrust government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation nullifying the DOT order is expected to win
final congressional approval Wednesday and be signed by the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Peanut-allergy sufferers say there is nothing nutty about the
allergies and that they can risk death by ingesting the nuts. A
1996 Mayo Clinic study found that allergens from peanuts can wash
through ventilation system filters and spread around an airplane's
interior.
</P>
<P>
   A peanut reaction can include an itchy mouth, wrists and hands,
swelling, hives, wheezing and a drop in blood pressure and can lead
to death unless a person gets a shot of epinephrine, a drug also
know as adrenaline that rapidly boosts blood pressure and heart
rate, stabilizing the body's vital systems.
</P>
<P>
   They say some can get a reaction by even smelling peanut protein
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Peanut Council in Alexandria, Va., says that
the idea of creating peanut-free zones was ``really an absurd
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the most practical way to go,'' said Jeannette
Anderson, the council's president. ``Anyone who has a small child
and is traveling on an airplane is very likely to have a peanut
butter sandwich stashed away... It creates a false sense of
security for passengers who think there will be no peanuts on an
airplane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
