<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Must we force physics upon our daughters?
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The knock on professional feminists is that women dislike them
even more than men. A man doesn't have to utter a peep when the
likes of Sally Quinn and even Betty Friedan deny all association.
Friedan broke with the National Organization for Women in the '70s,
criticizing its hardening ideology. Quinn, in The Washington Post
several years ago, wrote a piece no man could ever write. The
headline asked, ``Who Killed Feminism?'' The answer was given in
the subhead: ``Hypocritical Movement Leaders Betrayed Their Own
Cause.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is proud to be called one anymore, but the fact is that
all of us, male and female, are feminists in principle. We believe
in equal pay for equal work, in equal opportunities for men and
women, in equality before the law _ in short, we believe in
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   And we especially believe in fairness for our children. We don't
just believe in it; we will fight for it.
</P>
<P>
   So the radio ad by the Women's College Coalition last week
struck the ear with an odd note of remoteness from the lives of men
and women I know. Get your daughter interested in chemistry and
physics at an early age, it said in so many words. Point her toward
engineering, technology, computers.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was clear, and it was reinforced by a report the same
week from the American Association of University Women: Our girls
are getting shortchanged again. They're not going into the sciences
and engineering in the same numbers as boys.
</P>
<P>
   This in itself is not news, but the reasons given are. Because
it's hard to argue anymore that girls are restricted, new buzzwords
have entered the picture. Between the fifth and ninth grades, the
Women's College Coalition tells us, girls' talents and abilities go
``underground.'' In their hearts our girls are really chemical
engineers and mathematicians, but ``a chilly environment''
discourages them and so they settle for something else. And that
something else is, by implication, something less.
</P>
<P>
   If this is so, then what have all those women teachers in the
elementary schools and high schools been doing? Encouraging the
boys, but discouraging the girls?
</P>
<P>
   The Women's College Coalition, trusting studies by a pair of
academics named Myra and David Sadker, says that's exactly what
they've been doing. ``Women teachers have the same prejudices male
teachers have,'' says Jadwiga Sebrechts, president of the Women's
College Coalition. They toss the girls the softball questions and
look to the boys for more analytical responses.
</P>
<P>
   One listens to such things with a weary sigh. A glance at the
newspaper tells you the world's not a happy place for many people,
and here is someone worried about a gender gap in engineering. Why
should we be certain girls want to be engineers and scientists in
the first place? And why is it, by the way, that social and
developmental problems are preponderantly a male thing?
</P>
<P>
   It gets down _ of course _ to numbers. Only 8 percent of
graduate degrees in physics are awarded to females. To Jadwiga
Sebrechts this is a gender gap. It's obviously a statistical
difference _ you could even say a gaping one _ but is it
necessarily evidence of injustice? Are young women not going into
physics and chemistry because the environment conditions them to
look elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   When reality doesn't conform to expectation, something's wrong
with the environment. The Women's College Coalition, which
represents colleges in the United States and Canada, wants to
encourage women to consider other fields besides teaching,
psychology, home ec _ the girls' ghetto. But what percentage in
physics, say, would reflect a fair shake? Would it require
statistical parity _ something close to 50-50?
</P>
<P>
   Sebrechts, who was trained as a physicist, speaks only of ``a
critical mass,'' perhaps 15 percent, that would be enough to raise
the temperature in the physics department and encourage more women.
(There are places colder yet: ``The really bad ones for women are
electrical engineering and soil mechanics.'')
</P>
<P>
   But assume that 15 percent of the graduate degrees in physics
were going to women, and that it was enough to attract other women.
If it was double that _ 30 percent women, 70 percent men _ why
should one assume equity had been achieved? That's the problem when
numbers are the only evidence.
</P>
<P>
   On National Public Radio last week, a correspondent grave with
concern reported the American Association of University Women's
``findings.'' One third of college males major in some
technological field, but only one quarter of females. The worried
correspondent asked Christina Hoff Sommers, professor of philosophy
at Clark University, her thoughts. Sommers calls herself a feminist
but has problems with ``studies'' like this. Doesn't there seem to
be a gender gap? NPR's reporter asked.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers' weary sigh sounds just like mine. ``Absolute myth,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her book ``Who Stole Feminism?'' Sommers neatly exposes the
statistical sleights of hand from which all these gaps are deduced.
But you still have the hard fact that not many girls seem to like
engineering, chemistry and physics. To say it has to be the
environment _ but where exactly in the environment? _ sounds, after
a while, like witchcraft. Yes, and if the cat had her litter in the
oven, I suppose they'd come out biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Every father I know would be proud to see MIT confer a doctorate
on his daughter. Just as proud as he'd be if it were his son. But
what goes on in the hearts and minds of any parent takes in quite a
lot more than just that. The professional feminists have no sense
of this. To them, that's all there is _ the woman is her career,
and this rest is trappings. Wherever her interests and aptitude
take her, I pray my daughter finds more in her life than a career.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
