<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Launching Glenn into space _ again
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one of those weeks where the magazine world doesn't seem to
be operating as a well-oiled cartel, all of the newsweeklies
pumping out slick versions of the same cover story.
</P>
<P>
   What must be on America's mind, the editors of Newsweek ($2.95)
have ascertained, is shooting a 77-year-old senator into space _
and it has nothing to do with the Congressional investigation of
President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's cover is devoted to John Glenn's next space shot
(36 years after he rode Friendship 7 into history as the first
American to orbit the Earth), and is a launching point for a report
on the science of aging.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine says Glenn's Oct. 29 journey is reassuring, if for
no other reason than it reminds us that aging Americans can ``do a
lot more than crossword puzzles.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SHEPARD CASE: Time ($2.95) devotes its cover to the Laramie,
Wyo., murder of gay college student Matthew Shepard (``The War Over
Gays''), and how that slaying has galvanized the gay community and
cleaved the political landscape into factions for and against
acceptance of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay politics is more complicated than ever right now because
what seems like an irresistible force of cultural change is meeting
an immovable object of political resistance,'' reports the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Time/CNN poll, 64 percent of respondents believe
homosexual relations are acceptable, but 48 percent say they are
morally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   HOT JOBS: U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.95) explores the best
jobs for the future in an annual career guide. Among the Top 20,
according to the magazine, are careers in environmental accounting,
advertising Web specialist, communications technical writer, nanny,
physical therapist, real estate attorney and molecular biologist.
</P>
<P>
   An inside story (``Where Is Eric Rudolph?'') details the FBI's
search for the man whom the feds charged last week with three
Atlanta-area bombings, including the 1996 blast at Centennial
Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   `PUFF DADDY'S' TURNING POINT: Rap mogul Sean ``Puff Daddy''
Combs is interviewed in Essence ($2.75) by the musician's friend,
godmother and the magazine's editor-in-chief _ ``Auntie'' Susan
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Combs tells her that the 1991 incident in which nine young
people died when fans rushed the doors at a celebrity basketball
event in New York that he helped promote ``broke me .. . the world
turned against me. ... For a while I was probably clinically
insane.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he's turned his life around and is spending more time
with his children. ``I feel good that at this age what I'm most
concerned about is finding inner peace and happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   GIVING THANKS: Life's Thanksgiving issue ($3.99) considers the
``100 Best Things About America Now,'' which includes No. 37,
``Aging Gracefully'' (see: John Glenn), and No. 52, ``The Taco Bell
Chihuahua.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEXT: The New Yorker ($3.95) offers cultural forecasts on
TV, theater, fashion, books and music in its double Next! issue.
Among its picks: the Fox cartoon ``Futurama,'' coming in January
from Matt Groening (``The Simpsons''). Also in The New Yorker:
Writer Louis Menand tackles the potentially mind-numbing subject of
Al Gore's political aspirations in a piece with a title that would
breath life into an obituary: ``After Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
