<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Founding Father's Sweet Apple grave to get its due
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anybody had ever told me I would jump up and down with
excitement over a group placing a headstone on an old grave in the
woods, I would have said it couldn't be so. But it was.
</P>
<P>
   I heard from George E. Thurmond that the members of the Piedmont
chapter of the Georgia Society of Sons of the American Revolution
are coming to Sweet Apple settlement at 11 a.m. Nov. 21 to place a
marker on the grave of James Adams, who was one of the builders of
my cabin.
</P>
<P>
   I knew about the grave. It's in the woods up the hill back of
Chadwick's store. The late Aubrey Chadwick walked me up there one
day shortly after I moved to Sweet Apple, and I was very touched to
see the lonesome, overgrown little grave.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for me to believe that a man who was in on the
birthing of our country could have been still alive and active when
his son cut the logs and put up my cabin early in the 19th century.
Neighbors told me Mr. Adams was a strong and active gentleman and
that those big rocks in the chimney were put there with his help.
</P>
<P>
   So now his service to our country is going to be formally noted
and celebrated. The Sons of the American Revolution have planned a
real program with a color guard, pledge of allegiance, unveiling a
marker, laying a wreath, taps and a benediction. I wouldn't miss it
for anything.
</P>
<P>
   There are not too many American Revolution veterans around, Mr.
Thurmond said. He knows of the graves of a few in Decatur, some in
an old cemetery near Tucker and some at Utoy cemetery south of
Atlanta. The most notable is the grave of John Clark, son of the
famous Elijah Clark, who went back to war with his wounded father
when he was a kid of 14, eventually became a two-star general and
was buried in Florida. His grave was later moved and now is marked
by a handsome monument in the national cemetery in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Thurmond suspects there were many Georgians fighting in the
revolution, but finding their graves has been difficult, although
he spends a great deal of time searching and checking with
historical groups. He feels that they should be well marked, and I
agree, especially since I feel a great bond with James Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Adams' great-great-grand-daughter Ann Wilt, who lives in
Charlotte, will speak at the ceremony, giving us some details of
his life. He volunteered July 24, 1776, with the 3rd Regiment of
South Carolina. I always wished I could have known him and asked
all those questions about where he fought and with whom.
</P>
<P>
   We will hear about him from Mrs. Wilt and her sister, Alecia
Jameson, who are to be at the grave-marking ceremony. I hope to
hear more of the Adams family, which dwelled in Sweet Apple cabin
so many years ago. They do know that he was married and had 11
children.
</P>
<P>
   The program will be open to the public, but there is a problem
about parking. They are asking people who wish to attend to meet at
the Kroger shopping center at Crabapple and Arnold Mill roads,
where car pooling will be provided. Chadwick's store and the little
grave are only three miles from there.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Thurmond calls it a one-grave cemetery, but Larry Chadwick
suspects there were other graves there, now sunk into the earth and
unmarked. He doesn't know why it was chosen for burials, since
there is no church close by, but he is pleased to report that weeds
and underbrush are being cut so the walk up the hill won't be as
difficult as I remember.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
