<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking `AIM' at suicide: Prevention plan unveiled
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time in this country when few people knew what to do
if someone choked on a piece of food. Now almost everyone knows
about the Heimlich maneuver. That didn't happen by accident.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of activists, health professionals and government
officials has proposed a similar _ if more complicated _ campaign
to reduce suicide, which takes the lives of more Americans than
AIDS or murder.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday in Atlanta, U.S. Surgeon General
David Satcher unveiled a national suicide prevention strategy that
emphasizes better training, more research, increased access to
mental health care and, above all, heightened public awareness
through education in the schools, Web sites, toll-free numbers,
resource centers and public service announcements. It's all
designed to put suicide on the national radar and convince people
that they, and not just doctors, can do something about
self-destructive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purely medical approach will not do the job,'' Satcher
said. ``By the time most suicidal people come into contact with
medical care, it's much too late.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy grew out of the National Suicide Prevention
Conference, a first-time summit of experts, activists and
policy-makers held last weekend in Reno, Nev. It was organized by
Jerry and Elsie Weyrauch of Marietta, who lost a daughter to
suicide. The conference resulted in 80 detailed recommendations,
which were boiled down to three areas of emphasis, summarized by
the acronym ``AIM'':
</P>
<P>
   -- Access. Enhance access to mental health services and improve
recognition of depression.
</P>
<P>
   -- Illuminate. Broaden public awareness and reduce the stigma
associated with mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   -- Methodology. Fund more research into the causes of suicide
and evaluate prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just making a list here. We're going to do things,''
said Mark Rosenberg, director of the CDC's violence prevention
branch, which has taken a leading role in the suicide fight.
``Suicide is preventable, and we can't keep that secret any
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
