<HEADER>
A7606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GENDER WARS, STILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been more than three decades since the
landmark 1964 Civil Rights Act decreed that job discrimination
against individuals on the basis of gender _ or race, color,
religion and national origin _ is not only morally but legally
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here we are, still stuck with a congressional leadership
determined to apply a double standard when it comes to federal
health benefits available to men and women.
</P>
<P>
   In the era of the two-paycheck household, House Republican
leaders waged a last-ditch battle to block insurance coverage for
contraceptives to protect women in the federal work force against
unwanted pregnancy. Both men and women benefit from birth control,
but the only prescription contraceptives available are taken by
women, who also bear the major care-giving burden of raising
children.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, those same conservatives readily approved $50 million
to subsidize prescriptions for Viagra to energize the sexual
relationships of male military personnel and veterans. The
government encourages men to have sex, but is reluctant to protect
women from the consequences of sex.
</P>
<P>
   Does this contradictory attitude toward the health care needs of
men and women make sense? Is sexual schizophrenia good public
policy? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   But it does reflect both the power of the religious right over
Republican politics and an ingrained cultural pattern that still
thinks that when it comes to sex it is okay for boys to be boys but
not for girls to be, well, like boys.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last sticking points in the massive budget battle
this week was a provision under which all federal employee
insurance plans must cover contraceptives just as they cover other
medical prescriptions. Currently, only 19 percent of federal health
plans cover all five of the most widely accepted contraceptive
drugs or devices _ birth control pills, diaphragms, IUDs, Norplant
and Depo-Provera _ and 10 percent offer no coverage whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   The battle was primarily symbolic. The law would affect only
federally employed civilian women of childbearing age. But if the
federal government dismisses contraceptives as unimportant to
employee well-being, private industry can feel free to do the same.
Often it already does.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Rep Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., a broad coalition of moderates
and liberals pushed the contraception amendment through both the
House and Senate attached to a major spending bill. But when it got
to the House-Senate conference, House Republican leaders
unilaterally tried to ax the provision in secret and thwart the
majority will. They were puppets for pro-life advocates who
dominate the GOP and view birth control as only slightly less
sinister than abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Lowey and her allies were on the alert, rode to the
rescue and saved the day _ and the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 Alan Guttmacher Institute study showed that in general
women pay about 68 percent more in out-of-pocket health expenses
than men, partly because many insurers don't cover basic
reproductive health services. By contrast, many insurance plans
provide coverage for male-only needs, such as drugs for urological
and prostate problems.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad that after so many decades we are still treating
women's health needs differently from men's _ and unequally.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was exposed 22 years ago, when the Supreme Court
ruled that the General Electric Company could exclude pregnancy in
its disability coverage for workers because, Justice William
Rehnquist wrote for the majority, it was ``not gender-based
discrimination at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist went on to note that insurance companies were free to
cover some risks and not others, and that there was no risk from
which men were protected but not women, or vice versa. The fact
that only women got pregnant was irrelevant
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the high bench, composed then entirely of male
justices, was oblivious to the fact that prostate problems,
male-only ailments, were commonly covered by insurance. Only
Justice William Brennan, in his dissent, noted acidly that ``it
offends common sense to suggest that ... pregnancy is not, at the
minimum, strongly sex-related.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision was so unjust that within two years
Congress passed a law specifically prohibiting discrimination
against pregnant women in any area of employment and requiring
employers with health plans to include coverage of the costs of
pregnancy and childbirth. President Jimmy Carter signed it
immediately, and most employers currently accommodate pregnant
workers without undue disruption or difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Now the issue has passed from equal treatment in the workplace
for pregnancy to equal treatment for prevention of it. And
conservatives are still trying to give women the short end of the
stick and claim gender discrimination has nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The new argument is that while insurance plans provide coverage
for male-only needs such as Viagra, those are medically necessary
costs. This is news. An erection may be desirable, but medically
necessary?
</P>
<P>
   Birth control, by contrast, is depicted as merely preventive and
therefore not necessary. What? Are not immunization shots, blood
pressure pills and allergy medication preventive measures commonly
covered? Tell the potential sufferers they are not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Equity for women in prescription insurance is still elusive. But
thanks to Lowey, Congress has made a start, despite Speaker Newt
Gingrich and his cronies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
