<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report: Press too reliable on Starr as source of information
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A report released Monday by an independent journalism watchdog
suggests that the press has become overly reliant on Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr as the source for reporting the scandal
involving President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington D.C.-based Committee of Concerned Journalists
found that overall coverage of the White House crisis in the last
seven months was sound, and the industry had been avoiding many of
the ethical lapses _ such as using unidentified sources _ that were
evident when the story first broke in January.
</P>
<P>
   But the 38-page report ``The Clinton Lewinsky Story: How
Accurate? How Fair?'' also observed that some journalists at major
TV stations and newspapers had developed ``a penchant to emphasize
the perspective of investigators over those being investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also cited a quote from Starr in which he said his
dealings with the press were akin to working with ``informants.''
Critics of Starr's office have accused him of leaking secret grand
jury testimony in order to shape public opinion. The judge
presiding over the grand jury has also asked Starr to show cause
why he should not be held in contempt for leaking prejudicial
information.
</P>
<P>
   The report focused on six major ``threads'' that had been widely
reported in the case, everything from the infamous blue dress
belonging to Lewinksy to apparently false stories that Clinton also
had affairs with other White House interns.
</P>
<P>
   In most of those stories, the report concluded, ``the press
ferried speculation, some of which could have been construed as
threats from investigators into news accounts, raising questions
about whether the press was sufficiently wary of being used by
sources.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
