<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7608 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOLFE-COX     10-20 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fictional Croker looms large over Atlanta's landscape until his
real estate empire goes bust in Wolfe's new book
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though the Atlanta Chamber of Commerce is not likely to put Tom
Wolfe's latest novel on its required reading list, the city comes
off much better than some people feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $28.95) will not hit
shelves until Nov. 10, but some reviewers received advance copies
Monday. Without divulging too much of the plot, here's a preview of
what to expect:
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia-born novelist's first major work since ``The
Bonfire of the Vanities'' 11 years ago begins in the heat of
Freaknik and ends with the cool teachings of the Greek Stoic
philosopher Epictetus. In between, Wolfe uses a broad brush and a
wide canvas to capture the multiple racial and economic layers of
metropolitan Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The novel traces the lives of three men: Charlie Croker, an
Atlanta real estate developer and conglomerate magnate; Roger White
II, a black lawyer in a white-glove Atlanta firm; and Conrad
Hensley, the 23-year-old son of hippie parents.
</P>
<P>
   Croker, a former Georgia Tech football hero, has a young second
wife, a 29,000-acre South Georgia plantation, a half-empty office
complex in Cherokee County and a debt of more than a half-billion
dollars. As the novel opens, Croker is on the verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Another key player is Fareek ``the Cannon'' Fanon, a black
superstar running back at Georgia Tech whose athletic prowess
propelled him out of the city's slums. Fanon is accused of
date-raping the white daughter of one of the city's wealthiest blue
bloods.
</P>
<P>
   As word of possible criminal charges against Fanon leaks out,
racial tensions begin to bubble, and Roger White II, an upscale
black lawyer, is asked to represent the athlete and keep the lid on
a potentially explosive situation.
</P>
<P>
   Especially concerned about the problem is White's old Morehouse
College classmate Wesley Dobbs Jordan, who is in the midst of a
re-election campaign against black activist Andre Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the characters may sound familiar, but Wolfe has been
careful to make them composites of real Atlantans. Fleet's charge
that the light-skinned mayor is a ``beige half brother'' echoes the
Marvin Arrington-Bill Campbell campaign, but Wolfe casually
mentions Maynard Jackson and Bill Campbell as previous mayors in
the same paragraph as Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for the real estate developers. Wolfe uses
pieces of several developers _ from John Portman to Tom Cousins _
to create the larger-than-life Croker.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the novel's main character is Atlanta, which
is described perfectly by Jordan as a baseball: ``After you take
the white horsehide cover off, you come across a ball of white
string. ... Finally you get down to the core, which is black, a
small hard black rubber ball. Well, that's Atlanta. The hard core,
if we're talking politics, are the 280,000 black folks in South
Atlanta. ... Wrapped all around them, like all that white string,
are the three million white people in North Atlanta and all those
counties ... Cobb, DeKalb, Gwinnett, Forsyth, Cherokee, Paulding.
...''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, who was introduced to Atlanta and South Georgia
plantation life by real estate developer Mack Taylor and his wife,
Mary Rose, makes use of his reporter's skills in describing the
city. In one section, Jordan takes White on a driving tour of
Atlanta, up Piedmont Road into Buckhead and onto West Paces Ferry
Road, Tuxedo Road and beyond. As they drive, Jordan explains that
Atlanta is 1,000 feet above sea level and they're driving uphill.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some people in Atlanta are more elevated than others,''
Jordan says, ``and you know what they say always flows downhill.
You and I live in the best parts of South Atlanta, but don't kid
yourself. We still live downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe touches on every area of Atlanta, from Buckhead to
Bankhead, and on social levels from ``Chambodia'' _ the ethnically
diverse community along Buford Highway _ to the cream of Atlanta
society that belongs to the Piedmont Driving Club.
</P>
<P>
   In one chapter, Wolfe presents an acerbic view of Atlanta's arts
community in describing a show of homoerotic paintings at the High
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   As Croker looks in horror at some of the images, he wonders if
he's out of step with the times. ``Or were all these people ...
afraid to let it be known that they weren't sophisticated enough to
be cosmopolites of the new Atlanta, the international city?''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Rose Taylor, who has known Wolfe for years, admitted that
there were risks involved in introducing him to the inner sanctums
of Atlanta society.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of Tom's work is controversial,'' she said. ``And even
though he's a good friend, you don't open the door to the city you
love without considerable pause. His work is grounded in such solid
journalism, though, you have to trust that he will get things
right.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CHARACTERS
</P>
<P>
   -- Charlie Croker, a former Georgia Tech football hero who's now
one of Atlanta's biggest real estate developers. Because of a
failing ego project called Croker Concourse in Cherokee County, he
is more than $500 million in debt and in danger of losing his South
Georgia plantation, Turpmtine.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fareek ``the Cannon'' Fanon, a black football hero at Georgia
Tech who came from the slums. Fanon, a cocky, flashy athlete, is
accused of date-raping the daughter of one of Atlanta's wealthiest
blue bloods.
</P>
<P>
   -- Roger White II, a black lawyer from a silk-stocking firm who
is asked to represent Fanon and help keep a lid on the bubbling
racial unrest.
</P>
<P>
   -- Wesley Dobbs Jordan, Atlanta's black mayor, who is so
concerned about his light skin that he takes up golf to get a dark
tan in time for his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   -- Andre Fleet, a black activist who refers to Jordan as a
``beige half brother'' and is campaigning on the slogan ``It's time
Atlanta had its `first black mayor,''' discounting Maynard Jackson,
Andy Young, Bill Campbell and Jordan as not being dark enough.
</P>
<P>
   -- Conrad Hensley, a young man who is laid off from his job at
the Croker Global Foods Warehouse near Oakland, Calif., and finds
himself working as Charlie Croker's attendant after the developer's
knee replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   -- Raymond Peepgass, senior loan officer at PlannersBanc. In
charge of collecting the past-due loans from Croker, Peepgass has
financial problems of his own and is living in a small apartment
after his wife, miffed about Peepgass' affair with a Finnish
hooker, kicked him out of their Snellville house.
</P>
<P>
   -- Serena Croker, Charlie Croker's young ``trophy wife,'' who is
harder to handle than the rattlesnakes on Turpmtine plantation.
</P>
<P>
   -- Martha Croker, Charlie Croker's first wife, who finds herself
abandoned by Atlanta society after her divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
