<HEADLINE>
AILING KING HUSSEIN JOINS CLINTON TO PROD MIDEAST PEACE TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jordan's King Hussein threw his considerable
prestige into the Middle East peace talks Tuesday as he joined
President Clinton to push for an accord between Israel and the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The king, ailing with cancer and recovering from chemotherapy,
arrived at the Wye Plantation on Maryland's Eastern Shore amid
signs both sides were willing to continue negotiations to complete
a pact this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Hussein is a person of great integrity who has enormous
support amongst many different peoples in the Middle East. He's
someone who we hope will be able to instill in the two delegations
a greater understanding of the need to make the tough choices that
are necessary to reach an agreement,'' said James Rubin, the State
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we're into a phase of very hard bargaining, a lot of
the underbrush has been cleared away,'' Rubin said. ``It's part of
the end-game that is getting more and more serious. As we indicated
earlier, some obstacles have been overcome, but significant gaps
remain.''
</P>
<P>
   The peace talks in the rural Wye River setting entered their
sixth day with Clinton, having canceled a two-day campaign trip to
California, again spending the afternoon and evening at the Aspen
Institute compound.
</P>
<P>
   The president has spent five of the six days at the rural
complex, shuttling between the delegations. The negotiations have
been likened to the Camp David talks two decades ago that resulted
in a historic peace agreement between Israel and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The mood between the delegations of Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
brightened considerably Tuesday following a series of harsh
exchanges Monday stemming from a grenade attack in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, quoting anonymous sources, reported that
the Israelis and Palestinians have reached a tentative
understanding on several key points. The preliminary agreement
calls for Israel to withdraw from an additional 13 percent of the
West Bank over a 12-week period while the Palestinians move to
confiscate weapons from militant groups and to jail terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The United States would act to verify weapons seizures and
jailings, according to AP. But a major sticking point was whether
Israel would withdraw from even more territory.
</P>
<P>
   CNN reported disagreements over whether there would be a third
redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank, whether the
Palestinian Authority would extradite suspected terrorists to
Israel and whether the Palestinians would remove language in their
charter calling for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Israel had been pressing for a partial agreement. But AP quoted
Palestinian official Yasser Abed Rabbo as saying, ``we will reject
any formula for a partial agreement. We are insisting on a
comprehensive agreement, and that's what President Arafat has told
all the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and Palestinians remain in the interim stage of a
1993 peace accord that called for these issues to be resolved by
May 1999 so the discussions could turn to even more difficult
issues. Arafat has threatened to declare a Palestinian state if
there is no agreement by May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This phase of the peace talks have been locked in stalemate for
19 months after a series of terrorist attacks against Israelis.
Netanyahu repeatedly has demanded Palestinians craft a detailed
security plan for combating terrorists before agreed to cede more
control of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the right-wing factions of Netanyahu's coalition
government have threatened to topple him if he makes any agreement
during the Wye River talks to give back land.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank and East Jerusalem were once part of Jordan. King
Hussein, who lost the territory to Israel during a war, has called
for using the West Bank land for a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   The king, undergoing cancer treatment at the Mayo Clinic in
Minnesota, flew to his Washington area home on Monday. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright urged him to join the Wye River session.
King Hussein brokered a pact between the two sides last year over
Hebron. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
