<HEADLINE>
FLOODING SWAMPS CITY ON BANKS OF GUADALUPE RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, Texas _ The surging Guadalupe River rose higher than
anticipated here Tuesday as it continued on its destructive path,
displacing not only hundreds of people but dozens of wild animals
from a zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Alligators, ocelots and bald eagles were reluctantly freed from
cages to escape drowning in the rushing water.
</P>
<P>
   And rescuers interrupted early morning Mass at a downtown chapel
in Victoria, forcing the priests, nuns and about a dozen
parishioners to leave before floodwaters got any deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still hadn't had communion,'' said Sister Silvia Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had two or three hours before any water came,
but nobody thought it would happen,'' she said as she and another
nun were led to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 feet of rain in the San Antonio area swamped the
Guadalupe, sending floodwaters cascading downstream into cities
like Victoria. Hundreds of homes in the city were reported damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Zoo, spread out on six pristine acres in Riverside
Park here, was under several feet of water, trapping about 250
native Texas animals as the river rose to more than 31 feet,
blanketing everything but the tops of trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the animals we had to let go. We cut wires and let
them out,'' said Sherry Hornstein, executive director of the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let birds, deer out ... red wolves, four alligators. Goats
and pigs were on the roof. We're not worried about the pelicans,
ducks and geese because they can swim'' Hornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Zookeepers were in shock and in tears as they put the few
animals they could save in pet carriers to take to veterinarian
clinics. They said they didn't want to ask authorities for a boat
because they were being used to rescue people from homes or
rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come first,'' one worker said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day in this South Texas city of 65,000, rescuers
in helicopters, boats and city dump trucks plucked drenched
residents from flooded homes.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Mader, the city safety officer, said there was a danger of
power being cut off throughout Victoria because water was nearing a
dike at the Central Power and Light substation.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhoods of Greens Edition, Old Victoria and Cheapside
that hug the river as it bends around the city _ and much of
downtown _ were under water. Mader said 600 people had left their
homes, and boats and helicopters had rescued at least 60 people
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The police, firefighters and Red Cross workers had gone door to
door Monday, warning people to get out, but not everyone heeded the
warning. After all, the river had never come up so high before.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't cooperative yesterday. That's why we're having to
rescue them now,'' fire Capt. said Rafael de la Garza said Tuesday.
``These people coming out now, we talked to yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   At an abandoned railroad bridge at the working-class
neighborhood of Under the Hill, the river roared below like a giant
waterfall. With tears streaming down their faces, several residents
watched as the water violently smothered their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are old-fashioned. They didn't believe they would
get flooded,'' said Robert Averyhart, who went to Victoria from
Houston to get his parents out of the house. ``They got out today
just to satisfy me and my brother. Otherwise they would have
stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was Henry Martinez, 80, who wouldn't leave without his
three dogs, King, Rusty and Chula. Shaking with fear, two Doberman
pinschers and a dachshund were brought out of a flooded, home,
pulled against their will on leashes against the current.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't coming out unless I got my dogs. I love my dogs,''
said Martinez, adding: ``They protect my house ... This is the
first time they've been in water.''
</P>
</TEXT>
