<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CONTROVERSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WHO WAS DENIED ABORTION IN LOUISIANA UNDERGOES PROCEDURE IN
HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Louisiana woman with a potentially deadly heart
condition underwent an abortion in Houston Tuesday, after she was
denied the procedure in her home state.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Lee, 26, was in good condition at St. Luke's Episcopal
Hospital after the operation.
</P>
<P>
   She had been on a list for a heart transplant at Louisiana State
University Medical Center in Shreveport when she accidentally
became pregnant about 10 weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of two sons _ Kevin, 5, and Nick 3 _ sought an early
abortion because her heart specialists said the pregnancy would
endanger her life and the medications she takes could harm the
fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Because of her precarious medical condition, she needed to have
the operation in a hospital where her heart could be monitored. She
asked that it be done at the LSU Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, whose heart condition qualifies her for disability benefits
including Medicaid, must depend on public funds for her health
care. She and her husband divorced earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But medical center officials refused to perform the abortion,
citing state law that allows pregnancy terminations to be done in
public institutions only when the mother's life is endangered, or
in the case of rape or incest.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of five doctors that considered Lee's case determined
her risk of dying was less than 50 percent, said Elaine King, a
medical center spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a medical judgment call as to whether it (an abortion)
is necessary to save the life of the mother,'' King said. ``The
decision was that it (Lee's condition) did not meet the test.''
</P>
<P>
   LSU uses a 50 percent chance of survival as its benchmark in
making such a determination, King said.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana public institutions such as LSU Medical Center at
Shreveport and LSU Medical Center at New Orleans perform few
abortions. The Shreveport center has performed 10 in the past five
years, King said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Dr. Bernard Rosenfeld, an obstetrician-gynecologist,
reviewed Lee's records and said he considered her condition
life-threatening. Rosenfeld performed the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Lee suffers from abnormal heart rhythms and cardiomyopathy, a
gradual weakening of the heart muscles that began when she was
pregnant with her second child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pregnancy would increase the workload on her heart by
one-third,'' Rosenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there are no studies to pinpoint the risk she faced, but
he considered her heart problem to be one of the rare conditions
that is a medical indication that an abortion should be performed.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Nenney, a spokeswoman for Planned Parenthood of Houston
and Southeast Texas Inc., disagreed with the Louisiana medical
center's decisions not to provide the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as though the poor have returned to the dark ages in
the mid-1970s, when Congress declined to fund abortions for
low-income women,'' Nenney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call,'' Nenney said. ``Poor women across the
country, for the most part are in the same boat _ with or without
life-threatening health conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The uproar caused by the medical center's decision drew the
attention of national abortion rights organizations, which
mobilized to pay for the procedure and to find a safe, legal
abortion for the ailing woman. They estimate that the cost can run
as high as $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the major issue was finding a place for Lee to get the
abortion, said Maureen Breitell, government relations director for
the Washington-based National Abortion Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this kind of thing all the time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Poor women particularly are restricted because federal law
allows states to set limits on the use of Medicaid funds to pay for
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In 28 states, including Texas, the state-federal insurer for the
poor will pay for abortions only when the life of the mother is
threatened or when the woman becomes pregnant as a result of rape
or incest.
</P>
<P>
   Three states allow abortion only when the mother's life is
endangered; five allow public money to be used for abortions when
in instances of rape, incest, life endangerment and certain other
health conditions. Fifteen allow public funds to be used for
abortion in most or all circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   However, Medicaid limitations did not play a role in Lee's case,
said Breitell. Instead, she had to take the six-hour ambulance trip
from Shreveport to Houston, where her abortion was performed,
because of LSU's interpretation of state law, she said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
