<HEADER>
A7725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-     10-20 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN AUTHORITY ALLEGES SUSPECT IN GRENADE ATTACK IS `DOUBLE
AGENT' WORKING FOR HAMAS, ISRAELIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEBRON, West Bank _ The Palestinian who threw a grenade in a
crowded bus station was a ``double agent'' working for both the
Hamas organization and Israel's secret service, the Palestinian
Authority alleged and an Israeli television station reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army earlier had identified the grenade thrower as
Salem Rajab Sarsour, 29. The attack, which injured 66 people, took
place Monday in the southern Israeli desert town of Beersheba.
</P>
<P>
   The army said Sarsour had admitted under interrogation to
killing an elderly rabbi in August and to throwing two grenades
that injured 14 soldiers and eight Palestinians in September. Both
attacks took place in Hebron. He was arrested after witnesses
wrestled him to the ground following the grenade attack.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians officials Tuesday charged that Sarsour agreed to
work for Israel's Shin Bet internal security service after several
meetings with an Israeli agent in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority said that after the Shin Bet
blackmailed Sarsour, he turned to violence to clear his name with
Hamas. They based the allegation on the confession of an unnamed
friend of Sarsour's whom they arrested shortly after Monday's
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assailant, Salam Sarsour, was a double agent and has
provided the Israelis with information during a series of meetings
for which he received money for the information,'' the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian Authority holds the Israeli occupation
responsible for this suspicious attack,'' the statement said. It
characterized Monday's attack as a ``failed and suspicious attempt
to stab our Palestinian negotiating team.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's attack, which left 24 soldiers and 42 civilians
injured, temporarily overshadowed peace negotiations taking place
at the Wye Plantation in Maryland and prompted Israel to demand
that negotiators focus only on security-related issues. But by
Tuesday, a comprehensive deal on many outstanding issues looked
promising.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Channel One reported that the Shin Beit had met with
Sarsour two weeks ago and tried to hire him as an agent without
knowing he was responsible for carrying out the killing of Rabbi
Ranaan or the grenade attack on Yom Kippur, Judaism's holiest day.
</P>
<P>
   Channel One characterized the tryst as a ``friendly meeting''
and said that Sarsour had agreed to work for the Shin Bet, quoting
their their defense correspondence, who is privileged to
intelligence briefings.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army would not comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Khaleq Natshe, a Hamas spokesman in Hebron, said only that
his organization reserved the right to resist Israeli occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza. He would not comment on whether Hamas was
responsible for Monday's attack or on whether Sarsour had worked as
an agent for Israel's secret service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamas follows the way of resistance,'' Natshe said. ``It is
legal for us to fight the occupation, according to international
laws which say that an occupied people have the right to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army statement said that Sarsour, from an area of Hebron
that is under Palestinian control, had a history of Hamas activism
and had been jailed in 1989 and again in 1996 for activities in the
militant organization.
</P>
<P>
   An army spokeswoman said Sarsour told his interrogators that
Hamas' military wing, Izzedin al-Qassam had invited him to join its
ranks after he boasted to a high ranking Hamas official that he had
killed the rabbi, Shlomo Ranaan, in the Hebron settlement of Tel
Rumeida. The army refused to identify the Hamas official.
</P>
<P>
   Sarsour was then trained to handle fragmentation grenades and
given four of them to use in attacks in Israel, the spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   He threw the first one on Sept. 30, which is Yom Kippur,
Judaism's holiest day. On October 15, he went to Jerusalem to throw
another grenade, but left without carrying out the attack because
he failed to find a suitable target.
</P>
<P>
   Sarsour's alleged attacks heightened tensions in Hebron, a
divided city where 110,000 Palestinians and 450 Jews live in uneasy
proximity.
</P>
<P>
   Following the attacks, settlers complained that peace agreements
had brought only insecurity while 20,000 Palestinians living in
areas of the city still under Israeli control chafed under curfew
for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before there was this agreement, we didn't have terrorists
around our neighborhood with guns,'' said Baruch Marzel, a settler
leader from one of five settler enclaves lodged in the heart of
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday night, four times, these terrorists called the
Palestinian police shot toward Beit Hadassah and toward soldiers,''
he said. ``If this is peace, I would like war.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarsour, a successful plasterer with five children and a
comfortable home, was known in the community as a religious man. He
supported Hamas, but didn't fit the profile of a bomber, observers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most bombers are young, single, unemployed and hail from the
grinding poverty of Palestinian refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in
Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
