<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOVER-COX     10-20 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOVER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family, friends disbelieve wrongdoing of slain man in hotel
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Ga. _ If Phillip Dover was into anything dirty, it
certainly didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   The flashiest thing about the 31-year-old bachelor, his friends
said Tuesday, was his red convertible _ but it was a 9-year-old
Chevy Cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   His father, his boss and his former roommate all said the same
thing _ his execution-style slaying at the Atlanta Hilton had to be
a matter of ``being in the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dover roomed with Scott Shope, another dispatcher at GTO 2000,
until August, when Shope got married and Dover moved into a
two-bedroom apartment with a another friend, Chris Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Shope said he was the first in Gainesville to learn of Dover's
death, Atlanta detectives, he said, found a prescription bottle in
the hotel room with Phillip's name on it. They contacted the
pharmacy which issued it, and were given the telephone number at
Shope's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phillip was as average as you could be,'' Shope said. ``He was
a big sports fan, he liked to shoot pool, he hung out at places
like Damon's and Chili's and Appleby's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He hung out with the same people, did the same things. Once I
told him, 'You're as predictable as my grandfather.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Before going to work at GTO, Dover was a bartender at Appleby's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phillip never had any money,'' Shope said. ``He dated various
girls, but no one special. I lived with him for two years, and he
certainly kept it well hidden if he was into anything bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Dover's roommate, Chris Anderson, who works for a Gainesville
bank, arranged time off and, Shope said, went to stay with his
parents. ``He told me he's not going to live in that apartment any
more. He's going to move. The idea of living there doesn't give him
a comfortable feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phillip was basically a kind, gentle person,'' said Tom
Cornett, who runs GTO. ``He was a real good'' employee. Fornett
said his 20-person staff is eligible for weekly bonuses based upon
work performance and ``Phillip qualified for the bonuses 98 percent
of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornett would not say how much Phillip made, but he said
dispatchers in general ``are well-paid. Some dispatchers make more
than college professors.''
</P>
<P>
   Dover was ``quite a ladies' man,'' Cornett said. ``He was a
great trivia player, too. He was just a good all-around guy. We'll
miss him in more ways than one.''
</P>
<P>
   Dover's father Clarence, who lives outside Gainesville, called
Phillip ``a good man, a good son, a good child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago he got a DUI,'' the elder Dover said. ``That's
all the trouble he's ever been in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had a lot of cash,'' Dover said, ``and I'm not sure
he even had a credit card. He lived from paycheck to paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Dover said both he and his son were born in Atlanta. They moved
to Hall County in the 1970s, and Phillip graduated from East Hall
High School. After his parents divorced, the younger Dover spent
seven years with his mother in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he moved back here and stayed with us for a while before
he went out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a senseless thing that happened to my son,'' Dover
said. ``I'm ashamed to say I'm from Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
