A7750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TECHFSU-COX     10-20 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TECHFSU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech new to the 'big game;' FSU used to them
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Game of the Decade? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Game of the Century? That would be a strech.
</P>
<P>
   But given what's on the line _ first place in the ACC, a
possible spot in the Bowl Championship Series and an outside shot
at competing for the national championship _ Saturday's meeting
between No. 20 Georgia Tech and No. 6 Florida State will be the
biggest game played in Bobby Dodd Stadium in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   And given where Georgia Tech's football program was in 1994
(1-10), its players, coaches and fans are justified in viewing
Saturday's contest as a possible watershed game on the way back to
respectibility.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida State, the view is significantly different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game, no doubt about it, but at Florida State we
play three or four of these every year,'' said Ross Brannon, a
sophomore offensive tackle. ``We're used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tallahassee, it's been a running joke that Florida State
plays in a ``Game of the Century'' at least once a year. In the
1980s, it was usually against Miami. In the '90s, it has been
against the Florida Gators. And here lately, some of the Seminoles'
ACC brethren have elevated their programs enough to challenge their
dominance of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Florida State's players say, they love a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, it was North Carolina, ranked in the Top 10 all
season. Throughout the summer of '97, Florida State's players
constantly read and heard from the North Carolina media that this
was the year that the Tar Heels would unseat them from the ACC
throne. North Carolina would win, they said, because the Tar Heel
defense was superior to the great unit at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   It was a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 8, No. 2 Florida State went to Chapel Hill to play No. 5
North Carolina in what was billed as the biggest game in the
history of the ACC. It was never a contest, as the Seminole defense
had nine quarterback sacks and won 20-3. The game wasn't that
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a perfect example of the way our guys step up in
the big game, especially when they are challenged by somebody,''
quarterback Chris Weinke said. ``Anytime you challenge our defense,
watch out.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Miami had the poor judgment to throw down
the gauntlet to the Florida State offense. After a few down
seasons, the Hurricane had a competitive team _ and they had the
Seminoles in the Orange Bowl on Oct. 10. Several members of the
Miami secondary, most notably cornerback Leonard Myers, stated
publicly that they were going to shut down Peter Warrick, the
Seminoles' All-America receiver candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick had seven catches for 190 yards and punctuated his
performance with a 62-yard touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Georgia Tech, fresh off an emotional 41-38 win over
Virginia, with a group of eager players getting ready for the
biggest game of their lives. The Yellow Jackets, one would hope,
will have the good sense not to issue any bulletin-board material
that might motivate the Seminoles further.
</P>
<P>
   But they really don't need it. Because of its 24-7 loss to
N.C.State on Sept. 12, Florida State has no margin for error. The
Seminoles must win if they want to claim their seventh ACC title in
a row. Getting back into contention for the national title is a
long shot, anyway, but if Florida State loses to Georgia Tech, it
will have no shot. It would be an unaccustomed feeling for a
program that for 11 consecutive seasons has won 10 or more games
and finished in the final top four nationally.
</P>
<P>
   In short, another challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is riding on this game; we know that,'' defensive
tackle Jerry Johnson said. ``We can't slip up any more. We're
playing on the road on national television. That's about as big as
it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's players think their big-game experience is a
significant advantage as they prepare to come to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, if you haven't played in a big game, you choke
under the pressure,'' Brannon said. ``I didn't play well at North
Carolina last year because I had never experienced it. The seniors
knew how to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On a week like this, the adrenalin is higher and the coaches
are more uptight than normal. You can just feel it,'' Weinke said.
``Some guys have never played in that kind of atmosphere and don't
know how to adjust. They crumble under the pressure. Our guys are
in this situation year in and year out. They know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   What Florida State expects Saturday night at Bobby Dodd Stadium
is a packed house screaming at the top of its lungs. They expect to
get Georgia Tech's very best shot in a game that could set up a
magical season should the Yellow Jackets win. They expect just
about everything and everybody to be against them.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and they also expect to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kind of games you live for,'' said defensive
back Tay Cody, a sophomore from Blakely. ``I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
