<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-FEATURE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wildcat defense putting more pressure on offenses
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Kentucky coach Hal Mumme has earned the reputation
of a gambler, with his penchant of lighting up the skies and taking
several risks on offense. Now, the Wildcats are taking some chances
on defense, too.
</P>
<P>
   In Mumme's first season in Lexington a year ago, Kentucky ranked
sixth nationally in total offense, but the Wildcats came away with
only a 5-6 record. The problems were on defense, where the 'Cats
ranked at the bottom of the SEC, allowing 392.2 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Kentucky defensive coordinator Mike Major, who
worked with Mumme at Valdosta State for five years, has installed a
``Black Flag'' defense designed to put more pressure on opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Major returned only five starters from last year's much-maligned
unit; Kentucky has 16 freshmen or sophomores on defense on its
two-deep depth chart. But the 'Cats are making some strides _ in
wins, if not statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats enter Saturday's SEC East showdown against No. 11
Georgia with a 5-2 record, but they're still ranked next-to-last in
the league in total defense, allowing 392.4 yards per game,
slightly more than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their defense gives them a little better pressure,''
Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``Last year, they played a lot more
soft coverage. The biggest difference is results. They're stopping
teams and keeping them out of the end zone a little better, but
they're still giving up a lot of yards and points.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is ranked fifth in the league in total offense, gaining
more than 388 yards per game. But Georgia looked fine-tuned in only
three of its first six games _ against Kent, LSU and Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, Mumme has accepted the mindset that if an opponent
is going to score, it's going to do it quickly, so he can get his
high-powered offense and quarterback Tim Couch back on the field.
In a 51-35 loss to Florida on Sept. 26, Kentucky surrendered three
touchdowns in a span of only 2 minutes, 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky is pressing more in its secondary, with the two
cornerbacks playing bump-and-run coverage. The Wildcats are
blitzing on nearly every play with either a linebacker or safety
and have 15 sacks in seven games, including five in last week's
39-36 upset at LSU.
</P>
<P>
   That's what apparently has Donnan confident heading into the
game, the first of three road trips in a row for the Bulldogs. ``If
they play us like they've played everybody else, we might throw as
many passes as they do,'' Donnan said. ``The man coverage just
presents you a lot of opportunities. We give them a little bit more
of a defensive dilemma than maybe some other teams do.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Freshman quarterback Quincy) Carter can run and he can run
the option. It's hard to defend in that man coverage when you can
do that. We feel like what we've set our package up to be will be
effective against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
