</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-MARTIN-FEDPROBE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds investigate Martin
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli and Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons wide receiver Tony Martin is under
federal investigation and suspected of laundering drug profits for
longtime friend and convicted narcotics trafficker Rickey Brownlee,
Martin's attorney said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has contacted me in an official capacity, but I've
heard it from enough people to believe it,'' attorney Kieran Fallon
said. ``The U.S. attorney's office doesn't usually send
correspondence to someone detailing an investigation, but there's
something there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've talked to family, friends, acquaintances ... so you
know what's going on. On the other hand, I have no reason to
believe Tony has done anything illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was traded to Atlanta from San Diego on June 3, is
being investigated by at least two federal agencies, the U.S.
Attorney's Office in Miami and the Drug Enforcement Administration.
Martin's name also is included in a pending FBI file on Brownlee,
who is from Opa-locka, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Asked earlier this week if he is the subject of an
investigation, Martin said: ``I just don't know. I really don't
know.'' Martin denied that he is part of any drug-laundering
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was a student at Miami Northwestern High School when he
met Brownlee, who was dating Martin's aunt. The men remained
friends despite an eight-year age difference.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 10, a few weeks after Brownlee's arrest, Martin signed a
retainer in which he agreed to pay Brownlee's attorney, Milton
Hirsch, $175,000 for Brownlee's legal fees. A few days later, about
the same time that authorities subpoenaed his financial records,
Martin stopped payment on the check. Hirsch sued for breach of
contract, but he might drop the action if he is removed from
Brownlee's defense, which could happen by the end of his month.
</P>
<P>
   Martin confirmed that the money was to help cover Brownlee's
legal expenses. ``I wanted to help (Brownlee), but my lawyer said
that wouldn't be a smart thing to do, because it would get me into
the papers,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlee, 41, faces seven counts of heroin and cocaine
trafficking charges and is scheduled for a February 1999 trial on
charges dating to the mid-1980s. When Brownlee was arrested in
January, he was driving a black Mercedes SL-500 that was leased in
Martin's name, according to the U.S. attorney's office. That car is
an element in the money-laundering allegations that were added in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have subpoenaed Martin's financial records,
but Fallon emphasized that they have neither questioned Martin nor
requested to interview him. Fallon said it is not unusual for a
person under investigation not to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Aiello, vice president of public relations for the NFL,
said the league is aware of the allegations. ``We are following it
through our security people, and that is all I can say on the
matter,'' Aiello said. He did note that ``improper associations''
by any league player would be ``a cause for concern'' that could
lead to action by the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who will continue to play, hasn't allowed the situation
to affect him on the field. He leads the Falcons in receptions (27)
and receiving yards (492) and has three scoring catches. San Diego
officials said they were unaware of any allegations against Martin
when he was traded to the Falcons for a second-round choice in the
1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Brownlee is a south Florida businessman who owns a popular
restaurant, a car wash and several other buildings in and around
Opa-locka. He was convicted twice in the 1980s of cocaine
trafficking and has spent seven years in prison. He reportedly
moved 80 to 100 kilos of cocaine weekly, but authorities have had
difficulty tracing the profits.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI file alleges ties between Brownlee and Central American
and South American drug lords. The portion of the file on Martin
has been marked ``secret'' and is accessible only to selected FBI
personnel. An FBI spokesman said that is common practice in many
cases that include allegations against a high-profile personality.
</P>
<P>
   In the money-laundering charges, prosecutors contend that
Brownlee conspired with persons ``known and unknown to the grand
jury'' to conceal profit from a drug operation.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for two federal agencies said more charges could
be added soon, with ``superseding indictments'' possible within the
next month. From the Federal Detention Center in Miami, Brownlee
said Martin had come to his aid but perhaps backed off when he
became part of the federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is one of the best (people around), but when the feds
turned up the heat on him, he did what most people would do,'' said
Brownlee, who declined to discuss his case or any alleged
involvement by Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities might attempt to force Hirsch to testify in
the Brownlee case and on the fee arrangement with Martin. It is not
unusual for a third party to agree to such payments in drug-related
cases, Hirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (federal authorities) have put attorneys on notice,''
Hirsch said. ``If you have the temerity to represent someone in a
drug case, then the fees you collect are going to be scrutinized.
You're behind the eight ball. I said to (Brownlee), `Is there a
white knight?' He turned to Martin. But I should add that all I
know about Martin are two things: He is a friend of Brownlee, and
he owes me $175,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon declined comment when asked if his client exercised poor
judgment in agreeing to aid Brownlee.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Martin said, ``At one time, he very much
helped me when I didn't have the things I have now. He helped me go
back to college. He kept money in my pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he regretted that he might not be able to help his
longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could still help him,'' Martin said. ``And I would
help him if I could, if I knew I wouldn't come under so much
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli and Matt Winkeljohn write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
