u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLF-FEATURE21-CO     10-20 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-FEATURE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aiming for East Lake: Much on the line as Championship nears
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It might decide the money title. It could determine
the PGA Tour Player of the Year. It will distribute $4 million
among 30 players.
</P>
<P>
   Not too shabby for East Lake Golf Club's return to the pro golf
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Next week's Tour Championship is about to complete its
invitation list. After Sunday's conclusion to the final full-field
event of the PGA Tour season, the National Rental Car Classic, the
top 30 money-winners will be determined and the East Lake field
decided.
</P>
<P>
   Which means Billy Payne, the tournament's general chairman, is
stirring, on a smaller scale, those same emotions last affected by
the Olympic Games. In some ways, Payne has even more anticipation,
because this is a game that both excites and exhausts him. He
didn't have a lot of experience in synchronized swimming or the
balance beam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obsessed by the game,'' Payne said Tuesday. ``While not
very good at it, I love it dearly. ... I kind of have the same kind
of feeling with the Olympics. I didn't care who won, just so the
competition was close.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval has a chance to make neither the money title nor the
player-of-the-year voting very close at all. With $720,000
available for first prize at East Lake, the former Georgia Tech
player ($2,464,408) is leading No. 2 Jim Furyk, who is passing up
the National Car Rental at Disney World after winning at Las Vegas,
by $644,074. With a fifth victory, at Disney, Duval probably could
end all the discussions. In that case, O'Meara probably would need
to win the Tour Championship to outvote Duval for player of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   East Lake member Stewart Cink of Smyrna is stuck at the 31st
spot, trailing No. 30 Andrew Magee by $61,867. Magee last year
grabbed the 30th spot on the final day, by $5 over Atlanta's Billy
Andrade (now 42nd). Cink probably needs at least a fifth at Disney,
which would earn $80,000. If Magee plays well, Cink might require a
third and $136,000. Andrade needs a first ($360,000) or perhaps a
second ($216,000) to make it.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson has made a confusing move, deciding against an
appearance at Disney despite a tenuous situation at No. 29, less
than $7,000 ahead of Magee. If Watson misses the Tour Championship,
he will not have satisfied his minimum 15 events and will lose
pension points and player voting status for 1999. That could be
noteworthy, considering that Watson is an active voice in player
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials are winding down preparations, hopeful that
a cool snap to the weather remains moderate. Payne on Sunday will
hold a ``greenside chat'' with his 1,000 volunteers, who will park
at Turner Field as a dry run for tournament week, shuttle to the
course and then celebrate later with a volunteer party.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets available
</P>
<P>
   A limited number of weekly ($120) and daily tickets ($40) remain
for next week's Tour Championship at East Lake Golf Club and can be
purchased by calling 1-888-868-7849.
</P>
<P>
   The event is expected to be sold out by Friday, with a cutoff of
20,000 tickets for each of the four rounds, Thursday through
Sunday. A limited number of group packages also are available at
404-378-7687.
</P>
<P>
   Practice round tickets, which are good for any or all of the
three days (Monday-Wednesday) are $25 and can be purchased by phone
or at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   All parking is at Turner Field. Parking and shuttles, about 10
minutes to East Lake, are free.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
