<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Meara: Duval equally deserving
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Masters and British Open wins in the same season no
longer guarantee Mark O'Meara the PGA Tour Player of the Year
award. That comes from a good source _ O'Meara himself. On a
conference call Tuesday before next week's Tour Championship,
O'Meara, citing four victories and more than $2.4 million earned by
David Duval, said, ``I would obviously love to win it, but I can't
say that I just deserve it outright. If he (Duval) goes on to win
another tournament, I'd probably vote for him myself.'' As a
prelude to the Tour Championship, both players are competing in
this week's National Car Rental Classic at Walt Disney World, with
Duval the defending champion. A partner with Duval in last year's
President's Cup, where they went 3-0, O'Meara said, ``I truly
believed when he won (Kingsmill), he maybe deserved the player of
the year as much or more than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-tour challenge
</P>
<P>
   Allen Doyle is a rarity, playing this year on all three tours
under commissioner Tim Finchem's umbrella _ PGA Tour, Senior PGA
Tour and Nike Tour. With the combined earnings from all three,
Doyle has made a pretty solid $193,953, not including the $15,000
he won for taking a Senior Series event in Albany. Doyle's biggest
Senior Tour check came Sunday in Sacramento with a tie for fourth
in the Raley's Gold Rush Classic; the $54,000 pushed his season
total to $144,018 (69th) for only five events (a $28,804 average).
Hoping to move beyond lobbying each week for sponsor exemptions,
Doyle will go through Senior PGA Tour qualifying school. Regional
play is Nov. 9-13, with the finals Dec. 1-4 in Haines City, Fla.
Only the top eight gain fully exempt status for 1999. Marietta's
Joe Inman, who is 42nd on the money list with $396,502, would have
to win to make the top 31 for full exemption but probably will
qualify for at least 20 events just by making the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   Langer joins Sarazen field
</P>
<P>
   Squeezed out of some attention by the presence of the Tour
Championship, the Subaru Sarazen World Open nonetheless has
assembled a strong field for its final tournament Nov. 5-8 at
Chateau Elan. Added to the field this week was Germany's Bernhard
Langer, the two-time Masters champion. Squire's picks already have
gone to PGA Tour players Payne Stewart, Craig Stadler, John Huston,
Brad Faxon, John Daly and Tom Kite; and European Tour players
Andrew Coltart, Mathias Gronberg, Padraig Harrington, Miguel Angel
Jimenez, Paul McGinley and Peter O'Malley. Other Americans playing
include defending champion Mark Calcavecchia, Smyrna's Stewart
Cink, No. 2 PGA Tour moneywinner Jim Furyk, Bob Friendb Dudley Hart
and former Tech player Tripp Isenhour.
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   A two-time champion at Walt Disney World, Marietta's Larry
Nelson has gone back with the young studs for a week and is playing
in the PGA Tour's National Car Rental Classic at Lake Buena Vista,
Fla. . . . Alpharetta's Kelly Blackburn, the trainer for Nelson and
several other tour players, is hosting ``The Fitness Center,'' a
new, weekly addition to the PGA Tour's Web site
(http://www.pgatour.com). . . . A two-hour documentary, ``Arnold
Palmer: Golf's Heart and Soul,'' premiers Oct. 28 on The Golf
Channel. The 69-year-old Palmer, meanwhile, has been undergoing
radiation treatments in Latrobe, Pa., as a precautionary move after
his prostate-cancer surgery last year. Palmer's golf buddies at
Latrobe Country Club can't wait until the treatments are done. He
shot a 63 recently. . . . Ahead of his rehabilitation schedule
after right-shoulder surgery in April, Greg Norman will play in his
Shark Shootout Nov. 13-15 in Thousand Oaks, Calif. . . . Oakland
Hill Country Club near Detroit was selected as the site for the
2003 Ryder Cup matches, beating out favored Colonial C.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
