<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soccer notebook: Usual settings for DC
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The weather conditions were familiar for D.C. United,
if not ideal. The rainy, slushy field at Ohio Stadium on Sunday was
in no worse shape than the venues where they have taken MLS Cup
victories the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final contest played on the narrow 62-yard Ohio State
football field that has been the subject of league-wide griping,
the Columbus Crew kept their footing to earn an impressive 4-2
victory Sunday and send the Eastern Conference finals to a decisive
match today. The game will be shown live on ESPN2 at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. national team striker Brian McBride, playing on a bad
ankle, had two goals, as United's normally sturdy defense fell
apart early and couldn't hold firm after the visitors got to within
3-2 with 12 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the rain; it wasn't the field,'' United midfielder
Ben Olsen said. ``It was us.''
</P>
<P>
   United (27-9), which had won 13-straight playoff games, has
never lost in the postseason at RFK Stadium. Columbus (18-18),
which moves to a new 22,500-seat soccer-only stadium next season,
never has won in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MLS already has lost one top team for the championship match.
The Los Angeles Galaxy, which could have hosted Sunday's MLS Cup at
the Rose Bowl, was ousted in two games by the first-year Chicago
Fire, which won the clincher 2-1 in a shootout Thursday before an
MLS playoff record of 32,744 at Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   Rhinos win A-League
</P>
<P>
   The Rochester Raging Rhinos won their first A-League
championship Saturday with a 3-1 victory over the Minnesota Thunder
before a home crowd of 13,722. Darren Tilley had a hat trick for
the Rhinos. . . . U.S. national team midfielder Claudio Reyna, who
threatened to walk out on German Bundesliga side VfL Wolfsburg
after losing his starting position and captaincy, will remain with
the club through the end of the season. Reyna was one of several
starters benched after Wolfsburg, 16th among the 18 teams, got off
to a poor start.
</P>
<P>
   Zidane wants out
</P>
<P>
   French World Cup hero Zinedine Zidane, who feels unwanted with
Italian Serie A champion Juventus, has indicated a desire to go to
another club before his contract runs out in 2003. . . . A total of
11 red cards were issued in Spanish Liga Primera games over the
weekend, including six in the contest between Atletico Madrid and
Tenerife. . . . Andy Cole scored twice as Manchester United got to
within four points of England Premier League leaders Aston Villa
Saturday with a 5-1 romp over Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   They still want his 'Hod'
</P>
<P>
   England manager Glenn Hoddle is denying published reports that
he and captain Alan Shearer exchanged angry words after a 3-0 win
over Luxembourg on Wednesday to improve sagging hopes for
qualifying for Euro 2000. Hoddle came under heavy fire after an
uninspiring 0-0 draw with Bulgaria Oct. 10, with several newspapers
demanding his resignation. . . . European Champions' League
qualifying resumes today, with Inter Milan missing injured Ronaldo
and Roberto Baggio as it tries to stay alive at home against
Spartak Moscow. Also on tap are Sturm Graz at Real Madrid, Brondby
at Manchester United and Dynamo Kiev at Arsenal. The
Barcelona-Bayern Munich match will be shown live at 2:30 p.m. today
on ESPN2, while the network will air the Juventus-Atletico Bilbao
match on tape delay Thursday at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
