<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giving up big plays is secondary's weakness
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons cornerback Ronnie Bradford was caught looking
the wrong way Sunday, and by the time he looked the right way,
Saints receiver Keith Poole was sprinting 64 yards to the end zone
with a touchdown reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saints quarterback Billy Joe) Tolliver was coming out of the
pocket; I'm with the receiver (short) and happened to look at the
quarterback, and the receiver took off,'' said Bradford. ``You got
to know when the quarterback takes off they're going to try to go
deep.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the play hardly mattered. The Falcons beat the
Saints 31-23 to improve to 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the tendency to give up the big play has Falcons players and
coaches concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta pass defense is ranked next to last in the NFL,
allowing 260.2 yards per game, and the Jets (3-3), Sunday's
opponent, have the NFL's No. 6 passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also have allowed 10 passing plays of 38 or more
yards, six of 56 or more yards. In a three-game span _ all
victories _ the Falcons have given up pass plays of 72, 46, 39, 64
and 82 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, because had we eliminated a few of those
passes, we go from being the 25th defense to being about 15th,''
said Rich Brooks, assistant head coach and defensive coordinator.
``But until we execute . . . we will not be one of the best
defenses in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The same defense has 13 takeaways, including three
interceptions, and has scored in each of Atlanta's last three
victories.
</P>
<P>
   No single play has led to an Atlanta defeat; the 31-20 loss to
the 49ers was the culmination of many. The second play set the
tone, however, when Jerry Rice beat reserve cornerback Juran Bolden
and Robinson for a 66-yard touchdown. Bolden was waived two days
later.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons say the problem is not scheme or talent. It's a
matter of doing the right thing, like guarding deep when opponents
are behind. That's something rookie reserve cornerback Elijah
Williams hasn't done the last two weeks, while allowing touchdown
passes of 39 and 82 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (pass) rush also plays a role,'' Brooks said. ``We didn't
wrap up Billy Joe when we had him (on the play to Poole), and we
got caught peeking in the backfield. We've got to give up (the
short passes), and let the clock run. There's no excuse with
four-deep coverage to get run by when you're up two TDs in the last
four minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the players,'' said cornerback Ray Buchanan, the
team leader with three interceptions. ``You can't make too many
adjustments by cutting players because of the salary cap. Right
now, we're doing poor, but we're winning. Don't forget that. We're
5-1, and we've got time to get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
