<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Data delivery boosts BellSouth's revenue
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp.'s high-speed data business grew
sharply during the past three months, and its traditional telephone
business remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third quarter proved once again that BellSouth's growth
has momentum,'' said Duane Ackerman, the company's chairman and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the Atlanta-based company's data and digital
services, which include such high-speed, high-capacity data network
products as IDSN, T-1 and pathlink, rose 36 percent to $463 million
in the quarter, the company reported Tuesday. A year earlier, the
figure was $340 million.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, revenue for the quarter was $5.87 billion, up from $5.2
billion a year earlier. For nine months, revenue was $16.96
billion, up from $14.96 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported net income of $814 million, 82 cents a
share, down from $1.19 billion, or $1.19 a share, a year earlier.
Last year's figures included one-time income from the sale of ITT
World Directories and Optus Communications.
</P>
<P>
   For nine months, net income was $2.52 billion, down from $2.53
billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After data, the next-biggest increase in business for the
quarter came from add-on features to regular telephone service.
This includes such services as Caller ID and MemoryCall. Sales for
these features rose 20 percent in the quarter to $421 million.
</P>
<P>
   Regular local telephone service remains BellSouth's
bread-and-butter business. It reported third-quarter revenue of
$2.38 billion from local service _ by far the company's largest
single segment. The figure last year was $2.14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company added 94,000 residential access lines in the
quarter. Those lines were used for Internet access, fax machines
and second telephones for teenagers, among other things. The
company estimates that one in seven of its customers now have at
least two telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   While huge, the number of new lines adds to an already-big
customer base and represents only a 4.2 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   That's why BellSouth has been branching out into new lines of
business such as high-speed data and international wireless phones.
Wireless cable TV remains small and is not yet broken out
separately.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes these areas will offset the slowing rate of
growth for its maturing traditional telephone business.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
