<HEADLINE>
ENERGY DEPARTMENT'S ELIZABETH MOLER RESIGNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth ``Betsy'' Moler, the Energy Department
official who President Clinton twice passed over for the
department's top job in favor of Hispanic nominees, has resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Moler, who has served as deputy Energy secretary since June 1997
and as acting secretary for nearly seven weeks last summer, left
her job Monday after 30 years in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   Moler gave her colleagues no indications about her future plans.
She could not be reached for immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a computer message to Energy staffers, Moler said her job
there ``has been simultaneously more difficult, and more
interesting, than I could possibly have imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After ten years as a presidential appointee, and almost 30
years as a `fed,' I am ready for a change in my life,'' Moler said,
adding: ``I look forward to more time with my husband and
especially with my children (they're 13 and almost 8) and,
hopefully, a less frantic pace of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Moler, the former head of the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission, was widely viewed as a top contender for the Energy
secretary post, a cabinet position, after Hazel O'Leary stepped
down. But Clinton, concerned about the lack of a Hispanic leader in
his cabinet, asked former Transportation Secretary Federico Pena to
take the job.
</P>
<P>
   When Pena announced his plans to leave in April, Moler was again
identified as the heir apparent. But Clinton overlooked Moler again
and appointed Bill Richardson, the former U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations and another Hispanic, to the post.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson issued a prepared statement regarding Moler's
resignation, hailing Moler's ``integrity, determination,
intelligence and strong management skills.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
