<HEADLINE>
ET AL, ETC. AND SO FORTH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Journal News, a Gannett newspaper that made its debut on
October 12 in Westchester County, N.Y., ``has the usual teething
problems,'' reports the New York Post, an amused quasi-competitor.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent story from the Vatican was headlined ``Pope Signs
the Yada, Yada, Yada,'' an editor told the Post that he hoped
readers would think it was in Latin.
</P>
<P>
   In related news, some terms from the Dictionary of Contemporary
Latin, created by the Vatican Foundation and forwarded by  &UR; Dennis
Halac &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   _ Bracaelintea caeruleae means ``blue breeches'' or blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pastillum botello fartum means ``minced sausage lozenge'' or
hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   _ Directe collegatus means ``straight office connection'' or
online.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Prince Charles &LR;  and  &UR; Camilla Parker Bowles &LR;  are just back
from a cruise around the Aegean islands, their first vacation as a
couple. The Daily Mail quoted a ``senior royal official'' as
saying, ``They looked so sweet together, it brought tears to my
eyes.'' The yacht was borrowed.
</P>
<P>
   _ German-born  &UR; Heidi Klum &LR; , who was on the cover of the 1998
Sports Illustrated swimsuit issue and who plays opposite  &UR; Michael &LR; 
 &UR; J. Fox &LR;  in ``Spin City,'' pinpointed the difference between the Old
World and the New when Stuff magazine asked what she misses from
her homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Licorice,'' she said. ``We have all different kinds of
licorice at home. There are sugared kinds and real strong ones.
Here you have a lot of red licorice. I don't call that licorice. I
mean, it's just not licorice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When writer  &UR; Owen Edwards &LR;  saw his boldfaced name in a recent
Vanity Fair literary gossip item noting the imminent publication of
``Owen Edwards's ` &UR; Peter Beard &LR; 's African Adventure' (Universe),''
it was the first he'd heard of the book, which apparently had
already been published in Italy. Owens had written its introductory
essay about his friend Beard _ a photographer who knows his way
around Africa, the Hamptons and supermodels _ for the Village Voice
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards complained; a small amount of money was offered and
turned down; and Universe, a division of Rizzoli, told Edwards that
the books would be destroyed. ``I have no idea why,'' Universe's
 &UR; Deb Seager &LR;  told Personals. ``We're not publishing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ACADEMIC AFFAIRS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Economist  &UR; John Kenneth Galbraith &LR;  celebrated his 90th
birthday at a party thrown for him by Harvard University last week,
at which the founding of a $650,000 Galbraith fellowship fund was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest issue of San Francisco Frontlines _ which describes
itself as a progressive monthly _ describes  &UR; Maria &LR; 
 &UR; Dolores Rinaldi &LR; , a candidate for the Board of Education, as ``a
Virgo with Scorpio rising.'' ``Is this a qualification for the
Board of Education?'' asks  &UR; Herbert Gold &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ When  &UR; Matt Damon &LR;  tells his GI buddies an off-color story in
``Saving Private Ryan,'' he describes the butt of the tale as an
ugly girl named  &UR; Alice Jardine &LR; . According to the gossipy
academic-affairs journal Lingua Franca, Alice Jardine in real life
is a perfectly attractive professor of French at Harvard, where
Damon was a student for three years.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Good Will Hunting,'' Damon's character praises the work of
radical historian  &UR; Howard Zinn &LR;  of Boston University. Lingua Franca
says that Zinn, Damon,  &UR; Ben Affleck &LR;  and ``Good Will Hunting''
producer  &UR; Chris Moore &LR;  are hoping to work together as executive
producers of a docudrama series about historic events. Among the
themes are Columbus and the Americans &LR;  Indians; the Revolutionary
War; slavery; and class conflict.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Phenomenon of the Male Wedding Coordinator,'' a
sociological study recently completed at Texas Christian
University, found that more women than men work as wedding
planners, but that the men get paid more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dirty Words for Dummies:  &UR; John Joss &LR;  forwards the letters
column from the latest issue of Cycle World, which solves the
dilemma of how to use a four-letter word without employing a
four-letter word. An Indianapolis correspondent, addressing some
problems in the sport, asks, ``Why are dirt bikes so 'kin' ugly?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to push the frontiers of music forward. They
need no pushing. ... I'm sick of musicians saying, `I'm gonna play
whatever I want _ I'm an artist.' You're an artist? Paint my
house!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Gene Simmons of Kiss in Rolling Stone.
</P>
