<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVIERA MIGHT BE NCAA PREVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM INGHRAM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Want to know who will be the 1999 NCAA women's
collegiate champion? Then keep close watch on this week's 13th
annual Riviera Women's All-American Tennis Championships at Riviera
Tennis Club in Pacific Palisades.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the past 10 NCAA singles champions have graced the
courts at Riviera, including 1998 NCAA champion and 1996 Riviera
Champion Vanessa Webb of Duke. Last year's Riviera winner, Mirela
Vladulescu of Alabama-Birmingham, also returns.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the top 10 ranked women on the collegiate circuit are
at the tournament, which opened Tuesday with preliminary qualifying
and runs through Sunday. The singles championship is scheduled for
10 a.m. that day with the doubles to follow immediately after.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the toughest of the collegiate tournaments,'' said
tournament referee Jane Goodman. ``Because of the limited number of
participants, it makes it more competitive all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   Tournament official Allan Burns noted that 60 universities are
represented by more than 100 players.
</P>
<P>
   Area players who are scheduled to play include UCLA's Annica
Cooper; former Harvard-Westlake standout Marissa Irvin of Stanford,
who received a special wild-card entry because of her top junior
ranking; and Pepperdine's top doubles team of Angela Lawrence and
Nicola Kaiwai.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Augustus and Amy Jensen of Cal, last year's NCAA
champions, are the top seeds in doubles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
