<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      10-20 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS VOTES 333-95 IN FAVOR OF 1999 BUDGET AGREEMENT WITH
CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Nov. 3 elections looming, Congress turned a
vote on the final 1999 budget agreement with President Clinton into
a giant campaign advertisement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In floor speeches and staged events, Democrats and Republicans
spent the day bad-mouthing one another and claiming credit for
various aspects of the budget deal as they tried to maneuver into
the best political position going into the final two weeks of the
congressional campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The debate ended with an overwhelming vote of 333-95 in favor of
the massive spending measure after a rousing speech from House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who called the bill a ``win-win'' for
Democrats and Republicans and a bipartisan ``team effort for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We in fact produced a win-win bill. Yes, our liberal friends
get a few things, and in a free society where you are sharing power
between the legislative and executive branch that is precisely the
outcome you should get,'' Gingrich told disgruntled conservative
colleagues before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good bill. It deserves a yes vote by every member
and it is in fact precisely how the American system operates,''
Gingrich said to heavy applause.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate put off a vote on the measure until Wednesday. But it
was expected to pass with overwhelming support. White House
officials said Clinton would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The last in a series of temporary funding measures that has kept
the government running since the start of the new fiscal year on
Oct. 1 expires at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 30 members of the Texas delegation, Rep. Lloyd
Doggett, D-Austin, was the only Democrat to vote against the
measure. Also voting no were four Republicans; Kevin Brady of The
Woodlands, Joe Barton of Ennis, Sam Johnson of Plano, and Ron Paul
of Surfside.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's comments on the art of compromise came at the end of
long day of pure politics in the halls of Congress with Republicans
and Democrats jockeying for the upper hand in the election-year
public relations war.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats blasted away at Republican leaders for failing to
move any major legislation this year and for hammering together
``this monstrosity'' of an appropriations bill, as one senator
described it, that ran more than 4,000 pages and that no lawmaker
had time to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I know what's in the bill? Are you kidding? Only God knows
what's in this conference report,'' Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W. Va.,
said during a debate on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, meanwhile, moved to claim credit for increasing
defense spending and adding $1.2 billion for hiring new public
school teachers, although they were opposed to more education money
until Clinton threatened a veto.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of complaints from conservatives about the
single document that rolls eight appropriations bills worth nearly
$600 billion into one giant spending package. Many of the
complaints centered on the fact that it was hastily pulled together
in negotiations last week between the Republican leadership and the
president without members having a chance to fully consider
everything in it.
</P>
<P>
   When the bill was finally printed and delivered to congressional
offices Monday night, it stood nearly two feet tall and weighed
about 45 pounds, according to a Democratic aide who placed it on a
bathroom scale to see, he said, ``how much pork it's got in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats made sure it had a lot. In
addition to the big-ticket items to fund 10 Cabinet departments ,
the bill was filled with hundreds of smaller local spending
projects and special interest benefits designed in many instances
to help incumbents look good back home in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   In summing up why members should support it, Rep. Bob
Livingston, R-La., chairman of the Appropriations Committee,
described the bill as a compromise measure with a little something
for everybody that would be good for the country. He encouraged his
GOP colleagues to use it in their campaigns even though it might
contain elements they disagree with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to vote for this bill, and go home to our
districts and explain why we should come back as the majority in
the 106th Congress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Democratic leaders encouraged their rank and file to
support it, mainly because of the extra education funding. But
while encouraging their colleagues to vote for it, they called it,
as Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., put it, ``a god-awful mess,'' that
should never have been brought to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is symbol of wasted time and misguided priorities of
the Republican Congress,'' said House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., who blasted away at the Republicans for spending
too much time ``on investigations (of Clinton and the Democrats)
instead of legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative Republicans agreed with that assessment and
criticized their leaders for reaching an agreement with Clinton
that includes nearly $20 billion in emergency spending for
GOP-backed defense programs, peacekeeping forces in Bosnia and farm
aid that will have to be paid for from projected surpluses. The
disgruntled Republicans said it would jeopardize some of the
anticipated revenues this year and next that have been earmarked
for shoring up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about using $20 billion out of the government
surplus for new spending. This idea of using Social Security money
is not right,'' said Rep. Mark Neumann, R-Wis., who is running for
the Senate this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sham. It's an embarrassment and we should vote no on
this ugly bill,'' echoed Rep. Jon Christensen, R-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   The revolt by GOP conservatives, most of them new to the
Congress, brought an angry Gingrich to the floor, where he accused
them of being ``perfectionists'' unschooled in the art of
legislative compromise necessary to the survival of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't pass a bill ... you can't get anything done,''
Gingrich shouted. ``In a free society you have to have give and
take.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 2058EDT &QL; 
