<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABERNATHY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ralph David Abernathy III indicted on 35 countsBy Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When a Fulton County grand jury returned a 35-count
felony indictment against state Sen. Ralph David Abernathy III
Tuesday on charges he lied to get $13,000 in state funds, it broke
the hearts of those who had worked with the legislator's renowned
father to win civil rights for black people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad for him, and I'm sad for his family,'' said the Rev.
Joseph Lowery, a core member of the group that worked with Ralph
David Abernathy Sr. and the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. during the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Said the Rev. Hosea Williams, another King aide: ``When I think
of how his father sacrificed and suffered. The added hurt to my
heart is seeing the Abernathy name being drug through the mud.''
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy, a Democrat whose 34th District represents western
Fulton County and part of Cobb, is charged with 10 counts each of
theft by taking, making a false statement and violating of his oath
of office; four counts of forgery; and one count of influencing a
witness.
</P>
<P>
   The Fulton County grand jury indictment caps a Georgia Bureau of
Investigation probe into allegations that the senator forged the
names of volunteers and falsely claimed expenses or that he paid
employees for services like writing speeches. The indictment also
said Abernathy offered to pay a staffer $2,700 after the GBI
investigation began so she could substantiate Abernathy's claim
that he had paid her for legislative services. The felonies carry
prison sentences ranging from one to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Fulton County Judge John Langford set his bond at
$25,000. He is supposed to surrender by 6 p.m. Wednesday at the
Fulton County Jail and post bond.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a legislator was indicted was in 1992. State Sen.
Hildred Schumake and state Rep. Frank Redding were indicted on
separate federal extortion charges. Schumake's charges were dropped
after two mistrials, and Redding pleaded guilty to trying to extort
cash from undercover agents in return for stopping legislation that
would have shut harmed strip club businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the 19 grand jurors voted, Abernathy made a short
statement to them, denying that he had done anything illegal,
according to his attorney, Steve Strelzik. The law allows public
officials the special right to speak to a grand jury considering
charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's absolutely not guilty,'' Strelzik told reporters outside
the grand jury room of the Fulton County Courthouse as Abernathy
left the building via a back stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy's attorneys and some of his friends questioned the
timing of the indictment, which comes two weeks before state
Attorney General Thurbert Baker, who brought the charges, faces the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely astounding,'' said state Rep. Tyrone Brooks
(D-Atlanta) another key player in the 1960s civil rights movement.
``It just seems to be this is dirty, low-down politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker denied any political motivation. ``I'm going to make sure
we pursue public corruption wherever that might lead us,'' Baker
said. ``This office does not bend to the political winds of this
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment is the latest trouble for the son of one of the
pre-eminent civil rights leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS recently took documents from Abernathy's legislative
office as part of a similar federal investigation. Atlanta news
organizations reported earlier this year that there were letters on
the computer hard drive from Abernathy's legislative office
indicating the senator had hoped to get a $150,000 loan by using
his influence to obtain a Fulton County medical contract for a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, Abernathy was disqualified from running for
re-election when his $400 qualifying check bounced. And in
December, Abernathy was caught at Hartsfield International Airport
with marijuana in his underwear. He was fined $500, and a month
later, his Senate colleagues gave him a public reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   He had other highly publicized problems in 1994. In January, he
paid a fine for leading police on a high-speed chase through East
Point. Six months later, a woman said Abernathy barged in on her
while she was using a stall in an unmarked state Capitol restroom
and refused to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest tragedy is this will chip away at the legacy of
his father,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry was also concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as bad as you might think'' Lowery said. ``He's had a
streak of bad luck that became high profile. I deeply regret what
has happened, and I hope and pray that it's a mistake that he can
clear it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
