<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COGGINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida man's family baffled by murders
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEESBURG, Fla. _ They came to Alice Gutkowski's house Monday
morning with a pot of coffee and good intentions; three neighbors
in a central Florida retirement community trying to do what little
they could to help their friend through a very hard time.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, a maid in a high-rise hotel in downtown Atlanta,
more than 400 miles away, had discovered the bodies of Gutkowski's
51-year-old husband, Ronald, one of his co-workers, Gerrold
Shropshire, 50; and Phillip Dover, a 31-year-old business associate
from Gainesville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   They were in Atlanta to see the Falcons battle the New Orleans
Saints in the Georgia Dome on Sunday afternoon. Police say each man
was shot in the head between midnight and 8 a.m. Sunday, when a
maid opened the door to their room on the 24th floor of the Atlanta
Hilton &AMP; Towers.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, as the sun rose above the sprawling Highland Lakes
retirement community, Kathryn Benning and two neighbors came to try
to console Alice Gutkowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hadn't slept all night,'' Benning said. ``She was just
crying and crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Chris, a 23-year-old college student, had a premonition
about his father's trip, Benning said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said Oh, I'm so sorry about your father.' He said, It's just
bad,' and he hung his head,'' she said. ``He didn't really want his
dad to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Benning and two neighbors sat on a sofa with Alice Gutkowski for
an hour or so, hugging her when she cried and listening as she
tried to describe her shock. A neighbor plugged in a coffee pot and
poured a few cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just so broken up about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 1,500 people _ nearly all are 55 or older _ live in the
Gutkowski's neighborhood, a neat and quiet place where fountains in
front of some palm trees at the entranceway spray water two or
three feet into the air and people steer golf carts to the
clubhouse for card games or square-dancing lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Gutkowski drove down those streets most weekday mornings
for the last four years, since he and his family moved to Leesburg,
Fla., about 40 miles north of Orlando, from Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He and Shropshire worked in the office at Lester Coggins
Trucking Inc., a company in nearby Okahumpka, Fla., whose 300
drivers haul freight to the continental 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Denhof, the company's general manager, said both employees
were fine men on and off the job.
</P>
<P>
   He bristled at the notion that the killings were somehow related
to illegal drugs, describing Gutkowski and Shropshire as family men
who spent a good deal of time in church.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find nicer people. It just doesn't make sense to
us,'' he said. ``I think they got mixed up with some bad people in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutkowski attended Sunday mass at St. Paul's Catholic Church in
Leesburg. Shropshire went to New Covenant Baptist Church in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Their co-workers at the trucking company had taped a yellow
flier over the company suggestion box by Tuesday afternoon
announcing the creation of a fund to help the relatives that both
men left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all kind of reeling from it,'' Denhof said. ``They were
just well-respected people and everyone's shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his company had been ``bombarded'' with calls from
newspaper and television reporters. Relatives at the Gutkowski's
house spoke with reporters early in the day but declined to be
interviewed later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bixler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
