A7846 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLASMOKE-COX     10-20 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLASMOKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attorneys say smokers have themselves to blame
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A day after hearing lawyers for sick smokers paint
tobacco companies as greedy and deceitful, jurors in the first
class action lawsuit against the industry to go to trial heard
defense lawyers argue that smokers are responsible for their own
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about the choice to smoke and about what people
knew about the health risks of smoking when they made the choice to
smoke,'' attorney Robert C. Heim, who is representing Philip
Morris, told the six-member panel. ``It's about quitting smoking
and it's about responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an argument that has won for tobacco companies in most
previous lawsuits, but plaintiffs' attorneys are banking on
anti-smoking sentiment to help as many as 500,000 Florida smokers
win from tobacco companies damages that some observers believe
could reach $200 billion. On Monday, plaintiffs' lawyer Stanley
Rosenblatt said the companies have a long history of hiding
evidence and trying to convince the public that there is doubt
about whether smoking is dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Heim countered that companies have been responsible and
reasonable, and that the health impact of the habit has been known
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1604, the King of England wrote a book about smoking,
saying it was unhealthy,'' said Heim, who also noted that tobacco's
history is so woven into the American fabric that tobacco leaves
grace the columns on the U.S. Capitol Building. ``Henry Ford
wouldn't let his workers smoke because he believed it was
unhealthy, and Thomas Edison did the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the dangers of smoking have been known for so long,
smokers can't argue that they weren't informed when they took up
the habit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heim also argued that smoking is not addictive in the sense that
heroin is addictive, and that people can quit if they choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, 1.5 million people quit smoking every
year,'' he said. ``Over the last 30 years, 46 million Americans
have quit smoking and quit smoking for good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
