<HEADER>
A7847 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIPLE21-COX     10-20 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weekend of fun for men turns into heartbreak for survivorsBy
Lyda Longa and Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the everyday lives of Phillip Dover, Gerrold
Shropshire and Ronald Gutkowski, last weekend was to have been an
exciting high point: Dinner in Atlanta, an extravagant stay at one
of the city's upscale hotels on Saturday night and a pro football
game on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gutkowski, who worked with Shropshire at a trucking
company in Okahumpka, Fla., wanted to stay at a cheaper hotel
outside the city, Shropshire insisted on the Atlanta Hilton &AMP;
Towers.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a one-night stay and they could split the $180 cost
of the room. Besides, the Atlanta Falcons tickets were free,
provided by Dover's trucking broker company, GTO 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he had never made that trip,'' Maple Bronner said of
Shropshire, her fiancee. ``I remember Ronnie saying they should
stay at a smaller, less expensive hotel. But Gerrold wanted to have
fun. He really wanted Ronnie to have a good time also and they were
really looking forward to this trip. It's all they talked about.''
</P>
<P>
   A hotel maid found all three men shot to death in Room 2417 at
about 8 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police reported no progress on their investigation into
the slayings Tuesday, but did say they had found no ties to the
drug world with any of the victims. They did not retreat from their
earlier statements, however, that the killings appeared to have
been more than a random crime.
</P>
<P>
   Shropshire, who had recently turned 50, was engaged to Bronner,
lived in the Orlando suburb of Altamonte Springs, was a deacon in
his church and manager at Coggins Trucking Co.
</P>
<P>
   Gutkowski, 51, lived in Leesburg, Fla., with his wife Alice and
was a supervisor for Coggins Trucking.
</P>
<P>
   Dover, 31, was single, lived in an apartment in Gainesville,
Ga., about 50 miles northeast of Atlanta, and was a dispatcher with
GTO.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cornett, the head of GTO, and Scott Shope, another
dispatcher for the company and Dover's roommate until August, said
Dover had become friends with Shropshire through his job.
</P>
<P>
   As a dispatcher it was Dover's job to find the best freight
price for client shippers, and this is done by dealing with
dispatchers at trucking firms. Once a deal is struck, it is the
broker dispatcher's duty to monitor its progress through delivery.
The shipper pays the broker, and the broker then pays the freight
company.
</P>
<P>
   Shope said Dover and Shropshire had gone to other sporting
events together, but Cornett said this was the first time that
Dover had used the company's Falcon tickets.
</P>
<P>
   There were four tickets, Shope said, and it was his
understanding that Dover had invited Shropshire and told him to
bring a friend. Shope said Dover had offered him the fourth ticket,
but he was unable to go.
</P>
<P>
   Bronner was also offered the ticket, but because she was to
undergo surgery several days before the football game, she decided
to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Dover, Phillip's father, said he talked to his son
``toward the middle of last week'' and the young man asked if he
would like to go to Sunday's game. ``I told him I'd love to go, and
said, 'If you don't find anyone else, call me back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dover never called back, his father said, and that was the last
time they spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Bronner, who had met Dover earlier this year when she and
Shropshire traveled to Atlanta to see the Braves on some of Dover's
tickets, said she talked by phone to Dover on Saturday night.
Shropshire had called to check in before the three men went out to
dinner and Dover chatted with her from the hotel room for a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   During their conversation, Shropshire apparently told Bronner
that he and his friends would not drive anywhere, but instead would
walk around downtown so they could explore. They promised they'd
call after they returned to the hotel from dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Bronner said she had awakened Sunday morning in her Orlando home
wondering why Shropshire, a man she described as generous and
attentive, had not called the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole day went by and I was growing more and more
concerned,'' Bronner said. ``Finally I got a call from Gerrold's
daughter Kimberly, who lives in Raleigh, North Carolina. She had
gotten a call from Atlanta police asking about her father.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday morning, Orlando police officers showed up at
Bronner's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family didn't want me to go outside and talk to police,''
Bronner said. ``My daughter spoke to them instead and she came back
inside and told me Gerrold was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Atlanta police had speculated late Sunday and early
Monday that the murders may have been drug-related, Maj. Mickey
Lloyd on Tuesday emphatically said that police had failed to find a
``narcotics connection to any of the three victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said the victims' cars were taken to the GBI's crime lab
Tuesday morning for further investigation. ``There are certain
aspects of cases that are routine. We can't discuss it any
further,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell echoed comments of police Monday, saying
that the killings were ``not random'' and should not make anyone
feel unsafe downtown.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Campbell told a reporter: ``We will continue to get
the message out about downtown being safe. Interestingly enough,
there were tens of thousands of people in downtown for the Saints
game with the Falcons, or just coming to enjoy a pleasant weekend
in Atlanta. I don't think any of them saw or heard, or felt unsafe
while they were here. This tragedy is, I think, an individual act
that must be seen in that context.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the insistence of family and friends of the three
men that they wouldn't have been involved in drugs or illicit
activities, the mayor's spokesman, Jabari Simama, said Tuesday the
mayor stands by his earlier comments speculating that the killings
were ``not random.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the victims were forced to lie on their stomachs and
were shot in the back of the head, and because there was no sign of
forced entry into the hotel room, police believe his earlier
statements are accurate, Simama said. ``Random acts of killing
generally don't exhibit that type of planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyda Longa and Jack Warner write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
