<HEADLINE>
IBM SAYS PROFIT ROSE 10 PERCENT BUT WARNS OF UNCERTAINTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM reported a 10 percent increase in third-quarter earnings
Tuesday because of stronger computer sales, but the company's
executives warned that global economic uncertainty could lead to
short-term problems in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, the world's largest computer company, posted a profit of
$1.49 billion, or $1.56 a diluted share, compared with $1.36
billion, or $1.35 a share, in the quarter a year earlier. Revenue
for the period increased 8 percent, to $20.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The results were slightly above analysts' expectations of $1.53
a share, and the anticipation of a strong quarter had pushed the
company's stock up $10 over the last week, to a new 52-week
intraday high of $142.4375 Tuesday before retreating. The stock
fell $1.50, to $137.875, before the third-quarter earnings were
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the numbers is a mixed business story. The company's
sales of hardware, from its giant mainframes to personal computers,
increased by 4.2 percent, to $8.7 billion. This is a turnaround
from the first half of 1998, when a glut of personal computers and
delays in mainframe purchases hurt sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company's information technology services segment, which
provides software and computer equipment services to corporations,
was also strong, with revenue rising by 22.6 percent, to $5.7
billion. (IBM does not release earnings results for individual
business segments.) The company attributed this rise to a desire by
corporations to improve computer-related business efficiencies when
faced with an economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   On the negative side, however, was a decline in business in Asia
and Latin America along with continued problems in the company's
microelectronics business, which reflects severe price competition
in the manufacture of computer memory chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``While IBM is entering the fourth quarter with some real
momentum,'' said Louis Gerstner Jr., the company's chairman and
chief executive, ``we are facing a number of significant short-term
issues, including an uncertain global economic environment, ongoing
weaknesses in some parts of Asia and Latin America and continued
price pressures in semiconductors.''
</P>
<P>
   With strong earnings against a backdrop of business uncertainty,
IBM's chief financial officer, Douglas Maine, warned in a
conference call with analysts against overly optimistic
fourth-quarter earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are pleased with our strong third-quarter
performance,'' he said, ``economic uncertainties should lead to a
conclusion not to raise earnings estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   David Takata, an analyst at Gruntal &AMP; Co., said: ``The good news
is that IBM wasn't hit as bad as what the worst fears might have
indicated. I'm conservative, and I've expected the company to get
hit with some economic fallout. But it just hasn't happened yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Helmig, an analyst at Soundview Technology Group, said,
``Loud and clear, we got a lot of good news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly had a strong revenue performance and they are
well positioned in Europe and North America for a sustained
performance,'' he added. ``Still, with currency risks and with the
world economic scene, we'd all be better off to watch and see how
it unfolds rather than taking the good news of the moment and
increasing our expectations. That's the prudent approach.''
</P>
<P>
   With a cost reduction program in place, most of the increase in
revenue fell to the bottom line. Still, the company's gross profit
margin of 37.2 percent in the 1998 third quarter fell slightly,
compared with 38.2 percent in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
