<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU defensive line worries Tech
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Florida State always seems to have what separates the
good from the great in college football: top-notch defensive
linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida State defensive line has become a breeding ground
for NFL linemen, and this year is no different, leaving the Georgia
Tech a monumental task this Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   An offense that has scored only three points in its last two
meetings with Florida State has got to figure out a way to find
some air against a team that keeps plugging in outstanding
defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest vacancy this year was left by end Andre Wadsworth,
the third overall pick in the 1998 NFL draft and the highest pick
in FSU history.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, ends Reinard Wilson and Peter Boulware were
drafted in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   This year's crew is led by defensive ends Tony Bryant and Roland
Seymour and defensive tackles Jerry Johnson and Corey Simon, the
player who signed with Georgia in 1995 before an NCAA investigation
into his recruitment had him changing his plans. Remember the
names. Chances are you'll hear them again on an NFL draft day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all great athletes,'' Georgia Tech center Craig Page
said. ``Not necessarily bigger guys. But they all play extremely
low and come off the ball harder than any team that we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Seminole defensive linemen have been
considered ferocious. They have a reputation for feasting on
quarterbacks, talking some trash and taking late shots at
quarterbacks. But nobody denies their results.
</P>
<P>
   This game is not for the meek, and Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton
knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's the kind of game, if you're scared to get
hit, that you'd want to be in,'' Hamilton said. ``They put their
hands down and come straight up the field. They'll do anything to
get to the quarterback. They have a lot of speed throughout the
defensive line. I've got to stay poised back in the pocket. If the
rush comes, I've got to hang in there. If I've got to take a lick
for a completion, I've got to do that. If I've got to take off and
run, I've got to pick my times where I do that, also.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton knows one way Tech can hold off the rush is by
establishing the run, with draw plays or quick screens. Virginia
did a good job of stuffing Tech's running game, holding the Yellow
Jackets to a season-low 83 yards. The Yellow Jackets are not
fooling themselves into thinking any of it will be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can line up and slug it down the field,''
Tech coach George O'Leary said. ``You need to come up with some big
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was one in a line of six starting quarterbacks Florida
State knocked out of games last year. He was sacked five times in
the 38-0 loss and hit 11 times. He was able to complete only nine
of 18 passes, and he was intercepted once.
</P>
<P>
   He had his roughest game of this season last week against
Virginia when a hit by two defenders sent him out of the game for a
while with a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've watched film (of the Virginia game) and are probably
licking their lips a little bit,'' guard Jason Burks said. ``We've
got to have a great effort and make a pact Joe's not going to get
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Burks said what impresses him most about the FSU defensive line
is when he's seen a defensive tackle chasing a running back
downfield. And actually keeping up. Tech will have to figure a way
to neutralize that speed and do it a week after illegal procedures
and a physical Cavalier defensive front kept the Yellow Jackets
front from controlling the line consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't come close to playing our best game,'' Page said.
``Hopefully, it'll come this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
