<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 8th graf, corrects to read 'seventh day' sted of
'eighth'
 &HT;    MIDDLE EAST SUMMIT APPROACHES 'END GAME'; PROPOSALS FLOATED,
AGREEMENT STILL ELUSIVE
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israeli and Palestinian leaders were nearing
agreement on a complicated land-for-peace accord late Tuesday, as
President Clinton and Jordan's King Hussein worked into the night
to try to nurse six days of intensive summitry toward a fruitful
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat were reportedly within reach of a deal that would
call for Israeli troops to withdraw in phases from an additional 13
percent of the occupied West Bank and turn over authority for the
relinquished territory to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement would eventually leave the Palestinians with
effective control over some 40 percent of the long-contested land.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the Palestinians would agree to implement a set of
U.S.-brokered security guarantees aimed at combatting anti-Israeli
terrorism -- like the grenade attack that left 64 Israelis injured
in the southern city of Beersheba on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has insisted that Palestinians agree to take a number
of steps targeting terrorism, including the confiscation of illegal
firearms, close cooperation between Palestinian and Israeli
security officials and the arrest and, in some cases, extradition,
of suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin suggested that an
Israeli troop withdrawal would, under the U.S. plan, be carried out
in steps, contingent upon actual performance of Palestinian
security commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The initiative was designed to create a parallel process,''
Rubin said. ''As greater and greater security is provided and
implemented, greater and greater amounts of land will
</P>
<P>
   be turned over.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the talks had entered the ''end game,'' but he
declined to speculate on whether an agreement appeared imminent. A
White House official, speaking on background, left open the
possibility that negotiations could extend into a seventh day on
Wednesday, adding that Clinton has blocked out time to continue
with the summit as needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're into a phase of very hard bargaining,'' Rubin told
reporters gathered at the secluded Wye River Plantation Conference
Center, on Maryland's Eastern Shore, where the Israeli-Palestinian
summit has been underway since last Thursday. ''Some obstacles have
been overcome, but significant gaps remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was decidedly more upbeat, however, than on Monday, when
the terrorist attack in Israel threatened to scuttle the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''That did throw a wrench in the works,'' Rubin said, adding
that talks were moving ahead on multiple fronts on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are rushing around and trying to come up with bridging
ideas and ways to resolve existing problems,'' Rubin said, ''rather
than rebutting talking points.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said there was no hard deadline being imposed on the
talks, but he said the time for putting off difficult decisions had
passed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This cannot go on indefinitely,'' Rubin said, ''but we're
taking it one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who scratched a two-day campaign fund-raising trip to
California to remain engaged in the Wye talks, journeyed to the
isolated setting Tuesday afternoon for the fifth time in six days.
</P>
<P>
   There he was joined by Hussein, one of the most enduring figures
in the Mideast. The ailing monarch was called in by U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright to help Clinton try to salvage the
talks in the wake of Monday's attack.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein, who is suffering from cancer and has been undergoing
treatment at the prestigious Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., has
been a central figure throughout a generation of hostilities and
peace overtures between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked closely with the Clinton administration on the
issue since the Oslo accords set in motion the current peace
process in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ''King Hussein is a person with great integrity, who has
enormous support amongst many different peoples in the Middle
East,'' Rubin said. ''I do expect him to be a key player in this
drama.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in an unusually blunt moment, the ailing Hussein
expressed open frustration with Netanyahu's government, blaming him
in a letter for bringing the Oslo process to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   The process was essentially stalled for a 19-month period that
ended in late September, when Clinton brought Arafat and the
Israeli leader together for a brief Oval Office meeting that
resulted in the Wye summit.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 2 million of the world's 6 million Palestinians reside
in Jordan, which is sandwiched between Iraq and Israel. Jordan
would be greatly affected by the direction that any peace accord
might take between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
