<HEADLINE>
WILD RIDE ON WALL STREET LEAVES INDEXES MIXED AT THE END OF A BUSY
DAY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices went on a wild ride Tuesday, soaring for
most of the session only to retreat in the last hour or so of
trading and end up narrowly mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained ground for the fifth
consecutive session, the first time since June it has rallied for
that many days in succession.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip index, which at one point during the morning was
up 186 points, closed at 8,505.85, up 39.40 points, or slightly
under one-half of a percent. It is the first time the Dow closed
above 8,500 since Aug. 26. For the year, the 30-stoc index is up
7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index eked out a gain of
1.54 points, or a little more than 0.1 percent, to 1,063.93. But
the Nasdaq composite index fell 9.54 points, or 0.6 percent, to
1,639.19.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the S&AMP;P 500 has gained 9.5 percent; the Nasdaq
is up 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said business did not seem especially brisk Tuesday, but
trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange was heavy at 954
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   As conditions in the equity markets stabilize, money continues
to flow out of the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond fell by more than a
point, and the yield rose 5.07 percent, from 4.97 percent.
Short-term interest rates rose.
</P>
<P>
   While some stock investors apparently had second thoughts late
in the session about the wisdom of holding highly liquid,
well-known stocks, issues of smaller companies were popular all
day.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said they were encouraged by the continued improvement
in small caps, which have been battered so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index, made up of small-company stocks, rose
5.86 points, or 1.66 percent, to 358.31. And the New York Stock
Exchange composite index gained 2.78 points, or 0.5 percent, to
528.28.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enormous opportunity in small caps if we have
stability here,'' said Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and others said the market has run too far, too fast, and
may be due for a selloff. And the rise in the Dow has indeed been
dizzying: so far this month, it is up more than 10 percent, its
best monthly showing since January 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks got a big boost early in the day from several big banks,
including Chase Manhattan and Wells Fargo, which reported
third-quarter earnings that were better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, the nation's second-biggest bank, rose 1 15/16, to 45
5/16 after it said it earned 82 cents a share in the period, 5
cents a share better than the consensus forecast from Wall Street
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, which is merging with the Norwest Corp., rose 11
116, to 3789 16 after it said earnings rose 20 percent, which also
exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The results encouraged investors to believe that the worst is
over for the battered financial-services sector and helped to lift
stocks of money center banks and brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup rose 2 9/16, to 45 5/16. J.P. Morgan gained 2{, to
95]. Fueled by reports it might be acquired by Deutsche Bank AG,
Europe's biggest bank, Bankers Trust gained 4], to 59[. And Merrill
Lynch jumped 2 7/16, to 54 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, just over one-third of the companies that make
up the S&AMP;P have reported third-quarter earnings, and the good news
is they have come in as expected, even though the bar was
lowered,'' said Bob Gasser, head of block trading at J.P. Morgan &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the bigger test will come after we are through this
earnings season and people start looking out in the future, trying
to determine when they will trough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM gave investors reason to start thinking about the future.
The computer company reported Tuesday that third-quarter earnings
rose 10 percent, a number that exceeded Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But the company gave analysts a cautious reading its prospects,
saying that continued problems in Asia and Latin America and
decreased spending by corporations on high-technology equipment
could crimp profits in the fourth quarter and into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   IBM ended the day at 137~, down 1{. Early in the session, the
stock traded as high as 142 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have to contend with this sort of earnings
picture for a couple of quarters to come,'' Clark of Credit Suisse
First Boston said. ``We still have battles to fight, because people
are not looking forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
