<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT LAWYER SAYS US CASE BASED ON ``CRAZY QUILT OF EMAIL''
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. Tuesday branded the government's
antitrust case against it as a ``fundamentally misconceived
attack'' on free markets and on consumers, and said Justice
Department lawyers had unfairly tried to paint the software giant
as a ``great Satan'' and demonize its chairman, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not really an antitrust case, but a return of the
Luddites _ the 19th Century reactionaries who, fearful of
competition, went around smashing machines with sledgehammers to
arrest the march of progress,'' said Microsoft's lead attorney,
John Warden, as the company opened its defense to antitrust charges
in federal district court.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 20 states accuse Microsoft of
illegally using its monopoly hold on the market for computer
operating systems _ in which Microsoft's Windows software claims 90
percent market share _ to crush potential Windows competitors and
to bully its way into new markets. Monopolies are not illegal, but
their owners may not use their power to crush potential competitors
to the monopoly or to push into new lines of business.
</P>
<P>
   Warden said the government's case was built on ``a crazy quilt
of e-mail fragments'' and ``deposition excerpts that are taken out
of context.'' In cross-examining the first witness in the trial,
Jim Barksdale, chief executive of Netscape Communications Corp., he
suggested that Netscape incited the government lawsuit as a mere
business ploy.
</P>
<P>
   Warden's comments came on Day Two of what is considered the most
significant antitrust case in 15 years, and potentially one of the
most important ever. Rivals to Microsoft say a loss by the
government would give the Redmond, Wash.-based company leeway to
muscle its way unfairly into on-line banking, Internet commerce and
other new businesses. Allies of Microsoft say a government victory
would signal a new era of meddling in the market by antitrust
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The government claims that Gates, Microsoft's billionaire
chairman, feared that his lucrative Windows monopoly could be
undermined by the rise of two rival products: Netscape's Navigator,
a type of ``browser'' software used to view material on the
Internet, and Sun Microsystem's Java software, which brings
information to users over the Internet whether their computers are
powered by Windows or by another operating system.
</P>
<P>
   According to the government, Microsoft feared that Navigator and
Java would make it less essential for people to buy Windows-based
computers, as they could link to the Internet with computers
powered by software from Microsoft's rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement Monday, David Boies, the lead
government lawyer, said Gates' first response to this threat was to
approach Netscape in a June 1995 meeting with an offer to divide
the browser market, with Microsoft making browsers for all newer
IBM-compatible computers. If true, that would likely represent
illegal collusion by the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   When Netscape refused to cooperate, the government said,
Microsoft began a three-pronged campaign to damage Netscape.
According to the government:
</P>
<P>
   _Microsoft offered its own browser for free, a form of predatory
pricing designed to force Netscape to stop charging for its browser
and deprive Netscape of a key revenue source.
</P>
<P>
   _Microsoft tried to persuade other companies to abandon their
support and distribution deals with Netscape, using access to
Microsoft Windows as leverage. Without the right to sell Windows,
most computer makers cannot appeal to customers. Software firms
need access to the upcoming versions of Windows in order to make
and sell their own products. Microsoft illegally used the monopoly
power of Windows to turn Netscape's business partners against it,
the government said.
</P>
<P>
   _Microsoft ``tied'' its own browser, called Internet Explorer,
into Windows, so that anyone buying a new computer had an
inducement to use Microsoft's browser and found it more difficult
to use Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   Warden attacked each of these arguments in his opening statment.
</P>
<P>
   Building a browser into Windows allows people to use the same
program to view information, whether it is on the user's own
computer or on the Internet, Warden said. Microsoft engineers
wanted Windows to have this easy-to-use feature even before
Netscape existed, Warden said. Tying the browser to Windows was
aimed at improving Windows, not damaging Netscape, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Warden suggested while cross-examining Netscape chief
Barksdale, Netscape itself has tied new features to its browser,
such as an e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's contracts with computer makers and other business
partners were ``not only completely unobjectionable, but
pro-competitive,'' Warden said. The contracts did not choke off
Netscape's distribution channels, he said, as Netscape has plans
under way to distribute more than 100 million copies of its
browser.
</P>
<P>
   Warden also described the notion that Microsoft tried to divide
the browser market with Netscape as ``fantastical.'' He suggested
that Netscape mischaracterized the June 1995 meeting to the Justice
Department as a ``means of enlisting the government as Netscape's
protector.'' In reality, the meeting was a normal conversation
between two companies about how to serve customers better, Warden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also objected to suggestions on Monday by Boies, the
Justice Department's lawyer, that Gates misled the government in
videotaped depositions earlier this year. ``A personal attack on a
man whose vision and innovation have been at the core of the
benefits that people are reaping from the Information Age is no
substitute for proof of anti-competitive conduct,'' Warden said.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale is scheduled to return to the stand Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
