u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOWEAPONS-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      10-20 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOWEAPONS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE THREATENS TO HALT BIOWEAPONS TRIAL IN LIEU OF UNDISCLOSED
EVIDENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE _ A federal judge threatened Tuesday to halt the
trial of three men accused of sending death threats to President
Clinton after federal prosecutors failed to disclose investigative
information to defense attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, I want the information ... and I want it
produced immediately, as quickly as humanly possible,'' U.S.
District Judge Hilda Tagle told assistant U.S. Attorney Mervyn
Mosbacker. ``I'm very unhappy with this.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Oliver Dean Emigh, 63, Jack Abbott Grebe, 43, and Johnie Wise,
72, are being tried on charges of conspiracy and threatening to use
weapons of mass destruction in an alleged assassination plot.
Prosecutors say the men, members of the separatist group, Republic
of Texas, planned to modify disposable lighters to shoot cactus
needles coated with biological agents, including anthrax and HIV,
into their targets.
</P>
<P>
   No actual biological weapons were found, but the three are
accused of sending threatening e-mail messages to Clinton, U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's comments ended the second day of testimony, during
which a 45-minute FBI videotape was played, showing the men on the
evening that the threats were sent from an FBI informant's trailer
home in Harlingen.
</P>
<P>
   On the black and white videotape, two of the defendants, between
sips of homemade wine and talk about car repairs, instructed the
informant, John L. Cain, to send e-mails to President Clinton and
other top-ranking federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, there went Hillary and Billary,'' quips Cain, after
announcing he had sent the threat to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good deal,'' replies Grebe.
</P>
<P>
   The government indictment in the case says the e-mail messages
threatened: ``Your ... employees and their families have been
targeted for destruction by revenge ... Personal delivery systems
have been developed to inject bacteria and or viruses for the
purposes of killing, maiming or causing great suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   On the videotape, Cain also compliments Wise and Grebe for
targeting agency heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught if you're going to fight, pick on the biggest
one,'' Grebe replies. ``That way, you can make an example of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Cain can be heard on the tape asking the men what they
want him to do next, and he asks Wise when a prototype of his
homemade biological weapon, the modified cigarette lighter, would
be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done a thing,'' Wise replies. ``I'm just scattered
so thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise also can be heard on the videotape saying the first victim
of the biological weapon would be Cameron County Court-at-Law Judge
Migdalia Lopez, who angered Republic of Texas leaders by not
allowing defendants to represent themselves in her court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find out where she hangs out and when she gets
lunch or coffee,'' Wise can be heard saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic of Texas, which is split into several factions,
believes Texas was illegally annexed and is not part of the United
States. Cain has testified that he went to work in February for
local members of the group, and last March was made
``undersecretary of commerce'' at a meeting in Conroe.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys claim it was Cain who orchestrated the alleged
plot and entrapped the others. Cain was paid $16,000 to $18,000 as
an informant for the FBI. The government has not yet presented
evidence on whether the three defendants ever paid Cain to send the
e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers told jurors on Monday that Cain had a spotty
employment record and had attempted to become a police officer and
a police informant before the biological weapons case developed.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors, who had begun hearing the case on Monday, were excused
early on Tuesday after the judge questioned prosecutors and an FBI
agent about missing computer files that were kept by Cain, who is
the prosecution's star witness.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Dan Herink asked Tagle to declare a mistrial,
arguing that the government's failure to turn over the documents
before trial hampered his ability to defend his client, Grebe. The
judge denied the motion, but demanded that the records be produced
by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The three men face up to life in prison if they are convicted in
the case. They have been held without bond since their arrests last
July. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
