<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Wells, Norwest Shareholders OK Merger  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Shareholders for Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. and Minneapolis's Norwest Corp.
approved plans to merge yesterday, creating the nation's
seventh-largest bank.
<P>
   The move sets the stage for swift completion of this year's
second transaction involving a historic San Francisco financial
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks ago, BankAmerica Corp., the bank founded in
1904 by A.P. Giannini as Bank of Italy and later to become the
West's dominant financial institution, completed its sale to North
Carolina's NationsBank Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Now the spotlight shifts to Wells Fargo, the bank that opened
for business in 1852 to provide financial and express services in
the Gold Rush era, growing a century and a half later into
BankAmerica's chief rival.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo said 98 percent of its shareholders who cast votes
at a special meeting yesterday approved the proposed merger.
Norwest shareholders also approved the merger, including plans to
issue stock by Norwest to complete the deal and a change in the
name of the financial institution to Wells.
</P>
<P>
   While both banks sold to out-of-state institutions and described
their transactions as ``mergers of equals,'' their experiences
contrast sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Despite adopting the BankAmerica name, NationsBank is treating
its partner like a conquered province, putting its own people in
key positions and closing the bank's San Francisco headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Recent losses in investment and international banking at the old
BofA have marginalized executives of the San Francisco bank,
including former Chief Executive David Coulter, who announced his
resignation yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest is showing a much more even hand. The combined bank's
home office will be in San Francisco, and Wells executives are
getting plumb assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Chairman Rod Jacobs, for example, is getting the crucial
chief financial officer slot at the new bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more balanced distribution of responsibilities is very
noticeable at Wells Fargo,'' said John Wilson, a San Francisco
executive recruiter with Korn/Ferry International. ``That makes a
huge difference in morale.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Wells Fargo's style was much closer to NationsBank's
when it took over downstate rival First Interstate Bancorp two
years ago. The bank fired dozens of senior First Interstate
managers within days of the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Wells Fargo said its third-quarter profit rose 20
percent from a year ago as income from fees and deposit service
charges jumped.
</P>
<P>
   The bank said it earned $347 million, or $3.99 a diluted share,
compared to $290 million, or $3.23 a share, in the 1997 third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo's revenue, including interest and noninterest
income, rose 4.4 percent, while expenses were virtually unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Loans and deposits, though down from last year, rose slightly
from the end of June, a sign that service problems and customer
defections stemming from the bank's hostile takeover of First
Interstate Bancorp are no longer problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wells Fargo's earnings came in a little better than
expected,'' said Van Kasper &AMP; Co. analyst Joseph Morford. ``They're
characteristic of a regional bank without any exposure to emerging
markets or hedge funds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
