</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSMUT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Battle Over Cybersmut Set to Begin Again  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A coalition of civil liberties groups plans to file a lawsuit this
week challenging a controversial online pornography amendment that
is part of the $500 billion omnibus spending bill.
<P>
   Before the ink dries on President Clinton's expected signature
of the bill, the American Civil Liberties Union, Electronic Privacy
Information Center &UR;  &LR; and Electronic Frontier Foundation will file a
joint lawsuit in federal court in Philadelphia, alleging the bill
stifles the free exchange of ideas and could be interpreted
differently in various jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the suit will mirror an earlier suit that last year
successfully killed off the Communications Decency Act, Congress'
first attempt to limit cybersmut.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this becomes law, the Starr report would be illegal,'' said
Barry Steinhardt, president of the Electronic Frontier Foundation
in San Francisco. ``The same people who pushed the Starr report are
pushing this legislation. In its haste to make that extremely
graphic report available to millions of people online, Congress may
be the most successful pornographers in the history of the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping $500 billion appropriations bill is sprinkled with
high-tech-friendly legislation that liberalizes limits on foreign
visas, places a three-year moratorium on new local and state
Internet taxes and extends a research-and-development tax credit
for another year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the pornography amendments are considered a black eye
for the industry amid the flurry of last-minute legislative
victories. They are still opposed by free-speech advocates and
Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions would impose criminal penalties on commercial Web
sites that allow anyone 17 or under to access pornographic material
deemed ``harmful to minors.'' Violators would face up to $50,000 in
fines and six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, they mandate that adult-oriented sites require a
credit card or personal ID number to ensure that only adults can
access them; if not, the sites face state and local taxes. Internet
service providers would be required to provide information on
filtering software to block salacious content.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deja vu all over again,'' said an ACLU spokeswoman.
``We've gone through this before, haven't we?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the original
Communications Decency Act trampled free-speech rights. That
legislation, ironically, was also added at the 11th hour to a much
larger bill, the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the new legislation, scornfully called CDA II, ``suffers
from the same constitutional problems as the first CDA,'' said
Chris Hansen, senior staff counsel of the ACLU in New York. ``In
the name of protecting children, it tries to ban speech which is
constitutionally protected for adults.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In an attempt to narrow the bill in accordance with the
Supreme Court's CDA decision, the new anti-pornography measures
apply only to commercial Web sites instead of the entire Internet
and use a ``harmful-to- minors'' standard instead of a broader
indecency standard.
</P>
<P>
   The ``harmful-to-minors'' standard would allow access to
material that had redeeming social, political or artistic value,
such as Web sites on breast cancer or AIDS awareness. That
standard, its defenders claim, has been upheld in federal and state
courts for decades and is the legal basis for pornography statutes
in 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read the Supreme Court decision (on the original CDA)
closely and rewrote (the proposed legislation) to apply the
principles of pornography law to the Web,'' said Peggy Peterson,
communications director for Representative Michael Oxley, R-Ohio,
who authored portions of the bill. ``It's not legal for a child to
go into a video store and buy an X-rated film. Those materials are
placed behind a wall or under a table. We're trying to apply that
same standard to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson scoffed at arguments that the Starr report violates the
new anti-porn bills. She said the government document was released
for noncommercial reasons, did not contain graphic images and ``was
not designed to appeal to prurient interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil liberties groups ``complained the CDA was too broad.
Now they're complaining this bill isn't broad enough,'' said Shyla
Welch, communications director at Enough is Enough, a Fairfax, Va.,
nonprofit organization that wants to restrict online pornography.
``Is there anything that will make these people happy? I think we
know the answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
