u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      10-20 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S KING HUSSEIN JOINS CLINTON AT MIDEAST TALKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ Jordan's ailing monarch, King Hussein, a
staunch supporter of the Mideast peace process, joined President
Clinton at a Maryland retreat Tuesday as peace talks stretched into
a sixth day.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated US officials conceded that almost every effort to
solve one sticking point has been met with arguments about other
nettlesome issues. The officials said they will continue Wednesday,
and they hope that some kind of accord can be reached in time for
an upbeat ceremony at the White House by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that at least some agreements were close to being
signed, those familiar with the negotiations said that lawyers were
revising the exact language of documents being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're past the atmospherics and down to hard bargaining,''
State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Israel's pressing concerns about security had
pushed other issues to the back burner, Rubin snapped, ``You'd be
surprised how every issue can be on the front burner. The front
burner is full.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the negotiators are pressing ahead with
discussions about a Palestinian airport and seaport, despite the
Israeli view that the talks should focus on preventing terrorism,
catching terrorists and extraditing suspects to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday marked the fifth time in six days that Clinton has flown
out to Wye River conference center. That is an extraordinary
commitment for any president, especially one facing impeachment
hearings and trying to travel around the country and bolster
candidates from his party two weeks before congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and independent analysts who follow the talks said the
United States is still trying to get essentially the same agreement
that officials were working on a year ago. In exchange for giving
up 13 percent more of the West Bank, Israel would receive
guarantees that Palestinian Authority will deal severely with
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to add muscle to the negotiating team, Clinton's
advisers called on Hussein, who was being treated for cancer in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the afternoon, Clinton and Hussein held alternate
meetings with Palestinians and Israelis. A joint meeting was
expected in the evening to ``turn what had been a two-way, tag-team
diplomacy perhaps into a little bit more of a three-way, tag-team
diplomacy,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein ``can add his unique perspective to these talks,'' White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. Rubin said the king would be a
welcome guest, ``given his charisma, given his special role in the
past, given the extensive, warm feelings people have for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hussein has taken on the role as the region's most eloquent and
impassioned proponent of peace, leaving well in the past conflicts
Jordan had with Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1967, Hussein, joining the Arab front that attacked
Israel, lost control over the West Bank and East Jerusalem, leading
to many of the problems over boundaries that persist Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And in September 1971, under pressure from the United States and
Israel, he cracked down on Palestinian guerrilla bases operating in
his territory, forcing them to relocate to other Mideast states.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Hussein wrote a widely publicized _ although
supposedly ``private'' _ letter to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu excoriating the Israelis for damaging the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   US officials feel extraordinary pressure for several reasons.
For one thing, everyone fears that another terrorist attack will
destroy the peace process. For another, Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat has threatened to declare an independent Palestinian state
if negotiations are not over by next May 4, a target date for the
end of the peace talks that was set during negotiations in Oslo,
Norway, in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
