<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHEON-SFCHRON &LR;      10-20 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Healtheon Pulls Its IPO _ Cites Market Turmoil  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Deciding it did not have the cure for the stock market's latest
headaches and heartburn, Healtheon Corp. pulled its plans yesterday
for a $51 million initial public offering.
<P>
   The Santa Clara company, which puts health care billing and
other medical transactions on the Internet, said it would wait for
market conditions to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trading pattern in the stock could be highly volatile, and
that's a risk the board prefers not to take,'' chief executive Mike
Long said in a telephone interview. ``We'll remain a private
company, seek private capital and continue to evaluate the public
markets in 1999 to determine if the right circumstance develops
where we would consider being a public company.''
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon also announced a new, $40 million round of private
funding that will keep the company running into next year. Its
founder and chairman, Jim Clark, who owns almost half the company,
spearheaded the latest round along with existing investors such as
venture firms Kleiner Perkins Caufield and Byers, and New
Enterprise Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors salivated at the chance to join the latest
venture of Clark, who scored big wins when he co-founded Netscape
Communications Corp. and Silicon Graphics Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As late as October 1, Healtheon had announced that the IPO would
value the company at about $430.1 million. In a filing with the
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the company said it would
sell about 6.5 million common shares for between $6 and $8 each.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, however, the stock market was getting jittery as a
global financial crisis spread, President Clinton fell under attack
at home and large hedge funds reported huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   According to the investment firm Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, 75
companies have pulled their IPOs since August and 15 have gone
public in the same time period.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Theglobe.com, a New York Internet company, dropped
the price on its IPO and put off the sale of its stock until today.
Theglobe.com, which runs a Web community with 1.9 million members,
plans to sell 3.1 million shares at $8 to $10 each, down 25 percent
from the planned price of $11 to $13.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms, including NetGrocer, an online supermarket, have
stalled their IPOs. ``There are tons and tons of them,'' said David
Simons, managing director of Digital Video Investments, a New York
institutional research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Even Goldman Sachs, the venerable investment bank, withdrew its
IPO, partly because of its exposure to global turmoil and partly
because of the market's uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The only firm to deliver a successful IPO in recent weeks was
eBay, a San Jose online auctioneer that went public on September 24
at $18 a share. The stock soared 163 percent to $47.38 that day,
and it closed yesterday at $46.50, up $1.13.
</P>
<P>
   Investors thought eBay might jump-start the IPO market, but that
didn't happen, according to Ken Anderson, the assistant managing
editor of VentureFinance, a newsletter that tracks venture capital
and IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were hoping that it would open a larger window for
other companies to come out, but (the IPO's success) was based just
on eBay's qualities,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon's SEC filing acknowledged the company's uncertain
future, including the reluctance of the health care industry to
adopt new high-tech methods of conducting business.
</P>
<P>
   According to the filing, the company brought in revenue last
year of $13.4 million but lost $25.4 million. In the first six
months of this year, revenue grew to $20.7 million but losses also
mounted to $21.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Long, the CEO, wouldn't say when Healtheon expects to turn a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded in 1995, employs 470 people, most at its
Santa Clara headquarters. In July, the company acquired Metis, a
privately held firm in San Francisco with a similar business model,
and in February, it bought Actamed, &UR;  &LR; which supplies data networks
for health care firms and has offices in Atlanta and Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Long said the company planned to use the revenue generated in
its public offering to acquire more companies. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the decision to be a public company in the June time
frame, when the public markets were a lot different than they are
now,'' Long said.
</P>
</TEXT>
