<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOP-COX     10-20 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women are finding positive support after mastectomy surgery
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The transformation was immediate.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Motter entered the little shop three years ago feeling
depressed and self-conscious but emerged just one hour later
feeling ``pretty and feminine'' and ``like myself again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Piqua woman underwent a mastectomy in 1995 and remembers
dreading that first shopping trip for a prosthesis and bras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to come in and didn't want to show them what had
happened to me,'' she recalled last week while paying her annual
visit to the boutique.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I felt self-conscious about being fitted, but
everyone was so kind and understanding. After I found out that the
lady fitting me had gone through the same thing, it put me at
ease.''
</P>
<P>
   Her positive experience took place at Silhouette's For Women, a
Clayton shop that caters to those who have undergone breast
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The shop, its owners and merchandise reflect a new attitude
toward women in need of post-mastectomy apparel _ breast
prostheses, bra and swimwear.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Cancer Society, an estimated 178,700
new cases of invasive breast cancer will be diagnosed among women
in the United States during 1998. Each year more than 7,000 Ohio
women are diagnosed with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed over the years is both attitude and product
selection. With the disease being diagnosed earlier and with more
effective treatment, more women are surviving and becoming more
vocal and assertive about their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Old horror stories abound. Years ago, post-surgery women stuffed
bras with panty hose, socks or rice. Many recall handing male
pharmacists a prosthesis prescription and their bra size and
receiving a box in exchange with the response: ``Here, this oughta
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say early prostheses resembled a pink rubber ball or a
large goose egg.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Tracy, owner of Alberta's A Natural Look in Centerville,
keeps one of the old styles on the shelf at her store, which also
caters to women who've had breast surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see how far we've come,'' she says, holding up the
hard, weighty form.
</P>
<P>
   Those unpleasant, and often traumatic, experiences are mostly
just memories. These days a woman can expect excellence in both
selection and service.
</P>
<P>
   There's a natural-looking _ and feeling _ prosthesis to fit
every type of surgery and every size and shape of woman. The forms,
which run from $250 to $400, come in various skin tones, are made
of a medical-grade silicone and feel amazingly natural.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to improving appearance, a prosthesis helps maintain
weight balance and keeps the shoulder and spine straight after
surgery. It also provides protective padding for the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Companies make soft, fiber-filled forms for the weeks
immediately following surgery, and enhancers for those who have had
lumpectomies. For those who object to added weight, there's a
lighter-weight prosthesis; for swimmers, there are forms to wear in
the water. Nipples can even be added for a natural look under
revealing fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   For active women who want to ensure their prosthesis stays in
place, the newest breast forms attach to the chest with Velcro.
Women change the skin support every couple of weeks and the
prosthesis can be worn with regular bras.
</P>
<P>
   Another innovation: a breast form with a liquid-silicone back
that hugs the chest and provides natural movement. In development
is a form that will adhere to the chest by itself.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies typically cover the cost of a new prosthesis
every two years as well as post-mastectomy bras (known medically as
surgical carriers) each year.
</P>
<P>
   The special bras, which contain a pocket for the breast form,
are cut more conservatively at the cleavage line and fuller at the
arm hole. They come in a variety of pretty styles, including
camisoles. Specially designed bathing suits have also become more
stylish, a sharp contrast to the days when they were known as
``surgical suits.'' Some suits incorporate their own lightweight
breast forms.
</P>
<P>
   Some shops, such as Silhouette's, also stock wigs, hats and
turbans for those who have undergone chemotherapy and hair loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hats are cut deeper in the back at the base of the neck,''
explains owner Brenda Mitchell. ``A baseball hat doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of a wig didn't throw Sandra Dulaney, 50, after
chemotherapy because she had worked as a professional hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hair is very fine and I used the opportunity to change to a
new look with more luxurious and longer hair,'' Dulaney says.
</P>
<P>
   Shopkeepers say most women prefer to select the wig that comes
closest to their own previous style and hair color.
</P>
<P>
   At Silhouette's, synthetic wigs, which remain styled and require
only occasional washing and shaking out, range from $80 to $160.
Human hair wigs, which require regular styling, are $300 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a woman's cosmetics may need to be reconsidered
during cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women develop skin sensitivity during chemotherapy and
radiation,'' explains Raye Payne, who coordinates the ``Look Good,
Feel Better'' program for the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to advice from cosmetologists, the monthly
get-togethers provide free-and-safe cosmetics from leading
manufacturers to any woman undergoing any type of cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the business agree there's no reason for a woman to be
without a prosthesis, mastectomy bra or wig. Retailers and the
American Cancer Society provide post-mastectomy products and
fittings for those without funds or insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The new range of products are significant because they can help
a woman feel normal again, and get back to the business of living.
</P>
<P>
   Concludes Pat Motter, with a smile: ``I'm not so different from
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Moss writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
