<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSUFB21-COX     10-20 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSUFB21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In major categories, OSU's sacks a sore spot
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Ranked first or second in a majority of Big Ten
statistical categories this season, Ohio State's 10th place ranking
in sacks sticks out like a sore thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Yet OSU coaches and players don't seem too concerned the
Buckeyes have managed just 11 sacks this season, ahead only of
Michigan State's five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are we rated in pass defense?'' OSU defensive
coordinator Fred Pagac (pronounced Pug-itch) asked when questioned
about OSU's low number of sacks. When someone replied OSU is No. 1
in the Big Ten, Pagac says, ``Oh, well, then I'm not worried about
(sacks).''
</P>
<P>
   OSU head coach John Cooper had a similar reaction. He quickly
pointed out all of the categories where they rank at or near the
top: ``Total offense, first is Ohio State. Rushing offense, Ohio
State. Passing efficiency, Ohio State. Pass offense, Ohio State.
Scoring offense, Ohio State. You all with me?'' he said to
reporters earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The low number of sacks, it seems, is somewhat of a sore spot
for the country's No. 1 college football team. They'd much rather
talk about their strengths, and there are many. Ohio State is
ranked first or second in 18 of the 27 statistical categories,
including total defense and scoring defense, compiled each week by
the Big Ten. Such dominance makes their low sack ranking all the
more surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hoped we would be certainly in the top half (of the Big
Ten),'' Cooper said, when asked what his expectations were.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper continues to point out, however, OSU does not have the
experienced defensive linemen they've had in recent years in
players like Mike Vrabel and Matt Finkes (1996). ``We're so dang
young up there,'' Cooper said, referring to a starting defensive
line made up of three sophomores (Rodney Bailey, Joe Brown, Brent
Johnson) and freshman Ryan Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   The coach also blames opposing quarterbacks' quick, three-step
drops and opponents' preparation for the blitz as other reasons
OSU's sack total is low.
</P>
<P>
   ``(They) go three steps and get rid of the football, you're not
going to get many sacks,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several Buckeyes expressed surprise and disappointment at
how well two young quarterbacks, Illinois freshman Kurt Kittner and
Minnesota sophomore Andy Persby, played against them the past two
weeks. Kittner was 19 for 43 for 156 yards with no interceptions
while Persby completed 19 of 42 passes for 213 yards, one touchdown
and one interception. Determined to rattle and pressure them into
numerous interceptions and mistakes, the Buckeyes had to settle for
mostly just containing them.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, OSU's Pagac said he thinks overall his defense has
been playing up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've been pressuring the quarterback pretty well,''
Pagac said. ``I haven't been studying the stats. But our results
right now are fairly pleasing. We're making them throw the ball
when we want them to throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
