<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMICON21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mood at Semicon trade show reflects industry depression
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The mood on the floor of the Semicon Southwest
trade show reflects the depressed state of the semiconductor
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The noise generated by sales people chatting up prospective
customers was noticeably lower this year. Some sales people talked
on phones as they waited for visitors or they wandered over to
other booths to compare notes with other reps.
</P>
<P>
   Even the free candy, 3D glasses and buttons didn't draw as many
people as last year when the trade show burst at the seams with
booths at the Austin Convention Center and Palmer Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of those interviewed by the American-Statesman on
Tuesday said they are cautiously optimistic that recent profit
surprises and other positive news reported by chip makers are
indications of better times ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The show continues today at the Convention Center with an
exposition from 10 a.m.-6 p.m. as well as workshops and seminars.
It is sponsored by the trade group Semiconductor Equipment and
Materials International.
</P>
<P>
   The products exhibited at the show, Austin's biggest convention,
range from complex machines that can cost $2 million to tiny parts
such as bolts and hose fittings that can cost a couple of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider, it looks a little like a mix between Radio Shack
and a plumber's tool box: water filtration tools, hoses, robotic
arms, bright jump suits and silicon wafers all co-exist to create
the fantastically complex range of products and materials that go
into creating semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   A worldwide slump in prices for computer chips has echoed up and
down the chain of suppliers and chip makers. Companies from
Motorola down to the tiniest equipment makers have cut jobs,
tightened costs and postponed projects.
</P>
<P>
   Those economic conditions were sharply evident on the convention
floor Tuesday. Many exhibitors complained they were getting fewer
leads on customers and receiving fewer visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like about half to me,'' said John Wilczek, an
account manager for Johnson Matthey Electronics, which makes
electronics and materials. The company, based in Minneapolis,
Minn., has 3,000 employees,
</P>
<P>
   Wilczek, who works in the company's Austin operations, said
Johnson Matthey attended the show to keep pushing products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to cut costs as much as we can,'' he said.
``But we've been through these slumps before. You can't stop
working and you can't stop selling.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many exhibitors, Johnson Matthey sent fewer people to
Semicon Southwest than last year. A dozen employees worked the
booth and trade show floor, down from 20 who attended last year.
Leah Castillo, a marketing manager for Electro-Graph of Carlsbad,
Calif., said her company is facing its lowest point in 20 years of
doing business. Last year, the company had 45 employees. After two
rounds of layoffs, Electro-Graph is down to 28 workers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Castillo said old customers are coming out of the
woodwork to place new orders and business is picking up, ``slowly
but surely.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some light at the end of the tunnel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fewer sales leads, many attendees agreed that the chip
industry is due for a rebound, possibly within the next six months.
The buzzword on the trade show floor was ``cautious optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   Some said they're waiting for the ``hockey stick effect,'' a
sharp upturn in sales characteristic of the volatile semiconductor
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Those who seemed least fazed by the slowdown or imminent
turnaround at Semicon were businesses that don't deal exclusively
with the semiconductor business.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Davies, a sales manager for Fremont Calif.'s Oxford
Instruments, does research and some low-level manufacturing for
communications and electronics companies. ``Ironically, this year's
been our best,'' Davies said. For others, however, the news isn't
quite so good.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hotovec, a sales representative for Sunx Sensors of West
Des Moines, Iowa, said his sales have sunk over the last six months
and after a banner 1997, he'll be lucky to match previous years
with the leads he collects at Semicon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been terrible,'' Hotovec said. ``I got free tickets to
this show and sent them to 50 of my biggest customers. I haven't
seen any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar L. Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
