<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICROSOFT STRONGLY DEFENDS GATES' BUSINESS TACTICS
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft forcefully defended its chairman, Bill Gates, in
federal court, asserting that the no-holds-barred tactics of his
company are not only common in the computer industry but also good
for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The opening statement was made in the antitrust lawsuit brought
by the Justice Department and 20 states contending that the
software company used its market power to bully and bend
competitors, business partners and corporate customers to its will.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. TRADE DEFICIT GREW IN AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   The nation's trade deficit widened by $2.2 billion in August, to
$16.77 billion. The deficit for the first eight months of the year
is running about 50 percent above last year's levels.
</P>
<P>
   KAUFMAN PLANS TO BUY LEWIS HOMES
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Kaufman &AMP; Broad Home rose 4.7 percent, or $1.0625, to
$23.625, after the home building company agreed to buy privately
owned Lewis Homes, a leading builder in California and Nevada.
Kaufman already is the largest home builder in California and the
West. Its $409 million acquisition of Lewis, plus the assumption of
$135 million in debt, may presage a consolidation in the home
building business.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE BANK SHOPPING FOR A DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank has been scouting out American concerns to buy
that will enhance its international investment banking business.
Among the companies that bankers and analysts say Deutsche Bank
might be interested in acquiring are Bankers Trust, J.P. Morgan and
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   DOW JONES AND S&AMP;P CLIMB AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose for the fifth consecutive
day. It climbed 39.40 points, to 8,505.85. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gained 1.54 points, to 1,063.93. But the Nasdaq
composite index declined 9.54 points, to 1,639.19.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM RESTATES FISCAL RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam, the troubled small appliance maker, said that it had
restated financial results from six quarters to adjust for inflated
profits and greater losses than previously reported.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS JUMP 10 PERCENT AT IBM
</P>
<P>
   IBM reported a 10 percent increase in third-quarter earnings
because of stronger computer sales, but the company's executives
cautioned that global economic uncertainty could lead to short-term
problems in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan and Wells Fargo reported better-than-expected
earnings in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING GROUP SELECTS A WOMAN
</P>
<P>
   Olivia F. Kirtley, who is 47 and the chief financial officer of
the power tool accessories company Vermont American, was named
chairwoman of the American Institute of Certified Public
Accountants. She is the first woman in the institute's 111-year
history to lead the nation's largest professional organization for
accountants.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGES ARE SPENDING ENDOWMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent stock market slump, wealthy colleges and
universities have seen their endowments soar during the 1990's. Now
these institutions are loosening their purse strings and spending
some of their newly acquired bounty.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE APPROVES SPENDING PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   The House overwhelmingly approved the $500-billion federal
spending package last night. The Senate is expected to pass it on
Wednesday. The package accounts for about one-third of the
$1.7-trillion budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
