<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7919 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINOCHET-THATCHER-BOS     10-20 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-THATCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THATCHER HAD PINOCHET AS A GUEST TWO WEEKS BEFORE HIS ARREST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Two weeks before Prime Minister Tony Blair's government
authorized the hospital-bed arrest of Augusto Pinochet, Margaret
Thatcher, a Blair predecessor, entertained the 82-year-old former
Chilean dictator over cocktails at her opulent house in Belgravia.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting treatment captured the opposite views of
Pinochet held by Blair and his Labor Party contemporaries, liberals
who came of age in the 1960s and 1970s, and by the Conservative
Party long led by Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   To conservatives, Pinochet was a staunch ally, one they could
count on in Latin America when Britain went to war with Argentina
over the Falkland Islands.
</P>
<P>
   To liberals, Pinochet was a brutal dictator who imprisoned,
tortured and murdered thousands of his left-wing political
opponents and whose use of Britain as a sanctuary, whether to shop
or to avail of the medical care he was under when arrested, is a
disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's legacy will get a long, vitriolic airing here.
Recovering from back surgery at the London Clinic, he is not
expected to be well enough to make an initial court appearance here
for another two weeks. His lawyers say he will vigorously oppose
efforts to extradite him to Spain, where a judge wants to question
him about the murders of 94 Spaniards, Chileans, Britons,
Argentines and Americans during his reign between 1973 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   And in a move that could keep Pinochet here even longer than the
protracted extradition proceedings, a group of Chilean exiles here
said Tuesday they would file a lawsuit charging him with murdering
and terrorizing political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Pinochet is in custody in London, we for the first
time have the opportunity to lay these charges before a British
court,'' the group, Chileans in Exile, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said it was possible that Britain would not
extradite Pinochet if he were facing a pending legal action here.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have accused the Blair government of playing
politics with the legal system. Chilean diplomats say Pinochet, who
is a senator for life in Chile, had been traveling on a diplomatic
passport and his arrest violated diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
   But British government officials insist they have handled the
extradition request by the book. They say diplomatic immunity
applies only to heads of state and diplomats assigned specifically
to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's Cabinet has plenty of old ``lefties.'' For instance, the
man who will ultimately decide whether Pinochet is extradited, Home
Secretary Jack Straw, made an extraordinary pledge that he would
not let his old left-wing politics influence his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, meanwhile, are lapping up the opportunity to
portray Blair and his ministers as chablis-and-brie liberals who
want to sacrifice Pinochet, and the notion of diplomatic immunity,
to score points with the left wing of the Labor Party that accuses
Blair of going soft on the party's core principles.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial Tuesday, The Daily Telegraph, the most
right-wing of Britain's national newspapers, accused Blair of
turning the legal process into a political one.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the same newspaper, columnist Anthony Daniels argued
that despite Pinochet's record on human rights, he was a staunch
ally and improved Chile's economy during his reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one doubts that Pinochet was a murderer,'' Daniels said.
``But no one doubts either that he is the savior of his country. It
is the uncomfortable juxtaposition of these two facts which makes
him so difficult a figure to judge.''
</P>
<P>
   The discomfort extends to Blair's top aides, including Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, who is unable to take credit for the tough
stance taken against Pinochet because doing so would make the
arrest appear political.
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher's office confirmed that she and her husband, Denis,
hosted Pinochet at the couple's home in the exclusive Belgravia
section of London, just four days before the former dictator had
surgery on Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Worthington, a spokesman for Thatcher, said she ``regarded
it as a private meeting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
