<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERVICE-COX     10-20 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERVICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kindness at heart of shops
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As important as the advancement in
post-mastectomy products and styles is a new emphasis on service.
</P>
<P>
   Today's sales clerks are sympathetic as well as knowledgable.
Chances are that they or someone in their immediate family have
been diagnosed with breast cancer as well.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Adkins, owner of Personal Touch Apparel in West
Carrollton, says her primary reason for opening a shop was to help
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was diagnosed with breast cancer when I was 36 and had a
modified radical mastectomy in 1988,'' she says. ``I've been there,
and I know what my customers are going through. You never forget
that feeling of being told you have breast cancer . . . and the
fear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very personal service,'' says Brenda Mitchell, who
opened Silhouettes For Women in 1992 with her sister, Debbie Adams.
``For a woman to have to come in and take her blouse and bra off
and be measured can be difficult for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who had a mastectomy in 1991, thought there was a need
for a ``feminine, comfortable place, warm and inviting with a
salon-type setting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to be more of a shopping experience than a
medical visit,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Their shop is made pretty with scented candles and attractive
displays.
</P>
<P>
   Along with knowing how to fit a prosthesis, a good sales clerk
provides sympathy, a shoulder to cry on, encouragement and hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hug and kiss everyone who walks in here,'' says Isabella
Hammonds, 78, who's been in the prosthesis and bra business for 30
years as owner of Isabella's Bra-Tique.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who's been on the receiving end of her hugs and
kisses is Sandra Dulaney.
</P>
<P>
   ``About six years ago I was incorrectly fit with a prosthesis
somewhere else, and I was miserable for two years because my
clothes didn't fit right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettilynn Pasley, originally trained to fit mastectomy customers
at McAlpin's, says it is possible to supplement a woman's bra
wardrobe with those from regular manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know the product to know what it does,'' explains
Pasley, who now works in the lingerie department at the Dayton Mall
Elder-Beerman. ``Then when you see the woman, you know what to get
for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the range of products, shopkeepers still encounter women
who have had surgery but don't own a prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one lady who had surgery 14 years ago and had never been
fitted,'' says Shirley Adkins. ``She walked out looking natural
with a smile on her face and no one would ever have known she'd had
a breast removed,'' says Adkins. ``That's my main objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Moss writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
