<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT EARNINGS SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Tough cost controls and strong demand for its new
Windows 98 software boosted Microsoft Corp.'s net income by 58
percent, well ahead of analysts' expectations, and more good news
lies in store, the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it earned 56 cents a share in the quarter that
ended Sept. 30, compared to 36 cents in the same quarter a year
ago. Net income was $1.52 billion in the quarter, compared to $959
million in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   The net-income figures exclude two large one-time items: a $160
million gain from the sale of Softimage, and a $296 million
write-off from last year's purchase of WebTV Networks. With those
items included, net income was $1.68 billion this year compared to
$663 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues in the quarter totaled $3.95 billion, up 26 percent
from $3.13 billion in the same quarter a year ago, the first of
Microsoft's fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's strong results together with those of other
high-tech companies ``do not suggest an economic meltdown''
stemming from economic problems in Asia, Chief Financial Officer
Greg Maffei said. ``The PC business is prospering.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM, for example, reported a 10 percent increase in
first-quarter profits Monday, beating analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also appears poised for strong performance in the next
few quarters, he said, suggesting that analysts should raise their
current expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the consensus estimates from Wall Street are at
least a nickel per share light,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft shares fell 2 11/16, to 100 1/4, in regular U.S.
trading before the earnings were released. Later, in after-market
trading, the shares gained 3 1/2 to 103 3/4, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, Microsoft said, it has sold more than 10 million
copies of Windows 98, the latest version of its market-leading
operating system for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   It also reported record sales of its Windows NT Workstation
software, a kind of heavy-duty version of the operating system that
has mainly been used by businesses but increasingly is being aimed
at consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Office 97, the group of programs that includes word processing,
spreadsheet, presentation and other software tools, posted strong
results, though they have cooled somewhat from previous quarters,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   It shipped an early version of the next-generation software,
called Office 2000, to about 20,000 testers during the quarter, and
a second test version of its much-anticipated Windows NT 5.0 to
more than 250,000 testers.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei avoided predicting when the final version of NT 5.0 will
be ready, but said a third test or ``beta'' version is expected to
be distributed in the first three months of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
