<HEADER>
A7933 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COULTER-SFCHRON &LR;      10-20 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COULTER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BofA Chief Is Asked To Leave   By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Faced with an ultimatum by his board of directors, David Coulter
announced yesterday that he is resigning as president and chief
operating officer of financially beleaguered BankAmerica Corp.
<P>
   When BankAmerica agreed to sell out to NationsBank in April, it
was widely assumed that Coulter, 51, eventually would succeed Hugh
McColl as chief executive officer of the combined bank.
</P>
<P>
   But those prospects went out the window last week when the bank
revealed a shocking 50 percent plunge in earnings, largely because
of Bank of America losses from foreign loans and from a speculative
investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter, who served as chief executive of the company's San
Francisco-based predecessor before it was acquired by NationsBank
last month, said in a press release that he is leaving ``with
regret,'' but he declined to offer any explanation.
</P>
<P>
   However, a source close to the Bank of America said that board
member William Johnson, head of the bank's executive committee,
visited Coulter in San Francisco last week and urged him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted it sooner rather than later,'' said the source,
who asked to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did not return calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter is not coming away empty-handed. He will receive one of
the most generous ``golden parachute'' packages in American
business history _ severance pay, pension, stock and benefits worth
as much as $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   His departure effectively dismantles the old Bank of America _
for many decades San Francisco's largest and proudest financial
institution. Although the merged bank opted for the BankAmerica
name, its headquarters now repose in Charlotte, N.C. _ as do
virtually all of its key executives.
</P>
<P>
   McColl, chairman and CEO of BankAmerica, said in the press
release that it was ``painful'' to accept Coulter's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   But the source close to Bank of America management said Coulter
tried in vain to talk with McColl after being told to quit.
``McColl doesn't seem to feel that he needs to return David's phone
calls,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Both McColl and Coulter declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   No successor to Coulter has been named.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Joseph K. Morford, with Van Kasper &AMP; Co. in San
Francisco, said yesterday that the logical successor would be
Kenneth D. Lewis, who served as president of NationsBank before the
acquisition of BankAmerica, and currently serves as head of retail
banking at the merged operation.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Coulter's resignation _ which takes effect
October 30 _ came six days after BankAmerica reported the plunge in
earnings for the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tumble in earnings, Coulter's resignation was
greeted with ``shock and surprise'' by employees at the BankAmerica
Tower on California Street, one employee reported.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings plunge was caused by huge losses from trading
securities and currencies and was blamed primarily on the old BofA
side of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the trading loss stemmed from a $372 million write-off
of the bank's interest in a stock-and-options portfolio managed by
D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., a New York investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts speculated that Coulter may not be the only highly
placed BofA executive asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Also vulnerable, they said, are Michael Murray, head of
corporate banking, who oversaw the operation in which the losses
occurred, and Michael O'Neill, chief financial officer, who had
major responsibility for the bank's risk management.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Wilson, managing director for financial services and
recruiting with Korn Ferry International in San Francisco, says
many in the financial community had been expecting Coulter's ouster
since the Shaw losses surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not surprising at all,'' Wilson remarked. ``What was
surprising was that the bank reported worse earnings than expected.
The Wall Street analysts were caught off guard. People in business
hate surprises.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
