</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE EGOS ARE MISSING, SAYS AYUSO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A glance at the USC basketball roster confirms
that the Trojans will be deeper and more talented than a year ago.
But a more important change could be the team's attitude. Just two
days into practice, senior guard Elias Ayuso already notices a
completely different atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more togetherness. Everyone is willing to accept each
other and accept their roles,'' Ayuso said. ``It's not a lot of
egos like last year. We had too many egos.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby brought in five highly regarded players
expected to make an immediate impact for the Trojans, who were a
disappointing 9-19 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great talent this year. All the new guys fill in the
holes we had last year,'' Ayuso said. ``They all came in with a
winning attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayuso should know. He played on a summer-league team with four
of the five newcomers: 6-foot-9 forward Brian Scalabrine; 6-7
forward Sam Clancy; 6-7 forward David Bluthenthal and 5-10 point
guard Brandon Granville. The other new player is 6-3 guard Quincy
Wilder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five new players have shown they have skill. They can
compete. They are thinking like winners,'' Bibby said. ``To try and
change the whole thinking of the men's basketball program, we tried
to bring in winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine and Clancy are expected to compete for starting
positions, and all five players are expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   USC opens the season Nov. 17 at the Sports Arena against San
Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruiting update: USC expects to sign 6-4 guard Nate Hair of
Capistrano Valley next month. The Trojans have one other
scholarship and are pursuing 6-9 forward Tajudeen Soyoye from
Meridian Junior College in Mississippi. Florida State, Missouri and
Tulane are also recruiting Soyoye. He is originally from Lagos,
Nigeria. He is not expected to sign until the spring.
</P>
<P>
   __ Women's basketball: USC women's coach Chris Gobrecht is also
more optimistic, thanks to an infusion of healthy bodies. After
usually going with no more than six healthy players last season,
Gobrecht will have 12-13 players this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to be good,'' Gobrecht said. ``My biggest
excitement is with the return of Erica Mashia. Every time she goes
up and down the floor, I can't believe this is what we didn't have
last year. She's big-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashia, a 5-7 guard, has not played the past two seasons because
of a hip injury, and doctors had told her she would never play
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Women of Troy open the season Nov. 19 at the Sports Arena
against Boise State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
