<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SEARCH FOR DRIVER SWEPT OFF HIGHWAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAUL McKAY 
and SALATHEIA BRYANT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Authorities stepped up their search Tuesday for a man
who, along with a 38-year-old woman, was swept off a Montgomery
County road north of Houston as they tried to drive through rushing
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   As the search for the unidentified man continued along Spring
Creek and funeral arrangements were being made for the woman,
residents in Montgomery and Harris counties began cleaning up as
floodwaters from a weekend deluge slowly started receding in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
   To the west, however, folks along three rivers prepared for
floodwaters that continued rolling downstream and threatened to
swamp roads and invade homes in Fort Bend, Wharton and Brazoria
counties.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery County search got under way Tuesday afternoon
with sheriff's deputies aided by boats and a helicopter. The man
they were seeking reportedly had been with Beverly Kay Caldwell
when the pickup truck he was driving was washed off the bridge on
Cypress-Rosehill Road about 2:30 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell's body was recovered at 6 a.m. Monday from the cab of
the truck, which had come to rest against a tree.
</P>
<P>
   A witness who had pulled his vehicle to the side of the road
just short of the bridge told investigators that he last saw the
man standing on top of the truck as it moved downstream.
</P>
<P>
   The witness said the pickup passed him at a rather high speed
before plowing through the water ahead, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Deputy Bob Schuster, a marine division officer who
recovered Caldwell's body, estimated that the current was moving at
40 mph when the truck was swamped. That would not bode well for the
chances of Caldwell's companion surviving, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a current that strong in the black of night, he could
have been swept down the creek for miles,'' Schuster said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Red Cross workers closed a shelter at New Caney
Middle School in east Montgomery County after the last evacuees had
left. The flood-prone Peach and Caney creeks, the San Jacinto River
and the East Fork of the river had displaced many residents Sunday
and Monday, but the water was slowly retreating Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Classes are expected to resume Wednesday in the New Caney and
Splendora school districts, which had canceled school on Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for the Houston area Wednesday calls for a 20
percent chance of showers.
</P>
<P>
   In Harris County, creeks were beginning to recede although some
areas may see high water for a couple of more days, said Steve
Fitzgerald, chief engineer for the county flood control district.
</P>
<P>
   Several roads in far northwest Harris County _ including
Katy-Hockley Road and Mueschke Road _ will remain underwater for a
few days as the water continues to drain into the upper reaches of
Cypress Creek, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gutierrez, operations coordinator for Harris County
Emergency Management, said the San Jacinto River is expected to
crest at the U.S. 59 bridge Wednesday at 55.5 feet. It was at 55
feet Tuesday afternoon _ 5 feet above flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the danger is out of the way now,'' Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Two areas that could see higher water in the next few days,
however, are Rio Villa Park and Banana Bend, both on the San
Jacinto River south of Lake Houston. Many homes there are built on
stilts, but Gutierrez said about 100 residents were removed by boat
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jacinto also remained a stubborn intruder in northeast
Harris County's Forest Cove area, where many residents moved
possessions to higher ground Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A small group at a townhouse development on Hamblen Road stayed
home from work and stood guard near their community's private
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   As if there weren't enough problems, they were annoyed that
sightseers were driving through the water, creating waves that
pushed into homes.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the ants and the snakes _ and outsiders who
aroused suspicion among residents who had lost property to looters
in the October 1994 flood.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Fire Department had evacuated five people in the
area as of Tuesday, but Chief Steven Sparks said many residents
were not alarmed and didn't want to leave.
</P>
<P>
   To the east, in Liberty County, residents kept a close watch on
the Trinity River, which is expected to crest in the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Livingston dam floodgates were releasing 26,200 cubic
feet per second on Tuesday, which is 6,200 cfs above flood stage,
said Trinity River Authority spokesman Spencer Karr.
</P>
<P>
   ``But our lake seems to have stabilized and I don't think it
will rise much more than that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Liberty, the river was at 21.5 feet and rising, but still
under flood stage of 24 feet, officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   With the runoff from the heavy rains, the National Weather
Service projected that the river could crest at 25 or 26 feet,
which would not flood any homes but would submerge entry roads into
17 riverside subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   To the west and southwest of Houston, residents of low-lying
areas along the Brazos and San Bernard rivers in Fort Bend and
Brazoria counties were preparing to leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuations were recommended in the Valley Lodge community in
Simonton and also in the 30-home Tierra Grande subdivision outside
Needville, near the San Bernard River.
</P>
<P>
   On the west side of the San Bernard, in Wharton County,
officials had evacuated about 75 people Tuesday and planned more
Wednesday in anticipation of a flood that could exceed the record
flood of December 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they expect the Colorado River to crest at 50 to
52 feet Thursday, which might bring water up to the doors of the
county's new jail and its old courthouse building in nearby
downtown Wharton.
</P>
<P>
   Flood stage in Wharton is 39 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have people who have been warned and who are
waiting to leave,'' said Chief Deputy Bill Copeland. ``We have been
evacuating people since Sunday and a majority of the people are
using their heads and getting out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the old-timers will say they're not worried, but
it's coming this time, and it's likely to be 4 foot higher than the
record flood we had in 1991.''
</P>
<P>
   Many evacuees had left the Elm Grove area Saturday night.
Residents of Wharton's west end saw water spill out of Baumann's
Slough and lap across low-lying portions of their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
