<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-EMBEZZLER-COX     10-20 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-EMBEZZLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Customers surprised nice teller stole from them
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Phyllis Richardson has been described as a
solicitous thief, the bank teller who fostered a ``lovefest'' with
her elderly customers while she methodically siphoned money from
their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the image depicted by federal prosecutors on
Tuesday, when Richardson's trial began on 41 charges of
embezzlement, money laundering and mail fraud. They say Richardson,
37, stole between $1.2 million and $1.5 million over seven years
from 16 of her customers at the Community Savings Bank on Singer
Island, including a 92-year-old woman who once lived with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was cheerful, always very good with people,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney Neil Karadbil told jurors. ``Most of the customers
enjoyed the attention. Even today, some of the customers find it
hard to believe she would take money out of their accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson's lawyers are challenging her portrayal as a
cunning swindler _ and in so doing, they're putting her intellect
on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Arthur Addess said Richardson simply isn't bright
enough to pull off such a scheme. Could a lifelong C student with
an IQ of 81 successfully deceive bank officers and customers for
years by shuffling money from account to account? Could Richardson,
a woman who has trouble paying her utility bills, continue to
befuddle authorities who are still unsure where all the money went?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to ask yourself when we show you this
whether Phyllis Richardson had the intellect and the capacity to
pull off this $1.5 million scheme,'' Addess told jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Karadbil said the scheme was clever in some ways, simple in
others. Richardson, he said, set up certificates of deposit worth
less money than her customers intended and hid the difference. She
also drained their accounts in small withdrawals and disguised the
transactions with forged paperwork, Karadbil said.
</P>
<P>
   The transactions typically involved accounts for which the bank
did not produce monthly statements, but they were done under
Richardson's employee code, Karadbil said. The money was ``washed''
through separate accounts set up under the names of Richardson's
friends or sisters, then converted to cash, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme unraveled after one woman abruptly closed her account
and noticed the differences, he said. Richardson, of West Palm
Beach, was indicted in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is expected to get technical, and prosecutors have
outfitted the courtroom with computer monitors and a projector to
guide the jury through a litany of bank records. The trial is
expected to last about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Addess said the ``truck load'' of documents is nothing more
than trial by saturation, an attempt to overwhelm the jurors with
information.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Richardson could have concealed her employee code
if she were the thief, and noted that she's not living like a
millionaire _ she's filed for bankruptcy, her car has been
repossessed, her home is in foreclosure and she once had to borrow
$300 from one of her alleged victims to pay her electric bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let the amounts of money overwhelm you. Don't let the
frailty of the elderly people gain your sympathy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hiaasen writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
