<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-CAMPAIGNS-COX     10-20 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-CAMPAIGNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In eleventh hour of campaigning, voters watch ad war unfold
 &HT;    By Debra Jasper
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ With two weeks left to Election Day, the two
major party candidates for governor have brushed aside any talk of
an ad truce, and are instead bringing out the heavy artillery.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Democrat Lee Fisher's campaign unveiled a television
ad that thrashes Republican Bob Taft for his commercial on Fisher's
crime-fighting record _ a commercial that brought Taft's campaign a
rebuke from the Ohio Elections Commission for containing false and
misleading information.
</P>
<P>
   The Taft campaign fired back, accusing Fisher's camp of
similarly misleading the public with an ad on tax cutting proposals
, although Taft's accusation won't be heard by the Elections
Commission until today.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fisher ad says that for the first time in Ohio history,
the bi-partisan Elections Commission has found a candidate for
governor ``guilty of lying . . . Robert Taft's campaign knowingly
aired lies and broke Ohio election law,'' an announcer says. ``The
same laws Taft, as Ohio's chief election officer, is sworn to
enforce.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad shows a gavel slamming down and displays recent headlines
from across the state: ``Taft ads violated state law, panel says;
Board rules ads for Taft are false; Taft commercial ruled
untruthful; Taft camp scolded for TV ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's campaign manager, Alan Melamed, also handed out a
document that showed Taft's ad ran several times statewide over the
weekend, despite the Taft campaign's assertion Friday that it would
be immediately taken off the air and replaced by a positive ad.
</P>
<P>
   Taft has a ``reckless disregard for the truth,'' Melamed said.
``Bob Taft is bringing shame to the Taft name.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Buerck, Taft's spokesman, was quick to hit back, saying,
``Name calling and petty, cheap shots are exactly the type of
negative, nasty comments that voters are tired of.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it's not the campaign's fault the ads weren't pulled,
that most station managers go home on Friday afternoon and didn't
see the request to pull the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the TV news stations, this is not life and death,'' Buerck
said. ``There is no sense of urgency for these news stations to
change the ad. They get their money anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Buerck, meanwhile, accused the Fisher campaign of lying in a
current ad that says Fisher is the only candidate with a plan to
cut property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher has proposed giving Ohio homeowners another 15 percent
reduction on their property taxes by expanding the portion the
state pays from 12.5 percent to 27.5 percent. In the first two
years, the plan would cost Ohio $1.1 billion. Taft criticized that
plan as irresponsible and a day later proposed a modest plan of his
own that would cut property taxes for about 25,000 middle-income
retirees and disabled homeowners by an extra $53 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hypocritical of these guys to criticize our guys on
one hand and do the same thing on the other hand,'' Buerck said.
</P>
<P>
   The Elections Commission today is expected to rule on whether
there is probable cause the Fisher ad is misleading.
</P>
<P>
   It also will rule on whether there is probable cause that
another Taft ad misleads voters by using a partial quote from a
Cleveland Plain Dealer story to support a contention that Taft did
not raise taxes when he was a Hamilton County Commissioner. Taft
voted to put 14 tax increases on the ballot during that time, and
says he probably voted for them privately in the voting booth, but
says that's not the same as voting as an elected official to raise
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Melamed claimed Taft is following the same strategy he followed
during a 1990 campaign for the Republican nomination for governor
against George Voinovich. Taft started out running negative ads and
criticizing Voinovich for supporting tax increases _ including
taxes Voinovich didn't vote to enact himself, Melamed said. Taft
then proposed a ban on negative campaigning, a ban similar to the
one he proposed to Fisher on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, Taft acknowledged such a ban is not
going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on Lee Fisher's actions over the last four days, a
campaign free of negative, nasty ads is likely out of the realm of
possibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Jasper writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
