<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXFLOODS-VICTORIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
850 HOMES EVACUATED AS TEXAS FLOODWATERS SURGE THROUGH SOUTHWEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICTORIA, Texas _ Hundreds of people were evacuated from their
homes Tuesday, including many who had refused to leave and then
fled as floodwaters surged through their neighborhoods when the
Guadalupe River spilled over its banks.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria County Judge Helen Walker said more than 850 homes were
evacuated and estimates the damage will be in the hundreds of
millions of dollars. Though evacuations began as early as Sunday,
she said no one anticipated the extent of flooding witnessed
Tuesday, where portions of the river were more than four miles wide
north of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting water where we've never had it before,'' she
said. ``We're already three feet above the flood record in 1936 so
we have a whole new flood line.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Texas Sen. Ken Armbrister, D-Victoria, who was at the
evacuation site Tuesday: ``I've lived here 30 years and was the
police captain here before I was a state legislator. This is the
largest volume of water I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The river was expected to crest by this morning after rising to
34.26 feet Tuesday afternoon. Walker said the water level recorded
by city survey crews fluctuated most of the day over the record
31.3 foot level.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns centered on whether the river would crest a second time
when more water was expected to come from further upstream where
more than 20 inches of rain swelled rivers and creeks in and around
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   By late Tuesday, the waterline stood within two blocks of
downtown Victoria, about 125 miles southwest of Houston. Downtown
Victoria remained without power on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   National Guard units were arriving to assist Victoria police in
maintaining a 7 p.m. curfew to prevent looting. Other concerns
include health problems, primarily from the city water treatment
plant, which was partially submerged and had to be shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the county will seek federal disaster assistance
once flood waters recede and damage can be assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Tuesday was spent evacuating residents who earlier had
refused help, intent on waiting out the flood. U.S. Coast Guard and
Texas National Guard helicopters rescued people trapped on their
roofs or in treetops, including one woman and a child whose roof
was swept from underneath them. They were found unharmed downstream
clinging to tree branches.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said as many as 50 residents remained in the flooded
areas, refusing to be evacuated, including some who waved off
helicopters from second story windows with the floor below filled
with water. She said one man, apparently undeterred by the rising
water, was found barbecuing on his roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really had pleaded with people to take this seriously; that
this is a life and death situation,'' she said. ``If another two
feet comes up I don't know if they're going to be all right or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Before going to work Tuesday morning, Nick Ruiz Jr., 33, said he
drove a mile west from his home toward the river to inspect the
flooding. An hour and a half later, he returned home after his wife
called to tell him the water was entering their back yard.
j~%BRRW,d
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRA-Q-AND-A-COX     10-20 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Questions and answers on the waste proposal
</P>
<P>
   By Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is a disposal site under consideration for Texas?
</P>
<P>
   A .1980 federal law urges states to take responsibility for
waste generated within their borders. The Texas Legislature decided
in 1981 that the state would build a disposal site. In 1993,
lawmakers revised the plan to include waste from Maine and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the advantages of the Sierra Blanca location?
</P>
<P>
   A. It is remote, sparsely populated and dry. The site receives
about 12 inches of rain a year, and groundwater lies 700 feet deep
_ conditions that presumably would help guard against water
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is the site controversial?
</P>
<P>
   A. It is 18 miles from the Rio Grande, a major water source and
the U.S.-Mexico border. Residents of the area are primarily
low-income and Hispanic. There is a geologic fault beneath the
site, and the most powerful earthquake ever recorded in Texas
occurred about 60 miles southeast in Valentine in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who would run the site?
</P>
<P>
   A. state agency, the Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste Disposal
Authority. A separate eight-member interstate compact commission
with representatives from Texas, Maine and Vermont would oversee
the operation. The governor of Texas would appoint six of the eight
members, and one of those six would have to be from Hudspeth
County. Maine and Vermont would each name one member.
</P>
<P>
   Q. President Clinton recently signed legislation concerning the
plan. Doesn't that end the debate?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. Clinton approved a measure creating the interstate
compact. The state disposal authority still needs a license from
the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission. The commission
is to consider the license request Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is an interstate compact, and why are two New England
states in a compact with Texas?
</P>
<P>
   A. An interstate compact is a congressionally approved agreement
between or among states. Low-level waste compacts legally may
exclude waste from nonmember states. Texas originally planned to
develop a site without a compact, then decided to enter into a
partnership with Maine and Vermont when those states agreed to pay
a total of $55 million -- $50 million to Texas for site development
and $5 million to the host county for community assistance
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How is the conservation commission expected to rule?
</P>
<P>
   A. Unclear. The three-member commission could grant a license,
deny the request, take the matter under advisement or send the case
back to administrative law judges to gather more evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What did the administrative law judges recommend?
</P>
<P>
   A. Denial of the license. Two judges with the state Office of
Administrative Hearings said the waste authority had failed to
adequately examine the geologic fault beneath the site and the
potential socioeconomic effects of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can the conservation commission's decision be appealed?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. A party in the case would first have to seek a rehearing
by the conservation commission. An appeal subsequently could be
filed in state district court in Travis County.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Could the site become a national dumping ground for low-level
waste?
</P>
<P>
   A. Perhaps. State and federal laws allow _ but do not require _
the compact commission to accept waste from other states. But the
decision would be up to Texas because it controls six of eight
seats on the compact commission. In addition, the terms of a
license issued by the conservation commission could require a
license amendment and the state Legislature's approval before waste
from other states is accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the site needed?
</P>
<P>
   A. Three privately owned sites _ at Barnwell, S.C.; Clive, Utah;
and Richland, Wash. _ currently accept commercially generated
low-level waste, with the Barnwell site taking waste from Texas and
most other states. Capacity and access are adequate for now, but
long-term prospects are uncertain. Several new sites are in
planning stages around the nation, but not all will be needed to
handle the volume generated.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the sources of the waste that would be shipped to
the Texas site?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nuclear power plants, medical facilities, industrial concerns
and universities. Nuclear plants generate about 70 percent of the
volume and radioactivity.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How would waste be transported?
</P>
<P>
   A. By truck. Waste would be packaged in steel drums, steel boxes
and ``high-integrity containers.'' The latter are steel cylinders
with fiberglass on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How much would the site cost, and who would pay for it?
</P>
<P>
   A. The project has cost $53 million so far for engineering,
geological studies, legal fees and other expenses. The disposal
authority bills waste generators in Texas for the tab. The
authority predicts total costs of $91 million, including $36
million for construction. Maine and Vermont are to pay $25 million
each. Q. Who supports the proposed disposal site?
</P>
<P>
   A. STP Nuclear Operating Co., Houston Lighting &AMP; Power Co.,
Texas Utilities Electric Co., Advocates for Responsible Disposal in
Texas, South Texas Chapter of the Health Physics Society, Texas
Radiation Advisory Board, executive director of the Texas Natural
Resource Conservation Commission, and Mexico's ministries of
environment, foreign relations and energy.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who is opposed?
</P>
<P>
   A. Sierra Blanca Legal Defense Fund, Greenpeace Mexico, Texas &AMP;
Pacific Land Trust, Border Environmental Network, Sierra Club's El
Paso Group, International Environmental Alliance of the Bravo,
League of United Latin American Citizens, City of Austin, City of
El Paso, El Paso County, Presidio County, Culberson County, Ciudad
Juarez, Mexico's Congress, public interest counsel of the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are other states doing?
</P>
<P>
   A. California has licensed a proposed disposal site at Ward
Valley in San Bernardino County, but it is stalled because the
federal government has refused to transfer land to the state. State
regulators have recommended denial of a license for a site in
Nebraska. North Carolina has selected a site, but licensing is
stalled by financial issues. Pennsylvania and New Jersey have
suspended their search for a site. Connecticut and Illinois have
not selected a site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
