<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUERO-COX     10-20 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUERO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cuero hammered by flood
 &HT;    By Dylan Rivera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Four cows huddled on the roof of a house on
Heaton Street, buried Tuesday under 14 feet of water. Adventurous
boaters and rescue workers chugged along the southwest half of this
town, which has been choked by the unrelenting waters of the
Guadalupe River for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing waters forced 4,000 of Cuero's 7,000 residents to seek
shelter at the town's two schools, in their cars or in hotels as
far away as Hallettsville, about 60 miles away, DeWitt County
Sheriff Cliff Foulds said. ``Very few homes don't have house guests
right now, the hotels are filled and people are camping out,''
Foulds said.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary report to disaster officials in Austin Monday,
DeWitt County officials estimated that 300 homes had been
destroyed, up to 1,000 more had sustained major flood damage and
500 others had sustained minor damage.
</P>
<P>
   A mile northeast of Cuero at the Stevenson prison, where 1,300
convicts and about 150 guards had been stranded overnight by
floodwaters , officials decided to stay put after evacuation
efforts were stymied.
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon, prison officials said, a National Guard helicopter
had delivered a pump that was being used to drain the prison's
flooded sewage-treatment plant. As the floodwaters began to drop,
convict work crews were busy with squeegees and mops cleaning out
the mud and water.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Cuero, worried residents wandered up and down
Esplanade, the boulevard that divides the town into east and west,
hoping to hitch a boat ride to inspect their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Gottschalt, a construction contractor, discovered that
the flooding spared his house, on a ridge near the river. But he
knows many people, including his elderly mother, who lost their
homes and will need government disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can borrow money if I have to, but a lot of these people
here, they can't borrow nothing because they don't have nothing,''
Gottschalt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some families in the more affluent Northwood Estates subdivision
on the city's north side saw houses flooded up to 3 feet deep but
could drive up to their homes by Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteeen-year-old Emily Morrow rummaged through a jumble of
sheet music, grade-school homework assignments and toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to take my diaries, but I didn't get all of them,''
she said before turning back to the mess in her closet.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration turned to anger for some weary, wet residents. Many
who live on the south and west sides of town said they have been
frustrated for years by poor drainage and inadequate road
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Watching men from other parts of town cruise through their
neighborhoods in fishing boats only made some more frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to let me have that boat,'' Herbie Bryant said. ``I
know the way, but I don't got no boat because I'm a poor man.''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Rivera writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. American-Statesman staff writer Mike Ward contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
