<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-STATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History of leaks a subject of debate
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The low-level radioactive waste disposal site in
Maxey Flats, Ky., was declared a federal Superfund site because of
leaking waste.
</P>
<P>
   At a similar site in Illinois, radioactive tritium flowed into
groundwater. The same thing happened in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the proposed radioactive waste disposal site in
West Texas say leaks at the nation's six current and former
radioactive waste sites should serve as a warning against building
one in this state.
</P>
<P>
   But agencies that monitor those facilities say the leaks have
been controlled or reduced and have posed no threat to human
health.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission, Jim Kennedy, senior
project manager for low-level waste disposal, said that in decades
past, waste sites were poorly located and regulated. Some were
built in areas with heavy rainfall, and rainwater saturated the
trenches where 55-gallon drums contained liquid waste were buried.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened in Maxey Flats, which closed in 1977, and a
facility in West Valley, N.Y., that closed in 1975. At a defunct
disposal site in the Nevada desert, leaking drums are the most
likely culprit for tritium detected in the surrounding soil,
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Tritium, a radioactive form of hydrogen that mingles easily with
water, also has migrated out of trenches at the nation's two active
waste facilities, in Barnwell, S.C., and Richland, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Kennedy said, the contamination is below the
government's allowable limit for human exposure. The leaks prompted
new federal regulations for low-level sites in 1983 that forbid
burial of liquids, require improved storage containers and impose a
long list of restrictions on where disposal sites can be located.
</P>
<P>
   Those new regulations helped shape the proposed Texas site,
which would be located near Sierra Blanca in arid Hudspeth County
and would use reinforced concrete canisters to contain solid waste.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents, who contend that politics, not science, decided
where to place the proposed Texas site, say the state is risking a
repeat of history.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
