<HEADER>
A7976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRA-TRANS-COX     10-20 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-TRANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plan for radioactive cargo: Inspect every truck
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Low-level radioactive waste is routinely
transported without incident across Texas and the rest of the
nation. Special precautions nonetheless would be required for
shipments to a disposal site proposed for Hudspeth County.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires the Texas Department of Health to inspect all
waste before it is transported to the site. Shipments from Maine
and Vermont would be examined just inside the Texas line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legislators wanted to make sure, no matter how safe
transportation has been, that each shipment is inspected before
it's put on Texas highways,'' said Richard Ratliff, chief of the
Health Department's Bureau of Radiation Control.
</P>
<P>
   Spot inspections are now performed for shipments bound for a
disposal site in Barnwell, S.C. The requirement to inspect each
load for the Texas site would begin once the site went into
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which borders Interstate 10, would average two truck
shipments a week, said Rick Jacobi, general manager of the Texas
Low-Level Radioactive Waste Disposal Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Although comprehensive records were not kept before the early
1970s, state and federal regulators say no one has been injured or
killed by radiation as a result of transportation accidents
involving low-level waste during the past quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just not a big deal,'' said Joe Gilliland, a spokesman
for the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the good safety record is that low-level waste
must be packaged in steel boxes and other protective containers.
Radiation levels 6 1/2 feet from the vehicle must not exceed 10
millirems per hour, and the vehicle's driver must not be exposed to
more than 2 millirems per hour, or 16 millirems for an eight-hour
workday. By comparison, most people receive about 360 millirems a
year, primarily from cosmic rays and other natural sources. A
millirem is a unit for measuring the biological effect of
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   A worst-case accident _ such as a collision causing a fire that
released radioactive materials into the atmosphere _ would cause
exposures of 2 millirems to people who evacuate promptly and as
much as 200 millirems per minute to people who do not leave the
area, according to an analysis commissioned by the waste authority.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have not detected any health problems from exposures
at these levels. However, prevailing scientific opinion holds that
any exposure to radiation, no matter how small, poses some
increased risk of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups and other critics said the authority's
analysis understated the risk because it underestimated population
densities and omitted some waste from the calculations.
</P>
<P>
   But two state administrative law judges concluded that ``truly
extreme'' accident scenarios ``would not pose an exceptional risk
to the public even if they were to occur.'' They said the
transportation record is ``excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph K.M. Haurwitz writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
