<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAND-COMMISH-COX     10-20 1745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAND-COMMISH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Land commissioner race generates heat
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Forget the promises to keep beaches clean and
earn more oil and gas royalties from Texas' public lands to improve
schools. More than anything, it seems, the race to succeed Garry
Mauro as Texas land commissioner is a race about houses.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, houses.
</P>
<P>
   David Dewhurst, the Republican, has accused state Rep. Richard
Raymond, the Democrat, of living in the wrong one _ a house near
Bastrop, far from the legislative district Raymond is supposed to
represent. And Raymond has criticized Dewhurst for not paying
enough taxes on a house he owns _ a stately mansion, actually _ in
Houston's posh River Oaks neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   At times in recent weeks, it has seemed that, as much as
anything, Dewhurst and Raymond are battling against obscurity in a
race for an obscure job. For without the bickering reminiscent of
the old-time name-calling contests that years ago were an election
year staple in Texas, both campaigns concede that voters would
probably have paid far less attention to who will be the state's
27th land commissioner, a job created 161 years ago, when Texas was
still a republic.
</P>
<P>
   A Libertarian candidate, J. Manuel Montez, is also on the
ballot. Montez, 47, a Dallas teacher, did not return phone calls
for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the rhetoric, the campaign styles and backgrounds of
Raymond and Dewhurst provide the biggest contrast in the race _ and
an insight, perhaps, into how each would fill the $92,200-a-year
job they both want.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, 37, is a product of small-town South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Benavides, population 1,500, in the
politically notorious Duval County, Raymond was the son of a
longtime county employee and a schoolteacher. As a young man, he
recalls watching the corrupt political machine at work and vowing
to change things if he ever got a chance.
</P>
<P>
   At age 19, he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a poll watcher. People stuffed the ballot box, Box 3. We
challenged the election and won,'' Raymond explained. ``I was told
at one point, though, that if we didn't drop the challenge that
they would fire my mother. We didn't, and they did. It took her two
years to get her job back.''
</P>
<P>
   He said another challenge to the political machine also cost his
father his job. ``But I was always proud that my father was honest,
that he never stole anything,'' Raymond said.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond said his interest in politics blossomed while he
attended the University of Texas, where he earned a degree in
government. In 1984, he campaigned across Texas in Bob Krueger's
unsuccessful bid for U.S. Senate and then went to work for U.S.
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, as a special assistant.
</P>
<P>
   He later worked for U.S. Paul Simon, D-Ill., as an aide on
environmental and energy issues and then worked as an executive
assistant to Mauro _ the official he is now seeking to replace.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he was elected to the Texas House, where his
assignments have included the prestigious budget-writing
Appropriations Committee and energy and economic development
panels. He was a sponsor of the Texas Tomorrow Fund, which allows
parents to arrange for their children's future college education at
today's tuition prices.
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst, 53, was born and raised in a working-class section of
Houston. His father was killed by a drunken driver when Dewhurst
was 3, and he recalls many tough years in which his mother scrimped
and saved to get by. After graduating from Houston's Lamar High
School in 1963, he attended the University of Arizona, where he
played basketball and earned a business degree before enlisting in
the Air Force for a stateside tour of duty.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Central Intelligence Agency as a case officer
assigned to Bolivia in 1971, at a time when the leftist president
was ousted in a right-wing military coup. Dewhurst _ who is
prohibited by law from divulging details of his work _ laughs off
suggestions by some publications that he was involved in
cloak-and-dagger activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a junior case officer . . . Generally speaking, I helped
American tourists in trouble, handled visas, things like that,'' he
said in a recent interview. ``To suggest I did anything else I
guess is a backhanded compliment. But it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists he has had no ongoing contacts with the CIA, although
he was appointed by then-Sen. Bob Dole to a congressional
commission on intelligence issues in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After two years with the CIA, a bored Dewhurst _ ``I felt like
everything was happening in Washington, in the United States, and I
guess I felt like I was missing the action'' _ quit to become a
Houston-based energy consultant in South America.
</P>
<P>
   He soon started an oil service company. That eventually grew
into his current position as chairman of Falcon Seaboard Holdings,
but not before the oil bust of the mid-1980s nailed him. One of his
companies sought bankruptcy protection. Disgruntled business
partners sued him, alleging fraud and embezzlement. His finances
were a mess of red ink.
</P>
<P>
   While Raymond insists those troubles 10 years ago ``raise
serious questions about how David Dewhurst got his wealth,''
Dewhurst said there is no mystery about what happened. Ignoring the
advice of advisers who urged him to file for personal bankruptcy
and walk away, Dewhurst vowed to repay those he owed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me to avoid the grief, the poverty of paying people
back. But I was just too proud. I couldn't do that,'' he said. ``I
lived extremely frugally for three or four years, practically on
nothing. It was important to me that I keep my good name intact.
That took another five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dewhurst notes that several of the formerly disgruntled
business partners who sued him have been repaid for their
investments. Several now support his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Dewhurst's business ventures _ including
ventures to convert natural gas to electricity, a project in which
one plant alone was sold in 1995 for $226 million _ have paid off
handsomely. He sits on 22 corporate boards and those of the Houston
Grand Opera and Greater Houston Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   He reported his taxable income last year as $3.7 million. So why
does he want a job that pays only a pittance, in comparison?
</P>
<P>
   ``I became interested in politics several years ago,'' Dewhurst
said, explaining his donations to Republican Party heavyweights in
recent years, even a four-year stint as Texas GOP finance chairman.
``After everything good that has happened to me, I feel a need to
give back. I want to try to make a difference in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the River Oaks mansion that Raymond has tried to
make into a campaign issue, Dewhurst and his wife, Tammy Jo, a
former model, own two other homes in Houston, ranches in Colorado
and near Kerrville, at least one Austin house and a condo in Santa
Fe, N.M. They live in a rented Houston home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may own more houses that I don't live in than anyone else,''
Dewhurst laughs. ``I invest in real estate. What else can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Raymond says he makes less than $80,000 a year _
about $70,000 from oil and gas royalties, $7,200 as a legislator.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' political war chests are as mismatched, as well.
So far, Dewhurst has raised more than $4.6 million in donations, $4
million of that from loans he personally guaranteed and $160,000
from his own pocket. Raymond has raised about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that Dewhurst can run lots of television
commercials, a key to getting noticed in the final weeks before the
election. Raymond can run few. To try to get his name known, he has
resorted to a barrage of press releases attacking Dewhurst _ but so
far, they have drawn only limited press attention.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid conflict-of-interest questions concerning their
financial ties to the oil and gas industry, which the General Land
Office deals with, Dewhurst months ago placed his financial
holdings in a blind trust and Raymond has said he will donate his
oil royalties to school charities if he is elected.
</P>
<P>
   Though their careers are different, their campaign platforms are
similar. Both promise to boost earnings from Texas' 22 million
acres of public lands, which the General Land Office oversees. Both
promise to protect Mauro's legacy of protecting beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Both vow to expand benefits to Texas veterans. The Land Office
oversees several veterans' programs. Both endorse expanding a
program that takes natural gas from state lands and, instead of
collecting traditional cash royalties, sells it at a discount to
utilities who then pass along the savings to schools and state
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   And, even though the Land Office has little to do with Texas
school policy, both have made education a priority. Raymond says
Dewhurst favors a state-paid voucher program that ``would take $1
billion from our public schools and give it to elite private
schools and the home-schoolers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to focus on saving our schools,'' Raymond says. ``He
wants to ruin public education. I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst denies that. He said he favors a pilot voucher program,
like the one backed by Gov. George Bush. Dewhurst said it was a way
to give parents an option and prod public schools to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I favor public education. I am a product of public education.
I want to give our children a chance,'' Dewhurst said. ``I don't
want to turn public education upside down. . . . But my opponent
wants to maintain the status quo, and that's not fair to our
children when they are trapped in failing schools.''
</P>
<P>
   While education may be the public's interest, the race for land
commissioner is important to the political parties for another
reason: The winner will sit on the panel that will draw new
legislative and congressional district boundaries, and both parties
want to make sure they have the majority membership.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, both parties are watching the land
commissioner's race closely.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Dewhurst has appeared the confident winner.
Raymond has portrayed himself as ``the underdog who will win.''
</P>
<P>
   And should they not be elected?
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst said he will return to the world of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like public policy,'' Raymond says. ``I'll probably become a
policy wonk.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
