<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FLOODING SHIFTS DOWNSTREAM; FLOODWATERS COVER A QUARTER OF
STATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the death toll climbing to at least 22, the high water
ravaging the state shifted downstream Tuesday, inundating South
Texas and all but assuring this disaster a place among the worst of
Lone Star floods.
</P>
<P>
   So far floodwaters have covered nearly a quarter of the state,
according to the Texas Division of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   Several people are reported missing and thousands are homeless.
Swollen rivers swept along houses, cars and livestock.
</P>
<P>
   While insured losses related to the storms are expected to
exceed $90 million, total losses are almost sure to be in the
hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush requested disaster relief for 20 Texas
counties, a third of the staggering 60 counties that have seen
flooding since soaking rains began over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``God works in mysterious ways,'' said Bush, who toured a New
Braunfels neighborhood northeast of San Antonio Tuesday in addition
to viewing flood damage from a helicopter. ``Only three months ago
we were praying for rain because we were too dry. And now here we
stand at the site of the devastating flood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We get these sorts of floods periodically,'' said Bill Reed,
chief meteorologist at the National Weather Service in Houston,
recalling the rains in the fall of 1994. ``But this has got to be
approaching something monumental.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Central Texas, where some areas received as much as 20
inches of rain, residents of San Antonio and points north began to
clean up. In San Antonio, officials re-opened Interstate 281, the
downtown freeway.
</P>
<P>
   But in towns like Victoria, which sits on the Guadalupe River
about 125 miles south of Houston, helicopters plucked residents
from the roofs of houses as the coffee-colored river was expected
to crest early this morning at as much as 15 feet above flood
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in boats made similar rescues, often of residents
who had refused to leave their homes. The flooding knocked out
power downtown, left a small part of the city of 60,000 under water
Tuesday night and prompted locals to call the high water the worst
in more than 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Army National Guard estimated the swollen Guadalupe, usually
about 150 feet across, to span some four miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst flooding I've ever seen,'' said Mike Ratcliff,
Victoria County sheriff. ``Some parts of town are under 10 feet of
water.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cuero, 27 miles northwest of Victoria, three-quarters of the
town of 7,000 was under water after the Guadalupe crested at 49.78
feet, more than double its 20-foot flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   City Secretary Nancy Gips said at least 2,000 people abandoned
their homes to spend the night in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just taking it a minute at a time,'' she said. ``Until
the water recedes, we can't do much of anything except make sure
everyone's safe and dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Showers lingered in parts of South Texas but did little to
aggravate the situation. Forecasters predicted clear skies across
the state by Thursday night, possibly bringing to a close an
unlikely and highly charged weather system that has combined heavy
moisture from two hurricanes off Mexico's west coast, a slow-moving
cold front and a steady stream of moist air from the Gulf of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flooding is not uncommon,'' said Jon Zeitler, a forecaster
with the National Weather Service. ``What's uncommon is the amount
of rain that fell.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the Colorado River also was wreaking havoc on
South Texas communities downstream, such as the town of Wharton.
</P>
<P>
   While 7,000 people have been evacuated from their homes
statewide since Saturday, some 1,500 are being temporarily housed
in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The floods are the third since August to strike Texas, with a
total of at least 31 dead. Nine died in the Del Rio floods, which
occurred when the remnants of Tropical Storm Charley stalled over
West Texas, and Tropical Storm Frances inundated Houston and
Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities continued to find flood victims Tuesday. In Caldwell
County in Central Texas, they recovered the body of 11-year-old
Heather Cottle in a Suburban 27 feet under water. Seven-year-old
Devon McCoy, with the young girl when the car washed off a road,
was still missing.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, where life was just getting back to normal after
three harrowing days, police discovered the body of a 37-year-old
man, while the body of a 6-year-old boy was found in Comal County.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio businesses, many of them suffering from water
damage, spent the early part of the week cleaning up mud and
debris. So too did homeowners, some whose homes were filled with
several feet of water. Home improvement stores were reporting brisk
sales of water vacuums.
</P>
<P>
   Up Interstate 35, in New Braunfels and east to Seguin, the
devastation of homes was even greater along the Guadalupe.
</P>
<P>
   The governor termed the damage he saw on the aerial tour
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine how swift and powerful the current must
be,'' Bush said. ``I can't imagine how ferocious nature must have
been to do the damage I saw.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
