<HEADER>
A7992 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     10-20 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING HUSSEIN JOINS IN EFFORT TO REACH MIDEAST PEACE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for inserts, rewriting throughout) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ With King Hussein of Jordan joining President
Clinton at the Middle East peace talks, optimism rose on Tuesday
that some kind of settlement will be reached between Israelis and
Palestinians after more than 19 months of stalemate and 6 days of
talking here.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans and the Palestinians are pushing for a
comprehensive interim accord, so that a final round of peace talks
can start now. But the Israelis have at different points suggested
the possibility of a partial accord, with later talks on some
disputed issues.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials said the parties were working on a comprehensive
accord that would involve trade-offs on the key sticking points.
Having identified the disputed issues for both parties, the
Americans are working on a single package of mutual concessions
that could produce a comprehensive interim settlement.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said the talks, originally scheduled to end
on Sunday night, would go late into the night again on Tuesday and
then into Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met on Tuesday with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, and then with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel,
and the three were expected to have dinner together. Hussein met
with Arafat and Netanyahu separately on Tuesday, in meetings of
about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One sticking point is the Israeli demand for putting on trial on
charges of attacks against Israelis a specific list of
Palestinians, including some members of the Palestinian police and
self-defense forces.
</P>
<P>
   Another is the method by which Israel will guarantee safe
passage for Palestinians between the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
The Israelis are offering regularly scheduled trains and busses,
while the Palestinians are insisting that individuals be allowed to
travel in cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis also say they must have a firm commitment from
Arafat that the full Palestine National Council will meet at some
point to amend publicly the Palestinian charter, formally removing
clauses that call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials complain that apparent Palestinian commitments
on specific security moves, like the confiscation of excess weapons
and the reduction of Palestinian forces to levels laid out in the
Oslo accords, suddenly seemed to disappear during the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that they have their territorial requirements met, the
Palestinian interest has been to erode Israel's security
positions,'' Dore Gold, Israel's chief delegate to the United
Nations, said on Tuesday night. ``But Prime Minister Netanyahu
remains firm in not letting that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Palestinians want clear assurances that a
third Israeli withdrawal from West Bank land, as required under the
Oslo agreement, will take place and be of a certain percentage. The
issue will be handled by the border commission of the so-called
final-status talks, but the Palestinians want American guarantees
of the outcome, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left the talks just after midnight on Tuesday morning
after making ``significant progress,'' officials said, on key
aspects of the security package that Israel demands from the
Palestinians in return for 13 percent more of West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   He returned here just after noon on Tuesday for another long
round of meetings, continuing his investment of 45 hours over six
days.
</P>
<P>
   Final-status talks under the Oslo umbrella are to produce a
peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians that will
settle the hardest remaining issues: whether the Palestinians will
have a state, what its borders will be, the rights of refugees and
the status of Jerusalem. After interim steps, the final talks were
supposed to have concluded by next May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the president would fly
to Los Angeles on Saturday, on a fund-raising trip for Democratic
candidates that he had postponed to continue these negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness of Hussein to come, despite his serious illness,
adds moral pressure on both sides to make the political sacrifices
required for peace. The king, 62 and battling non-Hodgkins
lymphoma, arrived at midday and is expected to remain overnight at
the Wye Conference Center near here.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Hussein has been in touch with all parties by
telephone. The Americans intend to ask him to work with both
parties when serious obstacles appear. Clinton has also spoken to
Egypt's president, Hosni Mubarak, to bring him up to date.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The State Department spokesman, James Rubin, said on Tuesday
night: ``This is the certainly the most intensive phase yet. But
there are significant gaps of substance and the linkages between
them. An inch is as good as a mile in terms of closing.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior American official said the work between the two sides
had turned serious in the last 12 to 15 hours, especially after
Clinton and his team had a two-hour meeting with Netanyahu and
Arafat before dinner Monday night, and then afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've seen this before, and I've seen this phase not lead
to an agreement,'' the official said. ``It's better than before,
but by no means enough to close.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American official said the Palestinian grenade attack on
an Israeli bus stop in Beersheba early Monday, wounding more than
60 people, ``acted as a sort of shock therapy to get them moving.''
But the official noted a degree of luck, saying, ``If 10 or 12
Israelis had been killed in the attack, the Israelis would have had
to pack up and leave these talks.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks here have followed a familiar pattern, another
official said. ``In the beginning, both sides came in with their
demands and won't move and repeat them and repeat them and repeat
them until everyone's sick of it, and then they begin to discuss
bridging ideas,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein, who flew to his Maryland home on Monday after being
discharged from the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota, was asked by the
Americans to come here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the king will help bring home to the two delegations
the necessity of making the tough choices that lead to peace,''
Rubin said. The king has proved indispensable to peacemaking in the
past, making a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 and helping the
Americans to get the Israelis and Palestinians to agree to the
Hebron accords of January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the king traveled to Netanyahu's office in Tel Aviv to
work out the last details of that agreement, by which Israeli
troops pulled out of most of Hebron and set a schedule, since
abandoned, for other troop withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   But his support for the invasion of Kuwait by President Saddam
Hussein of Iraq nearly caused the United States to break relations
with Jordan seven years ago. King Hussein's army has fought both
the Palestinians and the Israelis, beating back a Palestinian
revolt in 1970 and taking part in Middle East war in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 2237EDT &QL; 
