</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-EARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE GIVES NORTHWEST A LOSS; SOUTHWEST AIR PROFIT UP 40 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wounded badly by last month's pilots strike, Northwest Airlines
reported a $224 million third-quarter loss yesterday. Also
yesterday, Southwest Airlines, following the pattern of other
booming carriers, announced record earnings for the period.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest, the nation's fourth-largest airline, said that it
lost $2.91 a diluted share, compared with a profit of $290 million,
or $2.53 a share, in the corresponding quarter last year. Revenue
declined 31 percent, to $1.93 billion, from $2.8 billion in period
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest also said that negotiations with the antitrust
division of the Justice Department over its plan to buy a
controlling stake in Continental Airlines would be resolved in
``days rather than weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas M. Steenland, Northwest's chief counsel, said he
expected the government to file suit to block the deal and a
proposed alliance between the two carriers if no agreement was
reached soon, and he predicted that Northwest would win in court.
``Because we believe this transaction is pro-competitive, we would
anticipate that we would prevail,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said its operations were recovering quickly from the
strike, with traffic around normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some talk that the market might be softening,
but we don't see that in our own bookings at the moment,'' said
Michael E. Levine, an executive vice president in charge of
marketing and international operations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Northwest continues to suffer more than most United
States carriers because of the strike and its substantial exposure
in Asia, which accounts for nearly one-third of its revenue. The
airline put the total cost of the walkout, which grounded
operations for 18 days, at $630 million. It said it expected to
post another loss in the fourth quarter and for the full year.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Northwest fell $2.375 Tuesday, to $24.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest, the largest discount airline, said its net income
surged 40 percent in the quarter, to $129.6 million, or 37 cents a
diluted share, compared with $92.5 million, or 27 cents a share a
year earlier. Revenue increased 10 percent, to $1.1 billion, from
$997 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Kelly, Southwest's chief financial officer, said the key
factors in the quarter were strong passenger demand and low fuel
prices. Southwest's planes left the ground with an average of 70
percent of their seats filled, one of the highest levels ever. Fuel
costs dropped nearly 19 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly added that Southwest _ which is sought out each year by
officials of hundreds of cities hoping to attract its low-cost
flights _ planned to expand capacity 13 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Average seat growth for the industry is forecast at 5.5 percent,
according to analysts. Kelly said Southwest would like to grow even
faster if it could add more Boeing 737 jets to its fleet at
attractive prices.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Southwest Airlines fell 62.5 cents Tuesday to $20.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
