<P>
   (NYT17) SAN DIEGO, Calif. -- Oct. 20, 1998 --
BBO-YANKS-PADRES-1, 10-20 -- Yankees fans David Karp, left, and
Eric Garcia wearing their Coneheads before the start of game three
of the World Series on Tuesday night against the Padres. New York's
David Cone and San Diego's Sterling Hitchcock have kept game three
scoreless for the first five innings Tuesday night, with Cone
working on a no-hitter. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- NY-GAY-RALLY-2, 10-20 -- A
police officer approaches protesters Monday night in New York
during a rally against the killing of Matthew Shepard. For some of
the younger marchers, the demonstration that paralyzed parts of
midtown Manhattan was their first rally. For some older protesters,
the march was a return to the angry street protests that had so
often symbolized the militancy of the gay rights movement. (Thomas
Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) VAIL, Colo. -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- VAIL-FIRES, 10-20 --
Crime scene tape surrounds the remains of the 33,000 square-foot
Two Elks restaurant at the top of Vail Mountain on Tuesday. Seven
fires ravaged structures at the Colorado ski area early Monday
causing an estimated $12 million in damage. Arson is suspected in
the blazes. The Gore Range of the Rocky Mountains towers above the
scene at rear. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- DC-PODESTA-FLOATER, 10-20
-- President Clinton appoints John Podesta his new White House
chief of staff Tuesday, effective Nov. 1, replacing Erskine Bowles,
who may run for North Carolina governor. Podesta is shown embracing
his mother, Mary, at a Rose Garden ceremony. Behind them is his
son, Gabe, left, and his brother, Tony. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- CONGRESS-SPEND, 10-20 --
Speaker Newt Gingrich appearing with fellow Republicans at a
celebration Tuesday in Washington. Gingrich was criticized by
conservative members of the party over the spending package passed
by the House. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- MIDEAST-TALKS, 10-20 --
President Clinton and national security adviser Samuel Berger
leaving the White House on Tuesday to attend Middle East peace
talks. Optimism rose at the talks in Wye Mills, Md., that
settlement will be reached. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK-- Oct. 20, 1998 -- LUXURY-CARS, 10-20 --James
Press, vice president and general manager of Toyota Sales U.S.,
looks out from the driver's seat of one of Lexus' new sport utility
vehicles. Seated behind him is Bryan Bergsteinsson, the Lexus group
vice president and general manager. Since Toyota Motor Corp.
created the Lexus brand a decade ago, drivers have gradually
developed a fierce loyalty to it, transforming this upstart into a
major automotive success story. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) TETERBORO, N.J. -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- BLIMP-PILOT-PROFILE,
10-20 -- Blimp pilot Tracy Rockhold walks in front of his craft at
Teterboro Airport. ``Every landing is different,'' says Rockhold,
who guides the 205-foot-long airship from Goodyear some 1,000 feet
above New York's Yankee Stadium. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW DELHI, India -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- INDIA-COWCATCHERS,
10-20 -- New Delhi employs 100 or so cow catchers and their job
isn't easy. Civil disobedience paid off for this cow: she kept
going limp when a team of catchers got her on the ramp leading to
the truck. Eventually they gave up. (Barry Bearak/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- NY-GAY-RALLY, 10-19 -- A
protester waves a sign at a police officer during a rally to
protest the killing of Matthew Shepherd on Monday night in New
York. The size of the loosely-organized march, between 4,000 and
5,000 people, exceeded the expectations of organizers and police
alike. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- ALBERT-MEMORIAL-2, 10-20 --
The marble frieze around the base of the Albert Memorial depicts
figures in the arts, including Shakespeare, Homer and Cheops. After
a four-year, 18.7 million overhaul, the 200-foot-high structure,
signifying Queen Victoria's love for her dead husband, Prince
Albert, will again be unveiled to the public. The monument will
formally reopen in Kensington Gardens on Wednesday. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LONDON -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- ALBERT-MEMORIAL-1, 10-20 --
After a four-year, 18.7 million overhaul, the 200-foot-high Albert
Memorial, signifying Queen Victoria's love for her dead husband,
Prince Albert, and Britain's most elaborate example of high
Victorian neo-Gothic architecture, will again be unveiled to the
public. Albert's great-great-granddaughter, Queen Elizabeth, will
formally reopen the monument in Kensington Gardens on Wednesday.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- MCDONALD-CABARET, 10-20 --
Audra McDonald singing at Joe's Pub. The world evoked by her voice
is a place rich with fantastic art and extravagant feeling, a realm
where genres become weak in the knees and helplessly collapse into
one another. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- BROADWAY-NEW-PLAYWRIGHTS,
10-20 -- Four playwrights close enough to Broadway this season to
sniff the greasepaint: Rob Bartlett, bottom left, whose play jus
closed; David Shaber, bottom right, looking for a theater; Michael
Chepiga, top left, and Mark Victor Olsen. Plays by obscure writers
open all the time, but it is unusual to see so many untested
authors get a shot at the Great White Way. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN FRANCISCO -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- TOMASSON-BALLET, 10-20
-- Helgi Tomasson, artistic director of the San Francisco Ballet,
watching a rehearsal of ``Crisscross.'' The troupe opened Tuesday
night at City Center with a weeklong program aimed at reacquainting
New Yorkers with the company's distinctively style after a three
year hiatus. ``I wanted to give audiences an opportunity to get to
know the dancers better,'' Tomasson says. (Peter DaSilva/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- RESTAURANT-JITTERS, 10-20 --
A waiter takes orders at City Hall - a new eatery in New York's
TriBeCa. Despite concerns about the stock market, the mood at the
restaurant is optimistic. ``People always want to eat out,'' says
owner Henry Meer. (William Lopez/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ST. HELENA, Calif. -- Oct. 20, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 10-20
-- Heidi Barrett shovels grapes into a wine press at Grace Family
Vineyards in St. Helena. Ms. Barrett is one of the most
sought-after winemakers in the Napa Valley region. (Terrence
McCarthy/New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
