<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAILER SUFFERS PAINFAUL CATCH-22
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA kicker/punter Chris Sailer is caught between
a rock and a sore place: namely, his right groin.
</P>
<P>
   Sailer needs to kick during the week to maintain his gameday
timing. But if he kicks during the week, he'll aggravate the
strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be practicing, but the best thing is rest,'' he
said. ``The injury won't heal unless I rest. If I kicked during the
week, I'd be out a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Sailer suffered the injury three weeks ago, before the
Washington State game, and it has tightened steadily. He's missed
three of six field goals in that span: two were blocked, and he
shanked a 21-yarder in the final seconds of regulation against
Oregon, which, he insists, had nothing to do with his groin.
</P>
<P>
   Groin, shank, bad biorhythms, whatever _ it hasn't been the
season Sailer expected. A second-team All-American in 1997, he's
made just 3 of 8 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do what I normally do. That's frustrating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior from Burbank, Sailer felt the initial twinge Sept. 30,
during a post-practice kicking display for a local TV station. It
had nothing to do with distance or quantity of kicks; he simply
wasn't loose.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Sailer felt tightness while warming up for
Washington State. It was tighter the following week, at Arizona,
tighter still against Oregon. Now, he walks with a limp and gets 3
to 4 hours of treatment per day.
</P>
<P>
   The pain is greatest early in the week, then relents until
Saturday. The more rest he gets, the better it feels. The more rest
he gets, the less timing he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best of what we've got,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   If Sailer has to relinquish one of his duties, it'll be
kickoffs. Walk-on Chris Griffith will travel to Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play,'' Sailer said. ``Even if I'm only 50 percent,
I'll kick. There's no question in my mind. I won't miss a game.
There's no other option.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Stat of the Week:!off! The Bruins have scored at least 40
points in five consecutive games, a school record.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!He's here. He's there. He's...:!off! Senior outside
linebacker Brendan Ayanbadejo, a Santa Cruz native, was named
captain for an unprecedented second consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As well as he's played, being a senior, being from the Bay
Area, there were too many pluses,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from safety Larry Atkins, Ayanbadejo is the Bruins' best
defensive player, fourth in total tackles (22) but first in
tackles-for-loss (six), sacks (five) and fumble recoveries (three).
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Medical report:!off! It began with quarterback Cade
McNown and receiver Brian Poli-Dixon, then spread faster than a
UCLA scoring drive.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, 10 players missed practice because of the stomach flu.
Most had recovered Tuesday, but the Bruins were bracing for another
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes so fast,'' Toledo said. ``The ones that had it are
making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon, no longer flu-stricken, has turf toe and won't
practice this week. He's probable for the Cal game.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Welcome back:!off! Defensive end Kenyon Coleman had two
fumble recoveries against Oregon after missing 2{ games with a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of his better performances since he's been here,''
Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman will start at one end against Cal, Pete Holland at the
other.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!By the numbers:!off! The Bruins are 5-0 for the first
time since 1988, when they started 7-0 and climbed to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has won six consecutive games against ranked opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have scored on 83.8 percent of their red zone chances
(inside the opponent's 20-yard line). They have 23 touchdowns and
three field goals in 31 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA leads the Pac-10 in turnover margin (plus-2.0).
</P>
<P>
   Kickoff for the Stanford game Oct. 31 at the Rose Bowl is 3:30
p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
