<HEADLINE>
HOME-BUILDING GIANT KAUFMAN &AMP; BROAD ADDING ON WITH LEWIS BUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In a deal that makes it the nation's biggest home
builder, Kaufman &AMP; Broad Home Corp. said it is buying Upland-based
Lewis Homes for about $544 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are about 40 years old, and while they operate in
some of the same markets, namely Southern California and Las Vegas,
there won't be much product overlap because Lewis builds pricier
homes, executives said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lewis Homes just opened Oak Terrace at Stevenson
Ranch in the suburban Santa Clarita Valley, a development of 125
homes priced in the low to mid-$300,000 price range.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman &AMP; Broad, based in suburban Westwood, has about 600 units
planned or under construction in neighboring Ventura County and the
suburban San Fernando, Santa Clarita and Antelope valleys, with
some homes priced in the $180,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Karatz, Kaufman &AMP; Broad's chairman and chief executive
officer, said the acquisition will strengthen his company's lock on
the home-building market in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis Homes is an excellent strategic fit with our
operations,'' Karatz said. ``They have a similar operating
strategy, and their leading market shares in California and Nevada
combined with Kaufman &AMP; Broad's strong presence in those areas will
be a major boost to our market dominance strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale is expected to close in January and be ``strongly
accretive'' to Kaufman &AMP; Broad's per-share earnings on an annual
basis in 1999, Karatz said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the nation's largest privately held home builder, is
expected to generate 1998 revenue of $685 million on the sale of
3,500 homes. The company also owns about 24,000 lots and has a
backlog of some 1,200 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman &AMP; Broad's 1998 revenues are estimated at $2.4 billion on
about 15,000 deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company is expected to deliver about 21,000 new
homes next year, vaulting it past Pulte Corp. of Philadelphia as
the country's top builder in terms of units.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Lewis, executive vice president of Lewis Homes, said the
company decided to sell now because it could negotiate a deal from
a position of strength due to the vibrant housing market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaufman &AMP; Broad was a highly attractive merger partner from
the beginning, due to the similarities of the two operations,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Terms call for the Lewis Homes ownership group to receive $409
million in cash and Kaufman &AMP; Broad stock. The company will also
assume about $135 million in Lewis debt and the Lewis family will
get one seat on the Kaufman &AMP; Broad board.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has about 600 employees, and Kaufman &AMP; Broad about 2,300.
Minimal layoffs are expected.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
