<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SIBERIA (Yakutsk) _ To the Russians crazy enough to live
there, summer in the Siberian Arctic is merely a deep breath before
the next winter, a few weeks of melted ice and midnight sun in
which to gird for the next deep freeze. Either they use those weeks
to haul in enough food and fuel to make it to the next thaw, or
they shiver and starve through the coming months of darkness. It is
easy to call Russia's travails political or fiscal crises. But here
in the Siberian republic of Yakutiya, where a bad debt can condemn
thousands to months of hunger, they can be a matter of survival. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-GAY-MARCHERS (New York) _ For some of the younger marchers
who took to the streets on Monday night to protest the killing of a
homosexual college student in Wyoming, it was their first time in a
big demonstration. For some of the older marchers it was it was a
return to street protests after a long absence, a chance to revive
the chants of years past and practice the old street skills. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   VAIL-FIRES (Vail, Colo.) _ As Vail, the nation's most popular
ski resort, seeks to expand, it finds itself embroiled in battles
on several fronts. Environmentalists want to stop expansion of ski
trails in the back country and wealthy land owners are fighting a
plan to build lower income housing for people who work in Vail. At
the same time, an arsonist has set eight fires in mountaintop
restaurants. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RHODEISLAND-POLITICS (Providence) _ The somewhat wistful word on
the street here is that this year's governor's race is a bore, a
plodding match between two candidates who are so decent and civil
that they cannot summon the almost mandatory vitriol that has
traditionally made Rhode Island politics a full-contact sport. In
truth, the race between the incumbent Republican, a former U.S.
attorney named Lincoln C. Almond, and the Democratic challenger, a
former state senator named Myrth York, is close enough for both to
have summoned help from outside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-CLINTON-CRITICISM _ Responding to waves of grousing in
the nation's military about President Clinton's affair with Monica
Lewinsky, military leaders have begun warning officers and enlisted
personnel that they could well face punishment for public
denunciations of the commander-in-chief.
</P>
