<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      10-20 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ Of the four teams Texas A&AMP;M has played in each of
the previous three football seasons, only one has managed to keep
the Aggies on the losing end of the scoreboard all three times.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A&AMP;M defeated Texas once, Colorado once and Baylor in all three
matchups, but Texas Tech is 3-0 against the Aggies since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech definitely has been a thorn in our side,'' A&AMP;M tight end
Dan Campbell said. ``It eats you up. There are two teams I always
want to beat _ Texas is No. 1 and Tech No. 2. I want us to get that
thorn out of our side.''
</P>
<P>
   The most painful part for the Aggies is the fact that they could
have won all three games, losing two of the matchups by a field
goal and one by a touchdown at the end on an interception by former
Tech linebacker Zach Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have given us a lot of trouble, and that's the one team I
haven't beaten,'' A&AMP;M tailback Dante Hall said. ``And the way they
have beaten us is silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we owe them, but the stakes of this game make it
bigger because you can have sole possession of first place. This
could decide who wins the South in the Big 12. Everybody has their
eyes on the prize now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies (6-1 overall, 3-0 Big 12), who are ranked No. 8 in
the nation, are the only team in the South Division without a loss.
Tech (6-1, 3-1) is ranked 25th after falling 19-17 last weekend at
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever wins this game definitely has a plus in the race,''
A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said. ``Somebody is going to have to overtake
the team that wins this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning it for us is big because it would give Tech its second
loss, and Texas (2-1) still has Nebraska to play up there. If we
lose this one, we're all in the same boat. That's how it is in this
league. You're always dodging hand grenades and hoping somebody
else hits one.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason A&AMP;M hasn't been able to avoid losses against Tech the
last three years is turnovers. The Aggies have suffered 10
turnovers _ three interceptions and seven fumbles _ in their last
three meetings with the Red Raiders while Tech had two turnovers in
1996 and none in '95 or '97.
</P>
<P>
   But Slocum points out some other factors that have led to A&AMP;M's
demise against Tech. Injuries forced the Aggies to start two
inexperienced tackles in the game last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we went to Lubbock without our two starting
offensive tackles and our starting tailback (Hall),'' Slocum said.
``That was a tough place to break in. Their defense is very good,
and we would have had a tough time with them anyway, but trying to
do it with new starters at both tackles was a real chore.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum also emphasized that the losses have come under unusual
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like all three are games we should have won,'' he
said. ``They've been frustrating games for us. It has been kind of
strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw an interception at the end of the game (in 1995) that
was the winning touchdown. Last year, they won it when their backup
kicker (Tony Rogers) made a 47-yard field goal when it hit the
upright and bounced over.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat Slocum didn't bring up was the one at College Station
in 1996 when Tech fullback Sammy Morris turned a screen pass into
an 81-yard score for the winning touchdown. Two days later, Morris
was declared ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   But Slocum doesn't want to give the impression he thinks Tech
has been lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take anything away from Tech,'' Slocum said. ``They
put themselves in position to win those games. They don't beat
themselves, because they are extremely well-coached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spike (Dykes) has weathered a few storms there and now has one
of the most consistent programs in the conference. I always marvel
at how hard they play. You can never count them out against
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum thinks there might be a more subtle reason why the Aggies
have struggled at times against the Red Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always play well against Baylor because a lot of players
from both schools are from Houston and Southeast Texas and they
know each other,'' Slocum said. ``But you go down the Tech roster,
and our guys don't know many of them because those guys are from
West Texas. Playing Tech is not nearly as familiar for our players
as it is to take on Texas or Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Southwest Conference, we had lot bigger rivalries with
Rice and Houston, from the kids' standpoint, than we did with Tech.
So I've always thought this was a bigger game for Tech than it was
for us. But the situation with the Big 12 South is changing that.
Our players realize this is a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time A&AMP;M was ranked in the top 10, it was Tech that
knocked the Aggies out with a 14-7 victory at Lubbock in 1995. But
the A&AMP;M players believe things are different this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how important this game is,'' Campbell said. ``We can
open a gap between us, Tech and Texas. We need to win this one as
much as any game we've played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
