<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOPPY BUT LOVABLE MOORES COULD HAVE PADRES ON THE MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ San Diego Padres president Larry Lucchino, looking
like the captain of one of those million-dollar Mission Bay yachts,
wore a white shirt and a snappy double-breasted blue blazer to a
news conference yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   His blow-dried coif was deftly combed back for the appearance,
which was an opportunity to extol the virtues of a new ballpark in
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The dumpy guy next to him with the glasses wore brown slacks and
shoes and a plain beige shirt. A U.S.S. Peleiu baseball cap covered
his curly short black hair.
</P>
<P>
   You almost expected Lucchino to say, ``And now here's Joe Smith,
our assistant equipment manager, who will tell you why he will Vote
Yes on C.''
</P>
<P>
   Only this wasn't Joe Smith and he wasn't the equipment manager.
He's John Moores and he owns the equipment, the socks and jocks,
the rest of the franchise, and another billion or so dollars beyond
that.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that has been given to charity. The University of
Houston got $51 million. Emory University got $20 million, plus a
pledge for $50 million more. San Diego State got $10 million so
they could build Tony Gwynn Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He also founded the River Blindness Foundation and regularly
lets former president Jimmy Carter fly around the world on charity
missions in his own private jet.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Brothers apparently got nothing. A billion bucks and he
looks like Andy Griffith's next door neighbor, the one who does his
shopping at the local five-and-dime. This is a guy who was
complaining he couldn't wear his favorite blue jeans to Yankee
Stadium because they had champagne stains left over from the
National League playoff celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a pudgy computer geek,'' Moores pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   But if he'd get his nose out of a Sony Playstation and check out
the batting practice scene at Qualcomm Stadium yesterday, he'd see
how a billionaire is supposed to dress.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Chip Caray wore a charcoal grey suit to accent his brown
pancake makeup. Joe Morgan strutted around in a burgundy sports
coat, while Jon Miller wore a blue blazer and turtleneck.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the annoying but impeccable ``Arliss'' guy,
Robert Wuhl. He not only stars on HBO as super-successful sports
agent Arliss Michaels, but he's also the show's executive producer,
which lands him those steamy love scenes with Katarina Witt.
</P>
<P>
   Wuhl strutted around the field yesterday like he, and not
Moores, owned the place _ meeting and greeting every player whose
attention he could get. A camera followed at close range to capture
those moments that make Arliss the award-winning show that it is.
</P>
<P>
   Arliss: ``How you doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti: ``I could be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Arliss: ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti: ``We'll get it together.''
</P>
<P>
   Arliss: ``Have a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit Caminiti nodding, stage right.
</P>
<P>
   But Wuhl was truly stylish in his black-striped suit. Moores, on
the other hand, is a fool. If he dressed like Wuhl, he'd have a new
stadium right now.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he'll have to settle for the admiration, respect and
shameless fawning of every player, coach, manager and citizen in
the Greater San Diego area, at least those planning to Vote Yes on
C.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, they've become smitten with the pudgy computer geek
from Houston who took a measly $1,000 investment and built a
billion-dollar software business, then bought the Padres in 1994
and brought them instant respectability.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is one of a kind,'' Lucchino said. ``I've been in sports
for 25 years and I've never seen an owner that has the personality
and competitive nature that he has. The Padres and San Diego are
extraordinarily fortunate to have John Moores.''
</P>
<P>
   But the actual depth of that love will be tested Nov. 3, when
the citizens of San Diego go to the polls and vote on a $411
million ballpark to be built on the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Moores is pledging to spend at least $115 million of his money
to help build the place and promises to cover any and all of the
inevitable cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are a few irrational folks in San Diego who
steadfastly believe the geek with the champagne-stained pants
should take his billions and buy his own ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   But his wife, Becky, snapped back in ``USA Today'' by telling
those fools, ``Those people who think he's rich, he'll figure out a
way to stay here, are sorely mistaken. We've accomplished \Rthe
Padres success\S with a tremendous amount of debt. I'm not willing
to lose any more money, especially when we could be giving it to
starving children.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he's huggable and lovable, a generous geek who
doesn't know how to dress and hasn't heard of lemon juice for those
pesky champagne stains. But he found his way from Texas to San
Diego and he can find his way to Northern Virginia if that Nov. 3
vote doesn't pass.  &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
