<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LEVY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMOND LEVY, 69, DOCUMENTARIAN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edmond A. Levy, an Academy Award-winning
documentarian, died on Oct. 10 at St. Rose's Home in Manhattan. He
was 69 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his stepson William H. Judson said.
</P>
<P>
   Levy wrote, produced and directed more than 120 documentary
films. He won an Oscar in 1966 for ``A Year Toward Tomorrow,'' a
documentary short about the Vista volunteer program. Two other
short films, ``While We Run This Race'' and ``Beyond Silence,''
brought him Academy Award nominations.
</P>
<P>
   He also directed ``Mom, the Wolfman and Me,'' a feature film
starring Patty Duke. His television work included writing and
directing films for NBC, CBS and ABC as well as PBS and the Disney
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Toronto, Levy moved with his family to Buffalo, N.Y. He
was a graduate of Harvard University and studied acting at the Yale
Drama School and directing at the Actors Studio in New York. He was
the author of ``Making a Winning Short.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to William Judson, of New York City, he is survived
by his wife, Denise; two sons, Jonathan, of San Francisco, and
Jeremy, of Pittsburgh; two other stepsons, Stephen Judson, of New
York City, and Peter Judson, of Los Angeles; a sister, Kay
Michaels, of New York City; and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
