<HEADLINE>
VAN RAAPHORST HAS MORE TESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst underwent a
second battery of tests Tuesday as doctors continued to search for
a reason he has suffered nausea attacks before or during three
games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst underwent blood tests Monday, which did not reveal
any problems, and had further tests performed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's wrong,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``There was a battery of tests yesterday. We did another battery
today. We'll get the results tomorrow. Is he 100 percent? I don't
know. There was nothing from the blood test. He was worn down by
the end of practice (Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get to the bottom of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett emphasized Van Raaphorst will start against Oregon, with
Carson Palmer in relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Van Raaphorst is the starter until I say he's not,'' an
irritated Hackett said. ``Until something dramatic happens, we're
going to go with the same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst is at a loss explaining his bouts with nausea but
again ruled out nerves as the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't happened at the same time. That's why it's not
nerves,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``I was 9 of 15 (passing). I felt
great out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst acknowledged he has been bothered by reports he
might be bothered by nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more frustrating than if I have a bad performance,''
Van Raaphorst said. ``It's not an attack, but people are all trying
to find out what's going wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Words to regret?: In an answer sure to stir emotions in
Westwood, Hackett said Tuesday he believed Oregon was the best team
in the conference, even after its 41-38 loss to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't turn the ball over against UCLA, they win the game
handily,'' Hackett said. ``To me, this is the team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he might be inciting UCLA with his comments, Hackett
responded:
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA-USC is its own event. It's its own separate thing. I
don't know if anything can be put on the bulletin board to affect
that rivalry. We're going to play UCLA in the distant future, so I
can't worry about that. I just sat in a hotel room and watched
where one team kept turning the ball over and lost in overtime. I
don't mean that UCLA's not very, very good. That's my opinion at
this point, and it may not be true when we face UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Cusano doubtful: Hackett said linebacker Mark Cusano (sore
left thigh) is doubtful this week. Cusano tested his leg during
pregame warmups at Washington State and was unable to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels better, but I haven't tested it yet (this week),''
said Cusano, who did not practice Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett also said he didn't think right tackle Matt Welch
(mononucleosis) would play this week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Two down, one to go: Assistant head coach Larry Petroff has
one more kidney stone that needs to be removed, after having
surgery to remove two last week. He will probably wait until the
next month's bye week to have the procedure done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
