<DOCNO> NYT19981020.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8148 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-20 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INSTEAD of fast-breaking back to the bargaining table after the
in-your-face rejection by arbitrator John Feerick, NBA players have
headed to the Las Vegas gaming tables.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is fear and loathing will take on a whole new meaning
in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Some NBA players will feel the urge to double down every chance
they get. Press the hard eight. Split the aces.
</P>
<P>
   Baby needs a new pair of Bruno Magli shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them _ the NBA-minimum guys, the free agents and
borderliners _ will skip the trip or, egad, fly coach. They will
search for comped rooms and listen to Players Association leaders
and agents talk about strategies and plans.
</P>
<P>
   But what they should do _ and my guess is many players will _ is
wonder why at this most critical moment in the NBA lockout, the
Players Association acts as if this is some two-bit game of keno.
It acts as if it is playing with the house money, which, the rank
and file will remind leadership, it is not.
</P>
<P>
   This is the biggest gamble yet by the Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   In a league where the average salary is $2.6 million and the
last player on the bench makes at least $272,000, a prominent agent
was asked Tuesday how many players might nevertheless live paycheck
to paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than you think,'' he said. ``When you have more money in
your checkbook, you write bigger checks.''
</P>
<P>
   This is real. Real money is leaving players' pockets in the wake
of Feerick's decision. The owners have their sleeves rolled and the
pit-boss rake in their hands, and they are poised to scoop away
even more.
</P>
<P>
   When Feerick ruled Monday that owners do not have to pay up to
$800 million worth of guaranteed contracts during the NBA lockout,
it was a decision that should have given players no choice but to
concede the game and listen harder to the owners' proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 226 players lost in the decision, which came after
$100 million in salaries had been lost when owners canceled the
first two weeks of the regular season. More delays will only cramp
the players' style and put the season in danger.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently there were no calls made to commissioner David
Stern's office after Monday's ruling. There was little public
acknowledgment by the union that the only recourse is for players
to look harder at the owners' latest offer and think about
gathering in a room, locking the door and splitting this $2
billion-a-year enterprise equitably.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the union decided to keep its scheduled meeting in Las
Vegas, roll the dice and play it cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought the guys were zealous about staying committed
to the cause before,'' Players Association director Billy Hunter
said, ``they're probably more rabid than they were before.''
</P>
<P>
   My guess is, no, that's not true. And the players will say so
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the $800 million in guaranteed contracts
certainly will be honored when a new collective-bargaining
agreement is settled. But the $100 million in salaries is gone
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Another cancellation of games, which could be announced as early
as next week, will pull away millions more. Meanwhile, owners will
receive $25 million in television revenue even if no games are
played this season, thanks to smart TV-contract negotiating a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This lockout is beginning to hurt where it hurts the most.
Players will ask legitimate questions in Las Vegas and wonder why
they are sitting around gaming tables when the real jackpot is at
the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   A few cracks in the players' once-firm stance are showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder: Are you thankful for what you have, or are
you going to continue to play it out,'' Golden State's Muggsy
Bogues said. ``Sometimes, you need to look at the bigger picture
and be thankful for what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the Las Vegas meeting is to discuss the players'
bargaining strategy. But almost every player knows the best
bargaining strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Start bargaining. Soon. Like, yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, only three formal negotiating sessions have been
conducted since the lockout began July 1. With the players in
Vegas, the earliest another meeting could be held is Friday, but
nothing has been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the foot-dragging occurred because both sides were
waiting on Feerick's decision. When that decision came Monday, the
players should have realized who had the cards and sprinted to the
bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they played it cool. They acted as if nothing could
break their resolve and headed for the last place that people
worried about finances should go.
</P>
<P>
   We know Hunter made this decision. But was it Billy Hunter, or
Hunter S. Thompson?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
