<SLUG> BC-FBC-LONGHORNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Improvements on pass rush key among Texas's goals
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Quarterbacks grab headlines, but Mack Brown is
more concerned with who can grab quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the main question facing the Longhorns coach this week
is whether to start Major Applewhite or Richard Walton at
quarterback against Baylor on Saturday, Brown said he's got more
pressing things on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of issues that are more important than
that this week,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the areas in which Brown feels his Longhorns must make
great improvement over the last half of the season, when they'll
face two top-10 teams as they try to position themselves for a bowl
bid, is rushing the passer.
</P>
<P>
   Through six games the Horns have 10 sacks _ on pace to better
last season's total of 16 but still short of where they'd like to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest improvement defensively has to be in the pass
rush,'' Brown said. ``Everybody says it comes down to the defensive
backs, but if you leave NFL guys out there too long, they'll give
up plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas won't see a dominant passing attack the rest of the way _
none of the five remaining opponents average at least 200 yards a
game or are ranked higher than 61st in the nation in pass offense _
but they will face opportunistic passing games. Baylor, which
visits Royal-Memorial Stadium on Saturday, has two dangerous
receivers _ seniors Morris Anderson and Derrius Thompson, who could
provide a good challenge for Horns cornerbacks Joe Walker and Tony
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tall, physical and can run real good routes,'' Walker
said. ``As long as we play good technique we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   It'll help if they can get a rush. The Bears have allowed 18
sacks this year and have yielded nine interceptions, third most in
the Big 12, but Brown thinks the Horns will still have to blitz to
get good pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're going to have to bring extra guys to get
there,'' Brown said. ``We're still not, as a group, getting to the
passer with four (rushers). What has improved, though, is the
mentality that if we bring more, that we have to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Oklahoma and Iowa State, we blitzed more aggressively
(because) we knew we could get to the quarterback, rather than just
because Carl (Reese, defensive coordinator) called it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said there are other areas that will play key roles in
whether the Horns close the season strongly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two big stories of the last five weeks are: Can we keep
forcing turnovers? And, can we improve in the kicking game?'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is plus-5 in turnover differential, a tremendous
difference over the Horns' minus-20 of a year ago. Last year the
Horns forced only 14 turnovers, a number they're on pace to almost
double this season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said it's time for the freshmen on kick and punt coverage
teams to begin playing more consistently. Safety Lee Jackson missed
a tackle early on a 79-yard kickoff return by Oklahoma but ran down
returner Michael Thornton and pushed him out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them 'til midseason to be freshmen,'' Brown said.
``They have to be experienced. Rookie year dies at midseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges Mitchell is the only Horn to return a punt this season,
but he has only 10 returns on 35 opponent punts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done good things but we're not scoring,'' Brown said.
``People are kicking away from Hodges, so we've even tried to block
a few punts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Kris Stockton has been solid kicking off with the wind,
hitting the end zone on all but one of such kicks, but he must
improve on pooch kicks into the wind, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
