u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VAIL-FIRES-COX     10-20 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAIL-FIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vail fire heightens
 &HT;    By Chris Barker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Racing shifty October weather, an army of 50
federal and state investigators wielding high-tech computer
software today will descend on the charred remains of seven
``suspicious'' fires that burned $12 million worth of property atop
Colorado's largest ski area.
</P>
<P>
   And while local fire and law enforcement authorities for the
second day refused to speculate on the cause of the fires, local
sentiment revealed sharply divided visions of the future of the
popular recreation area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind if they just keep burning it down, actually,''
said Bruce McLaughlin, a 59-year old Minturn resident and business
owner.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin, a resident of the area since 1980, referred to the
possibility that the fires were set by arsonists opposed to a
controversial 885-acre expansion of Vail's back bowls. Tree
clearing and fence construction on the expansion began Friday after
a judge denied an appeal filed by environmentalists to stop
construction due to disruption of possible habitat for the Canadian
lynx. That work resumed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Andree, spokeswoman for the Eagle County Sheriff's
Department, said Tuesday that the early Monday morning blazes that
burned above 11,000 feet were ``suspicious.'' She refused to say
whether a criminal investigation was underway, but she said a force
of FBI, U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and Colorado
Bureau of Investigation officials were headed for Vail to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Romer called the fires an ``act of terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that mountain quite well, and it's inconceivable some
natural occurrence would cause simultaneous fires on that ridge,''
Romer said at a news conference in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Seven separate fires first detected about 4 a.m. Monday
destroyed a 33,000-square foot restaurant and the Vail Ski Patrol
Headquarters building and damaged several lifts. All of the damage
was related to facilities that would serve the controversial
planned expansion, which Vail officials said was still on schedule
to open to skiers in the 2000-2001 ski season.
</P>
<P>
   A media tour of the fire locations Tuesday revealed
still-smoldering ruins of two buildings and heavy damage to a lift
serving a popular back bowl. All of the damage - blackened eyesores
in the midst of a pristine 360-degree view from the Gore Range to
the Holy Cross Wilderness - overlooked the proposed expansion,
which Vail Resorts Spokesman Paul Witt said will eventually include
three lifts and a 20,000-square-foot restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters were hampered by poor access to the remote fires
and a lack of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's not much left up there and it's mainly due
to response times,'' said John Gulick, assistant fire chief of the
Vail Fire Department. ``We just couldn't really save much.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators plan to take advantage of what looks to be a
respite from the typical late fall pattern of storms on the
mountain to try to determine an official cause for the blaze. FBI
officials will use a computer program that compiles data gathered
in the investigation while CBI investigators will re-interview
possible eye-witnesses to the blaze, Andree said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of Minturn, a community of about 1,200 nestled in
a narrow valley southeast of Vail, suspected arson as the cause of
the fires immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But locals sipping coffee at the Cougar Ridge Cafe offered
contrasting views on whether or not such an act of sabotage would
be warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad but it's to be expected I guess,'' said Ted Rohr, 79.
``I guess people really resent Vail Associates. They just walk over
the people and with the money they've got you can't fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   Minturn just last month settled a bitter 18-month legal battle
with Vail Associates over water rights.
</P>
<P>
   A group of local residents on Tuesday said their kids can't
afford to live in a town where a small modular home lists in the
local paper for $528,000. They fear traffic and land value impacts
from the expansion will drive their sons and daughters away.
</P>
<P>
   But other residents said the detriments of Vail's ascension to
the top ranks of international ski resorts must be balanced by the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wood, a 49-year-old contractor who has worked for Vail
Associates in the past, said he's against the expansion. But that
isn't all he's against.
</P>
<P>
   'I'm totally against whatever happened,'' said Wood, referring
to the possibility the fires were deliberately set. ``I don't think
that's the best way to go about things.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he was holding out hope that the fires were caused by
an individual and not a larger group aimed at ski area development.
But he admitted that the damage didn't look to be the work of ``a
couple of guys going around with a blowtorch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is people taking the law into their own hands,'' Wood
said. ``I would like to think it was some wacko who is keyed into
(the expansion). That would be a lot easier to swallow than if it
was organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators refused to speculate on the exact timing of the
fire alarms that alerted officials to the fires. The fires were set
in two groups on two peaks separated by a 1 1/2-mile saddle
overlooking the back bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not go off simultaneously, there was a time lapse,''
said Andree, adding that authorities would use information gleaned
about the timing of the fires in their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The fires will not affect a planned Nov. 6 opening of the ski
resort or the World Alpine Ski Championships slated for late
January and the first half of February, Witt said. The fires won't
affect expansion construction, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary construction tasks include placing fencing, crossing
Two Elk creek and some timber clearing, Witt said. The expansion
into 885 acres of skiable terrain has been approved by U.S. Forest
Service and is scheduled to open some time during the 2000-2001 ski
season.
</P>
<P>
   And while some Minturn residents said the fires were the natural
result of a community pushed too far by a multi-million dollar
business interest, others decried the tactic of arson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us abhor terrorism, and that's what this is,'' said
Alan Lanning, Minturn's town manager. ``I don't think there's
anything that transpired between us and Vail Associates that would
warrant that kind of action.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Barker writes for the Grand Junction Daily Sentinel, Grand
Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
