<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK SABOTAGE CASE DISSOLVED
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors two years ago were building a case against
sus pects in the 1995 Amtrak derailment southwest of Phoenix,
according to the forewoman of the grand jury that heard evidence in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects were part of a ``small, close-knit group'' who
lived in the area of the derailment, said Betty J. Teague, an
Ahwatukee resident who led the panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they had an idea of who it was, but they couldn't put
it together with hard evidence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One person was killed and 78 injured as nine cars of the Sunset
Limited tumbled into a dry wash.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. Attor ney's Office in Phoenix said he
could not comment on the case, which has frustrated investigators
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   But while it returned indictments in the high-profile Viper
Militia case and dozens of other cases, Teague's grand jury was
never asked to vote on an indictment in the Amtrak case. It was
dismissed last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Teague's grand jury was empan eled in the fall of 1995, shortly
after the Amtrak derailment, which spawned a massive FBI probe.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hunted in vain for the saboteurs who pulled 29
rail spikes, pried the tracks apart, and used a wire to bypass an
electrical system that would have warned the crew of a break.
</P>
<P>
   A cryptic letter found at the scene and signed by ``Sons of the
Ge stapo'' began with a reference to the federal siege at the
Branch Davidian cult's enclave near Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the letter was a ruse and that the likely motive
was revenge against Amtrak or the Southern Pacific Railroad that
owns the track.
</P>
<P>
   Teague said the grand jury heard evidence about ``a small,
close-knit group of people who spend their weekends drinking a lot
of beer and commiserating'' in the Hyder area.
</P>
<P>
   But it ultimately led nowhere, Teague said.
</P>
<P>
   The Amtrak story took another turn this month as investigators,
acting on a tip, sought evidence in an abandoned mine shaft west of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Phoenix bureau spokesman Jack Callahan said Tuesday that
``There are materials that came out of that hole that we'll be
sending back to the (FBI) lab'' in Washing ton, D.C. Meanwhile, the
FBI added $200,000 to the reward in the case, bringing the total to
$320,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
