<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-BROWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ailing Brown will try to pitch Game 4
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ When someone asked Padres first baseman Wally Joyner
if teammate Kevin Brown would start tonight's World Series game, he
said with a smile: ``If he can stand up and throw a strike, he
wants the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears the sickly Brown will get the ball in Game 4 as the
Padres basically have no choice but to go with him. Not only are
they down to the Yankees, but the club is just not comfortable
pitching righthander and former Georgia Southern star Joey
Hamilton, who pitched in relief in Game 3 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   So Brown will go on three days' rest after spending much of the
last few days in bed with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not 100 percent,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said of
Brown. ``He still feels the effects. But we're optimistic that
he'll be fine and be OK to go.''
</P>
<P>
   What concerns Bochy is Brown might not be honest with him about
the severity of his sickness. Before Game 1, it was obvious that
Brown was bothered by the flu but told Bochy he was fine. Brown
didn't pitch poorly in that game, taking a 5-2 lead into the
seventh, but he appeared to tire there and came out after one out.
From there, the Padres bullpen blew up and the Yankees won 9-6.
</P>
<P>
   Does Bochy think that Brown will tell him he wants to pitch no
matter what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not confident he's going to be honest with me
knowing the kind of guy Kevin is,'' Bochy said. ``He's going to do
what he thinks is best for the ballclub, for us, and you like for
him to be honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like (Ken) Caminiti, I'm trying to get him to tell me exactly
where he's at right now, he's caught a little bug or something
here, too. And with the groin injury (Caminiti), I don't know if
he's 100 percent. And at this time, they want to be out there.
They're not going to make any excuses. If they can crawl out there,
they're going to try to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   I.J. Rosenberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
