</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-NOTES3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Torre uses Spencer against lefty
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Shane Spencer is back.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees rookie, who sparked the team in the American League
division series but wasn't used after struggling early in the
league championship, was in the lineup for Game 4 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The reason was obvious.
</P>
<P>
   In Sterling Hitchcock, the Yankees were facing a left-handed
starter for the first time in the postseason and Qualcomm Stadium
has a relatively short porch in left field, just 327 feet down the
line. Spencer, who hits from the right side, struck out on his
first two at-bats before doubling on his third one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have decided to have the switch-hitters coming off the bench
to pinch hit in case I need them,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
``I just felt that Spencer may be more of a power threat hitting
behind (Scott Brosius).''
</P>
<P>
   With the designated hitter not available in the National League
park, the Yankees certainly have a bench full of talent in the
games here, especially with the availability of the right-handed
hitting Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer hit .500 in the ALDS against the Rangers but was
1-for-10 against the Indians and hadn't played in 10 days. Spencer
is from nearby El Cajon and Torre was asked if that had anything to
do with his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wouldn't have told me that yesterday I wouldn't have
known anything about it,'' he said. ``No, I did it strictly on
hopefully the ability of putting the right guy in left field.''
</P>
<P>
   Field in brutal shape
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the San Diego State football team and the NFL
Chargers, the field was torn up and looked terrible for Game 3. The
only reason it was green was because the ground crew dumped 10,000
gallons of green vegetable dye on it. Even Yankees owner George
Steinbrenner said, ``The Chargers must have some hellish running
backs. When I was coaching in the Big Ten, I never saw a field this
bad. It is like a cow pasture.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking of dad
</P>
<P>
   Yankees left-hander Andy Pettitte, who will get the start in
Game 4 tonight, has certainly had his mind on other things. His
father recently underwent heart bypass surgery. How difficult will
it be for him to concentrate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think if I would have had to throw in New York, it
would have been real difficult,'' Pettitte said. ``But I had a
chance to talk to him (Tuesday) and he is feeling 100 percent
better. I feel great about everything back home and I don't think
it is going to be a problem at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   There were quite a few celebrities in attendance, including
tennis star Lindsay Davenport, Chargers quarterback Ryan Leaf,
country music singer Tricia Yearwood, who performed the national
anthem, actress Gillian Anderson of ``The X-Files,'' husband and
wife Matthew Broderick and Sarah Jessica Parker and Hollywood bad
boy Charlie Sheen. ... Qualcomm Stadium is the first park to host a
Super Bowl and a World Series in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   I. J. Rosenberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
