<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASAGRANDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASA GRANDE WATER PANIC DISSIPATES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASA GRANDE, Ariz. _ Students by the hundreds dutifully carried
bottles of purified water to school Tuesday as people in the city
struggled to get by without a clean municipal water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the panic after Monday's alert that dangerous bacteria
were found in the water delivered to the town by the Arizona Water
Co. It was replaced with the concern and frustration of families
and businesses forced to cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't let my kids take their baths Monday night, and I had
them use bottled water to wash their faces,'' said LaVonna Queen, a
hairdresser who ignored health officials' assurances that the water
was safe for bathing.
</P>
<P>
   Queen, who bought seven gallons of purified water Tuesday, said
she even switched to bottled water for her three cats' drinking
bowls.
</P>
<P>
   In a public notice issued Monday, the water company noted that
people who drink water contaminated by fecal coliform may
experience diarrhea, cramps, nausea and jaundice.
</P>
<P>
   Local doctors and the Casa Grande Regional Medical Center
reported dozens of calls from people complaining of illness. But
hospital officials said lab results require at least 48 hours and
said there had been no confirmed cases yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much a concern when you have the whole town on
alert,'' said Jova Bollig, office manager for Dr. John Hughes'
medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   With tap water off limits, restaurants and bars could not use
their soda fountains and were finding other ways to quench
customers' thirsts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't use the soda machine because it uses the same water
the city uses, and we had to stop selling soda,'' said Lawrence
Bowles, assistant manager of a Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, while clerks ran to the grocery story for
two-liter bottles of soda, Bowles dashed out to buy purified ice.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping at Desert Water &AMP; Ice, the city's only commercial
purified water retailer, Bowles loaded up his pickup with 375
pounds of bagged ice cubes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should get us through the night,'' he said
optimistically.
</P>
<P>
   Although the water crisis was a headache for some, it was a
bonanza for water-store owner Leonard Massey.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed everyone in town, including the elementary school
district, went to Massey's store with whatever empty containers
they could find to stock up on clean water.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Monday) was the biggest day we'd every had,'' he said. ``You
couldn't even walk in this store it was so busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice on Monday, the store's 800-gallon tank was drained and the
store was temporarily closed until more water could be sanitized by
reverse osmosis, an ultraviolet laser and processing through a
series of eight filters, Massey said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Tuesday's customers was Enrique Espinoza, head custodian
for Cottonwood Elementary School who filled 10-gallon water coolers
to supply classrooms today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shut off all the school's drinking fountains as soon as we
heard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until further notice, all district schools are purchasing
purified water and keeping drinking fountains shut off, district
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Casa Elementary School District Superintendent Frank
Davidson sent a note home asking parents to help during the crisis
``by sending their children to school with their own personal
supply of purified water for each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Queen is one mom who said she doesn't mind taking the
precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually don't drink the city water anyway because we don't
like the taste,'' she said. ``I send my kids to school with their
own water bottle every day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
