<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yankees put Padres in headlock
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Not even Trevor Hoffman can stop these Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In a World Series that all but ended on a Scott Brosius home run
here in the eighth inning, the Yankees came clawing back from a
three-run deficit and knocked off the Padres 5-4 in Game 3 Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Like the opening game, the Padres could have won this one only
their bullpen collapsed again, this time the great Hoffman himself
taking the dive.
</P>
<P>
   With Brosius going deep twice and closer Mariano Rivera hanging
on in a tense final two turns of the bat for the Padres, the
Yankees now lead the Series three games to none and no team has
ever made up such a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 starter Kevin Brown will try to extend the Series another
day when he takes the mound tonight for the Padres. But whether it
happens in Game 4 or in one of the final these games, the Yankees
don't look like they are going to be denied their 24th world title
and second in three years.
</P>
<P>
   They just don't quit. Sterling Hitchcock had them down 3-0,
those runs coming in the sixth off Yankees righthander David Cone,
who had held the Padres hitless for five innings.
</P>
<P>
   But in the seventh, the problems began for Hitchcock, the
postseason darling for San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius hit the first of his two homers, a solo shot. Rookie
Shane Spencer would follow with a double and Hitchcock was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees would score another in the inning and Padres manager
Bruce Bochy, obviously not very confident in his bullpen, went to
Hoffman in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   To the AC/DC song of ``Hells Bells'', Hoffman took the field and
the 64,677 at Qualcomm Stadium have rarely been louder. But it was
apparent very quickly that Hoffman didn't have his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Paul O'Neill and Bernie Williams then drove a ball to
deep right which Tony Gwynn caught on the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman then had problems just getting the ball to the plate
against Tino Martinez, finally walking him. Up walked Brosius, who
has come up with one big hit after another. And none may ever be
bigger in his career as he drilled a Hoffman fastball over the wall
in center field for a two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres would score one in the bottom of the inning as
Yankees manager Joe Torre also brought in his closer (Rivera)
early.
</P>
<P>
   I.J. Rosenberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
