<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A MESSY BUDGET ENDGAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Oct. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Few actions have brought more discredit on the 105th Congress
than the frantic deal-making that surrounded the budget
negotiations over the last few weeks. Pressed on by their leaders,
legislators are holding their noses and approving a sprawling, $500
billion measure that includes provisions they have not even read,
much less studied, from grants for the Red Cross and the Tennessee
Valley Authority to special favors for truckers and the peanut
industry.
</P>
<P>
   When the Democrats were in charge of Congress a decade ago,
President Reagan dropped one of these omnibus spending measures,
weighing 43 pounds, on the lectern during a State of the Union
Message and told Congress never to send him another one. This year,
President Clinton was eager to sign because he had achieved many of
his most important goals, from eliminating several anti-environment
riders to new money for schoolteachers, the International Monetary
Fund and distressed farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also enjoying watching conservative Republicans
fulminate over the way their own party stuffed the bill with costly
pet projects. Indeed, one of the more prominent casualties in this
process was the quaint notion that the Republicans are the only
reliable champions of smaller government. The budget contains
unnecessary spending for drug interdiction in Latin America and
various ill-advised military projects like covert operations in
Iraq and missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The budget process all but collapsed this year for three
reasons. First, the Republican leadership was so divided that for
the first time since the budget reforms of the 1970s, the House and
Senate were unable to agree on a unified set of spending ceilings.
Second, Republicans who had pinned their election hopes on
Clinton's impeachment problems simply failed to build a case for
their policies, particularly tax cuts. Finally, a projected $70
billion surplus meant that all sides exceeded the spending caps
enacted last year simply by calling $20 billion worth of items
``emergencies.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Congress allowed a handful of legislators and White
House aides, meeting behind closed doors, to approve one-third of
the overall $1.7 trillion federal budget. It was a dangerously
arbitrary process that produced large excesses as well as small
absurdities like the fracas over a government directive requiring
peanut-free zones on some airline flights to protect passengers
with allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby of Alabama said the directive, which was
repealed after fierce lobbying by the peanut industry, was an
example of ``why so many people have come to resent and distrust
government.'' He could just as easily have been referring to the
entire way in which Congress handled the budget. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-20-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
