<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-WATER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER REGULATORS TOUT SAFETY OF ARIZONA SUPPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take another sip of Arizona tap water, say Arizona water
regulators, who maintain the water provided by municipal and
private systems is very good to excellent.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems this week that left 30,000 residents in central
Arizona with undrinkable water could strike at any time,
environmentalists warn.
</P>
<P>
   Orders to boil water before drinking, or use water from
somewhere else, remain in effect Wednesday for Casa Grande and
Arizona City customers of the Arizona Water Co., said Amy
Rezzonico, spokeswoman for the Arizona Department of Environmental
Quality.
</P>
<P>
   Tests on Tuesday showed 24 of 39 samples were clean of total or
fecal coliform, indicators of potentially deadly and
disease-causing bacteria. Analysis of 15 more test samples will not
be completed until today, at the earliest, Rezzonico said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Dexel of Arizona Water Co. said he felt confident that,
after flushing the water systems for most of Tuesday, that the
boil-water notice would soon be lifted, a source of the
contamination identified and a solution put in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done, at this point, everything we can. We have
provided a good service to the community, and we will do so in the
future. This is an unfortunate event,'' Dexel said.
</P>
<P>
   The public health notice issued by DEQ on Monday sent Casa
Grande residents scurrying to local stores to buy bottled water,
some thing many Valley residents already do.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys by Arizona State University show three out of four
Valley residents drink either bottled or filtered water, and only
one in four drinks water from the tap. Reasons vary from concern
over water quality to the high mineral content and questionable
taste of Valley tap water.
</P>
<P>
   The Casa Grande water-contamination comes as Valley cities and
towns are in the midst of a campaign to assure their customers that
Valley tap water is safe to drink and tastes good, too, if you
chill it first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's excellent,'' Bing Brown, spokesman for Phoenix Water
Services Department, said of the city's tap water. Brown said the
public is being ``horribly misled'' by ``scare tactics'' used by
firms marketing water and water filtration systems.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix water customers next month will begin receiving a
six-page notice detailing efforts to ensure their water safety.
</P>
<P>
   Valley cities this month launched a ``Tap Into Quality''
campaign that emphasizes the more than 100 quality tests Valley
water undergoes to meet county, state and federal water standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did some research that shows there is a misconception about
the safety of tap water,'' said DeEtte Person, a spokesperson for
Scottsdale and the ``Tap Into Quality'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they don't like the taste. We just want them to make an
informed decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists contend that what happened this week in
Casa Grande could happen anywhere in Arizona, and already has in
some places.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Driscoll, state director of Arizona Citizen Action, the
state's largest consumer-environmental group, said Congress and the
Legislature need to do more to ensure water quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, the water that comes through our pipes is
susceptible to this kind of (bacteria) problem. We've been pushing
for tighter standards and tighter monitoring, and there's been
resistance on the part of Congress to providing that kind of
protection,'' Driscoll said.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies in recent years have recorded problems with
Arizona water, especially in rural areas:
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Citizen Action and the Washington, D.C.,-based
Environmental Working Group issued a report, ``Just Add Water,''
that ranked Arizona fifth-worst in violations of the federal Safe
Drinking Water Act. The report showed that more than 1.2 million
Arizonans and more than 50 million Americans had been exposed in
the previous two years to water that at one point or another had
failed to meet federal health standards. Disease-causing
microorganisms annually kill an estimated 1,000 people and cause 7
million illnesses nationwide, the report said. Water problems in
Milwaukee in 1993 left more than 100 people dead and nearly 400,000
ill.
</P>
<P>
   A federal report in 1996 also found that more than 100,000
Arizonans in 50 rural communities suffered from ``critical
drinking-water problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A state report two years ago estimated that it already has cost
more than $445 million to clean up polluted underground water
wells, and that is may cost billions to clean up hundreds more.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to improve Arizona water quality, the Legislature
last year authorized DEQ personnel to collect samples and conduct
tests for Arizona's small water systems. The Centralized Monitoring
Program was to start this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Legislature _ led by members concerned about adding more
state workers _ scrapped the plan in favor of a Monitoring
Assistance Program, in which private contractors would collect
water samples. The legislation, which Gov. Jane Hull allowed to
take effect without her signature, also gave $500,000 to water
trade associations to help conduct the tests for the smallest water
firms, those with fewer than 200 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Water Co. serves 20 other Arizona communities, including
parts of Apache Junction, Pinetop and Globe-Miami, with nearly
166,000 total water customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
