<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8175 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-HNS &LR;      10-20 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
LUBBOCK _ Fool me once, shame on you. Texas Tech 14, Texas A&AMP;M 7
(1995).
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fool me twice, shame on me. Texas Tech 13, Texas A&AMP;M 10 (1996).
</P>
<P>
   Fool me three times . Texas Tech 16, Texas A&AMP;M 13 (1997).
</P>
<P>
   Why is there no familiar saying for the third time?
</P>
<P>
   Probably because if it happens a third time, you were not fooled
at all. No, somebody just took advantage of you.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Raiders didn't fool the Aggies the past three years.
Nope, they just beat 'em, plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   They have yet to ``beat 'em like a borrowed mule,'' as Texas
Tech coach Spike Dykes is wont to say when someone betters his
squad, but they have beaten them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fortunate and had some good things happen to us and
had some big plays,'' Dykes said. ``I think it's one of those deals
that we have great respect for them. When you have great respect
for them, sometimes it brings out the best in you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they have a good program and a good team, and we're
gonna have to put our best foot forward to have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech is the only team to compile three consecutive victories
against the Aggies in the R.C. Slocum era.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is the only other team that even has three wins against
Slocum-coached teams, with its best streak against Slocum's Aggies
being consecutive victories in 1995 and '96. Tech is 4-5 against
the Aggies during Slocum's tenure; Texas is 3-6.
</P>
<P>
   The streak started with the ``Zach Thomas'' game in 1995. So
dubbed by Tech sports information director Richard Kilwien, it is
the way everyone else in Lubbock remembers the game as well.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask, ``Were you at the Zach Thomas game?'' Almost everyone
says yes _ Jones Stadium was filled to the hilt with 51,205 that
early-October afternoon _ and no one asks which game.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there were two big scoring plays in Tech's 14-7
victory that year, but one faded to relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman receiver Donnie Hart lined up on the left side with a
choice of two routes to run against Aggies senior defensive back
Ray Mickens.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster made the right read and beat Mickens on a nice
fade into the corner of the end zone for a second-quarter touchdown
that tied the game at 7.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Thomas who brought victory to the Red Raiders with an
interception and 23-yard return for a touchdown with 30 seconds
left. And it is Thomas who will always be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zach picks it off, runs it back for a touchdown, and the place
goes crazy,'' Hart said. ``It was pandemonium here _ one of the
biggest plays in Tech history. I caught a touchdown pass in that
game, and nobody remembers it. It's just a side note.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart's first career score might have a slightly less significant
place in history next to Thomas' touchdown, but then-freshman
defensive end Montae Reagor almost made Thomas' play ``the play
that never was.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagor, now the school's all-time sacks leader, did his best to
knock down the pass and remembers the ball just missing his
fingertips before Thomas hauled it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll never forget that moment,'' Reagor said. ``I can
still see Zach going around the corner, and then everything just
went wild. You couldn't stand still if you wanted to, there was so
much excitement on the field. It was a very exciting and emotional
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its amazing finish, the 1995 victory over A&AMP;M will
always have a special place in Tech fans' hearts. It was the teams'
final matchup in the Southwest Conference, and it ended the No.
8-ranked Aggies' 29-game streak without a conference loss.
</P>
<P>
   But the subsequent wins have been no less entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Red Raiders went to College Station and toppled the
revenge-minded Aggies 13-10, thanks to an 81-yard pass play from
Zebbie Lethridge to Sammy Morris with six minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Tech knocked off the 20th-ranked Aggies 16-13 on Tony
Rogers' 47-yard field goal with 19 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Is there some secret Tech has to playing so well against A&AMP;M?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just played hard and made big plays down the stretch
that enabled ourselves to be in position to win,'' Reagor said.
``That's what it takes in big ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the same approach this year. We have to prepare well,
go out there, play hard and try to correct the mistakes from the
previous games this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Accomplish that, and more memories will be built for the No. 25
Red Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Senior linebacker Kevin McCullar's first significant playing
time came against A&AMP;M in 1996, and he made seven tackles. Last
year, he forced a fumble from Aggies quarterback Randy McCown deep
in Texas A&AMP;M territory to set up Tech's lone touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has basically been effort,'' McCullar said. ``It's
not that we have better athletes; they have great athletes also. I
think we just put in great effort to best them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, A&AMP;M had always been expected to win, but Zach
made a big play a few years back and since then everything has been
going our way against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we know, though: It's gonna be a battle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
